<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-MULAN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISNEY GETS FAIRY TALE ENDING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURBANK, Calif. _ Mulan didn't just save China, she's saving The
Walt Disney Co. as well.
</P>
<P>
   Disney's latest animated movie, ``Mulan,'' has revived the
fortunes of its most precious division following several years of
less-than-stellar performances. With $84.8 million in domestic
grosses in its first three weeks through Thursday, ``Mulan'' has
outperformed expectations and should be hugely profitable for the
entertainment giant.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts believe ``Mulan'' could wind up with $140 million by
the end of its run _ far better than the $100 million final grosses
for 1996's ``The Hunchback of Notre Dame'' and last summer's
``Hercules.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie's early performance also reinforces the widespread
belief that rivals like Warner Bros., 20th Century Fox and
DreamWorks SKG face a rough road in challenging Disney's lock on
animated movies, dating back to its 1937 release of ``Snow White
and the Seven Dwarfs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact remains that no other studio has ever been able to do
anywhere near Disney's business in animated movies,'' said analyst
Stewart Halpern of Furman Selz. ``If you asked most parents what
they want, they'd say they were looking for more animated Disney
product.''
</P>
<P>
   Halpern estimates every dollar in domestic ticket sales for a
Disney animated movie translates to three dollars of operating
profit due to enormous markets for merchandise, home video and
overseas theaters.
</P>
<P>
   Halpern's estimate is conservative, with many analysts using a
multiplier of four to calculate animation profits. In the case of a
worldwide hit like 1994's ``The Lion King,'' Disney's operating
profits have gone past $1 billion, according to Jill Krutick of
Salomon Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
   ``Animation is the most lucrative venue for the company, as it
sparks a rainbow of related product sales over a period of years,''
said Krutick, who has a ``buy'' rating on the stock. She estimated
``Mulan'' would generate up to $350 million in operating profit
with foreign box office of $125 million to $175 million, U.S. home
video sales of 11 million to 13 million units and video sales of 8
million to 9 million units overseas.
</P>
<P>
   Krutick, who had originally predicted a domestic gross as low as
$80 million for ``Mulan,'' said its unique story helped widen the
audience beyond the core of young girls to include boys and more
sophisticated moviegoers. She also noted that although ``Mulan''
production costs were higher than ``Hercules,'' Disney's total
costs were about equal because it spent less on marketing
``Mulan.''
</P>
<P>
   For Disney, the success of ``Mulan'' also represents a bit of
redemption following 1994's departure of Jeffrey Katzenberg as
studio chief a few months after ``The Lion King'' became a
worldwide blockbuster.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though `Hunchback' and `Hercules' had respectable
numbers, people's expectations were so high because of `Lion King,'
'' said Linda Bannister of Edward Jones. ``You can't hit a home run
every time, but I don't think that it meant in any way that Disney
had lost its touch in animation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mulan's'' success is timely because Disney's other recent
films _ ``Armageddon,'' ``Six Days, Seven Nights'' and ``The Horse
Whisperer'' _ have failed to meet expectations. Even though
``Armageddon'' managed to gross an impressive $76.3 million in nine
days, this weekend's openings of ``Small Soldiers'' and ``Lethal
Weapon 4'' are expected to rob much of the disaster film's
audience.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, ``Mulan's'' solid numbers come with Disney facing
upcoming incursions in animation likely to be more formidable than
recent entries by 20th Century Fox's ``Anastasia'' and Warner
Bros.' ``Quest for Camelot.''
</P>
<P>
   Paramount will open ``Rugrats'' in November and a ``Beavis and
Butt-head'' sequel next year. Katzenberg, meanwhile, has maneuvered
the openings of DreamWorks' ``Antz'' and ``Prince of Egypt'' around
the November release of Disney's ``A Bug's Life.''
</P>
<P>
   But Wall Street favors Disney. Shares of Pixar Animation, which
co-financed ``A Bug's Life,'' have soared recently on positive
forecasts about the film.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very optimistic about `A Bug's Life,' '' Bannister
said. ``I'm of the mind that there are Disney films and then
there's everyone else. The name is synonymous with good quality,
and parents feel comfortable with it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mulan'' and the buzz over ``A Bug's Life'' validate Disney's
recent strategy of cutting back the number of live-action products
while boosting its animated operations. It plans to release four
animated movies next year _ ``Tarzan,'' ``Toy Story 2,''
``Dinosaur'' and ``Fantasia 2000,'' set for New Year's Eve.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
