<HEADLINE>
REDS' REMLINGER BLANKS DIAMONDBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - There was no place like home for two members of the
visiting Cincinnati Reds on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Chaparral High graduate Paul Konerko homered in his first start
for his new team, and Mike Remlinger, who lives in Scottsdale
during the off-season, pitched his best game in more than seven
years as the Reds beat the Diamondbacks, 8-0, at Bank One Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Barry Larkin, a true out-of-towner, homered twice, had
three hits in all and drove in five runs.
</P>
<P>
   Konerko, part of a trade that sent relief pitcher Jeff Shaw to
the Los Angeles Dodgers last week, started in left field and hit a
solo homer off Diamondbacks starter Willie Blair in the fourth
inning.
</P>
<P>
   That made it 2-0 at the time, and it was more than enough for
Remlinger, a lefthander who pitched a three-hitter for his second
career shutout. His first happened on June 15, 1991 while pitching
for the San Francisco Giants, shortly after he was promoted from
the Triple-A Firebirds.
</P>
<P>
   Coming into the game, Remlinger, who struck out seven and walked
five, was 5-9 with a 4.50 ERA. One of the losses was to the
Diamondbacks, last month.
</P>
<P>
   Blair took his 13th loss, tops in the majors. He also gave up a
pair of homers (Barry Larkin added one in the eighth) and now has
been taken deep 23 times, highest in the National League.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds, who won their sixth straight and 11 of their last 12,
took a 1-0 lead in the second inning when Willie Greene led off
with a single and Bret Boone walked. Konerko to hit into a double
play, Greene moving to third. Pokey Reese then hit a grounder wide
of first base. Travis Lee got to it, but Blair, covering first,
dropped the toss just as Reese was arriving with a head-first
slide. Reese got an infield hit and an RBI out of it as Greene
scored.
</P>
<P>
   As in the first eight innings of Friday's 5-4 loss, the
Diamondbacks offered little resistance. Yamil Benitez sent Reggie
Sanders back to the wall in center field, more than 400 feet away,
for long out in the second inning.
</P>
<P>
   Damian Miller led off the third inning with a double, but stayed
at second as Blair struck out, Devon White hit a lazy fly ball to
left and Danny Klassen was robbed for the second time by shortstop
Barry Larkin. In the first inning, Larkin went far to his left,
whirled and barely got Klassen at first. This time, Larkin went to
his right and threw Klassen out by a fraction.
</P>
<P>
   Blair appeared to be in command after the Reds' run in the
second. He gave up a two-out double to Larkin in the third, then
got Eddie Taubensee on a soft liner to second baseman Klassen.
</P>
<P>
   But with two out in the fourth, Blair grooved an 0-2 pitch to
Konerko. Delighted over such an offering, Konerko sent it into the
overhang under the scoreboard in center field. The blast, his fifth
of the season, was measured at 436 feet. The Reds led, 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   Lee walked with one out in the fourth and Jay Bell sent a
momentary thrill through the crowd of 47,323. But his long fly,
like Benitez's, settled into Sanders' glove near the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Blair provided a re-run of the third inning when Sean Casey
doubled with two out, then stayed at second when Larkin flied out
to right.
</P>
<P>
   White led off the sixth with a walk and after Klassen flied to
left, Matt Williams singled. There was one out, runners on first
and second and Lee, who leads all National League rookies in hits,
home runs and RBI, coming up.
</P>
<P>
   But Lee swung at Remlinger's first offering and grounded into a
double play started by second baseman Bret Boone.
</P>
<P>
   In the bottom of the inning, Benitez was hit by a pitch with one
out. But Dellucci grounded to Larkin, who started another double
play.
</P>
<P>
   It was still 2-0, but all of Blair's good work came undone in
the eighth. After Sanders struck out for the fourth time, Casey
doubled. Larkin then hit his seventh homer of the season. The
two-run shot gave the Reds a 4-0 lead and knocked Blair out of the
game. Alan Embree came in and immediately surrendered a pair of
singles and a wild pitch for the Reds fifth run.
</P>
<P>
   Gregg Olson pitched the ninth for the Diamondbacks and
surrendered a three-run homer to Larkin. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
