<HEADLINE>
EVENTUALLY, SMITH WILL PAY FOR TKACHUK'S EXTENSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX -  &UR; Keith Tkachuk won't come to Coyotes' training camp
without a contract extension. That should be a foregone conclusion
by now, about as obvious as  &UR; Lucy pulling the football from
 &UR; Charlie Brown.
</P>
<P>
   So what happens if Coyotes General Manager  &UR; Bobby Smith
continues to play hardball and refuses to negotiate a new
three-year pact _ a $33 million package that he pulled off the
table two weeks ago?
</P>
<P>
   Nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Smith will pay what it takes to keep one of the
NHL's top power forwards in a Phoenix uniform well into the next
millennium. Why? Because trading him isn't an option. Not after
dealing another proven 50-goal scorer,  &UR; Teemu Selanne, just over
two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, only a handful of teams can afford Tkachuk. Few of them
have anything the Coyotes want in return.  &UR; Pavel Bure and Vancouver
Canucks are out. So is  &UR; Adam  &UR; Graves and the New York Rangers.
Ditto with  &UR; Eric
 &UR; Lindros and Philadelphia (though don't ask me why).
</P>
<P>
   The only deal that would remotely make sense is a two-for-one
with the New York Islanders: Tkachuk for sizzling  &UR; Ziggy Palffy and
one of two top young defensemen,  &UR; Bryan Berard or  &UR; Kenny Jonsson.
</P>
<P>
   But that won't happen, either. Smith, like it or not, has proven
it. In the end, he will strike a bargain with Tkachuk and agent
 &UR; Bob
 &UR; Murray, just as he did with  &UR; Jeremy  &UR; Roenick two years ago after
JR's trade from Chicago. Just as he did last season after one-third
of the season with  &UR; Oleg Tverdovsky.
</P>
<P>
   Both players virtually got what they wanted after contract
disputes. So, too, will Tkachuk, whether or not you believe he
deserves between $33 million and $40 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows what's going to happen?'' Tkachuk said. ``Obviously,
that would be nice. But he's got to do what's best for the team.''
</P>
<P>
   What's best for the Coyotes, barring the perfect trade, is
facilitating Tkachuk as soon as possible. Yes, pay him the big
money. Even if he has two years remaining on his contract, which he
should _ but probably won't _ honor.
</P>
<P>
   Do it now and save face. Do it after 30 or 40 games, and the
Coyotes might as well kiss the playoffs goodbye. &QL; 
Bowman back?
</P>
<P>
   After meeting with him in Buffalo during the NHL entry draft, it
didn't appear likely that Red Wings Coach  &UR; Scotty Bowman would
return for another season.
</P>
<P>
   That may have changed. Bowman, concerned about his health after
the death of his younger brother, Jack, underwent a comprehensive
medical examination Thursday at William Beaumont Hospital in Royal
Oak, Mich. Afterward, he said he would be back for at least one
more season if the tests showed he was healthy enough to continue.
</P>
<P>
   The tests are due back Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took most of the day,'' Bowman told the ``Detroit News.''
``They let me out, so I guess that's a good sign.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowman, who turns 65 in September, would like a chance to break
 &UR; Toe
 &UR; Blake's record for the most Stanley Cups won as a head coach.
Bowman tied Blake with eight crowns after winning back-to-back
titles.
</P>
<P>
   Bowman will undergo knee-replacement surgery this summer,
regardless, which will keep him on the mend for at least two
months. &QL; 
Goalie go-around
</P>
<P>
   Toronto goalie  &UR; Felix Potvin apparently is off the trading block
after Edmonton refused to take him. The deal that would have been
preceded by the Maple Leafs signing Oilers goalie  &UR; Curtis Joseph to
a free-agent contract.
</P>
<P>
   The Potvin deal also was contingent on Toronto getting
defenseman
 &UR; Boris Mironov and rookie center  &UR; Boyd Devereaux in return.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired of the Felix Potvin fiasco,'' said Mike Smith,
Toronto's associate GM. ``He's one of the best goalies in the
league, and yet we received nothing but poor offers from other
teams. . . . We have no intention of trading him.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, no one knows what will happen with Joseph and fellow
free-agent goalie  &UR; Mike Richter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation hasn't changed for Curtis or Richter,'' Oilers
GM
 &UR; Glen Sather said. ``They're still trying to hold out for as much as
possible. It doesn't seem like it makes any difference where they
play, as long as they get the money they're asking.''
</P>
<P>
   If Richter doesn't re-sign with the Rangers, who tendered him a
three-year deal last week worth $5.4 million a season, he could be
out of luck. Florida and Vancouver, the two main clubs interested,
can't afford it.
</P>
<P>
   Slap shots
</P>
<P>
   Not including backup goalie  &UR; Jimmy  &UR; Waite, an unrestricted free
agent who may not be back, the Coyotes have jettisoned the most
core players from their roster among the 26 established clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix has purged at least 11 part- or full-time contributors
from last season, three more than the next-closest team. Among
those who won't be back:  &UR; Mike Gartner,  &UR; Jim McKenzie,  &UR; Craig
Janney,  &UR; Murray Baron,
 &UR; Darrin Shannon, &UR; Jim  &UR; Johnson,  &UR; Norm Maciver,  &UR; John Slaney and
 &UR; Michel
 &UR; Petit.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, a 13-year veteran who has spent two years with the
Coyotes, has been approached about the team's radio analyst job,
made vacant when  &UR; Tom Kurvers moved to West Coast scout for
Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who missed most of last season after suffering a
serious concussion, is expected to notify the club with his
decision sometime this week. Don't be surprised if Johnson moves
into a pro coaching career if he turns down the offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Olie the Goalie,'' Washington's  &UR; Olaf Kolzig, will be getting
married in Arizona next month. An off-season resident, Kolzig's
best man will be Bruins goalie  &UR; Byron Dafoe, formerly of the
Roadrunners. &QL; 
Bob McManaman can be reached at 602-444-8326 or at
bob.mcmanaman(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
