<HEADLINE>
NEW COMMISSIONER TAKES WELFARE OF GAME TO HEART 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It became official last week:  &UR; Bud Selig is now the ninth
commissioner in the history of the game. There are those who
believe this is the worst possible news baseball could have
produced.
</P>
<P>
   The reality of it all is that baseball has now joined the other
three major sports. Major League Baseball was the last of the major
sports to hold out on the thought of a truly independent
commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   The current landscape of professional sports, which have gone
from family-run franchises to being held by billion-dollar
corporations, has drastically changed. The NBA recognized this long
ago and  &UR; David
 &UR; Stern, generally regarded as the best of the commissioners, is not
the independent head of the sport he makes himself out to be, but
instead, someone whose agenda is geared completely toward the
owners.
</P>
<P>
   Selig will forever be linked to the canceling of the last six
weeks of the 1994 season, the single biggest black eye the game has
ever suffered. Even though Selig stood alone on the podium that
September day and canceled the World Series, every player in the
major leagues stood next to him. Both parties were to blame.
</P>
<P>
   Without question, Selig has nothing but the goodwill of the game
in his heart. Now that he is through juggling the Milwaukee Brewers
and the office of the commissioner, it's time for Selig to, in his
words, ``give every ounce of energy in his body to this job.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a man who has deep passion for the great game of
baseball. He just needs to remember that, which he should have no
trouble with, and Selig will be remembered as one of the people who
helped save baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Unless there has been a dramatic change in Selig's stance, he
will do the right thing and help bring baseball back to its
standing as the crown jewel of the major sports. It can be done,
and Selig is not a bad choice to help get it done. &QL; 
Renewing acquaintances &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Albert Belle, now with the White Sox, played for Cleveland
Manager
 &UR; Mike Hargrove for five years while in Cleveland. Belle felt
slighted when Hargrove selected  &UR; Ray Durham over Belle as the White
Sox's All-Star representative.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Hargrove was his own man, I think I would have been
picked,'' Belle said.
</P>
<P>
   Hargrove, who often tangled with Belle when the two were
together, denied he was pushed to select Durham over Belle.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was nobody in my ear about this,'' Hargrove said. ``I
made the decision based on the fact that Albert was picked last
year and didn't participate in anything. He didn't take the (team)
picture, he didn't take batting practice, nothing. And I'm not
going to waste a spot with somebody who doesn't want to play. It's
that plain and simple. I'm not so sure that Albert's numbers are
any better than anybody we picked.'' &QL; 
Orel's goals &QL;
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco's  &UR; Orel Hershiser, who greatly enjoyed beating his
former club Los Angeles last weekend, now has 186 career victories,
leaving him 23 short of where he wants to wind up.
</P>
<P>
   ``My ultimate goal is to win a world championship with the
Giants,'' Hershiser said. ``My secondary and personal goal is to
win 200 games and then win 209 games to get where  &UR; Don Drysdale is
at.''
</P>
<P>
   The late Drysdale, who befriended Hershiser during his many
years with the Dodgers, was 209-166 during his Hall of Fame career.
Hershiser, who is wearing No. 53 to honor Drysdale, is 186-129.
</P>
<P>
   The former Cy Young Award winner in 1988 is under contract for
$3.45 million this season and has an option for $3.25 million next
season. However, Hershiser can become a free agent if he pitches
176 innings. He's at 110. &QL; 
A red summer &QL; 
Cincinnati has lowered its payroll to the point where it can live
with it. Now the Reds want to go all the way with their plan to be
competitive by the time their new stadium is scheduled to open in
2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are no longer making deals for payroll reasons,'' GM  &UR; Jim
Bowden said. `Our payroll is the fourth lowest in baseball. That is
no longer an issue. The issue is to get to what our ownership
wants, which is a winner in 2002.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden has warned  &UR; John Allen, who has taken over the Reds in
 &UR; Marge
 &UR; Schott's absence, to not expect the Reds to compete in the coming
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I informed him that if in fact we start to trade the rest of
these key pieces, you can't come back in 15 months and say, `OK,
now we want to win,' '' Bowden said. ``Once you do this, you have
to be totally committed to what your direction has been. John Allen
was very emphatic. He said our game plan has not changed, and we
will not deviate from that.'' &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Pedro Gomez can be
reached at 602-444-2364 or at pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
