<HEADLINE>
LASORDA SHOULD LEARN TO READ FINE PRINT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The first I-told-you-so could be landing any
second now. Lobbed by the Dodgers employee who, in the dizzying
hours after Tom Lasorda became the club's general manager,
described a worrisome scenario that sounded very much like what
just took place in the Jeff Shaw trade.
</P>
<P>
   The theory was that Lasorda, as impulsive as he is inexperienced
in his new job, might pull a trade or some other player move
without regard for the complicated rules that govern major-league
transactions. The mistake might cost the Dodgers a player or a
bundle of money.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in keeping with his reputation for shifting blame (``It's
not my fault, Campanis is the guy!''), he might try to pin it on a
subordinate who could have prevented the error if only Lasorda had
given him the chance.
</P>
<P>
   In the for-instance, the employee proposed, a player might be
shipped to the minors for the third time, which the rules say would
make him a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   In real life, Lasorda's oversight in trading Paul Konerko and
Dennis Reyes to the Cincinnati Reds for Shaw on July 4 might be
nothing more than a minor embarrassment, a missed homework
assignment in the education of a GM. Or it might turn into
something worse, allowing the relief ace the Dodgers traded two top
prospects to acquire to leave in the winter.
</P>
<P>
   The Daily News reported Saturday that Lasorda didn't realize
that under the Basic Agreement between players and owners, because
Shaw has at least five (actually six) years in the major leagues
and was traded with at least a season (actually three) left on his
Reds contract, he has the right to demand the Dodgers trade him in
the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   The rule is designed to give some leverage to players who agree
to multi-year contracts, perhaps signing away a chance for free
agency, to achieve stability. Shaw liked playing in Cincinnati,
where he could live in his hometown: Washington Court House, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry about Shaw actually wanting out of Los Angeles. He
laughed about the report before the game against the San Diego
Padres Saturday night. ``I've been here two days, and they're
already talking about me leaving!'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw's agent, Joe Bick of Cincinnati, said there's no reason to
think Shaw would request a trade. ``We hope this isn't an issue at
all,'' Bick said on the phone. ``Jeff wants to go and do a terrific
job for the Dodgers and be a part of the ballclub for a long time
to come.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Shaw and Bick will hold onto the right, because it could
be the lever that pries more money out of the Dodgers. Teams often
make such deals to persuade players to waive their right when this
rule comes into play, which it does frequently when a veteran
player is traded. Like every summer.
</P>
<P>
   Which gets to the heart of the matter. This rule isn't exactly
obscure. It's quite a boulder to stumble over.
</P>
<P>
   And the mistake was completely avoidable. Apparently, Lasorda's
mistake was in making the trade. Rumors of it he had denied for
days before running it past Dodgers baseball operations
administrator Robert Schweppe, whose job includes reading the fine
print.
</P>
<P>
   The 174-page Basic Agreement is too complex for any GM to carry
around in his head. That's why Lasorda _ like Fred Claire before
him, and Al Campanis before him, and all but a handful of other
big-league GMs _ has people to double-check his work.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday Lasorda's boss, Dodgers president Bob Graziano,
declined to comment because he didn't want to appear to
second-guess Lasorda's player-personnel decisions. Other Dodgers
people were quick to defend Lasorda. They painted this as a rookie
mistake, probably inconsequential in the long run. He'll learn a
valuable lesson about communication.
</P>
<P>
   And Shaw's agent also downplayed the matter by saying of
Lasorda, ``I don't think it's a mistake at all. I think this deal
was going to happen whether he was aware of this particular issue
or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Something else to note in Lasorda's defense: The Basic
Agreement, which brought to a close the 1994-95 baseball strike,
couldn't be much more difficult to fathom if the IRS had written
it.
</P>
<P>
   Last March, Sports Illustrated spoofed the legalese of the
player-personnel rules in all the pro sports with a quiz that
began, ``So you think you could run a professional team ... ?''
This was question 26: ``What was the final holdup in the trade that
sent Chuck Knoblauch from the Minnesota Twins to the New York
Yankees for four minor leaguers and $3 million? (a) Any deal
involving $1 million or more is subject to the approval of the
executive council. (b) A major league player who has five years'
experience with the same team can't be traded for a player (or
players) who has no major-league service unless all parties clear
waivers. (c) Knoblauch would deal only with George Constanza.''
Answer: (a).
</P>
<P>
   Actually, there's another complication with the Knoblauch deal:
He, like Shaw, can demand a trade this winter. At least the Yankees
knew that before they got him.
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda probably will get lucky and none of this will make a
difference. The perception of the trade will rise or fall on the
performances of Shaw, Konerko and Reyes.
</P>
<P>
   But the same oversight under different circumstances could have
spelled disaster. It could have guaranteed that ``interim'' would
never become ``permanent.'' And it would have been too late to
blame Campanis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
