<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-SHEFFIELD-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHEFFIELD UNDERGOES NEAR-DEATH REBIRTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARC J. SPEARS  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Gary Sheffield seemingly had it all by the age of
27. There was a batting crown, two All-Star appearances and a big
contract.
</P>
<P>
   What Sheffield didn't have, however, was stability in his
personal life. Among the problems were charges of resisting arrest,
a restraining order against him, abuse accusations and concerns by
Major League Baseball about substance abuse.
</P>
<P>
   But before things became better, Sheffield's life took a turn
for the worse on Oct. 30, 1995. It fact, it almost was ended.
</P>
<P>
   Everything seemed fine when Sheffield, then with the Florida
Marlins, was driving through his old neighborhood of Belmont
Heights in Tampa, Fla. As his Mercedes reached a crawl near a stop
sign, a teen-ager dressed in a T-shirt and jeans walked up from the
rear of his car.
</P>
<P>
   Feeling comfortable in his old confines, Sheffield thought it
might be a buddy. It was quite the opposite. Sheffield began to
roll down his window when a shot rang out from a .25-caliber gun,
wounding him in the left shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The shooting) caused him to ... really look at life in the
long term,'' said Keith Jacobs, Sheffield's longtime friend and
chief operating officer of his companies. ``A lot of people look at
just the moment, (rather) than realize there is much more to life.
I believe he is looking at life through a different set of eyes
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, Sheffield began reading the Bible almost daily,
started cutting ties with shady acquaintances and hired a New York
publicist to help reshape his image. And, while his public image
was being restructured, his inner thoughts were being altered by
Evander Holyfield.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield, who had met Holyfield previously, became reacquainted
with the heavyweight boxing champion during the 1997 All-Star break
in Cleveland. Soon after, Sheffield had a phone conversation with
Holyfield, a deeply religious man, about building faith in God.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gradually, (Holyfield) was doing all the talking. And then he
just cut the conversation off and said he had to go train,'' said
Sheffield, who came to the Dodgers in a blockbuster seven-player
trade on May 15. ``But I did ask him a couple questions about why
he moved to the Lord. He said it was his only way for peace and
happiness.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't get into it too much, but I brought it up. I felt
that nobody has to call you to give you messages about the Lord. It
just so happened that the guy that called happened to be in the
Lord. God sends you signs in all kinds of ways, and I thought that
was a sign.''
</P>
<P>
   While others had been whispering into Sheffield's ear about
taking his faith more seriously, hearing it from a fellow sports
star made a much stronger impression.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gary needed to hear that from someone at the same level of
temptation,'' said Jacobs, who has been involved in Christian
ministry for 12 years. ``Money can be the root of all evil. A
person whose face is the same is easier to respect. It carried a
lot of legitimacy. Gary knew (Holyfield) could relate to his
situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know in (Sheffield's) society, no one is going to give you
a break. But Holyfield attested to him that none of his physical
treasures can give him what God can.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield, who will earn $10 million this year, said, ``It
amazes me when celebrities see me and say, `I am a fan of yours. I
like the way you play and swing the bat.' It's like, `You watch
me?' But I watch Evander Holyfield.''
</P>
<P>
   After his conversation with Holyfield, Sheffield said, he became
more serious about his faith. He began having frequent Bible
studies over the phone with Jacobs. He started attending chapel
services before games on Sundays. And he also began to look at his
life in a different way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody looked at me kind of funny,'' Sheffield said of his
first appearance at chapel. ``But I was so deep into it that I
didn't see other people. I was there to hear the word and not to
see who was looking at me. I know I was there to receive a
blessing, take it in and apply it to my life. After coming from
where I come from, that was a big step.''
</P>
<P>
   While Sheffield adopted a new view on life, there were skeptics
in baseball who wouldn't forget about his bad-boy image. When the
four-time All-Star came to Los Angeles, there might have been some
people in the Dodgers organization who wondered whether the
negative reputation was warranted.
</P>
<P>
   But first baseman Eric Karros said he kept an open mind and has
since learned that Sheffield is a positive influence for the
Dodgers, on and off the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you meet somebody for the first time, you may have
some doubt,'' Karros said. ``But I form my own opinion and I never
go with what is said, written or reported. From my experiences, he
is a great guy to have on the club.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield admits he used to have an I-don't-care attitude. He
didn't have much respect for the media and many people in baseball,
many of whom he believed treated him unfairly. He also never
thought fans really cared about him. But with rejuvenated religious
faith came a much different outlook.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows where he comes from and that he has been given a
pretty good walk in this life,'' said Dodgers utility man Jim
Eisenreich, who came over from Florida with Sheffield in the trade.
``He's respecting that and he is not taking for granted what has
been given to him. You can tell when you have a conversation with
him that he is very spiritual.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure (many people) would be surprised about (my
spirituality),'' said Sheffield, 29, who often wears a cross on his
silver necklace. ``But while the negative stuff was going on, I was
praying for people who were talking bad about me. When I look back
on everything that has happened bad towards me, I've been blessed
twice for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say I'm not worth anything and I'm getting double what
they say I'm worth. I've overcome all the odds. And the only way I
have done that is because God is looking out for me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
