<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-GOMEZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KLASSEN ALREADY OPENING EYES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Diamondbacks Assistant General Manager Sandy Johnson
has a saying: ``You can't mess up the good ones.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, in Danny Klassen, it appears that the Diamondbacks have
one of the good ones. Who knows, Klassen could even wind up being
one of the rare great ones.
</P>
<P>
   While it's far too early to talk about Klassen and greatness
together _ which may very well be there _ it is not too early to
talk about the future of the Diamondbacks, of which Klassen is
being counted on as a big piece of the puzzle.
</P>
<P>
   With Klassen all but up from the minors for good, joining first
baseman Travis Lee, Matt Williams at third and Jay Bell at
shortstop, the club will display its infield for the next five
years throughout the final 70-odd games.
</P>
<P>
   Only one questions looms: When do Klassen and Bell swap
positions? It is inevitable that the younger and more agile
Klassen, who doesn't turn 23 for another two months, will be moved
to shortstop with Bell, 32, switching to second base.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows, eventually they may switch us,'' Bell said.
</P>
<P>
   The bet is that the switch will take place during spring
training next year, allowing each to be comfortable with each other
and the switch. It's a scenario Bell, realizing the club will be
better in the long run, is aware of and will not fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great option to be able to think about,'' General
Manager Joe Garagiola Jr. said. ``Jay is such a pro, he'll do
whatever helps the team win.''
</P>
<P>
   Klassen has already generated a small fan club among his new
teammates, who remember being impressed with the natural shortstop
during his stay with the big-league club during spring training.
</P>
<P>
   ``You root for a guy like this,'' Andy Benes said. ``He reminds
me of Travis Lee. He's low key, and nothing really phases him.''
</P>
<P>
   In short, Klassen looks the part of a big-leaguer. Even when
he's standing still, he looks like he belongs. It's a gift some are
simply born with.
</P>
<P>
   ``You watch his actions and the way he handles himself and you
realize the kid's got a chance to stay here for a long time,'' Bell
said. ``He's certainly in a position to be a solid everyday and
reliable player. He's one of those guys that you'll look at in 10
years and ask him, `Are you going to manage?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Funny. Those are the exact kind of statements that were made
about Bell when he broke into the majors in the late 1980s. As it
turns out, there's an awful lot of Bell in Klassen, which can be
viewed only as a very good thing for the Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``He works very hard, and whatever weaknesses he perceives about
himself, he relentlessly works at getting rid of them,'' Manager
Buck Showalter said.
</P>
<P>
   Klassen has few weaknesses. His defense, which came into
question after making 50 errors at Double-A El Paso last season,
has been nothing short of brilliant since being called up. Don't
forget, he's been playing second base for less than six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Klassen made a spectacular play on a grounder to his left
Saturday night. Looking very much like perennial Gold Glove winner
Roberto Alomar, Klassen slid to his knees, snagged the grounder and
flipped to Lee for the out at first base.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere, Milwaukee Brewers General Manager Sal Bando is
hitting his head against a wall. It was Bando who decided to leave
Klassen exposed in the expansion draft not once, but twice. Barely
able to believe their good fortune, the Diamondbacks picked Klassen
with their fifth pick in the second round.
</P>
<P>
   In an interesting side note, then-Brewers owner Bud Selig walked
up to Bando at the Brewers' conference table after the second round
and the two had a lengthy discussion. You can bet Klassen's name
was mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, heck, even somewhat publicly, the Diamondbacks are
gushing over Klassen's potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``That they consider me this kind of player thrills me,'' said
Klassen, who has shed the No. 65 he wore in spring training for No.
7. ``It's an honor to be mentioned in the same sentence as Travis
Lee.''
</P>
<P>
   Get used to it, kid. It's going only going to continue. &QL; 
Pedro Gomez can be reached at 602-444-2364 or
pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
