<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BONILLA MOVES TO LEFT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARC J. SPEARS  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The kid has pushed the 35-year-old veteran to the
outfield. And if it helps the Dodgers, that is just fine with Bobby
Bonilla.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night against visiting San Diego, rookie Adrian Beltre
received his first start at third base since Bonilla, the usual
third baseman, came off the 15-day disabled list on July 3. The
last time Bonilla, who started in left field Saturday, played in
the outfield was Sept. 28, 1996, for Baltimore at Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Despite being sent to the outfield because of a 20-year-old,
Bonilla revealed no animosity about the change. Ironically, Dodgers
manager Glenn Hoffman previously said Bonilla was too big to play
left field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a third baseman .. I'm a left fielder ... I'm player. It
doesn't matter,'' said Bonilla. ``It doesn't matter where I play as
long as we win. This kid is good and he can help us. I told Hoff to
put me wherever he needs me.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla's stint in left didn't last long, however. He was thrown
out of the game in the second inning by home-plate umpire Bill Hohn
for arguing a called second strike. Beltre had a rough first
inning. He had a throwing error to home plate that helped the
Padres score two runs and he was also thrown out at the plate at
the bottom of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Beltre has probably the best throwing arm in the organization
next to Raul Mondesi, has above-average tools and was ranked as the
third-best prospect by Baseball America entering the season. He
batted second Saturday and entered the game batting .308 over his
previous six games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's what is best for the ballclub,'' said Hoffman.
</P>
<P>
   Bohanon a no-show: Since new Dodgers pitcher Brian Bohanon was
not put on the roster before the game, he was not in uniform.
However, the left-hander, who was traded from the New York Mets for
reliever Greg McMichael on Friday, will be activated in time to
start against the Padres this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers pitcher Dave Mlicki, who was Bohanon's teammate with the
Mets, said the Dodgers' new fifth starter has four or five pitches
and usually throws in the middle 80s. Bohanon (2-4, 3.15) has made
only four starts this season and has never been a consistent
starter in his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Bohanon) will give us a chance to win a lot of games,''
Mlicki said. ``I have no idea whether he is a better reliever or
starter.''
</P>
<P>
   Riggs checked: Dodgers second-base prospect Adam Riggs, who is
out for the season with torn cartilage in his right shoulder, had a
positive examination at Dodger Stadium on Saturday. Riggs, who was
ranked as the Dodgers' seventh-best prospect by Baseball America,
said he expects to start throwing again in four months and playing
in six. He also plans to play winter ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the first two weeks (after surgery), I couldn't tie my
shoes,'' said Riggs, 24, who had surgery June 2. ``I never felt so
helpless. It makes you appreciate having two arms.''
</P>
</TEXT>
