<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEAR-ABORTION WAS SECOND INCIDENT FOR DOCTOR
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD RUELAS and SUSIE STECKNER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
PHOENIX _ The doctor who two weeks ago delivered a baby he was
trying to abort was admonished by the state medical board eight
years ago for trying to abort another full-term infant.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Records also reveal that the Phoenix abortion clinic where the
baby was born, the A-Z Women's Center, has been the subject of
several lawsuits and at least seven allegations before the Arizona
Board of Medical Examiners.
</P>
<P>
   The June 30 attempted abortion has added fuel to the national
debate over late-term abortions and prompted investigations by
police, prosecutors, and the board.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1990 case, the medical board scolded Dr. John Biskind for
trying to abort a full-formed baby he said he thought was just 10
weeks old.
</P>
<P>
   The 18-year-old mother had told Biskind that she had her last
menstrual cycle about a month earlier, and she didn't appear to be
pregnant because she was seriously overweight, according to board
testi mony.
</P>
<P>
   Biskind told the board that as he began suction during the
procedure, he realized he was drawing too much fluid and stopped.
He ob served the woman for the rest of the day, then sent her home
with antibiotics. She delivered the baby hours later.
</P>
<P>
   The board faulted Biskind for misdiagnosing the pregnancy and
sending the woman home instead of to a hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Maricopa County Attorney Rick Romley said that he had not heard
of the 1990 case but that his office would look into it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course that would be rele vant to our investigation. We
would want to look at the pattern of his practice,'' Romley said
from his home Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Romley added that he has heard from officials and citizens all
over the country but won't let the politics of the case determine
whether he charges Biskind with a crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key, we feel, to this one, is just to keep it as objective
as possible,'' Romley said.
</P>
<P>
   No one from the medical board could be reached for comment
Saturday. A woman who answered an Ohio number for Biskind said he
wasn't available, and a woman who answered the phone at the A-Z
clinic on Saturday refused to com ment.
</P>
<P>
   The clinic has also taken some shots from the medical board.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Moshe Hachamovitch, the president of the A-Z Women's Center,
in 1992 received a letter of concern from the board for failing to
adequately document the age of a fetus.
</P>
<P>
   The board also issued a letter of concern in 1991 for failure to
file fetal death certificates. No other details were available
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Records show Hachamovitch has medical licenses in Texas, Massa
chusetts and Pennsylvania as well as in Arizona. He had a license
in Nevada, but it was suspended be cause he did not renew it, the
board there said.
</P>
<P>
   The case that sparked the current firestorm took place on June
30, when Biskind delivered a 6-pound, 2-ounce girl while performing
an abortion on what he thought was a 23-week-old fetus, police
said.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the child suffered skull fractures and deep
lacerations from the procedure. She shows no signs of brain damage
and will be adopted by a Texas couple, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The medical board has reportedly asked witnesses for sworn
testimony and documents and is considering holding an emergency
hearing to revoke Biskind's license.
</P>
<P>
   It is illegal, under Arizona law, to perform an abortion on a
viable fetus, unless it is ``necessary to preserve the life or
health of the woman.'' The statue says a doctor needs to have a
written statement justifying such a procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Records show Biskind has per formed two abortions on Arizona
women who bled to death. He was censured in 1995 for one death, and
the medical board is still investigat ing the other, which occurred
in April.
</P>
<P>
   Biskind graduated from an Ohio medical school in 1954 and still
holds a license in that state. A spokesman for the board there
refused to say whether or not Ohio officials were investigating the
doc tor.
</P>
<P>
   He also holds a California li cense. Officials in that state
said they are taking no disciplinary action against him. &QL; 
 &UR; Republic writer Heather Ratcliffe contrib
 &UR; uted to this article. &QL; 
 &UR; Richard Ruelas can be reached at
 &UR; 444-8473 or at richard.ruelas &LR; pni.com via
 &UR; e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
