<HEADER>
A0979 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-MCHALE-LADN     07-12 1516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-MCHALE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LABOR KEY TO SELIG'S FUTURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bud Selig was criticized for being indecisive during his six
years as acting commissioner of baseball. Now that he has accepted
the job full-time, Selig's legacy will come down to one issue:
labor peace.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly there are other problems _ interleague play,
realignment, revenue sharing. But baseball was devastated by the
1994 job action and knows it cannot absorb another financial and
public-relations pounding.
</P>
<P>
   No longer is the question how Selig, who owns the Milwaukee
Brewers, can provide an even hand in baseball matters when he
answers to other owners. Too many teams took a hit during the
strike to let that happen again.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a lot more contact and cooperation,'' said
Donald Fehr, director of the Major League Players Association.
``Memories are still sharp enough to make everyone a little
cautious, but I certainly think there's a much greater possibility
of a better relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he will spend most of his time in Milwaukee, Selig has
savvy major-league president Paul Beeston working the room in New
York. Beeston is the former president of the Toronto Blue Jays, who
appeared at one time to be a front-runner for the job Selig now
has.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do not underestimate the presence of Paul Beeston in the
future of baseball,'' Yankees owner George Steinbrenner said.
</P>
<P>
   Selig's best ally, however, might be baseball itself. Fans are
turned on by the home run chases and thinking much more about the
possibility of players they know breaking Roger Maris'
single-season record.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, there is only one decent division race, although Tom
Lasorda would beg to differ. But with four players and possibly
more taking a swing at Maris' mark, late-season attendance could
stay strong. Mark McGwire's St. Louis Cardinals are well out of the
NL Central race, but most of September is sold out at Busch
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   THE UNTOUCHABLES
</P>
<P>
   There appear to be only three players who the Orioles would be
absolutely unwilling to trade: Mike Mussina, Scott Erickson and Cal
Ripken. B.J. Surhoff probably is untouchable, too, but he remains
unsigned for next year. He is very well-liked in the organization.
</P>
<P>
   Closer Armando Benitez and left-hander Arthur Rhodes also would
be hard to acquire. Everyone else is available.
</P>
<P>
   First baseman Rafael Palmeiro would figure to be next in line
behind Roberto Alomar leaving Baltimore unless progress is made
toward a contract extension.
</P>
<P>
   After being cool on signing Palmeiro all season, the Orioles are
looking at his recent hot streak and now talking with agent Jim
Bronner. Predicted price: Four years at $35 million.
</P>
<P>
   Entering Saturday, Palmeiro is batting .327 with 11 homers and
27 RBI in his past 26 games. Despite the production, Palmeiro might
not find much of a market at the end of the season. There are a lot
of teams with power-hitting first basemen.
</P>
<P>
   It could be hard to get five years at $10 million per out there,
but you never know. Last year, the Red Sox gave Pedro Martinez $75
million when no team had awarded a contract for more than $60
million to that point.
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles, however, might find themselves in a philosophical
bind. They have had an unwritten rule that no one can make more
than Ripken, who is earning $7 million this season. Baltimore might
have to pay Palmeiro $8.5 million per year to keep him.
</P>
<P>
   SPEAKING OF PEDRO
</P>
<P>
   Martinez improved to 11-2, holding his ex-team, Montreal, and
the pitcher for whom he was traded, Carl Pavano, to two hits over
six innings in a 15-0 win recently. Martinez said he's happy in his
first season in Boston, but not as happy as he could be. ``I'm not
as happy as I thought I was going to be,'' Martinez told a group of
reporters, the majority of them members of the Montreal media. ``I
have a great team behind me. I'm playing for a great town _ a
little bit pushy sometimes _ very pushy sometimes,'' he said. ``I'm
doing my job. I'm having fun with the team. But I thought it was
going to be a bit different in some ways. But I'm not concerned.
I'm not regretting it. I'm fine here.''
</P>
<P>
   Come again?
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some personal things _ personal life off the field _
that's a little bit hard for me,'' he said. ``I'm used to a little
bit more privacy. It's a little hard.... I wouldn't say (Boston) is
difficult to live in. Boston is a very polite city. At least where
I live (Cambridge).''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez declined to get specific but indicated the intensity of
the fans is more than he anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I didn't expect was to have it in every game I stepped
out there,'' Martinez said. ``That was kind of a little surprise. I
thought they would understand that in some games I would have to
give it up and some games would go wrong. They don't take any of
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're very demanding. Believe me, the first ones to let you
know will be them. I hope that I can have every game from now on
(be) a nine-inning perfect game, where I can please everybody. But
I know it's not going to be that way, so I'm ready for my little
boos whenever I give up more than three (runs).''
</P>
<P>
   It was suggested that Martinez should not take the scrutiny so
personally _ that most fans ``love'' Pedro.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't say that,'' Martinez said. ``They `love' me only
until I screw it up out there. You have to go out there and give it
up and see how much they love you. I think they love me when I'm
doing my job. If I'm not doing my job, they don't love me nothing.
It's the way the fans are here. Bill Buckner cannot step in Boston.
He can't come back to Boston. They hate him forever.... It's going
to be hard for a city like this that eats and sleeps baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   THE CLASS OF '98
</P>
<P>
   Oakland's Ben Grieve, the most impressive offensive rookie in
the American League this year (.311, 12 homers, 55 RBI), and Tampa
Bay pitcher Rolando Arrojo (10-5, 3.06) were the only ones to make
the All-Star team from this year's potent rookie class.
</P>
<P>
   But Grieve, 22, and Arrojo, 29, are likely to have company in
the future.
</P>
<P>
   The rookie class of '98 also includes such talents as the Reds'
Sean Casey, Mike Frank and Paul Konerko, Detroit third baseman Gabe
Alvarez and fire-balling reliever Matt Anderson, Dodgers third
baseman Adrian Beltre, Arizona first baseman Travis Lee, Colorado
first baseman Todd Helton, Florida first baseman Derek Lee, Chicago
White Sox outfielder Magglio Ordonez and Chicago Cubs pitcher Kerry
Wood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played against most of those guys in the minors,'' Grieve
said. ``It's nice to watch and see how they're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all those youngsters are playing well right now, but they're
all expected to put up big numbers. The question: Will this go down
as one of the best recent rookie classes?
</P>
<P>
   ``It just depends how everyone does,'' Grieve said. ``If Kerry
Wood lives up to everything, it'll be remembered just for him.''
</P>
<P>
   DON'T TINKER WITH BELLE
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox's Albert Belle said last week he will use his
no-trade clause to scuttle any potential trades.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told (manager) Jerry Manuel, `I'm going down with the ship,'
'' Belle said. ``I made a choice to play for the Sox, and I'll do
that until the end of the contract.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem? Belle's contract has a no-trade clause only through
1998. Belle can be traded after this season. He also needs only one
more player to sign a long-term contract (three years or more)
worth $11 million a year and he can demand the last-place White Sox
give him a raise or let him become a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Belle says he'll try to make the best of this miserable
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty much (resigned to) suffering through this year,''
he said. ``I wasn't really projecting a rebuilding process, but
you've probably got to give it three years. You have to find guys
and run them out every day and let them learn from experience.''
</P>
<P>
   FIRST AND LAST?
</P>
<P>
   Omar Vizquel said Tuesday's All-Star game might be his ``first
and last'' since young shortstops Alex Rodriguez, Derek Jeter and
Nomar Garciaparra figure to dominate the league for years.
</P>
<P>
   So Vizquel wanted to make his trip special. He brought a video
camera with him and filmed his own highlight film.
</P>
<P>
   When he got into the cab at the Denver Airport, he turned the
camera on and interviewed the driver. ``I asked him, `What do you
think of Omar Vizquel?' He said, `Who is that?' I was having a
ball. I knew he'd have no clue.''
</P>
<P>
   Vizquel interviewed his AL teammates during the home run hitting
contest. He filmed manager Mike Hargrove talking during a team
meeting. He filmed the front desk of the hotel when he was checking
in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a ball,'' said Vizquel, who went 1 for 2 and started a
neat double play to get the AL out of trouble in the eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   When asked why he picked Vizquel over Garciaparra, Hargrove
said, ``To me, he's the best shortstop to ever play the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Vizquel, ``That was nice. He's seen me for five years. Him
saying that overwhelmed me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-98 0133EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
