</HEADER>
<BODY>
 600 DARE TO RUN WITH THE BULLS  
 (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK SHAFFER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MESQUITE, Nev. _ The testosterone-charged crowd of young males
had been drinking for hours, some for days, in anticipation of the
big moment when man would finally run with bull on U.S. soil.
</P>
<P>
   The samba beat emanating from the loudspeakers at Oasis Ranch
gave way to more than 100 decibels of Van Halen's ``Running With
the Devil.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good day to DIE, huh?'' screamed promoter Phil
Immordino into the microphone.
</P>
<P>
   That was greeted with a roar as hundreds of clenched fists
pumped skyward into Saturday's broiling desert air.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me at them,'' gushed one bearded man who was seen minutes
before taunting the penned cattle, prodding one animal &UR; that had
3-foot horns to charge into the corral siding. He took one final
gulp of beer and headed off for the starting line.
</P>
<P>
   With all the formalities out of the way, about 600 entrants got
their adrenaline flowing in a big way.
</P>
<P>
   At least, those who tried to run with the bulls straight down
the 40-foot-wide corridor over a quarter-mile course. The bulls had
been conditioned for a month to sprinting down the corridor, for
which they received generous amounts of hay in a corral near the
finish line.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the bull-running In the first heat, 12 bulls were
released at the same time. Only a handful of runners felt the need
to evade them by climbing the retaining fence.
</P>
<P>
   In the second heat, the promoters of Running of the Bulls
America Inc. mixed it up a bit by turning loose three different
groups, seven bulls at a time, which caught many of the runners off
guard.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the heats, a man zigged to the middle, right in front
of the second group of animals, and got trampled underfoot near the
midpoint of the run. The unidentified man suffered possible broken
ribs and numerous cuts and bruises. He was treated and released at
a Mesquite clinic, run promoters said.
</P>
<P>
   Another group of about a dozen people fell in a pile and a cloud
of dust, but the bulls ran around them. In all, three participants
were hospitalized or treated at the scene for injuries. Forty-one
spectators had to be treated for heat-related illnesses,
authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had us at their mercy,'' said Craig Williams, a Las Vegas
disc jockey, who was a wearing a hard hat with a camera lens taped
to the top of it. ``We were all down on the ground. It should make
great video.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams said he is very fortunate that the bulls weren't of the
fierce Iberian breeds that are used in the Running of the Bulls in
Pamplona, Spain, which this event was modeled after. Organizers
used a cross of Brahman and Angus breeds, which see service on the
rodeo circuits. Runners said that none of the bulls actually
charged after them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bulls looked like they were afraid of us,'' said Chris
Wahl of Las Vegas, who was near the release point on the first run.
``They went back in the pen and had to be prodded out by the
cowboys. They really weren't any problem in getting out of the way
since when they finally did get going they made a beeline to the
feed area.''
</P>
<P>
   John Ingalls of Las Vegas, at 66 the oldest man in the race,
said the fact that he has lost more than a few steps almost cost
him big time.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a group of five bulls that went right by me and I
got a touch out of one of them,'' said Ingalls, who said he
competes in marathons and runs 10 miles a day. ``It was a little
too close for comfort. But this is definitely a day I will never
forget.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the bull-running event, Mohave County deputies
arrested Immordino, who organized the event.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities tried to cite Immordino, 40, of Phoenix, for failing
to obtain a use permit for the special event, a misdemeanor.
Immordino refused to sign the citation and was booked into jail in
Mesquite, Nev., police said.
</P>
<P>
   Members of animal rights groups who monitored the event said
running with the bulls is something they would like to forget. They
said they hope that it doesn't increase in popularity. Event
organizers and Mohave County sheriff's deputies estimated that
about 6,000 people attended the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``This thing was just ridiculous. It's for thrill seekers who
must really have boring lives,'' said Jane Garrison of People for
the Ethical Treatment of Animals. ``But at least they didn't use
electrical shock on the bulls when they were so terrified of the
crowd at first.''
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Pacelle of the Humane Society said the bull run is far
from the cruelest thing involving animals that he has witnessed but
``it's definitely the stupidest thing I've seen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At least in Pamplona, there's a tradition attached to it,''
Pacelle said. ``Here, this thing is pure hucksterism.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mike Lansford, a co-promoter of the event, said that
Mesquite's Running of the Bulls won't be going away any time soon.
He said Lansford said his group signed a five-year contract with
Mesquite and plans to honor it. &QL; 
 &UR; Mark Shaffer can be reached at 444-8057 or at mark.shaffer &LR; pni.com
via
 &UR; e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
