<HEADER>
A0981 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN     07-12 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PADRES BEAT DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARC J. SPEARS  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ After the boys in Dodger blue became frustrated
with the men in blue, they never found a way to recover.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night's game against San Diego wasn't even two innings
old before Bobby Bonilla was thrown out after his teammates had
previously showed some frustration with the umpires. And while the
Dodgers lost their cool, the National League West Division-leading
Padres stayed calm during a 4-1 win in front of 48,950 at Dodger
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The loss snapped a two-game winning streak for the Dodgers and
pushed them 12{ games behind the Padres.
</P>
<P>
   The umpires began to made their presence known to the Dodgers in
the first inning. The Dodgers thought San Diego leadoff hitter
Steve Finley was out after Eric Karros went wide to pick up his
ground ball and feed it to Ismail Valdes getting over to first base
late. First base umpire Angel Hernandez, however, thought
differently to Valdes' chagrin.
</P>
<P>
   One out later, Ken Caminiti overran first after a single and
Eric Young thought he caught the Padre napping with the relay
throw. Again, Hernandez disagreed and Young showed his
disappointment by saying something to the umpire and then staring
at him.
</P>
<P>
   After Greg Vaughn walked to load the bases, Wally Joyner hit a
grounder to rookie third baseman Adrian Beltre. In trying to get
the easy force at home, Beltre tossed a high throw that tipped off
the top of catcher Charles Johnson's glove and two runs scored to
give San Diego a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried my best to stay on the plate, but the ball just
flipped out of my glove,' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers cut the deficit in half when Karros hit a one-out
homer off All-Star Andy Ashby in the second inning. Karros, who had
only three extra base hits in his previous 51 at-bats, reached just
the nine home run mark this season when he hit the ball into the
left field seats.
</P>
<P>
   But right when the Dodgers seemed to be on their way back, a
very questionable call ruined the momentum and sent Bonilla to the
showers. Following Karros' home run, the left-handed batting
Bonilla became livid when home plate umpire Bill Hohn called a
second strike on a pitch that appeared to be about a foot outside.
After they exchanged words, Hohn threw Bonilla out of the game.
</P>
<P>
   The disgruntled Bonilla then met Hohn face to face before being
restrained by manager Glenn Hoffman. While Hoffman was arguing with
Bonilla, three Dodgers coaches had to restrain him from getting to
Hohn. As he departed, Bonilla tossed his shin-guard a few feet
short of Hohn and then threw some catcher shin-guards on to the
field when he was in the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey guys, write what you saw,' a much calmer Bonilla dressed
in street clothes told reporters outside the Dodgers clubhouse
before visiting with his family.
</P>
<P>
   Hohn declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby was upset,'' said Hoffman. ``I just tried to keep them
apart. It was over the called strikes. I was glad to see (coaches
Mike) Scioscia and (Mickey) Hatcher out there. Bonilla's a strong
guy.'
</P>
<P>
   From then on, the Dodgers never seemed to locate any type of
spark and went the remainder of the game scoreless.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres took a 3-1 lead in the fifth when Finley's RBI single
off Valdes scored Chris Gomez. And in the sixth, the Padres went up
4-1 on a Joyner RBI double off Valdes that scored Greg Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes (6-9) lost his second straight game and allowed four runs
(three earned) on six hits in six innings. The right-hander, who
dropped to 4-2 at home this season, is just 2-4 in his last nine
starts.
</P>
<P>
   Ashby was superb as he allowed just Karros' homer, four hits and
struck out four in eight innings. And after Ashby left, he was
followed by All-Star closer Trevor Hoffman, the younger brother of
the Dodgers' manager.
</P>
<P>
   The NL save leader finished off his sibling's squad by striking
out three of the four batters to earn save No. 26.
</P>
<P>
   The game also fittingly ended with Hohn calling Karros out
looking at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to pick him apart to see if I could tip his
pitches,'' said the elder Hoffman about his brother. ``I haven't
seen him up close in a long time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
