them ill on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The family was treated at a hospital and released within about
two hours, but Israeli health officials found about 15 bottles from
the same store that smelled of paint thinner.
</P>
<P>
   Officials believe the bottles were stored near paint products
which corroded the plastic and soaked into the drink.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli Health Ministry Friday said the soft drink was safe,
but another consumer at a different store later complained of a
foul-smelling bottle. It is not clear whether or not the consumer
became sick from the soft drink.
</P>
<P>
   That resulted in the ministry Saturday advising consumers to
smell the family-sized bottles before drinking -- advice that made
the front pages of local newspapers. In addition, an Israeli
consumer group called on consumers not to buy the soft drink until
the end of a health ministry investigation.
</P>
<P>
   By Sunday afternoon, the health ministry released a statement
saying that Coca-Cola was safe to drink. And a health official, on
Israeli television, acknowledged the confusion surrounding the
ministry's advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``In any case, it's not the Coca-Cola plant,'' said Yair
Nechmad, marketing manager for Central Bottling, the Israeli
Coca-Cola bottler.
</P>
<P>
   Nechmad said the cause of the second incident was not yet known,
but the traces of foreign chemicals in the soft drink were lower
than standards approved for drinking water.
</P>
<P>
   The company sells about 300 million of the 1.5 liter bottles a
year in Israel, a country of just 6 million people.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola has enjoyed a favored status here. It continued
selling in Israel throughout the years that Arab countries
boycotted companies doing business in a country they refused to
recognize. Now, the boycott is over and both Coca-Cola, and rival
Pepsi, products are on the market.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
