<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-COKE _ JERUSALEM _ Is it the real thing? That's what a
Coca-Cola bottler here is trying to determine. The bottler urged
Israelis on Sunday to ``drink without fear'' despite the recall of
100,000 bottles following the discovery of chemical traces in the
soft drink in two towns. Central Bottling Co Inc began removing the
1-1/2-litre bottles of Coke from shops last week and Israel's
Health Ministry urged the public on Saturday to sniff-test the
bottles for possible contamination. The Israeli bottler insisted
its products and factories were safe. Moshe Wertheim, president of
Central Bottling, told army radio that an investigation would
determine whether the chemicals had seeped through the plastic
bottles because of improper storage or care. He said police were
also investigating the cause. (Kaplow, Cox News Service). EDs: To
move by 3 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   SHARKS _ WASHINGTON _ Failure by Gulf and Atlantic Ocean states
to enact regulations is undermining federal protection of
endangered sharks, the Ocean Wildlife Campaign reported Monday.
(Shook, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Eds: MOVED Friday for release Monday, July 13.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   FLAFIRES-LOOKBACK _ In 1989, state foresters visited the woody
lots of Palm Coast and asked its residents: exactly how afraid of
wildfire are you? Going door to door, they handed out 200 surveys
to homes most likely to burn if a blaze broke out. Only 94 bothered
to answer. The survey came just four years after a deadly wildfire
season killed two firefighters, burned 443,816 acres and destroyed
131 houses in Palm Coast, a subdivision carved out of forests in
rural Flagler County. Less than half quizzed even knew about the
fires. So is there a lesson to be learned here? (Staletovich, Palm
Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   RYANWHITE _ POMPANO BEACH, Fla. _ Jeanne White knuckled a
teardrop from her cheek as she spoke about greed and exploitation.
``They called me greedy, but their homes would buy ten of mine,''
she said. ``There's nobody more greedy than the Steiners.'' White
believes that Joel Steinger and his brother Steven Steiner (who
altered his name) live in ocean-front homes and drive new Mercedes
Benz sedans because they capitalized on the familiar name of her
late teenage son, Ryan White. (Kane, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   NAACP-SPOTLIGHT _ ATLANTA _ Religion's role in civil rights
movement today (e.g. how receptive religious leades are to NAACP's
efforts to mobilize mass religious support for voter registration
and political action campaigns for civil rights legislation, and to
spearhead effective letter-writing campaigns to elected official
representatives, etc.) and how effective politically they are.
(Blake, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 20-30.
</P>
<P>
   NAACP-AIDS _ An ``Outrage over AIDS: A walk for action'' was
held Saturday in Atlanta in conjunction with the NAACP convention.
This is pretty signficant for a major African-American organization
to be organizing this, because historically, the black community
has not been proactive in prevention efforts. (Brett, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   NAACP-NOTES13 _ ATLANTA _ Convention notebook of highlights,
including awards. art. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 10-15.
</P>
<P>
   NAACP-DAY _ ATLANTA _ The best of what's happened during the
day's events. (Oglesby, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   PROSPERITY-POLL _ Most of us are better off, but few of us are
frivolously spending our money, vacationing in the Riviera or even
flying off to Vegas in the middle of the night. Results of DDN
poll. (Dempsey, Dayton Daily News).
</P>
<P>
   PROSPERITY-PROFILE _ Three years ago Glenn McGee was young,
uneducated and homeless. In June he graduated from Sinclair
Community College and is headed for a job at a machine shop. McGee
has taken advantage of the demand for skilled labor in this
economy. (Dempsey, Dayton Daily News).
</P>
<P>
   PROSPERITY-JOBS _ Dayton's economy was one of the strongest in
the nation in the 50s and 60s, and it was largely an economy built
on blue-coller work. Today, jobs that can pay as much as $50,000 a
year after a two year apprenticeship are going begging. (Dempsey,
Dayton Daily News).
</P>
<P>
   GAGOV-BARNES _ Profile of Roy Barnes, Democratic candidate for
Georgia governor. First of such profiles. (Walston, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   GAGOV-BOWERS _ Profile of Mike Bowers, Republican candidate for
Georgia governor. First of such profiles. (Pruitt, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT
</P>
<P>
   NBAF _ ATLANTA _ Coverage of opening weekend of National Black
Arts festival, which runs through July 19. Crowd sights and sounds,
with critical overview. Festivalgoer quotes. (Dollar, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TV-SURFER _ From California, updates on coming new fall season
from the TV critics meeting. (Harris, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
ETA: 9 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   EDS: The following enterprise stories moved earlier in the week
and are still good for Monday use.
</P>
<P>
   US-RUSSIA _ MOSCOW _ U.S. President Bill Clinton and Russian
President Boris Yeltsin had made no secret over the last several
months that they would like to have a summit in the fall. As
Clinton wound down his long trip to China, the word began spreading
that he was leaning toward just such a meeting. After confirming it
on Monday, the White House can expect a wave of criticism from
opponents near the level it received before the China trip. There's
plenty of ammunition: the sickly Russian economy; Kosovo upheaval;
India-Pakistan nuclear race; trade with Iran; NATO expansion; and
space cooperation. Clinton had been awaiting Russia's Parliament to
ratify the SALT II nuclear arms pact, but his decision to go seems
to be aimed at pressuring the Duma into such a ratification vote.
(Holmes, Cox News Service). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   With US-RUSSIA-BOX _ The issues facing a Clinton-Yeltsin summit.
(Holmes, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-BACKLASH _ TEHRAN, Iran _ Iran's conservatives are fighting
back. A year after the election of the moderate but not powerful
President Mohammed Khatami, concerned fundamentalists have arrested
and impeached key supporters. The political climate seems to swing
daily between reform and backlash. (Kaplow, Cox News Service).
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   JOURNAL-IRAN _ TEHRAN, Iran _ These are nervous times in Tehran.
I could sense the difference from my last trip in December, when
reformers were gleeful about the prospects for changing their
fundamentalist nation under newly-elected President Mohammed
Khatami. Now, reformers are channel surfing between World Cup
soccer games and the trial of a popular mayor, accused of
corruption by a justice system run by religious hardliners. Though
Tehran is full of articulate, informed people with a lot to say,
slightly fewer wanted to be quoted this time. The day after
watching a World Cup match with a group of young Iranians, one
called and asked that I not tell anyone I was with them. These
days, hanging out with foreign journalists can be controversial,
especially if the evening in question included cassettes of Western
dance music. (Kaplow, Cox News Service). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   NEWDEMS _ From millionaire Michael Coles in Georgia to noted
trial lawyer John Edwards in North Carolina, Democrats in the South
are betting on a crop of ``New Democrats'' to help them reclaim
lost territory in the old
</P>
<P>
   Confederacy. (Foskett, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   APRIL-OLIVER _ WASHINGTON _ Her career has been spent behind the
cameras, but her highly public firing by CNN has thrust April
Oliver into the media spotlight. The 8 1/2-month-pregnant Oliver
now spends her days trying to persuade the journalism world that
her firing was unjustified and her story about the U.S. military
using nerve gas to kill defectors in Southeast Asia is true. (Dart,
Cox News Service). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NIH _ WASHINGTON _ In the middle of fights over campaign
finances, tobacco legislation and other bones of contention,
President Clinton, House Speaker Newt Gingrich, the Senate
Republican leaders and congressional Democrats all agree on a
fairly major initiative: that the research budget of the National
Institutes of Health should be dramatically increased, even doubled
over the next decade. To officials at Emory University in Atlanta,
which hopes to propel itself into one of the top 10 research
institutions in the country during that time, this is welcome news.
(Nesmith, Cox News Service 1250) MOVED.
</P>
