<P>
   CUBA-COMMANDO (Miami) _ As Luis Posada Carriles nears the end of
his career as the most notorious commando in the anti-Castro
underground, he details for the first time his 37-year relationship
with exile leaders in the United States and with the American
authorities. By Larry Rohter and Louise Bardach.
</P>
<P>
   SMALLARMS-CONTROL (Oslo, Norway) _ In what diplomats say is the
first endeavor of its kind, the United States and 20 other
governments will gather here on Monday to grapple with how to stop
the spread of assault rifles, pistols, hand grenades, mortars and
other small arms. By Raymond Bonner.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-IMF (Moscow) _ From wires: Russia on Sunday announced
that it had secured a massive bail-out loan from the International
Monetary Fund aimed at saving the country's troubled economy from
collapse. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-ELECTION (Tokyo) _ From wires: Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto hinted he was ready to resign after voters, angry about
Japan's economic woes, handed his Liberal Democrats an embarrassing
setback on Sunday in parliamentary elections. By Nicholas D.
Kristof.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-POLITICS (Tokyo) _ A look at some possible successors to
Hashimoto. By Nicholas D. Kristof.
</P>
<P>
   KOREA-ALERT (Tokyo) _ South Korean military commanders put
troops on the country's eastern coast on alert and declared a
curfew in the area after finding the body of a diver whom they said
was a North Korean commando. By Nicholas D. Kristof.
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-UNREST (Belfast) _ Three Catholic children are burned
to death in a sectarian arson attack. By James F. Clarity.
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA-RDP (Lagos) _ Developments after Abiola's funeral.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   OILFIELD-WASTE-SUIT (Grand Bois, La.) _ Four years ago, an
oilfield dump in the hamlet of Grand Bois in the Louisiana bayou
accepted a big shipment of sludge from Exxon. Like all oilfield
waste, it's toxic. But Congress has exempted the oil industry from
the usual precautions required of most other industries involved in
hazardous waste disposal. Many of the 350 residents of the town
started getting sick; now they have filed suit against Exxon and
the owners of the dump. Jury selection in the case begins on
Monday. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   USAF-PILOT-TRAINING (Mountain Home, Idaho) _ The U.S. Air Force
is scrambling to find or expand the airspace and bombing ranges it
says it needs to train pilots. But the plans are running into
fierce opposition from ranchers, environmentalists, commercial
airlines and people settling in fast-growing metropolitan centers,
especially out West. In the post-Cold War era, fewer people are
willing to tolerate the military's low-flying planes and sonic
booms.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-TALKS (Flint, Mich.) _ Developments in the GM-UAW
negotiations. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Coded w)
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS-INCUMBENCY (Washington) _ For years, political
ad-makers played down Washington and incumbency. But this election
season, incumbency is in vogue. An examination of hundreds of
advertisements broadcast thus far show that more than anything
else, Democrats and Republicans are using words like ``experience''
and ``record'' in their scripts and citing specific bills they
passed. Some ads even feature the majestic Capitol dome that for so
many years was viewed as too regal. The ads are the best evidence
thus far of a dramatically changed political climate this year. By
Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   COLUMNS
</P>
