<P>
   GEOCITIES (Undated) _ Geocities is the most with the least. It
has shot up to be one of the top-rated Web sites in the world, with
1.9 million people creating home pages. Yet so far its revenue is
microscopic, $4 million last year. Of course, that isn't stopping
Geocities from going public. The story will look at the financial
questions about the company's business and the broader question of
what is this online community phenomenon? By Saul Hansell
</P>
<P>
   BIGSIX-SOFTWARE (Undated) _ Ernst &AMP; Young, like all of the ``Big
Six'' accounting firms, has plunged into the lucrative business of
installing the complex software packages that become the nervous
systems of today's companies. But the software work, which has
quickly bloomed into a multi-billion-dollar business for the
accountants, has raised concerns among federal regulators that
auditors could forget their main duty of being a watchdog for
investors in their quest for profit.
</P>
<P>
   IBM-WATSON-LABS (Undated) _ A look at IBM's Watson Labs to
examine the larger issue of how ideas are generated in high-tech
labs and the challenge of taking them into the marketplace. By
Steve Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   STREAMING-SOFTWARE (Undated) _ The streaming technology that
allows music and video to be sent over the Internet to personal
computers is still a curiosity as a medium and a puzzle as a
business. But Real Networks Inc., the leader in streaming software,
is making announcements on Monday that represent steps toward
developing both the medium and its business model further, industry
analysts say. By Steve Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   DEUTSCHEBANK-U.S. (Frankfurt, Germany) _ Deutsche Bank, reeling
from the recent defection by several top investment bankers, is
looking to buy or team up with an American investment firm to shore
up its position. By Edmund L. Andrews.
