u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RYANWHITE-COX     07-12 1173
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RYANWHITE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jeanne White responds to greed allegations
 &HT;    By Gary Kane
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   POMPANO BEACH, Fla. _ Jeanne White knuckled a teardrop from her
cheek as she spoke about greed and exploitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They called me greedy, but their homes would buy ten of
mine,'' she said. ``There's nobody more greedy than the Steiners.''
</P>
<P>
   White believes that Joel Steinger and his brother Steven Steiner
(who altered his name) live in ocean-front homes and drive new
Mercedes Benz sedans because they capitalized on the familiar name
of her late teenage son. Ryan White became a young hero during his
struggle to attend school though diagnosed with the human
immunodeficiency virus. He died in 1990 at the age of 18.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a year, the Steinger brothers evoked the name Ryan
White to solicit cash from good-hearted people and HIV medications
from charitable pharmaceutical companies. They used the image of
the sandy-haired teen in pamphlets and on their internet site.
</P>
<P>
   The brothers promoted their Ryan White Foundation for Medical
Treatment as a new hope for those who couldn't afford the costly
treatments that combat the virus.
</P>
<P>
   They created the foundation to help those treated at Community
Healthcare of Broward, a non-profit clinic founded in 1996 by
Steiner and a few associates. The clinic featured an in-house
pharmacy, Commcare, a for-profit business started by Steinger and a
few backers.
</P>
<P>
   Foundation money paid for medications provided by Commcare to
the clinic's patients, according to Steiner.
</P>
<P>
   A Palm Beach Post investigation revealed last month that
Commcare generated large profits from one type of treatment when it
billed Medicaid and private insurers. The state agency for
Healthcare Administration, which oversees the program, is
investigating some of the pharmacy's bills.
</P>
<P>
   White responded by revoking the Steinger brothers' right to use
the Ryan White name.
</P>
<P>
   The brothers countered by telling area news reporters that they
had decided to drop the Ryan White name because Jeanne White
demanded a $150,000 salary, doubling her compensation. The
foundation had better uses for the money than to provide White a
fatter paycheck, they said.
</P>
<P>
   White felt stung by the remarks, particularly because she
thought of Steiner as a close friend.
</P>
<P>
   She had defended the brothers after The Post revealed in January
that they also worked in the viatical trade _ which promises
investors a profit when they buy into the life insurance policies
of AIDS patients and other terminally-ill people. She also had
overlooked the brothers' past business problems, including a
recently settled lawsuit that accused them of civil racketeering.
</P>
<P>
   To say that her salary demands prompted the Steingers to drop
the Ryan White name from their foundation was nothing but a
smokescreen, White said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the spin they're trying to put on this mess,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   White had indeed suggested that her $75,000 salary be doubled.
But she did so after the Steingers urged a merger of their
foundation with the Ryan White Foundation, the Indiana organization
she founded in 1990 with the help of television celebrity Phil
Donahue.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was going to double my work, I felt I should be
compensated,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Indiana foundation hesitated to move toward a merger
(underscored by the fact that there was never even a link between
the two foundations' web sites on the internet). The proposal
aroused suspicions. After all, the Steinger brothers' foundation
had been using the Ryan White name for only a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of little flags went up,'' White recalled. ``My board
(in Indiana) was requesting a lot of things, like financial
information, and getting nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Indiana board wondered what the Florida foundation did with
its money, she said. Board members also were confused about
Commcare and who profited from its operation. Steiner eventually
produced an impressive financial report, White said. But it
prompted other questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wondered how Steven could live in such a big house and say
that he didn't take a salary,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Steiner co-owns a home with his friend Henry Fecker III
that sold for $530,000 in 1996. His brother Joel, whose name seldom
appears on financial documents, lives in a beach-front home owned
by the Oceanfront Revocable Trust. The trustee is Michael McNerney,
an attorney who represented the brothers' foundation, clinic and
viatical business. The home sold for $617,500 in 1996, according to
Broward County records.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, White was often troubled by the brothers' criticism
of the Indiana foundation and their obsession with raising money.
</P>
<P>
   ``They pitched a story about how much money there is out
there,'' she said. ``I think money is the only thing the Steiners
think about.''
</P>
<P>
   White said she was embarrassed by some of the methods used by
the Florida foundation to solicit support. Olympic champion Greg
Louganis and actress Judith Light, who played Jeanne White in the
television movie about Ryan, were among several celebrities angered
by letters they received from the foundation, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no idea they were sending out those letters. They were
using pressure tactics. I was very upset,'' White said.
</P>
<P>
   She also had to soothe the outrage of several prominent AIDS
researchers who learned that their names were being used in
magazine ads promoting the Community Healthcare of Broward clinic.
The researchers had agreed only to lend their names in support of
the foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Doing business with the Steingers seemed like a good idea when
she signed a contract with them in 1996, White said. They were
paying the Indiana foundation $5,000 a month for the right to use
the Ryan White name, she said. And the influx of cash was welcome.
The Indiana foundation had been struggling financially for the past
three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helped us a lot, although they didn't like paying the money
to us,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Florida group also offered the Ryan White Foundation a
chance to grow. The Indiana organization, which focuses on
educating youth about HIV, hoped to open offices in clinics the
Steingers planned to open nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made a lot of promises,'' Whites said. ``I was snowed a
lot of times.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, White planted a for-sale sign in the front lawn of
her Pompano Beach residence, a comfortable house with a backyard
pool overlooking the fleet of pleasure boats parked behind other
homes lining the nearby canal. She bought the home for $192,600 a
year ago after refinancing the family residence in Indiana, she
said. It allowed her to keep an eye on the Florida foundation, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   White doubts the Florida venture will damage the reputation of
the Ryan White Foundation in Indiana. But she views her experience
with the Steinger brothers as a painful lesson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very careful now about what I put my faith and trust in,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
