<HEADLINE>
ACCOUNTS AND PEOPLE IN THE ADVERTISING WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Barbara Eden, who played the mischievous genie on the
long-running TV series ``I Dream of Jeannie,'' is blinking her way
back onto television by appearing in commercials for Lexus and Old
Navy.
</P>
<P>
   The spot promoting the 1999 Lexus RX 300 for the Lexus division
of Toyota Motor Corp. is centered on a heavyset, scruffy
archeologist who discovers a bottle in the sand, then takes it with
him as he travels across the desert in a generic sport utility
vehicle. Ms. Eden, inside the bottle, is tossed and tumbled because
of the vehicle's poor ride, so she blinks and transforms the
generic model into an RX 300 _ and the driver into a handsome hunk.
The spot was created by Team One Advertising in El Segundo, Calif.,
part of Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi PLC.
</P>
<P>
   In the commercial for the Old Navy clothing chain, owned by Gap
Inc., Ms. Eden joins the Old Navy regulars _ Carrie Donovan, the
former fashion editor, and Magic the dog _ in a quirky tale set in
Morocco that includes snake charmers, jugglers, stilt walkers and
dancers. The spot was created in-house.
</P>
<P>
   Messner Vetere Wins Miramax Films Account
</P>
<P>
   Miramax Films has named Messner Vetere Berger McNamee
Schmetterer Euro RSCG in New York to handle its New York
advertising account, which includes print media buying with
billings estimated at $25 million as well as various creative
assignments. The media duties had been handled by Harvest
Communications in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Messner Vetere, part of Havas Advertising, was awarded the
account by Miramax, a unit of Walt Disney Co., after a two-month
review that also included Harvest and four other New York agencies:
Ammirati Puris Lintas, part of Interpublic Group of Cos.; Deutsch
Inc.; Partners &AMP; Shevack, part of Wolf Group, and Saatchi &AMP;
Saatchi, a unit of Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi PLC.
</P>
<P>
   Bates Announces Deal; ATC and IQI Merge
</P>
<P>
   Two agency deals have been announced.
</P>
<P>
   Bates Advertising USA in New York, a unit of Cordiant
Communications Group PLC, agreed to acquire Churchill Group Inc.,
an agency in Houston that specializes in business-to-business
public relations, advertising and research. Terms were not
disclosed. Churchill has 40 employees and fee income of more than
$5 million from clients like Exxon Chemical, Mobil, Shell and Time
Warner Cable.
</P>
<P>
   And ATC Communications Group in Dallas and IQI Inc. in Los
Angeles completed a merger to form Aegis Communications Group, an
integrated marketing services company. Terms were not disclosed.
Aegis will have more than 8,500 employees and revenue estimated at
$250 million from clients like AT&AMP;T and American Express. Stephen
McNeely, chief executive of IQI, and Michael Santry, chairman and
chief executive at ATC, become co-chairmen of Aegis and McNeely
also becomes chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Accounts
</P>
<P>
   --Red Robin International Inc., Englewood, Colo., to McClain
Finlon Advertising, Denver, and Linhart McClain Finlon Public
Relations, Denver, to handle the account of the casual dining
restaurant chain, which had been handled by Evans Group, Seattle,
now the Publicis unit of Publicis SA. Billings were estimated at $2
million to $3 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
