<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDIA TALK: JOURNALISTS' METHODS UNDER SCRUTINY; AUTHOR DECLARES
INDEPENDENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Maine, Ohio, Wash.)  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Who? What? When? Where? Why? These are the questions journalists
are trained to ask. But the question that continues to haunt
journalists who are hauled into court is ``How?'' How did the
journalist get the information? How did he or she approach sources?
What did the journalist say to the subjects of the story?
</P>
<P>
   Last week's verdict by a jury in Bangor, Maine, against a
producer and correspondent for the NBC News program Dateline NBC is
the latest in a string of setbacks for news organizations
challenged not on their accuracy but their methods.
</P>
<P>
   As of Friday, NBC News had made no decision about appealing the
$525,000 verdict awarded Wednesday by the jury in Bangor. The jury
agreed with a trucking company and one of its drivers that the
producer and correspondent for a ``Dateline NBC'' report on
long-haul trucking failed to live up to assurances that their
report would be positive.
</P>
<P>
   This brings to three the number of pending cases that turn not
on the accuracy of journalists' reports but on their methods.
``Journalists ought to take note of the way juries react, not only
because of the risk of damages, but because of what it says about
what the American public thinks about journalism these days,'' said
Floyd Abrams, the prominent lawyer and expert on the First
Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. District judge in Cincinnati is still considering a
charge of misrepresentation brought by the credit reporting firm
WDIA against Business Week. A Business Week reporter had filed a
form asking for information and _ although he said he worked for
Business Week _ also said his purpose in gaining the information
was related to ``employment'' concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question of a reporter's ethics was key,'' said John
Cobey, who represents WDIA in the suit, which is being brought
under the Fair Credit Reporting Act _ the very act whose
effectiveness the reporter was testing.
</P>
<P>
   The supermarket chain Food Lion won a jury verdict in 1996
against ABC News, whose producers had provided false information on
employment forms, then used hidden cameras to get video
documentation of shoddy food handling in one store. An appeal is
pending.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever comfort news organizations can take in this legal
climate comes from a federal judge who argued that it makes little
sense to trust a journalist's pitch. A 1995 ruling by Richard
Posner overturned elements of a lower court's finding that ABC was
guilty of fraud and trespass as a result of a Primetime Live
broadcast which sent test patients with concealed cameras into a
Chicago eye clinic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investigative journalists well known for ruthlessness promise
to wear kid gloves,'' Posner wrote. ``They break their promise, as
any person of normal sophistication would expect. If that is
`fraud,' it is the kind against which potential victims can easily
arm themselves by maintaining a minimum skepticism about
journalistic goals and methods.''
</P>
<P>
   Inspirational Author Founds Her Own Press
</P>
<P>
   Seeking more creative and financial control over her work, Betty
Eadie, a best-selling inspirational writer, has formed her own
press, Onjinjinkta Publishing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just seemed like the obvious next step to getting my books
out and getting them out the way I wanted them,'' Ms. Eadie said.
``Dealing with publishers isn't always so easy, and then they end
up owning your book. This is my life's work, and to be in control
of that is wonderful.'' Ms. Eadie's third book, ``The Ripple
Effect: Our Harvest,'' is due out in October, with a first printing
of 50,000 copies.
</P>
<P>
   But the house expects to go back to press several times based on
the performance of Ms. Eadie's previous two books, which have sold
more than 7 million copies combined. Her first book, a near-death
account titled ``Embraced by the Light,'' was published by Gold
Leaf Press, while the second book, ``The Awakening Heart: My
Continuing Journey to Love,'' was published by Pocket Books; it
reprises the near-death theme she sustains through her third book.
</P>
<P>
   Onjinjinkta, which is based in Seattle, also plans to publish
books by other inspirational authors, issuing four to six titles
per season. (Onjinjinkta means ``rose in bloom'' in the language of
Ms. Eadie's Lakota Sioux mother.)
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Eadie said she had been offered her own imprint by several
publishing houses, the type of arrangement recently accepted by the
author Sarah Ban Breathnach, who will run Simple Abundance Press at
Warner Books. But Ms. Eadie wanted still more autonomy than an
imprint would have afforded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even with your own imprint, you're working within their time
frame,'' she said. ``The work I'm doing requires my own time
frame.''
</P>
<P>
   Next February, Onjinjinkta is planning to release a book by a
first-time author, Roy Mills, titled ``The Soul's Remembrance.''
The book is about ``Mills' pre-birth life,'' according to Peter
Orullian, one of three editors at Onjinjinkta.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Onjinjinkta Enterprises, which Ms. Eadie started three
years before, bought the rights to the hardcover version of
``Embraced'' from Gold Leaf Press, and plans to release a new
edition around the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The success of feel-good books like the ``Chicken Soup for the
Soul'' series, which has sold 30 million copies, shows that the
inspirational market holds promise. But Ms. Eadie's faith in the
market comes less from figures, she said, than from ``the knowledge
I received during my near-death experience.''
</P>
</TEXT>
