<HEADER>
A1157 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRITISHOPEN-KUCHAR-CO     07-12 0645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITISHOPEN-KUCHAR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    British Open may be turning point for amateur champ
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTHPORT, England _ Matt Kuchar flies 4,100 miles to the 123rd
Open Championship at Royal Birkdale and signs as many autographs as
he might at The Varsity. Indeed, it could be a signature destined
for collectible status if this evolves as Kuchar's last major
championship as an amateur.
</P>
<P>
   Since the U.S. Open, where the U.S. Amateur champion from
Georgia Tech tied for 14th and seriously contended for a while,
it's become one of the biggest questions in golf: When will Kooch
take the loot? If you thought he's been smiling broadly to this
point, imagine the grins if a pile of money replaces a pile of
school books.
</P>
<P>
   The more Kuchar speaks about when he will turn pro, the more it
sounds like he's going soon. Quite possibly, before the U.S.
Amateur Aug. 24-30.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a chance to go after my dreams, to play pro golf and to
see how well I can do as a professional,'' Kuchar said Sunday after
a windblown practice round at Royal Birkdale. ''The time is right
for me to really chase that dream.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Kuchar has proven his worth in a tie for 21st at the
Masters, a tie for 14th at the U.S. Open and a new outdoor record
for most marketing-friendly smiles by an amateur. The only question
is whether Kuchar goes now or waits a little longer. Doubtfully,
though, could his marketability improve. As Vinnie Giles of Pros,
Inc., a contender for landing him, says, ''Barring something
phenomenal like winning the British Open, he's pretty close to his
apex right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Kuchar doesn't expect to match his other major
championship success at his first British Open, the questions are
sure to continue this week. Already, Kuchar has been tracked down
at the house where he and his parents, Peter and Meg, are staying.
Matt will remain overseas until the Palmer Cup the first week of
August to do some sightseeing, play some more famous courses and,
perhaps as an added bonus, be tougher to locate.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everybody wants to know, especially after the U.S. Open, 'When
is Matt turning pro? Is this the best time?''' Kuchar said. ''I'm
just split right now. I don't know what's going to happen. There's
so many positives for getting my degree and so many positives for
turning pro, it just seems like one doesn't outweigh the other
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The chief positive is fairly obvious and minimizes the
aggravation of calls or meetings with ''hundreds of agents.''
Millions are available for Kuchar in an endorsement package as soon
as he says the word. Sometimes it appears he's already made up his
mind.
</P>
<P>
   While his father/caddie, Peter, said, ''You can be rest assured
nothing will happen prior to the Palmer Cup (the first week of
August), asked whether there could be an announcement between then
and the U.S. Amateur (three weeks later), Peter said, ''Maybe
then.''
</P>
<P>
   While it no doubt bothers Kuchar that leaving Tech would damage
another shot at an NCAA title, nobody would blame him for going.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a chance to set myself financially for a long period of
time,'' Kuchar said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hopefully, it works out well enough where I will be set, that
this is the prime time for me to go and turn pro, and that sponsors
want me.''
</P>
<P>
   Kuchar sounds very much like a young man wanting it to be over.
Although dizzied about ''going from a no-name to where people know
me almost everywhere,'' some of the fun has been removed from his
game.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not really into it yet, dealing with agents,'' he said.
''It's flattering, but it's almost too much. Everybody has the same
promises they're making. It's been a battle as far as who wants to
do this and who wants to do that. It's been a lot to handle.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
