<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITISHOPEN-PARNEVIK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Parnevik thrives on disdain for convention
 &HT;    By Craig Dolch
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ In the game of life, Jesper Parnevik has
never aimed for the center of the fairway.
</P>
<P>
   That becomes obvious at first glance. With his retro-style
clothes and a flipped-up bicycle cap, Parnevik looks more like he's
from the '60s than someone who's trying to shoot in the 60s.
</P>
<P>
   And his sense of fashion is only the tip of his nonconformity.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a guy who believes in reincarnation, eats volcanic dust
to cleanse his system, has had his blood analyzed by radiation,
uses stroboscopic glasses, meditates as the sun rises over his
South Palm Beach home, has had his metal fillings replaced with
ceramic ones to reduce mercury levels and once drove to the wrong
city for a tournament.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder Jesper (it's pronounced Yes-per) is called Spaceman on
the PGA Tour. It's somehow consistent that Parnevik, the son of
Sweden's most famous comedian Bo Parnevik, doesn't seem to care
that everyone thinks he's a little goofy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any image is a good one,'' Parnevik said. ``Maybe there isn't
that much to write about in the golfing world. I don't mind at all.
If anyone can have fun on my behalf, I'm happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Lately, Parnevik has had another odd habit of almost winning the
British Open, which starts Thursday at Royal Birkdale. Twice in the
last four years, Parnevik has finished second in golf's oldest
major.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Parnevik had a two-shot lead on the 18th hole at
Turnberry _ until he did something silly. Thinking he was behind
instead of ahead, he tried to birdie the final hole and instead
made bogey. That enabled Jupiter Island's Nick Price to win the
claret jug after he eagled the 17th hole.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, Parnevik had to be devastated after he just failed to
win his favorite tournament, right? But that would have been the
normal response.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my first chance to win a major, but I didn't deserve it
yet,'' Parnevik said. ``It would have been too soon. Besides, in
the long run it's just your name on something, isn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   Parnevik also seemed poised to win last year's British Open at
Royal Troon when he took a two-shot lead into the final round. He
led for most of that Sunday, until Justin Leonard got hot on the
back nine and shot 65 to catch Parnevik (73) and win by three
shots.
</P>
<P>
   Parnevik said he was able to handle that defeat because he had
no illusion of winning when he showed up. In fact, he said his game
was in such disrepair when he arrived at Royal Troon that he had to
be thrown off the range the night before the first round because of
darkness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was almost in a state of panic because I didn't have any
game to turn up on Thursday with,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Parnevik somehow held his game together and shot a first-round
70, finishing with three consecutive birdies. So in a vintage
Parnevik move, he inexplicably changed putters and started the
second round with a three-putt.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, after shooting a pair of 66s, Parnevik had a two-shot lead
over Darren Clarke. But like in '94, he felt he was behind instead
of ahead because of a questionable swing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't explain how it feels to stand on the first tee with
about 15 different swing thoughts and you don't know where the ball
is going,'' Parnevik said. ``But even though I wasn't playing well,
I still thought I could shoot around par and win. That was probably
the toughest day I ever had on a golf course.''
</P>
<P>
   At least Parnevik, 33, can laugh at his disappointments, a trait
he acquired from his dad. Bo Parnevik not only taught his son
humor, he used him in his act when Jesper was young and growing up
in Stockholm, Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   The younger Parnevik thought he would follow into his dad's
profession until he was introduced to golf when he was 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then he stopped collecting jokes and started collecting golf
balls,'' Bo Parnevik said. Because the nearest golf course was 40
miles away, Bo helped his son learn the game by letting him hit
floatable balls in a lake behind their house.
</P>
<P>
   Even when Jesper stopped doing comedy, he still amused those
around him with his strange interests. Bo remembers when his son
became involved in music and put together an orchestra to go along
with his piano playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's always been interested in different things,'' Bo Parnevik
said. ``He was always a very curious boy.''
</P>
<P>
   Jesper didn't outgrow that trait, nor does he intend to. After
recently talking religion with fellow pro Bernhard Langer, he
immediately read the Bible and the Koran cover-to-cover.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am curious and I like to try different things,'' he said.
``But all those things started with a small thing and they have
been building up. You get really hooked on something and try it
out, but a few months later you don't want to do anything at all.
I've been quite normal the last couple of months.''
</P>
<P>
   The image of normalcy is confused by his unusual attire, the
stovepipe pants and the flipped-up lid he adopted while a student
at Palm Beach Junior College in Lake Worth, Fla., trying to get a
tan. He played well that day.
</P>
<P>
   His clothing continues to be a source of discussion on Tour,
both pro and con.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stuff he wears is so retro that by the end of the day you
wind up digging brown and blue,'' says Brandel Chamblee.
</P>
<P>
   Parnevik's response? ``As far as my clothes go, if Tom Weiskopf
could win the British Open (in 1973) with the pants he had on, I
mean I can win wearing purple pants, no problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Parnevik's unusual wardrobe and quirky lifestyle left him open
for some wisecracks from other pros when he first joined the PGA
Tour in 1994. But Parnevik soon proved his game was no joke as he
showed quick improvement on the Tour's money list _ from 120th in
'94 to 84th in '95, to 53rd in '96 and 12th last year, when he had
five second-place finishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before I got to where I am playing well, I know they thought I
was crazy. Like, I didn't have a clue,'' he said. ``But if you're
doing OK, you can pretty much do what you want.''
</P>
<P>
   Parnevik continued to impress when he was a captain's choice on
last year's European Ryder Cup team and played a key role by
winning two points. He finally won on the PGA Tour this year at
Phoenix, celebrating in his own unique fashion by lighting up a
victory cigar as he walked up to the 18th green.
</P>
<P>
   And what would he do if he stopped his close-but-no-cigar
finishes at the British Open next week?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not really sure you want to know,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Dolch writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
