<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COWBOYS-PREVIEW-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cowboys will unveil changes during training camp
 &HT;    By Rick Cantu
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ New coach. New training camp site. New offense.
New players.
</P>
<P>
   As the Dallas Cowboys prepare for training camp in Wichita
Falls, they can only hope a fresh start reverses the memory of last
year's 6-10 record.
</P>
<P>
   The mention of 6-10 still grinds on team owner Jerry Jones.
During his tenure at Valley Ranch, his teams have been judged by
his three Super Bowl trophies, not his three losing seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we should have won just six football games last
season,'' Jones said. ``I have every reason to think we can compete
for a championship.''
</P>
<P>
   The first step in rebuilding an aging franchise was dumping its
head coach, Barry Switzer, and hiring energetic Chan Gailey from
the Pittsburgh Steelers. During his first 100 days in office,
Gailey showed quiet confidence and an iron hand.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the veterans, particularly quarterback Troy Aikman and
receiver Michael Irvin, said Gailey's no-nonsense approach might be
the tonic the Cowboys need to regain their stature as NFL bullies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The newness is exciting,'' Aikman said. ``We're working hard,
but I can't say we're working any harder than we have in previous
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey installed about 80 percent of his offense during the
team's three mini- camp sessions in the spring. Fans who attend
camp at Midwestern State University will see a wide-open offense,
one that features up to four receivers on a given play.
</P>
<P>
   This is a far cry from the team's grind-it-up-the-middle past,
but the players insist Gailey's offense is not laced with gimmicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Receivers are all over the place,'' said Billy Davis, who once
likened the playbook to a Chinese menu. ``It doesn't look
organized, but once you look at the playbook it's very organized.
Everyone has structured assignments.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who witnessed last season's disaster knows the Cowboys
needed to restructure an offense that ranked 20th in the league. An
offensive system that helped win three Super Bowls in the '90s had
become outdated and predictable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure predictable is the right word,'' Irvin said. ``If
that were true I doubt that I'd have three rings in my closet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite honestly,'' Irvin added, ``maybe defenses had been
catching on to what we were doing. That probably hurt us the past
few years. Maybe it was time for a change, time for us to explore
something new.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what the dismissal of Switzer and hiring of Gailey should
provide. Something new. Something to worry opposing defensive
coordinators. And as the Cowboys prepare for the opening day of
practice in the 100-degree heat of Midwestern State University this
week, there will be other changes in the air:
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys will showcase two new defensive ends. Greg Ellis,
taken in the first round of April's draft, replaces Tony Tolbert at
left end. He broke Lawrence Taylor's career record for sacks at the
University of North Carolina. The other side will be taken by
Kavika Pittman, a slow-developing player who was drafted two years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   The offensive line will have one new starter, former Miami guard
Everett McIver. He will play on the right side, next to tackle Erik
Williams. The other big change is left guard Nate Newton, who lost
about 80 pounds this year in an effort to salvage his career.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to give Aikman a few extra seconds to look for receivers,
Gailey has introduced a shotgun offense. The Cowboys haven't used
the shotgun with any regularity since Danny White was the
quarterback. When asked if he likes the new formation, Aikman said,
``If it helps us win games, I'll like it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey will again utilize Deion Sanders as a two-way player.
Sanders was rarely used as a target in Switzer's system, but he'll
``be more than just a decoy'' this year, Gailey said.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in his career in Dallas, Emmitt Smith will
have a proven backup. Former Seattle running back Chris Warren
signed a three-year deal with the Cowboys and will be used mainly
as a third-down threat. Warren is one of only 14 players to rush
for 1,000 yards in four consecutive seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey has emphasized a youth movement, cutting several of the
team's old reliables. Bill Bates and Herschel Walker are not under
contract _ although both could be re-signed this summer _ and Mark
Tuinei and Tolbert hope they can come back from major injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Cantu writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
