<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHORTSTOPS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Shortstops with big pop
 &HT;    By Cheryl Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Omar Vizquel figures his highlight films should be in
black-and-white.
</P>
<P>
   That's about how outdated he feels. He looks at the guys playing
shortstop and he's almost glad he has nine major-league seasons
behind him and has already established himself as one of the game's
best defensive shortstops.
</P>
<P>
   Because lately, that's just not good enough.
</P>
<P>
   Gone are the days when the little guy personified the position.
Now, it's become the glamour spot. Think of shorstops, and
Seattle's Alex Rodriguez, the Yankees' Derek Jeter and Boston's
Nomar Garciaparra are the ones who come to mind.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez is batting .308 with 27 homers _ he had 23 last season
and 36 in '96 _ and 72 RBI. Jeter has already matched his home run
totals in each of the last two seasons with 10, while batting .310.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra was the AL Rookie of the Year last season. His 56
RBI so far this season are more than half of the 98 he hit in '97.
He also hit 30 homers and batted .306 that season. He's now hitting
.313 with 13 homers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can dominate the game at that position,'' Vizquel said.
``It may never go back to having smaller defensive players who hit
.250 with no power. I belong to that era.''
</P>
<P>
   It could be just a coincidence that baseball has three
superstars at the same position who are basically the same age.
Jeter and Rodriguez are best friends; they met through a mutual
friend when Rodriguez was a senior in high school and Jeter was in
his first season of professional ball.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter stays at Rodriguez's house when the Yankees are in
Seattle. They even decided that whoever married first _ Jeter
recently broke up with pop diva Mariah Carey _ would give the other
$5,000.
</P>
<P>
   Graciaparra isn't as flashy as the other two. He hangs out with
utility infielder and Red Sox teammate Lou Merloni. He doesn't say
much, but according to Vizquel, he's the best player of the three.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alex Rodriguez is one of the best offensive shortstops, and
defensively, I like Jeter a lot,'' Vizquel said.``But Garciaparra,
he's got the whole package.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeter said it's way too early to credit them with
revolutionizing the position. He named Cal Ripken Jr., Robin Yount,
Alan Trammell and Barry Larkin as guys who redefined what a
shorstop is.
</P>
<P>
   His manager sees it a little differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of like catchers when Johnny Bench was playing,''
Joe Torre said. ``Especially when it comes to pop. Omar Vizquel
takes a backseat to no one defensively, but the offensive people
are the ones who get all the attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre said he doesn't think kids who want to play shortstop will
start focusing more on their offense. Jeter was told very early on
defense is the priority in winning.
</P>
<P>
   But will a guy like the Mets' Rey Ordonez, whose defensive plays
could make up an entire SportsCenter highlight reel, but who's
batting .241, ever be named an All-Star?
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still room for the guy who hits .240,'' Rodriguez
said.
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl Rosenberg writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
