<BODY>
 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
  (HLW)
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
Page 1, Monday, July 6. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (212-556-1927).
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-COMMANDO (Miami) _ As Luis Posada Carriles nears the end of
his career as the most notorious commando in the anti-Castro
underground, he details for the first time his 37-year relationship
with exile leaders in the United States and with the American
authorities. By Larry Rohter and Louise Bardach.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-IMF (Moscow) _ From wires: Russia on Sunday announced
that it had secured a massive bail-out loan from the International
Monetary Fund aimed at saving the country's troubled economy from
collapse.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-ELECTION (Tokyo) _ From wires: Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto hinted he was ready to resign after voters, angry about
Japan's economic woes, handed his Liberal Democrats an embarrassing
setback on Sunday in parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-UNREST (Belfast) _ Three Catholic children are burned
to death in a sectarian arson attack. By James F. Clarity.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   GIFT-TO-BROOKLYN (New York) _ A college professor and his wife
have left millions of dollars to Brooklyn institutions, including
Brooklyn Polytechnic. A tale of heartwarming generosity made
possible by savvy investing. By Karen Arenson.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS-INCUMBENCY (Washington) _ For years, political
ad-makers played down Washington and incumbency. But this election
season, incumbency is in vogue. An examination of hundreds of
advertisements broadcast thus far show that more than anything
else, Democrats and Republicans are using words like ``experience''
and ``record'' in their scripts and citing specific bills they
passed. Some ads even feature the majestic Capitol dome that for so
many years was viewed as too regal. The ads are the best evidence
of a dramatically changed political climate this year. By Richard
L. Berke.
</P>
