<DOCNO> NYT19980712.0043 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-12 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1170 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GAGOV-BARNES-COX     07-12 1172
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAGOV-BARNES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia Governor's race: Roy Barnes profile
 &HT;    By Charles Walston
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Roy Barnes won't deny that he's made some mistakes
during his 24 years in state government and politics.
</P>
<P>
   The way he sees it, that's not all bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learn from my mistakes,'' Barnes said recently. ``I've
gotten older, and hopefully wiser.''
</P>
<P>
   Some hard-won wisdom is evident in the effort Barnes is waging
to become Georgia's next governor. In 1990 he ran a gubernatorial
campaign that fell behind early in TV advertising and never managed
to connect with voters. Barnes finished third that year in the
Democratic primary.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Barnes has raised more money than any candidate in
either party, and has conserved his resources for TV by tightly
limiting other spending. Most important, he has a message that many
voters seem to like. A poll conducted last week for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution showed Barnes leading among 365 likely
Democratic voters with 40 percent, compared to 24 percent for his
closest rival, Secretary of State Lewis Massey.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes has hammered issues like school discipline, health care
reform, a property tax cut and incentives for businesses to open
on-site day care programs. The over-arching theme of his campaign,
though, is his experience as a lawmaker.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes was elected to the state Senate in 1974 at the age of 26,
and for years he was the youngest member in the chamber. He quickly
became chairman of the powerful Judiciary Committee, and beginning
in 1983 served as Gov. Joe Frank Harris' floor leader in the
Senate, helping to pass legislation including the Quality Basic
Education Act and measures to clean up Georgia's rivers and lakes.
</P>
<P>
   As Harris' floor leader, Barnes also served as a member of the
Growth Strategies Commission, which looked for ways to manage
suburban sprawl, traffic and pollution. Many of the panel's
recommendations involved regional cooperation, and they have been
largely ignored over the last decade as growth-related problems in
metro Atlanta have worsened. Still, Barnes believes the Growth
Strategies Commission laid the groundwork for solutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``From being on the Growth Strategies Commission, I came to
believe that a regional approach is going to be necessary to deal
with the big problems on our plate today,'' Barnes said. ``If we
had followed some of those recommendations, we would already be a
long way ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes gave up his Senate seat in 1990 to run for governor, but
his effort was doomed from the start. Then-Lt. Gov. Zell Miller had
an issue that would prove unbeatable: a promise to start a state
lottery.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes opposed the lottery in 1990, and he learned the hard way
that voters agreed with Miller, not him. Today Barnes says the
lottery is here to stay, and points out that Miller, too, was once
opposed to state-sponsored gambling. Miller changed his lottery
stand late in 1988, just prior to his first gubernatorial campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes worked in the Legislature this year to pass a
constitutional amendment that, if voters approve it in November,
will permanently earmark lottery revenues for HOPE scholarships and
other education programs. Massey, one of Barnes' Democratic rivals,
originally proposed a similar idea, but the version that passed the
Legislature combined language from both of their proposals.
</P>
<P>
   After losing his first bid for governor, Barnes returned to the
Legislature in 1993 as a member of the state House, which he found
``more diverse and more rambunctious'' than the Senate. ``It helped
round me,'' he said of his move to the House. It also connected him
to a valuable political network; most Democratic House members,
including Speaker Tom Murphy (D-Bremen), are backing Barnes for
governor.
</P>
<P>
   Among his fellow lawmakers, Barnes has a reputation as a witty
orator and a wily strategist, traits he honed in his career as a
lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from the University of Georgia law school,
Barnes began his career as a Cobb County prosecutor in 1972. Two
years later he went into private practice, and did mostly criminal
work until the 1980s, when the bulk of his business shifted to
civil cases.
</P>
<P>
   Today Barnes' civil clients are split almost evenly between
defendants and plaintiffs. Some of his major clients include
Kennestone Hospital, the Marietta Daily Journal newspaper and
trucking firms. He has successfully sued several strip clubs in
highly publicized cases involving fatal auto accidents caused by
patrons or employees of the clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes' work as a lawyer could be a liability with voters.
Massey and Republican candidate Guy Millner recently criticized him
for representing an accused child molester at a legal hearing three
years ago. Barnes said he was contacted by the defendant's employer
to help obtain a consent order, which prosecutors didn't oppose,
allowing the man to move out-of-state while he awaited trial.
</P>
<P>
   After the consent order was obtained, a different lawyer took
over the defendant's case, which resulted in a guilty plea and a
sentence of eight years on probation.
</P>
<P>
   Though Barnes is now worth about $10 million, he still practices
law in an unassuming building near the Marietta square, and lives
in Mableton, not far from where he grew up. He and his wife, Marie,
have three children.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes has pumped at least $828,000 of his own money into his
campaign, accounting for about 20 percent of the total $4.2 million
he had raised as of last month. Other major sources of
contributions have been lawyers and health care firms. Prominent
supporters include former governor Harris, who is chairman of the
Barnes campaign, and Gwinnett County developer Wayne Mason. Groups
endorsing Barnes include the Georgia Sierra Club and the state
Police Benevolent Association.
</P>
<P>
   Roy Eugene ``Roy'' Barnes
</P>
<P>
   Age: 50
</P>
<P>
   Party Affiliation: Democrat
</P>
<P>
   Residence: Mableton
</P>
<P>
   Education: Bachelors and law degrees, University of Georgia
</P>
<P>
   Profession: Lawyer
</P>
<P>
   Political experience: State representative 1993- present; state
senator 1975-1991; ran for governor in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Personal: Wife, Marie; three children.
</P>
<P>
   Highlights:
</P>
<P>
   Favorite line: ``If you can choose who changes the oil in your
car, you should be able to choose who delivers your baby,'' a line
that he has used in speeches and in a campaign ad promising HMO
patients more choice of doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Favorite theme: With all the Democratic candidates talking about
education, juvenile crime and the environment, Barnes has tried to
convince voters that his experience makes him the one who can best
deliver on promises.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign method: Barnes became the Democrat to beat when he
began his TV ad campaign six weeks before anybody else. He was able
to do it because he raised more money than his opponents, including
$828,000 of his own funds, and because he did a better job of
saving his resources for TV.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
