<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-12 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1171 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GAGOV-BOWERS-COX     07-12 1300
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAGOV-BOWERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia Governor's race: Mike Bowers profile
 &HT;    By Kathey Pruitt
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In a pounding thunderstorm on a night when all his
rivals were absent, Mike Bowers made good on a promise to speak at
a south Fulton forum.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the cinder block basement, he waited patiently through
the potluck buffet and speeches by a half-dozen down-ballot
candidates for his turn at the podium. Exactly what you'd expect
from the man who built a reputation as Georgia's Boy Scout.
</P>
<P>
   That straight arrow image, honed during 16 years as the state's
attorney general, was supposed to be Bowers' ticket to the
governor's mansion, as the first Republican to live there since
Reconstruction. But after admitting to a 15-year adulterous affair
with his former secretary, Bowers' job now is convincing many
Georgia voters that he's still a good guy, and more importantly,
good governor material.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you called Guy Millner's temporary services agency and told
them you needed to fill the office of governor of the state of
Georgia, I'm the candidate they would send,'' Bowers says in a jab
at the Republican frontrunner, who made his fortune in the staffing
business.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Bowers' political resume is complete. A West Point
graduate and retired Georgia Air National Guard reservist, he knows
government from the inside. In 23 years at the state Law Department
advising state agencies, he joined with the Georgia Bureau of
Investigation in a ticket-fixing probe that resulted in the firing
of the long-time Georgia State Patrol Commander, and he sued the
state's personnel board for open meetings violations.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, he made plenty of enemies. His vigorous defense
of the state's sodomy law and withdrawal of a job offer to a
lesbian after she planned a public commitment ceremony with her
partner earned Bowers the enduring ire of gays and lesbians
nationwide. In light of his long-standing affair, a violation of
Georgia's sex laws, Bowers now admits he was a moral hypocrite.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's powerful House Speaker Tom Murphy (D-Bremen), an ally
of the former patrol commander, makes little secret of his disdain
for Bowers, likening his tactics to the ``Gestapo'' in probing the
ticket-fixing scandal. Repeated run-ins with the House leaders
often resulted in clipped pay raises or overlooked budget requests
for Bowers and his office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I think Mike killed a gnat with a sledgehammer,''
said House Majority Leader Larry Walker (D-Perry, Ga.), who says he
nonetheless likes Bowers. ``Everything is black and white to him.
In the political world, everything is not black and white. There
are shades of gray.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bowers also made lots of friends, especially among the law
enforcement sector. In spite of Bowers' conversion to the
Republican Party, Gov. Zell Miller hailed his resignation last year
as the departure of an ``honest, able and hardworking'' man. ``I
like the way he operates,'' Miller said. The media frequently
exalted Bowers as a champion of open records and clean government.
</P>
<P>
   ``He says duty, honor, country. I believe in that,'' retired
Kennesaw, Ga. teacher Duane Young said, proudly wearing a T-shirt
with a picture of Bowers and his wife walking out of the Capitol on
qualifying day. ``The Democrats are so entrenched, it's going to
take somebody with experience to beat them.''
</P>
<P>
   But some voters are looking at a different set of job
qualifications.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure I can trust Mike Bowers,'' Ralph Bradley, a parts
technician from Albany, Ga. said, echoing the concerns of many
social conservatives who have backed away from Bowers' candidacy.
``If a man can't respect his vows to his wife, how can he respect
one to the state?''
</P>
<P>
   A contrite Bowers disclosed the affair, and apologized, more
than a year ago. Both he and his wife of 35 years, say they've
rekindled their marriage and kept their family together. They're
constantly on the campaign trail together and have mortgaged the
farm _ literally, placing a note on their 47-acre spread in Jackson
County _ to help finance the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I truly believe we are almost being penalized because we
stayed the course and kept our family and our marriage together,''
Bette Rose Bowers said as her husband's former mistress renewed the
controversy with a series of media interviews earlier this spring.
``If he'd decided to run for governor as a divorced man, none of
you would be asking these questions.''
</P>
<P>
   Some supporters, like Susan Rutherford, a pastor's wife from
Paulding County, Ga. say their decided to back Bowers because of
how he handled the incident. ``I see the heart of this man and I
say this is someone I can get behind,'' she said. ``To have the
heart to say I messed up and want to do right, I can appreciate
that.''
</P>
<P>
   But political scientists give Bowers' campaign little chance of
rebounding from the scandal enough to win the GOP nomination,
especially since more than a third of the primary voters are
Christian conservatives. He lags significantly in the polls, and
his disapproval rating is the highest among all candidates for
governor.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of his personal life, Bowers is urging voters to focus
on what he plans to do in office. He continues to attack areas he
was familiar with as attorney general _ crime and punishment.
Speeding up the death penalty, cutting crime rates on Atlanta's
streets, which he once compared to war-ravaged Sarajevo, and
forcing prisoners to serve 85 percent of their sentences are at the
top of his agenda. He also advocates a statewide grand jury system
to prosecute government corruption and an end to affirmative action
programs anywhere in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   And add the city of Atlanta to his list of political foes.
Bowers vows to wrest control of airport operations from the city
and force a state takeover of the city's antiquated sewer system if
it isn't immediately brought into compliance with environmental
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   All those are subjects, Bowers says, that GOP frontrunner
Millner isn't equipped to tackle because he won't debate them in
the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's got what it takes to govern?,'' Bowers asked. ``It's
that simple. Part of that is just showing up.
</P>
<P>
   Michael ``Mike'' Joseph Bowers
</P>
<P>
   Age: 56
</P>
<P>
   Party Affiliation: Republican
</P>
<P>
   Residence: Stone Mountain, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Education: Bachelors degree, West Point; masters degrees,
Stanford University and University of Utah; law degree, University
of Georgia
</P>
<P>
   Profession: Lawyer
</P>
<P>
   Political experience: Sixteen years as attorney general; seven
years in U.S. Air Force; 27 years Georgia Air National Guard.
</P>
<P>
   Personal: Wife, Bette; three children.
</P>
<P>
   Highlights:
</P>
<P>
   Favorite Line: (Directed to GOP rival Guy Millner) ``The
Republican primary probably won't be decided on questions of crime,
education or public policy. The issue is: Can you buy Georgia? It's
just that simple. Who's got what it takes to govern?'' Part of that
is just showing up. You may be able to hide in an election, but you
won't be able to hid in governing.''Favorite Theme: Experience
money can't buy.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign method: Divides his time between fundraising and
criss-crossing the state meeting voters. Uses some TV advertising,
but is most effective in front of a crowd. Has appeared at numerous
forums and debates to point out that his chief GOP rival, Guy
Millner, has refused all but two invitations to share the stage
with the Republican candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign tidbits: Served 16 years as Georgia's attorney general,
most of that as a Democrat, before switching parties. Dropped
quickly from GOP frontrunner and party-favorite status after
admitting to a 15-year adulterous affair with a former employee.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
