<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, July 13, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clusters of showers and thunderstorms will drench parts of the
Southeast on Monday as low pressure aloft lifts sultry air near the
ground into towering thunderheads from Arkansas to the Florida
peninsula. Damaging winds, hail, and heavy rain are likely in some
of the storms. Spottier thunderstorms will also percolate by late
afternoon in the increasing warmth and humidity over the central
Appalachians.
</P>
<P>
   Light southerly breezes in combination with developing high
pressure aloft will provide ample sunshine and burgeoning warmth in
the Middle Atlantic States and most of the Northeast. High
temperatures will be about 5 degrees warmer than recently in most
areas.
</P>
<P>
   A front preceding the surge of warmth will support clouds and a
few thundershowers over interior northern New England while a line
of strong thunderstorms ignites ahead of a cold front in the late
afternoon heat over parts of Michigan and eastern Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   Blisteringly hot and humid air will expand northward from Texas
to South Dakota. High temperatures will exceed 100 degrees in much
of Texas, while highs in the middle 90s torment the rest of the
Plains states except North Dakota and eastern Montana.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, a cold front invading the Pacific Northwest will lead
to a few thunderstorms over the valleys east of the Cascades, while
low clouds and spotty showers plague the coast. Ample sun and
seasonably warm temperatures will prevail in California and Nevada
while afternoon thunderstorms develop in the afternoon over the
southern Rockies and intermountain plateaus.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: A Streak Ends
</P>
<P>
   The streak of 31 consecutive days of reaching 90 degrees or
higher came to a halt in Memphis, Tenn., this past weekend. Before
Saturday, the last time the daily high temperature failed to reach
at least 90 was on June 9. Rain-cooled air from thunderstorms and
persistent cloud cover was the primary reason for the streak's end.
During the past month, the ascending air currents that breed clouds
and precipitation were absent across the Deep South as a stubborn
high-pressure zone at 18,000 feet held steady over the region. The
longest streak of days exceeding 90 degrees in Memphis was 54, in
1980.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
