<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HISTORY TELLS US HIGH CONSUMER CONFIDENCE ISN'T NECESSARILY GOOD
NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   You can't imagine how frightening it was to learn that consumer
confidence hit a 29-year high last month. Whew! Talk about a
terrifying development. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How's that? Historically high consumer confidence is bad news?
If this puzzles you, it's time for a history lesson. Just because
the animal spirits of consumers are at their most salubrious since
1969, this isn't necessarily a good thing. Not for the stock
market. Not for the bond market. And not for the economy. At least
it shouldn't seem so if you're old enough to remember what the
economic future held for Americans about this time 29 years ago. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   June 1969, you see, was a time when it seemed things just
couldn't get any better. And, sure enough, they didn't. In fact,
although most Americans were as happy as pigs in slop, the country
was about to enter the most dismal decade of the postwar period. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The '60s had been a gangbusters time for the stock market, and
in 1969 the Dow Jones industrial average topped out at 969 on May
14. Just as the magic 1,000 plateau seemed attainable, though,
things turned nasty. The stock market plunged, and by year's end
the Dow was at 800. On May 26, 1970, the blue-chip indicator
bottomed out at 631, which represented a 35 percent loss in a
little more than a year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The market began to recover, but it was slow going. The Dow
didn't regain its May 1969 level until late 1972. It subsequently
did breach 1,000 and hit 1,052 in January 1973, but it would be
nearly 10 years before it got that high again. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The '70s were marked by stock market wallows, hyperinflation,
political crises, stratospheric interest rates, economic blahs,
energy shortages and frequent fits of national malaise. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By the end of 1982, signs of recovery had emerged, and the Dow
Jones industrial average closed the year at 1,047. This was only 8
percent higher than the 1969 peak. Inflation, meanwhile, had sent
the Consumer Price Index soaring 165 percent. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To give you an idea of the differences between 1969-1982 and
1983-1997, here are some numbers beyond what happened to the Dow
Jones industrial average: Gross domestic product rose about $2
trillion, to $3 trillion, between 1969 and 1982. Since 1983,
however, it has expanded $5 trillion, to about $8 trillion.
Meantime, job growth from 1969 to 1982 was only about half the rate
of the 1983-1997 period. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Given the euphoria that marked the '60s, anybody daring enough
to predict in '69 that a 13-year period of stagnation and woe was
just ahead would have had his prognosticator's license revoked.
Nevertheless, that's what happened. You can look it up, as Casey
Stengel liked to say. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Does this mean history is about to repeat itself? Nobody knows,
but this walk down memory lane isn't meant to imply that 1998 is
1969. Rather, the purpose of reviewing economic history is to
remind anyone interested that nothing is dead-solid perfect, even
though it has tended to seem so for just about the entire decade of
the '90s. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Being cautious isn't fashionable these days, which explains why
the surge in consumer confidence is perceived as good news. It
tends to validate the view that happy consumers mean more happy
times ahead. As the dreadful years from mid-1969 to late 1982
remind us, however, it doesn't always happen that way. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-98 1751EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
