<HEADLINE>
3RD TAKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK MONTGOMERY  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   during a flood.
</P>
<P>
   Their daughter balked (``I'm tired of water!''), so they waited
until she graduated from high school in 1996. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now Verdot mans the wheel of their boat as the family glides
through the glassy calm of the Osage. ``This makes it all
worthwhile,'' he said, squinting toward the sunset. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Downstream in Rhineland, Steve Wehrle enjoys a splendid view
from his remodeled kitchen. He'll enjoy it even more the next time
the Missouri bloats. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be tickled to be where I'm at,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, he and his family lived in the flood plain. The
whole town lived down there. Then came that manic July, when
Rhineland went underwater three different times. ``We knew that if
nothing was done, this would've turned into a ghost town,'' said
Wehrle, the mayor. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So Rhineland stepped up. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Emergency Management Agency provided $10,000 to each
homeowner willing to truck a house up the hill overlooking Missouri
94. Or, residents could use the money to build anew. Grassy parcels
where cattle grazed were awarded in a lottery, and the Wehrles were
the first of many to put their home on wheels. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``People would be sitting for dinner and a crew would come in.
`House coming through. Could you move your car off the street?' &UR; ''
Wehrle recalled. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone has been doing so much work on their homes, getting
situated, they haven't had much time to sit on the porch and relax.
When they do, it'll feel more like home again.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Today about 140 people live on the hill. Only one old-timer
chose to stay in the valley. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wehrle still runs Gosen's Cafe, rebuilt on the north side of the
highway _ a precious 4 feet higher than the south side. He grows
watermelons on the lot where his home stood. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some would consider Portage des Sioux _ its face to the
Mississippi River and its back to the Missouri _ to be in an
unlucky spot. But people have always known you can shape your own
luck. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JoAnn Meyers and a sister had taken out a $50,000 loan to launch
Red's Again Restaurant &AMP; Bar. The establishment had been run by
their father under the name Red's 30 years earlier. Meyers wanted
to show him that she could bring the old place back to life. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It opened July 1, a week before 4 feet of water filled the joint
and swept all the meat from the refrigerator. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The easy option for Meyers was to give up and cut the family's
losses. She instead applied for an emergency federal loan _ this
one for $125,000 _ and worked feverishly to reopen so she could
start paying off the loan. Six months later, with a lot of
volunteer help, Red's Again was Red's Again. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Friday nights the town crams in for catfish. On Saturday,
ribs. People laugh and drink and, as a rule, they don't ramble on
about the flood. Thirteen persons now work there to handle the
crowds, and virtually every afternoon, old Red himself eases into a
chair so his daughter can serve him dinner. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``He takes quite a lot of pride in what we were able to do,''
Meyers said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She speaks for so many upstream, who know this: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, the Missouri River shows us how strong it can be. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And it shows us how strong we can be. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
