<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-12 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1183 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MISSOURI-FLOOD-KAN &LR;      07-12 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSOURI-FLOOD-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECOND TAKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK MONTGOMERY  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   named sky.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Steve Shirley of the Hardin Cemetery Association points to the
new pond. ``Some people think the cemetery looks prettier with the
lake here,'' he says. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Eighty-five feet deep in parts, it resulted from the Missouri
River's gouging a new channel through the cemetery's heart,
disturbing 793 grave sites and sending caskets and vaults into the
hole, or as far as 15 miles downstream. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The damage in Hardin far surpassed the physical. Today it is
spelled out on a marker just erected: ``In Remembrance of Those
Displaced and Unidentified'' with 525 names. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ed Wolfe still grieves. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The casket of his infant son _ Christopher, who died in 1975 _
drifted a mile east and lodged in a ditch beside a gravel road.
Christopher's casket was reburied in October 1993. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd have been 22 years old now,'' said Wolfe, a jeweler in
nearby Richmond. ``To go through it again was just devastating.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The remains of Wolfe's father never were recovered. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The lack of remains does make a difference. I used to talk
with my father when I visited the cemetery'' he said before his
voice choked. ``But this is something we just all have to get
through. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not for us to question God; the reason this happened is
that a man-made levee gave way.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The currents roll on east toward Marvin Casner's modest
farmhouse in Carroll County, where his family has lived since the
1920s. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's see _ 1946, good season,'' recalled Casner, 76, ``1947,
flood; 1948, good season; 1949, wetter than heck, but it never
flooded; 1950, good; 1951, flood &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You get a flood one year and figure you make it back the
next.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the '93 flood, some soil experts predicted that
the sand would render the land surrounding Casner worthless for 10
years. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Today, lush green cornstalks reach the top of Nelson Heil's car
as he drives the back roads near the river. The Carroll County
commissioner scoffed at the way outsiders size up the hazards of
flooding: ``I hate that term `flood plain' with a passion. We call
it a river bottom. Great ground.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Heil bumped across the Norfolk Southern railroad track and
stopped his car near another cornfield. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to Wakenda _ or what's left of it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Only the folks who run Womack's Garage remain. All other
residents in 55 homes accepted emergency buyouts by the federal
government, which turned the land over to the county. A local
farmer is growing 20 acres of sweet corn between the rubble of
street grid, which marks where a town, already withering before
1993, once stood. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After the homes were bulldozed, the former town council erected
a monument beneath a bell that long ago clanged in the Walnut Grove
Baptist Church. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Wakenda,'' the inscription reads. ``Incorporated 1869.
Unincorporated 1996.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The view near Interstate 70's Rocheport exit is different from
what motorists saw before the flood. Gone are the clean rows of
soybeans that seemingly stretched forever. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of acres of the Overton Bottoms now are managed by the
U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service as a wetland preserve. Saplings now
poke up from deep silt. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I appreciate the sight of manicured crops, but I also
appreciate what the natural world offers,'' said J.C. Bryant of the
Big Muddy National Fish and Wildlife Refuge. ``That area is like a
young bird _ looks pretty ragged at first. But in 15 years you'll
see a young forest. It'll be beautiful.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Harold Verdot decided three years ago that life was too short to
spend it in fear of the next monster flood. So he and his wife took
out a $55,000 loan and built a home on the very spot in Taos where
the Verdots were forced to swim in 1993. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Verdot and his daughter, Crystal, earned a measure of national
fame during the flood when a photographer for /{The Kansas City
Star/} captured them retrieving personal effects in a submerged
trailer belonging to Verdot's mother. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The family took a chain saw to the trailer after the Osage and
Missouri rivers receded. In its place stands a tasteful,
three-bedroom house on a concrete foundation 8 feet high. Their
furnace, air conditioner, satellite dish and even electrical
outlets are at least a foot above the 1993 water line. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``That old river teaches you stuff _ things to do and not to
do,'' Verdot said. ``Some people might think it foolish. I guess
you have to experience life out here to understand.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 1995 death of a downstream neighbor, oddly, was the
catalyst. He had just finished adding two stories to the top of his
riverside home when a heart attack struck. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I got to thinking,'' said Verdot, who then lived near a busy
street in Jefferson City. ``I don't want to die before having a
chance to enjoy being here on the river.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Beverly agreed on one condition _ that the house have stairs on
the /{outside/} to prevent snakes from swimming into the living
room during a flood. &QL; 
(MORE)
</P>
</TEXT>
