<DOCNO> NYT19980712.0056 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-12 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1185 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC--KAN &LR;      07-12 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC--KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVISITING VICTIMS OF THE 1993 MISSOURI FLOOD, FIVE YEARS LATER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK MONTGOMERY  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Five years ago, water. Belligerent, brown water everywhere. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Hamburg, Iowa _ a couple of miles from where the Missouri
River claws south into the state that shares its name _ the water
rose to the windows of the Pizza Hut. They called it the Great
Flood in Hamburg. They called it the Great Flood everywhere. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last month the water came back. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Eight hundred people were evacuated at night. Their cars and
pickups clogged Main Street, just as they did in 1993. Once again,
they jerked to a halt and made U-turns to fetch a favorite toy or
heirloom left behind. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This time the recurring nightmare boiled up from the Nishnabotna
River, which flows into the Missouri. Most of Hamburg, including
the Pizza Hut, was spared. But the scare was enough to get
residents wondering. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Once in a generation, you can handle it,'' said farmer Glenn
Stenzel, whose boyhood home got 3 feet of water. ``Twice in a
generation, people leave. Twice in five years?'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The water was receding one recent Sunday when a weary Stenzel
rose to sing in the First Baptist Church choir. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The hymn begins: ``We are often tossed and driv'n on the
restless sea of time.'' And it ends, ``We'll tell the story how
we've overcome. For we'll understand it better by and by.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here in the deepest valleys of the Mighty Mo _ of quiet towns
and stubborn factories, of spectacular crops, tiered bluffs and,
wherever you turn, freshly sided homes _ longtimers such as Stenzel
do understand. At least they understand better than folks on high
ground. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They understand that this churning channel, like God, giveth and
taketh away. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Downstream in St. Joseph, Brenda Reed doesn't live in a flood
plain and can't even see the river from her home. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1993, in their seventh year of marriage, she and Chuck
were beginning to enjoy security. They had bought a new Saturn.
After almost 10 years at Sherwood Medical Industries Inc., Brenda
had risen to quality-control inspector, pulling $11 an hour. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The rains didn't bother her until that first week of July. On
her drive to the plant, she passed National Guardsmen stacking
sandbags. She only stayed at work until noon, when the water
reached 3 inches up the tires of her Saturn. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard on the 6 p.m. news that day that the second shift
should not report,'' she recalled. ``That's when all our lives
started to change.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sherwood was one of two St. Joseph employers that closed for
good because of the flood. The shutdowns displaced more than 1,000
workers, and local unemployment jumped to 12 percent. Reed was
rejected for a job at Wal-Mart because she had no high school
diploma, so she spread textbooks on her kitchen table and took six
months of adult education classes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, Chuck was laid off from the state transportation
department. The washer and dryer broke down before Christmas.
Brenda turned to Catholic Charities for help in paying a month's
rent and utilities. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of families I knew split up. My husband and I just stuck
together,'' she said. ``We found out from the flood that we were a
lot stronger than we thought.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Brenda Reed got her GED. Today she is putting in her
fourth year at a tanning company, cutting leather. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   St. Joseph is recovering, too, thanks to a high-powered campaign
to attract new companies with grants, loans and tax credits.
Unemployment has ebbed below 4 percent. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The city ``has pulled itself out of the muck,'' /{The Washington
Post/} declared last fall. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As for Reed, she admits she'd take her old job at Sherwood in a
heartbeat, though she remains bitter. How bitter? One day her
12-year-old son needed stitches after cutting his head, and Reed
made sure the needle wasn't made by Sherwood. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A small garden occupies the spot where the home of Lewis and
Clark State Park Superintendent Richard Klein used to stand. He
moved to higher ground. Pointing to a dozen houses remaining on the
north side of Sugar Lake, Klein said, ``You couldn't pay me to live
there.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Lux is staying on the north side, and the new house he's
building is perched atop 15-foot I-beams. Frankly, he's glad the
others left. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You had these suburban types who moved in, chasing a rainbow,
wanting to live on a lake,'' he said. ``First time it floods,
they're out of here. They're devastated. Like, they didn't know
this was a flood plain?'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lux's son turns 5 late this month. Born just as the rains began
to ease in 1993, he was named Sky. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
