<HEADER>
A1189 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRIDGES_KANSAS-KAN &LR;      07-12 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRIDGES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRASS-ROOTS EFFORT CAN'T SAVE GRASS-ROOTS BRIDGE IN ALLEN COUNTY,
KAN. 
</HEADLINE>
 _ KANSAS-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM FISHER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (HUMBOLDT, Kan.) _ Today it's called Slack Creek, but a century
ago, when strong, skilled men gathered on its banks, it had a good
German name, Schleicher's Branch.
</P>
<P>
   After two years of backbreaking work, it had a good German
bridge, too. Those men had assembled seven graceful arches, a
wondrous rock structure held together not by mortar but the simple
physics of compression.
</P>
<P>
   And now, because of simple economics, the Allen County landmark,
listed on the National Register of Historic Places, will be
demolished next year.
</P>
<P>
   Its replacement will be a no-frills, $150,000 box-culvert span
of concrete, wider for the big farm equipment that moves around the
countryside, safer for motorists and a quicker link to Humboldt,
Iola and Chanute.
</P>
<P>
   The passing of what locals call the Seven Arch Bridge saddens
Martha Hagedorn-Krass, architectural historian at the Kansas State
Historical Society in Topeka. She said the register designation
would simply come off when the bridge comes down.
</P>
<P>
   ``A grass-roots effort there to save the bridge was not
enough,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The bridge itself was a grass-roots affair. In 1898, the year
it's thought the construction began (there are no exact records),
it was a necessity.
</P>
<P>
   Then, most folks farmed, so moving crops and commodities to
market meant survival. The creek, which occasionally ran amok, was
a barrier. Allen County said it had no money. So the men _
no-nonsense farmers _ built the span themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Gottlieb Roehl led the work, with help from William Mueller,
their four sons, and two men named Fred Crane and Fred Fisher. The
crew used the material at hand _ limestone. They quarried it,
shaped it precisely by hand, fitted it together without mortar, and
allowed gravity to tighten and strengthen the structure.
</P>
<P>
   What resulted was a graceful, 156-foot-long, 16-foot-wide bridge
that looks as if it were lifted whole from deep in some German
forest or an isolated Scandinavian dell.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was always too narrow and carried too low a load limit,''
said William King, Allen County's director of public works. ``But
it did its job.''
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, King said, a trench for a telephone line was cut
right down the middle of the bridge. The ditching machine sent
vibrations through the structure, which caused a rapid
deterioration of its structural integrity.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, after inspecting the bridge's deterioration, county
officials closed it by piling boulders at each end. Since then,
residents have been making a three-mile detour and complaining
about the inconvenience.
</P>
<P>
   King said the county had four choices:
</P>
<P>
   Do nothing and risk lawsuits; build another bridge next to it,
effectively spoiling the view, and still hazard litigation with a
nearby ``attractive nuisance''; renovate it for at least $300,000
with no guarantee anyone could do the work; or carefully document
the bridge through photographs and measurements, then tear it down.
</P>
<P>
   That last option was the one taken by Allen County
commissioners. King said that he'd had a couple of letters in
opposition to the decision but ``that most people understand this
county just doesn't have the money to do everything.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It'd be different if this bridge was downtown in Iola,'' King
said. ``Say, over a creek there. Where it could be quaint.
</P>
<P>
   ``But out here in the country, with all the big farm equipment
and vehicles moving around, it's just too small. Even if we did
restore it _ and who says we could find people who'd have the skill
those old-timers did? _ we'd have to put a new deck on it. And
that'd ruin its looks.''
</P>
<P>
   Surveys show that about 50 vehicles a day will use the new
bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Hagedorn-Krass said her office had pointed out to King's office
that some federal funds were available for restoration of the
bridge, ``but that didn't seem to interest them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What you need is a commitment to save the bridge, and that was
never strong enough in the local area,'' she added. ``So now we're
doing mitigation _ large format photography and measurements so we
know exactly what has been lost.''
</P>
<P>
   She noted that the bridge would have been torn down eight years
ago without a local effort to place the bridge on the National
Historic Register.
</P>
<P>
   Charley Roehl, 76, Gottlieb Roehl's grandson, also is
disappointed the old bridge will come down. Born 18 years after his
grandfather died in 1903, he said his father, Fred Roehl, worked on
the structure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The funny thing was that he never really talked about what it
was like when they did it,'' said Charley Roehl. ``They just built
it. Period. That's the way they did things then.''
</P>
<P>
   Roehl said his grandfather spoke German and was a stonemason in
the old country. After immigrating here, he bought 320 acres of
rocky land just south of the bridge. The family story was that old
Gottlieb, who died soon after the bridge was completed, just had
too much stonemason in him to buy any other kind of land.
</P>
<P>
   Junior Gerken, 77, a Humboldt resident who's taken an interest
in the bridge, thinks most of the work was done in the winter when
the farmers had time on their hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``What people forget is that the creek where the bridge is runs
over solid rock,'' Gerken said. ``Without that footing, that old
bridge would have sunk into the muck years ago. And it helped make
it as strong as it was.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerken said the lack of mortar in the bridge didn't surprise
him, even though nearby Iola, Humboldt and Chanute became huge
producers of cement at the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roehl and Mueller were both skilled stonemasons,'' Gerken
said. ``Cement was almost brand new. I doubt if they even thought
of it. First, they likely didn't have any money for it. More
important, they knew stone. They didn't need it. Not to build a
bridge.''
</P>
<P>
   King said there had been discussions of offering stones from the
bridge to anyone who might want them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Souvenirs,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
