<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-AIRLIFT-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE BERLIN AIRLIFT': RECALLING THE FIRST VICTORY OF THE COLD WAR
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: Production notes are at the end of review. Time, channel are
for New York area. Please check local listings.) 
(js) 
By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was the West's earliest victory in the Cold War and an
exhilarating hour in the long face-off between communism and
democracy. ``The Berlin Airlift'' takes us back 50 years to when a
defeated and divided Germany was the main arena of confrontation
between the Soviet Union and the Western allies. It may be only a
historical footnote now, but as Monday night's spirited documentary
confirms, the West's stand with the people of Berlin against a
Soviet takeover still brightens the memories of those who delivered
the goods.
</P>
<P>
   The scene was set by the post-World War II splitting of Germany
into Western and Eastern sections. Berlin, stranded in the Eastern
zone, was itself divided among the four victorious powers: the
United States, Britain and France on one side and the Soviet Union
on the other. Soon, with the collapse of the wartime alliance,
Moscow stepped up the pressure on its former allies to leave
Berlin, mounting a blockade of the city that left only air routes
open to the West.
</P>
<P>
   The allies, led by Harry Truman and the U.S. commander Gen.
Lucius Clay, resisted, and the story is told mainly by the American
and British pilots who were pressed into a round-the-clock supply
airlift that moved from what one calls a ``hasty, helter-skelter
beginning'' to an astoundingly smooth operation. Despite bad
weather and buzzing Soviet planes, the shipments built steadily
from basics like coal and dried food (the transports were filthy
and stank of fish) to everything from heavy equipment to cigarettes
to toys and candy. One pilot, Gail Halvorsen, was known to German
children as ``the chocolate bomber.'' Another pilot says of the
demanding schedule (one plane took off every three minutes), ``You
became like a bus driver.''
</P>
<P>
   With Berliners pitching in to unload the planes, self-interest
created a new alliance between the former enemies. ``We were
buddies now,'' a pilot says, and West Berlin became a symbol of
democratic aspirations behind the Iron Curtain. When the harsh
winter of 1948 stirred uncertainty over whether the planes could
continue fulfilling their mission, president Truman reportedly
overruled his skeptical advisers. He said, ``We're going to stay in
Berlin,'' and stay they did.
</P>
<P>
   The spirit was catching. There's Irving Berlin entertaining the
troops in occupied Germany with a song called ``Operation
Vittles.'' By the spring of 1949, when the Soviet Union ended the
blockade, the transports had flown 277,000 flights. Casualties,
mostly from accidents, were light. A pilot sums up the achievement:
``We saved a city without firing a shot.''
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   THE BERLIN AIRLIFT
</P>
<P>
   PBS, Monday at 9 (Channel 13 in New York)
</P>
<P>
   Produced and directed by Robert Frye; Laurie Rackas, senior
producer; Ruth Schell, editor. A production of WETA/Washington and
Bolthead Communications Group Inc. For WETA: David McGowan,
executive in charge. Paul Duke, host.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-98 1757EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980712.0064 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-12 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1193 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UNKNOWN-BURY-KAN &LR;      07-12 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNKNOWN-BURY-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY BURIES AIRMAN WHOSE REMAINS WERE IN THE TOMB OF THE
UNKNOWNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW SCHOFIELD  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ America's unknown soldier from the Vietnam War was
buried Saturday, surrounded by family, friends, dignitaries and
some who simply wanted to show they cared. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1st Lt. Michael Blassie _ 26 years after death and 14 years
after his remains were placed in the Tomb of the Unknowns _ was
finally laid to rest by his family and country. He was hailed as a
hero, role model and symbol of hope among families of this nation's
missing in action. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Blassie died in Vietnam after his plane was shot down during a
1972 bombing run. In 1984, his remains were placed in the Tomb of
the Unknowns to symbolize the unidentified dead from that war.
High-tech DNA testing this year gave those remains a name and led
to Saturday's burial. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On a cool morning, beneath thick gray clouds, an estimated 3,000
people turned out at the Jefferson Barracks National Cemetery to
bury Blassie. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The crowd included U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen, House
Minority Leader Richard Gephardt and military leaders, as well as
old friends and old soldiers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tom Wrinkle of St. Louis showed up in a black POW T-shirt and
camouflage pants. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know him, but I'm a Vietnam vet and I thought it was
important to pay my respects,'' he said. ``I never got over to the
Tomb of the Unknown Soldier. I came here seeking some closure.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The ceremony began with the song ``Amazing Grace'' and Blassie's
family stepping from black limousines to take seats under a tent
and surrounded by headstones commemorating 130,000 other war
veterans. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The family was followed by six Air Force pallbearers, who slowly
carried the flag-covered coffin from a hearse to the burial spot.
As they set the coffin down, four F-15s in formation screamed
above. The front fighter jet, which peeled up and away to symbolize
the lost soldier, was quickly lost in the clouds. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Blassie's sister, Air Force Reserve Capt. Pat Blassie, said that
because of the circumstances of her brother's long-overdue return
to St. Louis, the family thought it was essential to share his
burial with the public. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Tomb of the Unknowns, he didn't belong only to us, but
to everyone,'' she said. ``We are so thankful you wanted to join us
here in a celebration of his life.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other siblings spoke of the pain of losing him in 1972 and how,
until his remains were identified, they still dreamed he lived. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But they also spoke about their feelings after he was
identified. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked myself what's so important about just six bones,'' Pat
Blassie said. ``Well, it was important because he was my
brother.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But she said she also turned to the Bible and found meaning in
that Joseph had insisted his remains be taken out of Egypt for
burial. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such an important promise we make to all those who risk
their lives for our freedom,'' she said, ``that we won't forget
about them and leave them behind.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The family also spoke of the overwhelming support and
condolences they received, especially letters detailing memories
from their brother's old friends. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two old friends from the Air Force wrote to say they had named
sons after Blassie. A third told how Blassie had introduced him to
soccer, and how he had now gone on to run a soccer program for
2,000 children. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And family members spoke of the importance of God to them at
this time, and how they believed his identification was a sign that
Americans should work hard to bring peace to other families still
waiting for the remains of a loved one. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We give all the glory to God for bringing Michael, an American
hero, home at last,'' Pat Blassie said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As the ceremony closed to the strains of a mournfully slow
version of ``Taps'' and seven rifles were fired three times each in
a 21-gun salute, Blassie's mother accepted an American flag, folded
into a triangle. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Blassie's remains were buried among a group of graves for World
War II veterans, only a dozen yards from a headstone for three
young fliers who died in a bombing run over Germany. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cemetery officials said that the spot of his headstone was
traditionally the site of their Memorial Day services and that,
beyond family memorials, he would be remembered each year with a
small American flag placed by local Boy Scouts. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Blassie was 24 when he died. He was a recipient of the Silver
Star for gallantry in action, the Distinguished Flying Cross, a
Purple Heart for wounds received in action and an Air Medal with
Four Oak Leaf Cluster for meritorious achievement during flight. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
