<SLUG> BC-ROMEO-BALLET-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRANKO'S `ROMEO AND JULIET': HARD ON PERFORMERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ John Cranko and Kenneth MacMillan seem to have a
corner on the ``Romeo and Juliet'' market, at least so far as dance
in New York is concerned. The Cranko production, presented by the
Stuttgart Ballet at the New York State Theater on Saturday
afternoon and evening, is less theatrical than the MacMillan
staging, created three years later, in 1965. Cranko's characters
also tend to be more recognizably human and less prone to
larger-than-life bursts of passion and pyrotechnical display.
</P>
<P>
   The small touches of extra humanity are endearing, but Cranko's
simplicity places a special burden on the performers. There is very
little for them to hide behind as actors. The Stuttgart's powerful,
wrenching performance of ``Onegin'' on Friday night promised much
for these two closing performances of the company's Lincoln Center
Festival season. But though well danced, ``Romeo and Juliet,'' set
to the Prokofiev score, was for the most part dramatically bland on
Saturday. And this is a ballet that cries out for identification
with the characters, from the performers and the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Julia Kramer and Ivan Cavallari, the matinee leads, were
affecting in the sheer youthfulness of their interpretations.
Cavallari's Romeo was a puppy whose playful, heedless exuberance
had not yet been trained out of him by life. Ms. Kramer was a
little more knowing, as ballet Juliets tend to be, but empathic and
pretty enough to be convincingly alluring. Their youthful sweetness
brought extra color to the balcony pas de deux, with its exquisite
airborne, sharp-angled lifts.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Tewsley and Sue Jin Kang, the evening's leads, were most
affecting in the desperate bedroom pas de deux, when Romeo must
leave Juliet after their first night together. Ms. Kang suddenly
came to dramatic life, suggesting that this Juliet, alone and
entrapped, knew she would never see her love alive again. But while
Ms. Kramer and Cavallari never grew enough as characters to reach
the necessary tragic grandeur, Ms. Kang and Tewsley failed to
prepare one for that climax.
</P>
<P>
   The scrappy Mercutios were a touchingly innocent Thomas Lempertz
(matinee) and a more playful Krzysztof Novogrodzki (evening). Both
Benvolios, Filip Barankievicz (matinee) and Alexander Zaitsev
(evening), had something of Tewsley's creamy amiability. Marcia
Haydee, the company's former prima ballerina and director, once
more nearly stole the show as Lady Capulet, a mama not to be messed
with.
</P>
<P>
   Ludmilla Bogart, Juliet's sensible, loving nurse at both
performances, embodied Cranko's human touch, in a lead cast
completed by Lior Lev and Ugur Seyrek as the surly matinee and
evening Tybalt, Douglas Lee as a weedy young matinee Paris, and
Ivan Gil Ortega as the evening's more calculating fiance. Kanako
Sakamoto stood out in the corps for her juicily articulated
dancing. James Tuggle conducted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-98 1758EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980712.0066 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-12 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1195 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NBAF-COX     07-12 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NBAF-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta plays host to National Black Arts Festival
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar and Sonia Murra
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Shortly after 10 a.m. Friday in the Atlanta
Renaissance Hotel downtown, the first panel of the ten-day National
Black Arts Festival was already taking notice of this gathering's
importance.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is history,'' began author Barbara Smith, the moderator
of ``Conversation: The Direction of Gay and Lesbian Literature.''
``You'll be telling your grandchildren that you witnessed this.''
</P>
<P>
   At that moment Smith was referring to a panel that included
million-plus seller E. Lynn Harris (``Invisible Life''), James Earl
Hardy (``B-Boy Blues''), recent two-time Lambda Award winner Lisa
C. Moore (``does your mama know '') and Kathleen E. Morris
(``Speaking In Whispers'').
</P>
<P>
   But hers was a sentiment being echoed throughout the various
sites of the sprawling biennial festival on the opening weekend of
its tenth anniversary event.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Levy was one of the few in front of the main stage at the
Roots and Branches Folk Art &AMP; Vendor Market in Atlanta's Piedmont
Park Saturday who was not beating the heat under a tree. She said
she stumbled on the event as she and two friends were walking
through the park. She took a seat as the Praise House Shouters of
South Carolina, whose members are all over 70, began their
performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just out here to share in this great experience and be a
part of the community,'' said the 29-year-old. ``I mean, we are all
one community.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a community that has gathered in large numbers, noted Allen
Grose of Washington, D.C. His wife Doris sold their wood sculptures
at the 1996 Roots and Branches festival, which was staged on Auburn
Avenue. ``The people came, and bought, but many mentioned they
didn't really like the area it was in,'' she recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad we're here in the park this time, even though the
crowd seems to be moving in slowly, but surely.''
</P>
<P>
   By early afternoon Saturday, a few hundred people had been drawn
to the free event, which opened with a ceremonial drum procession
and continued with hour-long sets from blues and zydeco acts. The
site made a more appealing public space than Sweet Auburn, where
the music was too easily overlooked. At Piedmont Park, the stage is
front and center, even if much that surrounds it is the usual
kitsch and corndogs.
</P>
<P>
   The heat index made air-conditioned Greenbriar Mall an almost
uncomfortably crowded place all weekend. ``Any Saturday is a busy
Saturday in a mall,'' said Travis Davis, supervisor of the
southwest Atlanta mall's Peppermint Music. ``But this is
ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   This was also different. Along the length of the mall, the
NBAF's Artists' Market was set up, offering mostly paintings,
jewelry and clothing from across the country. Luckily, Durham,
N.C.'s John Keith didn't have to drive that far to pick up his
print of Atlanta artist Maurice Evans' ``Trio.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to be back at work on Sunday so I came down Friday to
try to take in as much as I could,'' said the 30-year-old, who had
also been to Friday's opening ceremony at the Atlanta Civic Center
and to Underground Atlanta _where the Doll Exhibition &AMP; Artists'
Market is being held.
</P>
<P>
   ``There just aren't many opportunities to take in so much,''
Keith added. ``So it was worth the time on the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Painter Wayne Manns of Bloomington, Ind. could have stayed at
home and offered his wares at the Black Expo. ``But I had heard
about the crowds that come to the National Black Arts Festival, I
believed it, I came, and now I'm seeing it,'' said Manns, who had
sold two pieces in the first few hours. ``There's a lot of people
looking and expressing interest, but cash registers are ringing all
over and I am overwhelmed. It is so great to see our people
supporting the arts and supporting each other.''
</P>
<P>
   A week before the kick-off of this year's festival, budgeted at
$2.6 million, NBAF marketing director Carlos James reported sales
of nearly 3,000 tickets. But nearly 5,000 people packed the opening
ceremony that featured poet Maya Angelou, signaling a robust start.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, we're pleased,'' said James in the crowded lobby of the
festival's main venue, the Renaissance Hotel. The NBAF hopes to
attract 1.5 million people by the time it closes Sunday . ``We seem
to be on pace.''
</P>
<P>
   Out of space is what the festival was late Saturday, as Sunday
morning approached. By 12:05 a.m. organizers were turning
ticketholders away from the midnight performance by monologuist and
Performance Art program curator Phyllis Yvonne Stickney. The
150-capacity hotel meeting room was oversold. A 1:30 a.m. show had
to be added.
</P>
<P>
   Among the attendees for the second show was comedian George
Wallace, who remarked: ``Look around, (there's) old and young black
people hanging together, supporting one another. With the NAACP
(convention) in town this is the blackest city in the country at
this moment. And it's a beautiful thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
