<HEADER>
A1197 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SURFER13-COX     07-12 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SURFER13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Lyle V. Harris
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service PASADENA, Calif. _ Ted Turner has just
<TEXT>
ordered lunch, slipped off his suit jacket and confessed
matter-of-factly that he wants to save the world.
<P>
   He seems to be referring to the the whole world, mind you, not
just the parts he owns outright, which is a pretty good-sized
chunk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have more money than I can spend intelligently, so what else
should I be doing with my life?'' he wonders aloud _ and loudly _
while waiting for his chicken quesadillas to arrive.
</P>
<P>
   World-saving, or at least Turner's version of it, drove him to
spend nearly four years on ``Cold War,'' a 24-part documentary that
will debut Sept. 27 on CNN.
</P>
<P>
   ``It bothers me that younger people would rather watch
'Seinfeld' but they don't understand the Cold War,'' says the CNN
founder and co-chairman of Time Warner Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the most expensive war the world has ever seen and it
was the most dangerous because it endangered every man, woman and
child on the planet. If they don't understand the past, they won't
know where they're going.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner, who arrived here Friday to unveil his pet project to a
convention of television writers, called the documentary ``the most
important piece of television in the past decade.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe. But he spent much of his visit apologizing profusely for
the ill-fated story of the moment: The Tailwind report on CNN's
newsmagazine ``NewsStand'' that had alleged deadly nerve gas was
dropped by U.S. forces on Laos during the Vietnam war.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tailwind was just an unfortunate thing that happened in the
last couple of weeks,'' Turner says during lunch. ``But it's old
news, and everything that can be said about Tailwind has been said.
Tailwind is ending, the Cold War is the new news.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner's idea for the massive ``Cold War'' was inspired by
British filmmaker Jeremy Isaacs' ``The World At War,'' a landmark
1974 documentary about World War II. Turner says he was so
impressed, he handpicked Isaacs to produce ``Cold War.''
</P>
<P>
   The globe-trotting documentary examines the 45-year long
struggle from the perspective of those who shaped it, and lived
through it. They include Mikhail Gorbachav, Fidel Castro and U.S.
presidents Gerald Ford, George Bush and Jimmy Carter.
</P>
<P>
   At its exhaustive length, Turner says he's aware viewers may
consider that watching the ``Cold War'' will be the television
equivalent of eating their broccoli. But even if they don't devour
it in one sitting, he hopes they will nibble on it over time and
ultimately digest its importance.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the telecast, there's a companion book, a CD-ROM,
and a website on CNN Interactive (CNN.com/Cold War). Turner says
video copies of ``Cold War'' will be made available to schools and
unversities here and abroad, and will be sold as a boxed set.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of people are going to buy the videos, and we'll
have to figure out how to run it again and we'll keep running it.
The one thing about this is that it's timeless. People will be
interested in it 100 years from now.''
</P>
<P>
   SEEN AND HEARD
</P>
<P>
   Standup comic and ubiquitous MTV personality Bill Bellamy will
lend his voice to the title character in ``Skeeter's Show,'' a new
kid's program that combines puppetry and live-action next season on
Nickelodeon. Bellamy's felt-and-styrofoam character uses hip-hop
phrases like ``getting jiggy'' and has a crew of high-profile
friends who will make guest appearances, including Los Angeles
Laker Shaquille O'Neal, R&AMP;B singer Usher and former ``Martin''
co-star Tisha Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   TV Land will bring Norman Lear's ``All in The Family'' to its
prime-time oldies schedule this fall. On Oct .5, fans of the sitcom
will see one of three lost pilots filmed for the show that never
aired. The episode features Archie Bunker (Carroll O'Connor)
insulting his Irish son-in-law, before Rob Reiner joined the cast
permanently as the lovably liberal loser Mike ``Meathead'' Stivic.
TV Land will kick off the show's launch with a marathon Oct. 12-16.
Also being added to the reto network's lineup are square-jawed cop
dramas ``Dragnet'' and ``Adam 12.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Wilson of the Beach Boys will be featured in ``Endless
Harmony: The Beach Boys and Their Music,'' a documentary by VH1 set
to debut Aug. 23. Wilson, the only surviving brother who formed the
core of the band whose feel-good music brought out the surfer in
all of us, appeared at the Television Critics Association
convention in Pasadena. Moving stiffly and looking pale, Wilson
said he has overcome the problems with drugs and a ``nervous
breakdown'' that nearly ended his life and career. He's recorded a
new album and expects to be touring again soon.
</P>
<P>
   MTV is trying to re-create ``Ted Mack's Amateur Hour'' and
``Star Search'' with ``The Cut,'' a new show that will give unknown
musical acts a shot at stardom. The show trvavels to various cities
and holds auditions for five performers. The winner will film a
professionally made video which will be shown on the cable network.
The show starts Sept. 14. No word on whether, or when the show will
come to metro Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: channelsurfer(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
