<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-12 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1199 &Cx1f; tth-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-ONIONS-WALLAWALL     07-12 1169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-ONIONS-WALLAWALLA-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWEET, DELICIOUS WALLA WALLA ONIONS HAVE ARRIVED TO TEMPT TASTE
BUDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GBREGORY ROBERTS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   So sweet, you can eat them like apples!
</P>
<P>
   So sweet, they won't reduce you to tears!
</P>
<P>
   It's Walla Walla onion season again, a time when the juicy
regional treasures stream into grocery-store produce bins in the
Pacific Northwest and consumers snap them up for topping burgers or
bolstering salads. And if not quite as sweet as a ripe Red
Delicious, they certainly are milder than their garden-variety
cousins.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for that is the high water content of Walla Wallas
and other sweet onions, which dilutes the pungent, tear-producing
sulfuric compounds in the pulp. The flip side of succulence is
shorter shelf life: Sweet onions bruise more easily and spoil far
more quickly than ``dry'' onions, which are bred for durability.
</P>
<P>
   Authentic Walla Wallas grow only in Walla Walla County in
southeastern Washington and adjoining parts of Umatilla County in
northeastern Oregon. Harvest of the early varieties begins in
mid-June, and the season stays strong till late July. Some late
varieties are picked in mid-August and may be available into early
September.
</P>
<P>
   One way to extend enjoyment of Walla Wallas is through proper
selection and storage. Start by picking onions that are round, with
elongated necks, and with dry, paper-thin skin without bruises. If
kept in a cool, well-ventilated spot, they can last up to six
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The stored onions should not touch one another. They may be
spread on chicken wire or mesh. Another technique puts worn-out
pantyhose to good use: Drop an onion down a leg, knot the hose
above the onion, then drop in another onion, knot the hose, and so
on; hang the hose and snip beneath the lowest knot to use.
</P>
<P>
   Sweet onions also may be wrapped in foil in the refrigerator to
prolong their life. And they may be frozen: Chop the onions and
spread them on a cookie sheet in the freezer; when frozen, seal
them in bags or containers.
</P>
<P>
   Although the nature of a sweet onion argues for eating them as
fresh as possible, cooks may incorporate them in relishes or sauces
to summon up the onions' savor out of season. Refrigeration will
keep those preparations for a few weeks; freezing or canning can
preserve them for months.
</P>
<P>
   Walla Walla sweet onions trace their lineage to the island of
Corsica, a French possession in the Mediterranean Sea near Italy.
In the late 1800s, a French soldier took the seeds of an Italian
sweet onion from Corsica to Walla Walla.
</P>
<P>
   Growing in rich, well-watered volcanic soil, the onions
flourished in the warm days and cool nights of the region and
developed an identity ultimately protected by a federal
agricultural regulation in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Walla Wallas are not the only sweet onions, and Corsican seeds
are not the only source. Seeds from a given onion variety will
yield a crop with different characteristics in different growing
regions, and other onions with above-average levels of water and
sugar and below-average levels of sulfur have earned sweet
reputations of their own.
</P>
<P>
   Among them are Vidalias from Georgia, Mauis from Hawaii,
Carzalias from New Mexico, Texas 1015s, OSO Sweets from Chile and
Sweet Imperials and Italian Reds from California. Seasons vary, and
availability and distribution may be limited.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some recipes using Walla Walla sweets, or other sweet
onions:
</P>
<P>
   Sweet Onion Confit
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds Walla Walla or other sweet onions, peeled and sliced in
rings
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon ground juniper berries
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   Melt butter in heavy non-aluminum pan. Add onions and juniper
berries. Heat over low heat for 90 minutes or until very soft. Add
salt. Seal in containers and refrigerate up to three weeks, or
freeze. To serve, heat until warm and use as a spread on bread or a
filling for tarts, or dilute with a rich stock to make onion soup.
</P>
<P>
   Makes about 2 cups.
</P>
<P>
   From Bruce Naftaly, Le Gourmand, Seattle
</P>
<P>
   Sweet Onion and
</P>
<P>
   Sweet Cherry Relish
</P>
<P>
   2 medium Walla Walla or other sweet onions, peeled and thickly
sliced crosswise
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil, as needed for grilling
</P>
<P>
   One-half pound sweet cherries, pitted and halved
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fresh marjoram, minced
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter cup sherry vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon honey
</P>
<P>
   One-half teaspoon freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Fire up the grill. Brush onion slices with olive oil and grill
on both sides until soft and well marked by the grill. Remove
onions to a cutting board and coarsely chop.
</P>
<P>
   In a bowl, combine onions, cherries, marjoram, sherry vinegar,
honey and black pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Seal in container with top layer of olive oil and refrigerate up
to two weeks, or process in a boiling-water canner for long-term
preserving.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, set aside to allow flavors to mingle for 15 minutes or
more and serve at room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Makes garnish for four entrees.
</P>
<P>
   From Matt Costello, Palace Kitchen, Seattle
</P>
<P>
   Roasted Sweet Onion Puree
</P>
<P>
   3 medium Walla Walla or other sweet onions, halved
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper
</P>
<P>
   Place onions cut side down in a skillet with the olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   Place in a 350-degree oven 30 to 40 minutes or until soft. Peel
off outer skin and pass through a food mill on the fine setting.
Add a little chicken stock until puree is a creamy consistency.
Season with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Seal in container with a top layer of olive oil and refrigerate
up to two weeks, or freeze.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, heat to warm and spoon around grilled duck or game.
</P>
<P>
   Makes about 2 cups.
</P>
<P>
   From Matt Costello, Palace Kitchen, Seattle
</P>
<P>
   Apricot and Sweet Onion
</P>
<P>
   Chutney with Toasted Coriander
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons whole coriander seed
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds ripe fresh apricots, pitted and sliced in {-inch wedges
</P>
<P>
   2 medium-sized Walla Walla onions, peeled and sliced \ inch
thick
</P>
<P>
   One-and-one-half tablespoons chopped fresh ginger
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon whole yellow mustard seed
</P>
<P>
   One-half teaspoon hot red pepper flakes
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter cup red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Three-quarters cup brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   Three-quarters teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 cinnamon stick
</P>
<P>
   Toast the coriander seeds by tossing them in a small dry
saucepan over medium heat until they turn a darker brown and become
fragrant. Grind the seeds in a spice grinder or blender. Put all of
the ingredients into a large heavy-bottomed saucepan and cook,
uncovered, over medium-low heat for 45 minutes, or until very
thick. Stir often to prevent the chutney from sticking to the
bottom of the pan. Remove the cinnamon stick. Cool and seal in a
container and refrigerate up to two weeks, or freeze, or process in
a boiling-water canner for long-term preserving. Serve the chutney
at room temperature with grilled meats.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 1 quart.
</P>
<P>
   From Jerry Traunfeld, The Herbfarm, Fall City, Wash.
</P>
</TEXT>
