<SLUG> BC-IOWA-ARTS-1,000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN DES MOINES, ART IS SERVED MAINSTREAM, NOT SUBVERSIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BRUCE WEBER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ It was a bit of Americana, stirring and
sincere. Sockless, in baggy shorts and a tennis shirt as though
fresh from a holiday barbecue, the governor himself, Terry
Branstad, stood on the Capitol's steps and introduced the Des
Moines Symphony to some 20,000 Iowans gathered on the lawn and in
the parking lot. This was the night before Independence Day, the
occasion of an annual concert here. Rain clouds sprinkled a few
drops on the crowd, but didn't dare spoil the party, dispersing as
the evening darkened.
</P>
<P>
   In the fading light, the gold dome of the Capitol glinted, even
under its scaffolding. And by the time the orchestra rendered a
George Cohan medley; a tone poem by its guest artist, Mark
O'Connor, a country fiddler, and reached the climax of the ``1812
Overture,'' many in the audience were cheering the musicians and
waving tiny flags. Des Moines takes ardent pride in both its
cultural institutions and its mainstream values.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, therein lies a conflict. Although audiences in Des
Moines, a city of 400,000 people with a healthy corporate base,
have supported their symphony, their well-regarded opera company,
their world-class art museum and their community theater for more
than a quarter-century (and dozens of others for not quite so
long), no one is claiming the city as a hotbed of experimentation
or even as terribly tolerant of art that leans to the subversive.
It was only a decade or so ago that a patron stood up at a
performance of ``A Chorus Line'' at the Civic Center of Greater Des
Moines, demanded that the profanity be halted immediately and had
to be escorted from the theater.
</P>
<P>
   ```Angels in America' would not play well here,'' said Jeff
Chelesvig, the general manager of the Civic Center, which is the
city's only site for professional theater. ``I'd love to do it, but
I couldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the role of the arts in Des Moines is a curious one,
characterized by cultural officials as both a strength and a
weakness of a community that is generally enthusiastic if narrowly
focused.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think there's a general perception here that the arts are
supposed to be entertainment,'' said Kenneth Hopper, the executive
director of the symphony, who, like other cultural officials in
town, sees himself as an educator of a sort. The symphony featured
seven world premieres last season, well received, Hopper said,
though he added that it thrills him when people applaud between
movements of a Beethoven symphony, because it means the audience is
full of new members.
</P>
<P>
   ``Opera is not indigenous to Iowa, but I've felt proud of our
audiences,'' said Jerilee Mace, director of the 26-year-old Des
Moines Metro Opera in Indianola, a dozen miles to the south, which
has 1,500 subscribers. ``They're growing into an appreciation of an
unusual repertoire.''
</P>
<P>
   That would apply to a current production, Lee Hoiby's adaptation
of ``Summer and Smoke.'' After each performance, delighted patrons
swarm the lobby to meet the performers, still in costume, a company
tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Most people acknowledge that, unlike the two major university
towns nearby _ Ames, home of Iowa State, to the north, and Iowa
City to the east, where the University of Iowa (and the renowned
Iowa Writers Workshop) is located _ Des Moines is more a center of
capitalism than intellectual ferment, an indistinct place that
struggles with the image of blandness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come from Des Moines,'' Bill Bryson wrote at the beginning
of his dyspeptic travel book, ``The Lost Continent''
(HarperCollins). ``Somebody had to.'' And though Bryson may not be
held in particularly grand repute in his hometown, he isn't
disputed much.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just like the rest of the country,'' said Louise Noun,
an art collector who specializes in work by women. ``Same crime,
same culture, just in smaller quantities.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Noun, it must be said, however, is pretty distinctive
herself, having turned 90 in March, just after serving as curator
for a show of an early 20th-century Iowa painter, Agnes Weinrich,
at the Des Moines Art Center. (It travels to the Provincetown Art
Museum in Massachusetts next month.)
</P>
<P>
   Preferring Poetry to Auto Racing
</P>
<P>
   There are, of course, other local residents who defy the
mainstream cultural stereotype. One is James Autry, a former
president of the Meredith magazine group here (Meredith Corp.
publishes Better Homes and Gardens and other magazines), and the
author of several management books and a book of poetry.
</P>
<P>
   Nine years ago, irritated that a group of businessmen had
sponsored a Grand Prix auto race in town, Autry helped found the
Des Moines National Poetry Festival, which has brought poets like
Galway Kinnell, Carolyn Forche and Czeslaw Milosz for weekends of
readings and workshops. More than 800 people took part in the
eighth annual event in May.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I'm pleased to say, as a postscript, that the Grand Prix
is out of business,'' Autry said.
</P>
<P>
   Another offbeat arts entrepreneur is John Gaps III, an
Associated Press photographer and the author of ``God Left Us Alone
Here'' (Lone Oak Press), a collection of his photos from war zones
with accompanying poems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what Des Moines is,'' Gaps said. ``It doesn't
have enough of any one influence to be any one thing. There's not a
preponderance of pain here, but there is a preponderance of
introspection.''
</P>
<P>
   Gaps is plumbing that introspective vein; he has started both a
small publishing house and a literary magazine, Stand Alone,
devoted primarily to Iowa writers. ``The most prestigious literary
publication in Iowa is The Iowa Review,'' he said, ``and there's no
one from Iowa in it.''
</P>
<P>
   The main influence on the culture of Des Moines, however, is
commerce. A center of insurance and agribusiness, the city has a
downtown where 65,000 people go to work every day, more than in
Kansas City, Detroit or Phoenix. Companies like Meredith, Principal
Financial Group (which commissioned a sculpture by Maya Lin for its
corporate headquarters) and Pioneer Hi-Bred International are the
primary benefactors of the city's cultural institutions.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Cultural Groups as a Selling Point
</P>
<P>
   Pioneer, for example, the world's largest seed-corn producer,
endows a string quartet, the only four salaried players in the Des
Moines Symphony. Part of this is enlightened self-interest,
perhaps. Recruiting executives and technically trained workers has
become difficult in Des Moines, where unemployment is less than 2
percent, so many companies are reaching out nationally. A local
study showing that Des Moines has more cultural organizations per
capita than cities like Austin, Texas, and Portland, Ore., is
regarded as a selling point.
</P>
<P>
   The arts scene, said Eric Fogg, the program manager for
community development at Pioneer, ``comes up in most interviews,
and if it doesn't come up, we'll bring it up, because we're pleased
with the quality and quantity of the arts in Des Moines.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, as in many other cities that have expanded away from the
center, downtown more or less clears out after dark. And though
situated prettily at the junction of the Des Moines and Raccoon
Rivers, the city has acres of riverfront that have gone
unexploited.
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, the city has only just begun to address the
lifelessness at its heart at night, with proposals pending before
the local government to create a downtown arts district, establish
incentives for converting abandoned warehouses to residential
lofts, and build an entertainment center that would include a
24-screen movie complex, restaurants, shops and nightclubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The resources are here to invest in culture and
entertainment,'' said David Feehan, president of the Downtown
Partnership, an organization of businesses. ``The likelihood is
that we'll build $750 million worth of stuff downtown in the coming
years.''
</P>
<P>
   This is encouraging talk, given the relative noninvolvement of
the government; frustrated by the lack of support, the city's
cultural institutions have recently formed an alliance to begin
seeking funds from the suburbs. On the state level, Iowa ranks 42nd
among 56 states and territories in arts dollars spent per capita.
</P>
<P>
   ``Government support is terrible, pathetic,'' said David
Kruidenier, 77, the former chairman of Cowles Media Co., which
owned The Des Moines Register before it was sold to Gannett in
1985. ``Iowa is kind of an odd place. It's been so agriculturally
oriented that I think the arts have been viewed as frivolous. But
there has been a change among business leaders, a recognition that
we haven't paid enough attention to esthetics.''
</P>
<P>
   Kruidenier was among those who selected I.M. Pei, in the 1960s,
and Richard Meier, in the '80s, to create new wings for the Des
Moines Art Center, whose main building was designed by Eliel
Saarinen in 1948. The first museum built in the United States after
World War II, it stands on a rolling, city-owned greensward west of
downtown. Most residents consider it the city's cultural jewel,
though it seems to be appreciated by a remarkably insular group; of
its 110,000 visitors a year, 90 percent are Iowans, said Jessica
Rowe, the acting director.
</P>
<P>
   What others are missing is a collection that holds, among dozens
of works by 20th-century masters, the Edward Hopper painting
``Automat,'' which is featured on a 32-cent stamp; a white square
by Robert Ryman much like the bone of contention in the Tony
Award-winning play ``Art,'' and ``Amazing Juggler,'' by Kuniyoshi
Yasuo, which Nikita Khrushchev once stood before in Moscow as he
denounced modern art.
</P>
<P>
   Vegetable Art With a Dash of Humor
</P>
<P>
   The Pei wing, a contemporary sculpture court, is particularly
lively, with arresting pieces by Donald Judd and Claes Oldenburg
(whose giant umbrella in front of the Civic Center downtown makes
him well represented in Des Moines).
</P>
<P>
   An installation by Red Grooms, depicting a booth at the Iowa
State Fair, includes busts done in vegetables of native Iowans like
John Wayne and Herbert Hoover, and indicates that, if anything,
Iowans will tolerate a little humor about themselves.
</P>
<P>
   A current exhibition of Iowa artists is an eclectic group of
works, including paintings, kinetic sculptures and photographs. But
at least one artist featured in the show, Sarah Grant-Hutchison,
seemed a quintessential representative of Des Moines. An abstract
painter who has had exhibitions in many regional museums, she was
asked 12 years ago by a Meredith publication, Weekend Woodworker,
to design a wooden nativity scene. She balked at first, but agreed
when she was told her fee would be $500.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to her painting, she now runs Sticks, a company that
makes original furniture with wood-burned and painted designs,
employing 55 people and represented by 125 galleries around the
country. Sales last year were $2.5 million, and the company, having
outgrown its studio, is putting up a new building.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've come to love the business end of things,'' Ms.
Grant-Hutchison said, as mainstream an American artist as perhaps
there is. ``It's as creative and challenging for me as my
painting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
