<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-12 18:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1205 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHERNOW-PROFILE-ART-6     07-12 1101
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHERNOW-PROFILE-ART-655&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISCOVERING THE ROOTS OF JOHN D. ROCKEFELLER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(lb) 
 By DINITIA SMITH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Ron Chernow's editor at Random House, Ann Godoff, first
suggested the idea for a biography of John D. Rockefeller Sr.,
Chernow thought it was a very bad idea. To Chernow, author of ``The
House of Morgan,'' which won a National Book Award in 1990,
Rockefeller was a ``ghostly'' figure.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seemed impenetrable,'' Chernow said last week.
``Secretiveness was at his very essence. He spent his life trying
to evade the notice of the press and politicians and others.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, there had been relatively few full-scale biographies
written about the man who founded Standard Oil and went on to
create one of the century's great fortunes. Most books on the
Rockefellers had been family sagas, and ceased their accounts of
Rockefeller's life around 1897, when he essentially retired from
Standard Oil.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no confidence I could penetrate his masks and
disguises,'' Chernow said. ``You can't write a biography of someone
you hate. I had heard too many times of people who had pulled out
of a biography after a year'' because they were unable to penetrate
the Rockefeller mask, he added.
</P>
<P>
   But to appease Ms. Godoff, Chernow went to the Rockefeller
Archive Center in Sleepy Hollow, N.Y., where he found a
biographer's gold mine: 1,700 pages of interviews with Rockefeller
done by William O. Inglis for an unpublished biography.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was something about him that repelled me,'' Chernow
said, ``his sanctimoniousness. But he had an extraordinary passion
and intelligence. As soon as I saw the interviews, I saw that he
had a powerful voice. It was a rare opportunity for a biographer to
write about a subject both very well known to posterity but also
very unknown.''
</P>
<P>
   The result was Chernow's 676-page book ``Titan: The Life of John
D. Rockefeller Sr.,'' which was praised by Jack Beatty in The New
York Times Book Review as ``a triumph of the art of biography,''
and has been on the nonfiction best-seller list for six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In researching the book, Chernow discovered some of what he
believed were the reasons for Rockefeller's extreme reticence and
his rigid puritanism. The key to his personality, Chernow said, was
the figure of his father, William Avery Rockefeller, a snake-oil
salesman and adulterer who left his family penniless. A sexually
profligate figure, William brought his mistress, Nancy Brown, to
live in the house with his wife, Eliza, who was John D.'s mother.
Nancy bore William Avery two illegitimate children.
</P>
<P>
   In Chernow's view, William Avery's behavior was a source of
unending shame to his son and resulted in John D.'s penny-pinching,
puritanical personality. ``John D. defined himself in opposition to
his father,'' Chernow said.
</P>
<P>
   Chernow, who is 49, had originally wanted to be a novelist. He
spent five years working on the Rockefeller book in the rented
two-bedroom apartment in Brooklyn Heights that he shares with his
wife, Valerie, a retired teacher and a sculptor.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockefeller family cooperated fully in his research, Chernow
said. ``It is a family which on certain topics is riddled with
strange silences,'' Chernow said. ``John D. Jr. was never able to
ask his father directly about the accusations about Standard Oil.
There were always unanswered questions about the legitimacy of John
D. Sr.'s half sisters. It produced an uneasy conscience in the
family. A couple of the Rockefellers said to me, `We want to know
more about William Avery.'''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, no one in the family seemed to know where William Avery
was buried, Chernow said. He was eventually able to solve the
mystery, discovering the grave site in Freeport, Ill., where he was
buried under an assumed name, Dr. William Levingston.
</P>
<P>
   Chernow said his task as a biographer was to humanize
Rockefeller, a man who had become almost a cartoon character, a
Dickensian figure: tiny, mummified and bald, leeringly handing out
dimes to schoolchildren.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``Rockefeller was the great corporate criminal of his age,''
Chernow said. He was a ruthless competitor, devouring smaller
businesses as he built Standard Oil, conspiring with the railroads
to get rebates not only when he gave them his own oil to transport,
but also when they transported his competitors' oil.
</P>
<P>
   In 1914, his operatives opened fire on striking miners in
Ludlow, Colo., killing several of them. In addition, two women and
11 children were asphyxiated as they hid in an underground bunker.
In 1902, Rockefeller was ``humbled, but not impoverished'' by the
crusading journalist Ida Tarbell, whose father had been put out of
business by Rockefeller. The government began investigating
Standard Oil, which led to its breakup in 1911.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rockefeller always claimed that much of what happened with
Standard Oil had either never happened or had been done by
underlings,'' said Chernow. ``I was able to show that he
masterminded it. To that extent, he comes off worse.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Chernow said, Rockefeller was also a devoted husband who
did not marry into inherited wealth. He was a good father who got
down on his hands and knees to play with his children and arranged
free afternoons to be with them.
</P>
<P>
   Chernow also documents Rockefeller's widespread philanthropy.
His money was responsible for the founding of Spelman College, for
black women, in Atlanta. He also involved himself in other issues
affecting freed blacks. ``For moguls of that era, he was quite
devoid of prejudice,'' Chernow said.
</P>
<P>
   He financed the founding of the University of Chicago, and
established Rockefeller University in New York. ``He funded the
development of a vaccine against yellow fever,'' Chernow pointed
out. ``Rockefeller University developed a serum for cerebrospinal
meningitis.''
</P>
<P>
   Rockefeller embodied the best and worst in the American
character, Chernow said, ``all the money madness, the grasping for
power and riches and also its fundamental decency.'' Like the
Puritans, Rockefeller both worshipped money and feared money.
</P>
<P>
   ``William James, who was one of the few people Rockefeller
opened up to, once said of Rockefeller that he was `so complex,
subtle, oily, fierce, strongly bad and strongly good,''' Chernow
said. ``I leave it up to the reader to decide if the world would be
a better place if this man hadn't lived.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
