<SLUG> BC-FOOD-COLUMN-OWEN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FISH DISHES, RICE WITH MONTANANS' FLAIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN OWEN  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the same week, two generally unfavorable reviews of the movie
``The Horse Whisperer'' appeared in newspapers published in
Missoula, Mont.
</P>
<P>
   Both were written by relatives of mine. Both felt Robert Redford
was guilty of stereotyping Montanans.
</P>
<P>
   I'd have to agree, even though I have not yet seen ``The Horse
Whisperer.''
</P>
<P>
   My argument with Redford (not endorsed by my wife or any other
woman I have met) concerns the film ``A River Runs Through It.''
His stereotype of the Montana fly fisherman varies wildly from my
childhood memories.
</P>
<P>
   It was my experience that the ``art'' of fly-fishing consisted
of slapping mosquitoes with one hand and trying to rescue line from
a bush with the other, while making sure your struggles and
frustrations didn't cause you to step on a rattlesnake. Oh yeah,
and in parts of Montana the post-fishing experience consisted of
nude ``tick checks'' to deliver you from often-fatal Rocky Mountain
Spotted Fever.
</P>
<P>
   My father was an avid fisherman, but he thought a fly was
something that buzzed in your ear while you were affixing a worm to
your hook.
</P>
<P>
   I wasn't wildly crazy about worms. I actually preferred to fish
with a fly. But the places I chose to do it were far away from
mosquitoes and, usually, far removed from trout. I would stand in
midstream away from bushes, wildly whipping my fly line around for
15 or 20 minutes. Then I would go back to the cabin to eat some of
the fish my father caught on worms, in mosquito heaven.
</P>
<P>
   That was long before people flew from New York City to Montana
for the opportunity to catch, and release, a few trout. That, of
course, is a completely idiotic pursuit. Do the mosquitoes give
back the blood? Do the airlines refund your fare if you are skunked
on the Blackfoot River? Blame it all on Robert Redford.
</P>
<P>
   I now do my angling in reliable fishing holes like Costco, where
you can often buy enormous farm-raised trout for about $1.25
apiece. Since they often come four to a package, I sometimes
smoke-cook them on a Weber. The leftover fish are still good the
next day, cold or reheated.
</P>
<P>
   Weber BBQ Trout
</P>
<P>
   Trout (you pick the number)
</P>
<P>
   Garlic salt and freshly ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   Rosemary sprigs, enough for two per trout, or dried rosemary
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkle inside of each trout with garlic salt and pepper. Lay a
couple of rosemary sprigs in the cavity or sprinkle lightly with
dried rosemary.
</P>
<P>
   Light coals in covered barbecue and soak some hickory or other
wood chips in water. When the coals are ready, distribute them
around the outside of the barbecue and toss on the wet wood chips.
Lay a sheet of foil over the rack and top with the trout (I have
cooked four medium trout at a time). Cover the barbecue and let the
fish smoke-cook for 20 to 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Serve one trout on each plate. The top layer of skin should peel
back easily.
</P>
<P>
   If the ``old fishing hole'' yields some farm-raised salmon
instead, I might cook up some:
</P>
<P>
   Salmon in Cider
</P>
<P>
   1 small onion, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 serving-size salmon fillets
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons cooking oil
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter cup chopped ham
</P>
<P>
   Three-quarters cup fresh bread crumbs
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup sweet red pepper, chopped
</P>
<P>
   Three-quarters cup apple cider
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter cup apple vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Spread onion slices in oiled oven dish slightly larger than
needed to lay out the fish. Top with the fillets, skin side down.
Spread with the mustard.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oil in a small skillet and saute the ham and red pepper
pieces briefly. Stir in the bread crumbs. Distribute this mess over
the salmon fillets.
</P>
<P>
   Mix the cider and vinegar and pour around the fillets.
</P>
<P>
   Shove the dish into a preheated 350-degree oven, uncovered, for
30 to 40 minutes or until the salmon is no longer dark red inside.
Serves two.
</P>
<P>
   I like fried potatoes with trout. This rice dish from Joanne
Booth goes great with any kind of salmon.
</P>
<P>
   Joanne's Rice-Peanut Pilaf
</P>
<P>
   Two-thirds cup raw long-grain rice
</P>
<P>
   One-and-one-half cups water
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter cup butter
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped salted peanuts
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon curry powder
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter teaspoon dry mustard
</P>
<P>
   1 bay leaf
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter teaspoon black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon grated lime rind
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter cup lime juice
</P>
<P>
   Simmer the rice in one-and-one-half cups water or according to
package instructions, until soft and fluffy. Remove from heat.
</P>
<P>
   In a skillet, melt the butter and add the onion, peanuts, salt,
curry, mustard, pepper and bay leaf. Stir-cook until lightly brown,
then remove and discard the bay leaf. Stir in the cooked rice. Just
before serving, add the lime juice and rind. Serves four.
</P>
<P>
   As for the subject of Redford's latest film, I once asked Hall
of Fame jockey Eddie Arcaro whether he had particular affection for
any horse he had ridden. Arcaro just looked at me, mouth ajar, as
though I had asked him if he had ever dated a goat. He knew what I
know.
</P>
<P>
   John Owen writes ``The Intermediate Eater'' weekly for the P-I.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
