<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-12 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1208 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PILOBOLUS-DANCE-REVIE     07-12 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PILOBOLUS-DANCE-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ORANGOTANGO': INVENTIVE TUMBLING AND WHIMSICAL MONKEYSHINES
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. on-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(js) 
 By JACK ANDERSON c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Pilobolus Dance Theater turned the Beauty and the
Beast story into a bit of monkeyshines on Saturday night at the
Joyce Theater, when it offered ``Orangotango,'' a new comic duet
choreographed by Alison Chase.
</P>
<P>
   A costume designed by Angelina Avallone made Matt Kent resemble
an Argentine gaucho. But the way the choreography required him to
lurch and fumble suggested that this fellow was a decidedly gauche
gaucho. The impression of clumsiness was intensified as Kent put an
ape mask on his right hand and stared at it quizzically. Moments
later, he slipped it over his head. But the fact that he had now
become a facially hairy ape seemed to embarrass him, and to hide
his appearance, he pulled his sombrero so far down that it obscured
the features.
</P>
<P>
   When Rebecca Anderson entered, he tried to dance with her to
recorded tangos by Astor Piazzolla. Yet the character Kent
portrayed was obviously maladroit, and Ms. Anderson had to give him
a few dancing lessons and guide him through the steps. She also
became curious about why his sombrero concealed his face. Raising
the hat, she gazed at him. Far from appalling her, what she beheld
made her decide that she liked this big ape.
</P>
<P>
   Kent gained confidence after that. Animal passion sometimes
threatened to overwhelm him as he partnered Ms. Anderson. But she
managed to tame any attempts at rough stuff, and he eventually
carried her off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Orangotango'' was a pleasant diversion, even though the
choreography tended to run out of jokes as the duet proceeded. In
fact, several dances by Pilobolus, which are often created through
a collaborative process, share the fault of being more inventive in
their first scenes than in their later ones. Even so, they do get
off to remarkable starts.
</P>
<P>
   Take, for instance, ``Untitled,'' which ended the evening. It
has been surprising people ever since it was choreographed in 1975
by Robby Barnett, Martha Clarke, Moses Pendleton, Michael Tracy,
Jonathan Wolken and Ms. Chase. What causes the gasps of wonder are
the opening episodes in which demure damsels in long 19th-century
dresses suddenly rise to the height of giants, as if, like Alice in
Wonderland, they had swallowed magic potions that made them grow.
The women (Tamieca McCloud and Ms. Anderson, at this performance)
proceed to give birth to nude men who emerge from under their
skirts.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the work shows attempts to preserve decorum, and the
choreography is entertaining throughout. But nothing that follows
those astonishing first moments quite equals them, and they cast
their spell once again at the Joyce.
</P>
<P>
   The program also included works from the repertory. The oldest
was Mr. Wolken's ``Pseudopodia,'' a solo from 1974 that turned Ms.
Anderson into a ball and sent her rolling across the stage.
Although Ms. Anderson's body remained on the ground, her giddy
tossings and turnings made the dance light and airy in spirit.
</P>
<P>
   Pilobolus began as an all-male group, and its productions often
feature male dancers. The present company's men (Gaspard Louis,
Trebien Pollard, Mark Santillano and Kent) were admirably virtuosic
as they scurried and swirled and then did flip-flops over one
another in ``The Particle Zoo,'' a swift-paced ensemble, which
Barnett, Tracy and Wolken created in 1990. And the troupe's two
women and four men got together to form friezelike groupings at a
more deliberate tempo in ``Elysian Fields,'' which Ms. Chase and
Tracy choreographed last year.
</P>
<P>
   Both ``The Particle Zoo'' and ``Elysian Fields'' have a tendency
to ramble. Nevertheless, the action does take the dancers through
some technically spectacular territory.
</P>
<P>
   Pilobolus keeps tumbling through July 25 at the Joyce Theater.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-98 1820EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
