<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-12 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1209 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LUCKYBASTARD-BOOK-REV     07-12 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUCKYBASTARD-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LUCKY BASTARD': WEASELING A MOLE INTO THE WHITE HOUSE
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Publication notes are at end of review.) 
(nk) 
 By CHRISTOPHER LEHMANN-HAUPT 
  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Truth may be stranger than fiction, but in his darkly
entertaining new novel, ``Lucky Bastard,'' Charles McCarry has
taken the American political scene of the past half-century or so
and made of it something considerably stranger than the truth.
</P>
<P>
   The lucky individual of his title is John Fitzgerald Adams, a
young man from working-class Ohio who may well be the love child of
John F. Kennedy, if certain souvenirs of his mother's experiences
in the Navy during World War II are credible evidence. Whether they
are or not, Jack Adams has the irresistible smile, the remorseless
sexual drive and the gift for politics of his namesake.
</P>
<P>
   As Arthur, a Soviet agent who teaches political science at
Columbia, explains to his handler, Dmitri Alexeyivich, the narrator
of McCarry's novel: ``The point is, Jack has a great natural gift.
Since childhood, he has studied people, found out what they wanted,
and made them believe he was giving it to them even when he wasn't.
Without money, without influence, without connections, he has risen
to the top every time. He has this uncanny gift for making others
like him. Trust him. Want to help him. It's like a spell he can
cast at will.''
</P>
<P>
   So Jack may be just the young man to be recommended to Dmitri's
superior, Peter, a lieutenant general of the KGB so capable that he
``could make Andropov laugh and Brezhnev think,'' which, Dmitri
adds, was ``enough to make anyone fear him.'' As Dmitri explains,
Peter believes that the future of the revolution lies in America,
which, thanks to the Vietnam War along with ``pathological fear and
loathing for that nemesis of the faithful, Richard Nixon,'' history
had turned upside down. ``Golden opportunities were falling out of
its pockets,'' Dmitri adds.
</P>
<P>
   What Peter and Dmitri intend to do is befriend and compromise
Jack, underwrite a political career for him, turn him into an agent
of influence and then get him elected president. As Peter tells
Dmitri, referring to Alger Hiss: ``The same people who beatified
Alger will discover and love Jack _ the Jack we are going to design
for them. They will invest every kopeck of their moral and
political capital in him as soon as they hear him speak in
parables. To them, Jack's weaknesses will be strengths, his lies
truths, his crimes miracles.''
</P>
<P>
   Exactly how this plan is carried out is far too byzantine to be
summed up in this space. Nor is it fit for a family paper because
it exploits Jack's outsized sexual drive through the use of
``Swallows, as girls and boys who provide operational sex were
called by our organization,'' Dmitri explains.
</P>
<P>
   Suffice it to say that the plot thickens as intriguingly as in
any of McCarry's recent novels (``Shelley's Heart,'' ``Second
Sight'' and ``The Bride of the Wilderness,'' among others), with
Jack graduating from Harvard Law School, setting up a practice in
Ohio, winning a highly publicized police-corruption case and
beginning his clamber up the ladder of elected offices.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, McCarry displays the inside scraps of knowledge he has
picked up presumably from working in the CIA and writing memoirs
with the likes of former Secretary of State Alexander Haig and
former Secretary of the Treasury Donald Regan. How else could he
come up with such fables and facts as a ``Lubyanka breakfast''
being a cigarette and a bullet? Or that at the battle of Kursk,
between Germany and Russia, ``so many tanks were destroyed on both
sides that Americans saw the rust spot from the moon 25 years
later.'' Or that when the Russians made Janos Kadar the Premier of
Hungary after the 1955 uprising, to make sure that his attraction
to the ladies didn't distract him from his duties, ``the KGB
castrated him _ completely.'' Which, of course, they have to keep
threatening to do to Jack.
</P>
<P>
   And, as usual, McCarry exercises his disdain for the political
left, heaping scorn on draft dodgers, Vietnam War protesters and
``that community of right-thinkers that Peter called the
Unconscious Underground,'' whose members ``manned the junction
boxes of influence and opinion of America.'' What makes his
derision seem particularly vitriolic is that he identifies it with
Peter's, whose ``contempt for those Americans who loved us was
breathtaking,'' Dmitri reports, ``but that is the revolutionary's
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end, the novel's landscape begins to seem eerily
familiar, with Jack besieged by sex scandals as he strives for the
presidency, with his wife blaming a vast conspiracy for his
troubles, with campaign contributions coming in from questionable
sources, with an Asian financial crisis threatening to undo the
American economy and with problems connected with a bank's collapse
reaching out to ensnare Jack from the state where he once was
governor. Increasingly as it goes along, ``Lucky Bastard'' reads
like a ``Primary Colors'' written with imagination.
</P>
<P>
   The only moment that McCarry sounds less than completely cynical
is when a U.S. attorney general refuses to go after Jack. ``I
believe that democracy is God's work,'' he tells Jack's enemies.
``Jack Adams may be exactly what you say he is. But he was elected
... by the people, and the people is always right. It's up to them
to decide his fate.''
</P>
<P>
   This may well reflect McCarry's own outlook. On the other hand,
he has earlier described this attorney general as looking ``like an
especially stupid horse that had just awakened to find itself in
bed with the severed head of a Hollywood producer.''
</P>
<P>
   In any case, at the conclusion of ``Lucky Bastard'' it is not
the American people who decide if democracy can be saved from Jack,
but instead a determined individual, one of many vivid characters
in the story who push it beyond mere political satire into a
corrosively penetrating view of the contemporary cultural ethos.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `LUCKY BASTARD'
</P>
<P>
   By Charles McCarry.
</P>
<P>
   385 pages. Random House Bertelsmann(DG). $24.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
