<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-12 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1224 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IBM-WATSON-LABS-ART-8     07-12 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IBM-WATSON-LABS-ART-865(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IBM OPENS ITS RESEARCH LABS TO SURPRISING RESULTS
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(nk) 
 By STEVE LOHR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   IBM's famed research division, like so many parts of the
company, has been reshaped and refocused since Louis V. Gerstner
Jr. took over as the chairman of IBM Corp. five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The company's research unit had long been an unrivaled engine of
innovation for the computer industry. Its labs produced the Fortran
programming language, relational databases, the D-RAM memory chip,
the RISC chip design, token ring computer networks and five Nobel
laureates.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the business criticism of IBM's research efforts had been
that its labs were too insular, too ivory tower with too little
payoff for IBM. Indeed, an internal analysis at the start of the
1990s found that only 2 percent to 5 percent of the research
division's work went toward products and services for IBM
customers.
</P>
<P>
   The doors of IBM's labs are far more open today. IBM researchers
spend about 25 percent of their time with customers. Collaborative
work with leading universities has been stepped up. More outsiders
have been recruited, both to work full time and for brief stints.
</P>
<P>
   The new approach at IBM was evident last week when researchers,
summer interns and executives including Gerstner gathered for a day
for an exercise in free-range futurism _ unfettered discussions of
where technology may be heading by the year 2020. ``A real example
of the new IBM,'' Gerstner observed.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the change has been an attempt to tackle an increasingly
important challenge for technology companies in particular: How to
foster innovation and then translate new ideas into new products,
services and profits.
</P>
<P>
   At IBM, there are some encouraging signs that its performance on
that front is improving markedly. Its data-storage research, for
example, is behind the company's rise in the business of disk
drives for laptop computers, a higher-profit market in which IBM
now has a 40 percent share. Its researchers have also designed
low-cost, high-speed chips for use in cellular phones and other
wireless devices, which could open up a big new market for IBM.
</P>
<P>
   ``IBM always had the knock of not commercializing its
research,'' said Steven Milunovich, an analyst for Merrill Lynch.
``That's not really true anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   The company as a whole has rebounded remarkably from 1993, the
year Gerstner arrived, when the work force was slashed and IBM
reported an $8 billion loss. Last year, the company earned $6.1
billion on revenues of $78.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   An impressive comeback. But if IBM is to generate strong growth
for the future, its research labs must pave the way. And to make a
difference in a company the size of IBM, that means producing some
real winners.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real challenge is to come up with revolutionary technology
that blows away the competition as its labs once did in the
mainframe-computer era of 1960s and 1970s,'' said David Yoffie, a
professor at the Harvard Business School. ``It's not clear that IBM
can really do that anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing the business necessity of investing for the future,
Gerstner spared the research unit from the deep cuts absorbed by
some company operations. Last year, the research unit's budget
reached $600 million and its payroll increased to 2,785 people,
both figures higher than in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``IBM has valued and invested in its research operations even in
difficult times for the company,'' said Charles Kruger, dean of
research at Stanford University.
</P>
<P>
   To try to prod people to think big and commercially, IBM invited
an eclectic collection of 1,200 researchers, executives and summer
interns to a series of one-day sessions last week at the company's
seven research labs around the world.
</P>
<P>
   IBM often organizes so-called brainstorming meetings, but it had
not done anything as large before. It was an effort to put people
with different perspectives together, spark some original thinking
and impress the interns _ mainly computer science students _ that
IBM might be a good place to work someday.
</P>
<P>
   The largest of the gatherings was at IBM's research
headquarters, the T.J. Watson Research Center in Yorktown Heights,
N.Y. The morning began with a short talk by Gerstner emphasizing
that technology's highest purpose is to solve real-world problems.
``I want this to be something more than brilliant irrelevance,'' he
told the group. ``I want something substantive to come out of
this.''
</P>
<P>
   The day consisted largely of a series of mind-stretching games,
played in teams of a dozen or so. Questions were prompts: What will
a day in the life of a child be like in 2020? How will technology
change the look and operation of a home? What will be the most
far-reaching applications of ``deep computing,'' best known for its
use in IBM's chess-playing supercomputer Deep Blue, which beat
Garry Kasparov last year?
</P>
<P>
   Just what will come out of such sessions remains to be seen. The
musings, debates and product ideas were all recorded, and the
research staff will later pore through the record over the next
couple of weeks, panning for nuggets. ``We're looking for a few
themes we can cull out, perhaps prompting us to think about things
slightly differently in research,'' explained Paul Horn, senior
vice president of research.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Meyerson, a research scientist, came prospecting for
ideas, especially from the summer interns. ``You bet I expect to
get something out of this,'' he said. Meyerson recalled how a young
Egyptian graduate student from MIT walked into his office a few
years ago and proceeded to question long-held assumptions about the
speed at which electrons can travel through silicon. The student
proved to be correct, and his insight helped Meyerson's work.
</P>
<P>
   The blunt, burly Meyerson, 44, has become a kind of in-house
poster boy for how much things have changed within IBM research. In
the 1980s, he and a group of IBM scientists developed
semiconductors that used standard silicon with germanium, an
element that is so efficient at conducting electricity that it can
drastically reduce power consumption in devices using such chips.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Meyerson had hoped the chip design could be used in
mainframe computers. When IBM decided to overhaul its mainframes
with another chip technology, Meyerson was advised to fold up his
silicon germanium project. He did not. With the help of his
research superiors and a few believers in IBM's microelectronics
division, Meyerson set about channeling his orphaned project toward
a new market _ fast, cheap chips for use in cellular phones and
other wireless devices.
</P>
<P>
   IBM recently began large-scale production of its silicon
germanium chips, and the company believes this could become a
$1-billion-a-year business within five years. Today, Meyerson is
part scientist and part entrepreneur, building a business. He deals
with chip production problems, scouts for acquisitions and makes
sales calls to corporate customers.
</P>
<P>
   His campaign of semiauthorized guerrilla warfare within IBM, he
said, would have never been allowed to flourish in the old days.
``Now, the attitude is: If you've got a great idea, do it,''
Meyerson said. ``I never would have been allowed to do this five or
six years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   To the college interns, Gerstner's message that research must
make its way to the marketplace is a sermon to the converted.
Indeed, their main reservation seems to be that even the new IBM
moves too slowly for their tastes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to make products and make money,'' said Anit Agarual, a
junior at Cornell University. ``A lot of the things done here take
five years to get out of the labs or never make it into the
marketplace at all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
