<HEADER>
A1238 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT &LR;      07-12 0507
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: MUSEUM WITH A DIFFERENCE; MUSIC IN THE ALPS; GREAT
MUSICALS IN THE CAPITAL; JOURNEY INTO THE PAST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Switzerland)  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Most museums owe their collections to donors or
acquisitive curators. But the National Academy Museum at Fifth
Avenue and 89th Street is different. The collection of the academy,
founded in 1825, has been assembled by the artists, who have
provided a representative sample of their work as a condition of
membership.
</P>
<P>
   The collection is one of the country's largest: 2,200 paintings,
250 sculptures and some 5,000 works on paper by more than 1,200
artists. Beginning on Wednesday and continuing through Aug. 2,
``The Academy and American Art: History and Highlights'' features
more than 40 19th- and 20th-century works ranging from William
Merritt Chase and Thomas Eakins to Wayne Thiebaud and Jamie Wyeth.
Information: (212) 369-4880.
</P>
<P>
   Tuning Up
</P>
<P>
   In the scenic village of Verbier in the Swiss Alps, beginning on
Friday, the fifth Verbier Festival and Academy will fill the nights
with music until Aug. 2. The festival's orchestra in residence, the
Symphony Orchestra of the Curtis Institute, will be led by
conductors like Kurt Masur and Yuri Temirkanov, and the schedule
calls for such soloists as the violinists Sarah Chang and Maxim
Vengerov, the pianists Elisabeth Leonskaja and Yefim Bronfman and
the percussionist Evelyn Glennie.
</P>
<P>
   On opening night, with Antonio Pappano as conductor and Vengerov
as soloist, the festival will offer works by Mozart, Rodion
Schedrin and Berlioz. Information: 011-41-27-771-7050.
</P>
<P>
   Encores
</P>
<P>
   Rediscovered realms of American musical theater: That's the
prospect at the Eisenhower Theater in the Kennedy Center for the
Performing Arts in Washington when a concert series of of great
musicals opens at 7:30 p.m. on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The series, ``Words and Music,'' will begin with performances
through Sunday of ``Bells Are Ringing,'' starring Faith Prince in
the tale of a timid telephone operator's entanglements in the lives
of the people she listens to. Jule Styne wrote the music; Betty
Comden and Adolph Green provided the book and lyrics. Coming up are
``Purlie,'' from July 30 to Aug. 2, and ``Where's Charley?'' from
Aug. 13 to 16. Information: (202) 467-4600 or (800) 444-1324.
</P>
<P>
   Time Tripping
</P>
<P>
   SAG HARBOR, N.Y. _ A two-stage journey into the past beckons
theatergoers to the Bay Street Theater this week. The first
reunites them with Twiggy, the svelte supermodel of the 1960s who
went to Broadway and film roles. The second reunites them with Noel
Coward and Gertrude Lawrence. The vehicle is a musical biography
called ``Noel and Gertie,'' co-starring James Warwick.
</P>
<P>
   The show, with sets and costumes by Tony Walton, is the creation
of the critic Sheridan Morley, based on his biographies of Lawrence
and Coward, his godfather. The show opens on Wednesday and runs
through Aug. 2. Information: (516) 725-9500.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
