<HEADER>
A1242 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NAACP-AIDS-COX     07-12 0558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAACP-AIDS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Group protests to bring AIDS awareness into forefront at NAACP
conventionBy Jennifer Brett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Tracie Edness had used drugs, but no needles. She'd
had unprotected sex, but wasn't a prostitute.
</P>
<P>
   No way she was a candidate for the HIV virus, she thought.
</P>
<P>
   She was wrong. She was diagnosed a week before Christmas 1991
with the virus that causes AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   ``Behind every choice there is a consequence. That was my
consequence,'' said Edness, one of more than 50 people who marched
through downtown Atlanta Sunday in support of education and
prevention efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The event, called ``Outrage Over AIDS: A Walk For Action,'' was
part of the NAACP's convention.
</P>
<P>
   Edness, of Douglasville, Ga. yelled louder than anyone as the
marchers shouted ``No progress, no peace!'' and ``Action for
AIDS!''
</P>
<P>
   According to the NAACP, AIDS is the leading killer of black
people aged 25 to 44. Although blacks make up approximately 12
percent of the country's population, they account for about 57
percent of new HIV infections.
</P>
<P>
   Also, black women represent 56 percent of AIDS cases among
women, and blacks ages 13 to 24 are estimated to account for 63
percent of new HIV cases in that age group, the NAACP's statistics
say.
</P>
<P>
   ``This disease has reached astronomical proportions in black
communities and Latino communities in America,'' said NAACP
president and CEO Kweisi Mfume, who was among the marchers. ``The
best way to deal with it is to talk about it openly, get the myths
and the taboos off the table and to recognize that it can affect
and infect any of us.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the issue is one of social justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are advocating on behalf of all those who are infected with
this virus, all of those who are about to be infected and don't
understand that because of their behavior they will be, and all
those who have died as a result of this disease,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Marcher Victor Dunbar, who is president of the Fairfax, Va.,
branch of the NAACP, said he has lost two cousins to AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   ``These were men who were educated,'' Dunbar said. ``It's such a
waste. Both of these young men had a lot to offer.''
</P>
<P>
   He supports education efforts and more funding for research.
</P>
<P>
   ``It needs to be on everybody's landscape,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Edness, the HIV patient and counselor, said that before her
diagnosis, she had been telling her friends she'd been tested with
negative results.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was tested, I had no idea my results would come back
positive. But they did,'' the 39-year-old said. ``I was upset and
angry. I wanted to know who did this to me.''
</P>
<P>
   She learned three years ago who infected her, and has forgiven
him. But early on, she felt despair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I became very suicidal,'' said Edness, mother of three and
grandmother of four, none of whom are infected. ``I was walking the
streets of downtown Atlanta trying to figure out how I was going to
take my life.''
</P>
<P>
   She came across a stranger and told him she needed to talk. He
sat on a curb with her as she told him her story. Turns out he'd
been living with AIDS for five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `I don't know if I believe you, but just for today,
you've given me hope,' '' she told the man. ``I want to go home.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
