A1243 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NAACP-DAY-COX     07-12 0601
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAACP-DAY-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Youth delegates debate how to bring more students into fold
</P>
<P>
   By Christy Oglesby
</P>
<P>
   C. 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There is a balance between politics and parties and
academic achievement and activism. The challenge, said young black
students from across the country, is finding that balance so the
National Association for the Advancement of Colored People can
maintain its momentum on college campuses.
</P>
<P>
   The steady influx of young visionaries into the NAACP is
important enough to be the basis for this year's convention theme,
``Preparing Tomorrow's Leaders Today.'' However, many of the
students said they have difficulty bringing in soldiers and keeping
them motivated long enough to become generals.
</P>
<P>
   About 40 youth delegates gathered Sunday morning during the
organization's national convention at the World Congress Center to
discuss maintaining and growing college chapters, and their
frustration was obvious.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's the membership competition from popular fraternities
and sororities. Then academic demands leave little time for
political activism,'' said Taliah Givens, a panelist from Georgia
Tech, who said she often is in a laboratory until 3 a.m. when
school is in session. And no one can overlook plain old apathy.
</P>
<P>
   Where African-American students are plentiful, they can get
lulled into thinking they don't have to join their college NAACP
chapter because someone else will, one delegate said. And at
predominately white colleges, the pool from which to draw members
is pretty shallow.
</P>
<P>
   But the woe-are-we session didn't last long. Students
participating in Sunday's session soon discovered no shortage of
solutions or college activism, just a shortage of sharing
strategies among themselves. Delegates from the same states were
surprised to learn what was happening on campuses just two hours
away. By meetings end, many had resolved to share e-mail addresses
and use the NAACP's chat line to continue the flow of ideas.
</P>
<P>
   What started as frustration became determination after a young
woman from Ohio State University told the audience how the college
NAACP chapter took over the university's administration building
for eight days until school leaders heard its demands. The young
delegates applauded the action.
</P>
<P>
   Students share-- what they are doing on their campuses and
encouraged one another with offensive strategies, from securing
positions on college administrative boards to enlisting the help of
fraternal organizations in procuring members.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, said Taj Brown, 19, from Lock Haven University in
Pennsylvania, college chapters must not get duped into believing
they need to promote a party-packed agenda to compete with
fraternal organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not a social organization. We are an activist
organization,'' said Brown. ``When we are what we are supposed to
be _ political activist _ we will attract young people.''
</P>
<P>
   At the University of Toledo, the college chapter is starting a
mentoring program to reach out to younger children in the community
and regularly invites local politicians to keep chapter members
educated about the community issues outside of their campus.
</P>
<P>
   Dawnnay Butler, president of the University of Toledo chapter,
encouraged her fellow delegates to keep strong programs in place
and to focus on freshman who are looking to be a part of something.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be consistent,'' Butler, 20 said. ``People don't
want to be a part of anything that's not consistent.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
