<SLUG> BC-NAACP-NOTES13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Notebook: Quotes and scenes from the NAACP convention
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ ``Michael Jordan is not my hero,'' said 17-year-old
Lendeh Sherman, as she stood in front of two of her paintings on
exhibit at the World Congress Center, site of the NAACP convention.
</P>
<P>
   One painting depicts the four little girls who died when a bomb
exploded in their Birmingham church in 1963. It is untitled. In the
other, a black man sits at a lunch counter while someone pours
ketchup on his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``He might be hurt but he knows he's doing something that's
right,'' said Lendeh, who is from Maryland and will attend art
school in New York this fall. The man in the lunch counter
represents all those who took place in the famous lunch counter
sit-ins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may not know them, but we would not be where we are today
without them,'' Lendeh said.
</P>
<P>
   That piece is titled ``Heros.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Garrett can feel eyes on him as he walks the aisles of the
convenience stores in his small Ohio town. Last year when his
grandmother sent him into a grocery store parking lot to turn off
her car's headlights, a clerk in the store called the cops.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everywhere I go, there's somebody watching me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Steve, who wants to be a director, entered the Afro-Academic,
Cultural, Technological and Scientific Olympics (ACT-SO) film
competition with a short piece about the racism he endures. The
last scene is shot in his school, which he says is a haven from the
stares.
</P>
<P>
   ``The students treat me equally,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nefertiti Oji-Njideka, 17, has also lived with racism. When she
was in the fifth grade, her family lived with her grandparents for
a year while their home was being remodeled.
</P>
<P>
   She was the only black student in the school in her
grandmother's Kentucky town. It was then that she started writing
poetry.
</P>
<P>
   ``You feel a little bit better,'' said Nefertiti, who entered
the ACT-SO poetry competition. It is called ``Sunshine,'' and has a
simple, positive theme.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to make it a racial poem,'' she said. ``I'm not
bitter at all. I don't feel any hate.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in Dayton, Ohio, Nefertiti will be president of her senior
class this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Ricardo Durham, who remembers eating at the back of restaurants
when he was his son's age, brought 10-year-old Ricardo II to the
NAACP convention Sunday. He wants to start teaching his son about
those days, and the changes the NAACP has helped bring about.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went last year in Pittsburgh and had a real positive
experience,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ricardo II was indeed full of questions _ but they didn't
exactly involve civil rights. He wanted to know all about his belly
button. His dad explained that unborn children get nutrition
through the umbilical cord.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ice cream?'' the boy asked. ``Broccoli?''
</P>
<P>
   The elder Ricardo smiled and patiently answered his son's
questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We brought him down here so he can connect with the various
organizations,'' Durham said as he prepared to enter the convention
rooms with his son, who doesn't have to worry about being told to
sit in the back of restaurants. He can concentrate on more
important things, like belly buttons.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
