<HEADER>
A1245 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NAACP-SPOTLIGHT13-COX     07-12 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAACP-SPOTLIGHT13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Black churches, NAACP may have stronger bond in future
 &HT;    By John Blake
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The NAACP and the black church are two institutions
that have helped move the African-American community forward this
century, always taking the lead when issues of justice and civil
rights are being questioned.
</P>
<P>
   But the relationship between the NAACP and the black church has
historically been distant. That, however, may be changing.
</P>
<P>
   During the NAACP's national convention in Atlanta this week,
delegates will explore various strategies to insure its survival in
the 21st century. One option is working closer with the the black
church.
</P>
<P>
   Noel Erskine understands the complex relationship between the
NAACP and the black church. He is an associate professor of
theology at Emory University and author of, ``King Among The
Theologians'' (Pilgrim Press, $14.95). During a recent interview,
he shared his views about these two institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why has the black church and the civil rights movement been
so intertwined?
</P>
<P>
   A: The civil rights movement came out of the black church. The
connection was there from the start. The civil rights leaders were
ministers. The black politicians were ministers. The black church
is the one institution that we've always had that has somehow
remained intact. I don't think we can talk about civil rights
without talking about the black church at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why has the NAACP had a distant relationship with the black
church?
</P>
<P>
   A: The NAACP was different. W.E.B. DuBois (one of the NAACP's
founders) . . . was mesmerized by the black church. He gave us
wonderful critiques about the black pastor and the importance of
the black church. But he himself was more on the outside than the
inside of the . . . church. The NAACP was historically more
concerned with legal issues, which the black church didn't see as
its main agenda. But I think they're getting closer now.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How and why are they getting closer?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think that black theology, which came out of the civil
rights movement, is helping younger ministers, who grew up in the
'50s and '60s, to make the connection between the church and
justice issues. We had a tradition where we said that good church
people don't go to the court. The black church was unsure about
going to court to fight for justice. The church was content to sit
back and let the NAACP do that for us. But since (Martin Luther)
King and Malcolm (X), the black church has not been afraid to take
on justice issues, such as voting rights and desegregating schools.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Could the NAACP learn anything from the black church?
</P>
<P>
   A: In the long haul, if it is to survive, it must recognize the
importance of spirituality as the bedrock of the black community.
For good or bad, the masses of black people are still in the black
church. You can't get to those people without the . . . church. The
one person who discovered that was Jesse (Jackson). When Jackson
ran for president, everywhere he went, he went to the black church.
I remember going to one church and there were two collection
plates, one for Jesse and one for Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Has the black church lost its sense of political activism?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think we have. We have grown tired. There's not a national
forum. There's not a national consensus on issues. We're doing
stuff, but it's each little black church . . . There are many
issues that the NAACP and the black church could cooperate on
without both losing their focus.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
