u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NASCAR13-COX     07-12 0442
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASCAR13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Burton takes second consecutive Jiffy Lube 300
 &HT;    By Tom McCollister
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUDEN, N.H. _ As concession speech's go, the one delivered
Sunday by rival crew chief Ray Evernham on behalf of Jeff Burton
was right on the button with 50 laps remaining in the Jiffy Lube
300.
</P>
<P>
   Burton had a 5.6 second lead at the time of Evernham's missive,
and was able to put his Taurus on cruise control, taking the
checkered flag 7.43 seconds ahead of teammate Mark Martin.
</P>
<P>
   It was Burton's second consecutive Jiffy Lube 300 victory, and
career fourth overall. He won twice a year ago, at Texas Motor
Speedway and Martinsville Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   But none of those came close to Sunday's dominating victory. He
started fifth, was running second at the 75-lap mark, took the lead
for the first time at lap 80 and was leading at the 150th and
225th. He never ran lower than fifth and was in front for 191 of
the final 221.
</P>
<P>
   ''We win on Sunday by what we do on Saturday,'' Burton said of
the work by he and crew chief Frank Stoddard. ''In Saturday's
practice, we got passed by John Andretti. It got our attention. We
went to work and did more things on our race car.''
</P>
<P>
   It made a difference. Once the race was underway, he decidedly
had the best car.
</P>
<P>
   Only Gordon offered any challenge, leading four times for a
season low 73 yards. Martin had none. Pole sitter Ricky Craven led
for 13, but they came early, and he finished 29th.
</P>
<P>
   ''Nobody could touch the 99 (Burton). He definitely was in a
different league than the rest of us,'' Gordon said. ''I don't know
what they found, but they sure found something. We got out early
and led some laps, but I knew it was just a matter of time before
they ran us down.''
</P>
<P>
   Boring? Yes. To all but Burton. He had one close call that could
have ended his day on the first lap.
</P>
<P>
   ''I had messed up and missed a gear, and the 44 car (Kyle Petty)
got by me and scooted up the track, and when he did I went under
him. And he didn't know I was there and maybe I was pushing a
little too hard early.
</P>
<P>
   ''We got together and on the back stretch, he wanted to let me
know how he felt about it. So, the next thing I know, we're almost
in the grass, and I decided to to back off and get away from that.
That could have been it for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Others had their narrow escapes earlier. There were nine
cautions for 90 laps, and six cars failed to finish due to
accidents _ Hut Stricklin, Lake Speed, Gary Bradberry, Ted
Musgrave, Rick Bickle and Geoff Bodine.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
