<SLUG> BC-AL-WEEK13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    American League Week in Review
 &HT;    (EDS:The Sunday games still out: Red Sox-O's, Rangers-A's,
Mariners-Angels)
 &HT;    By I. J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST
</P>
<P>
   _ Records: Yankees 4-0 (65-20), Orioles 3-0 (41-50), Blue Jays
1-3 (47-45), Red Sox 0-3 (52-36), Devil Rays 0-4 (34-56).
</P>
<P>
   _ Interleague records: Yankees 13-3, Red Sox 9-7, Blue Jays 9-7,
Orioles 5-11, Devil Rays 5-11.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wild-card hunt: Red Sox lead league, Blue Jays 7 1/2 games
back.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big story: The Yankees just keep rolling along. They have
won 10 straight and at the current pace would win an incredible 124
games, eight more than the major league record.
</P>
<P>
   _ The hot bats: The Yankees are still without the .353-hitting
Bernie Williams, who was supposed to be back after the break but
aggravated his knee injury on a rehab assignment.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big arms: New York's David Cones has allowed just three
runs in his last 28 innings and became the league's first 13-game
winner.
</P>
<P>
   _ The unexpected: Saturday's sellout for the Devil Rays was
their first since opening day.
</P>
<P>
   _ The injuries: The Orioles placed designated hitter Harold
Baines on the DL with a strained left hamstring. Jeffrey Hammonds
replaced Baines.
</P>
<P>
   _ The scoop: Tampa Bay has been shut out in five of its last 12
games.
</P>
<P>
   CENTRAL
</P>
<P>
   _ Records: Tigers 3-1 (37-51), White Sox 2-2 (37-53), Indians
2-2 (52-37), Royals 2-2 (40-50), Twins 2-2 (42-48).
</P>
<P>
   _ Interleague records: Indians 10-6, Twins 7-9, White Sox 7-9,
Tigers 7-9, Royals 9-7.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wild-card hunt: None.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big story: Baseball is trying to eliminate the large
number of two game series next year but to make the new schedule
work the White Sox will play a one-game series at Baltimore to open
the season.
</P>
<P>
   _ The hot bats: Cleveland's Manny Ramirez has 36 RBIs in his
last 24 games.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big arms: Tigers righthander Brian Moehler is now 8-0 at
Tiger Stadium with a league low 2.05 home ERA.
</P>
<P>
   _ The unexpected: with two more appearances, Indians reliever
Paul Assenmacher will pass Walter Johnson for 20th on the all-time
list.
</P>
<P>
   _ The injuries: Indians hitting coach Charlie Manuel will have
quadruple bypass surgery after having a mild heart attack during
the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   _ The scoop: The Tigers are trying to acquire Joey Hamilton from
the Padres and the rumor is the deal would have the Reds sending
Pete Harnisch to San Diego and Cincinnati getting prospects from
Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   WEST
</P>
<P>
   _ Records: Rangers 3-0 (51-39), Mariners 2-1 (39-52), Angels 1-2
(50-37), A's 0-3 (41-48).
</P>
<P>
   _ Interleague records: Angels 10-6, Rangers 8-8, A's 8-8,
Mariners 7-9.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wild-card hunt: Angels 2 1/2 games back.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big story: What has happened to the Angels? They have won
only once this month and the Rangers have passed them, going in
Sunday's action with a half of a game lead.
</P>
<P>
   _ The hot bats: Seattle's Ken Griffey Jr. is on fire. Since June
23, he has hit nine homers, brought in 17 runs and raised his
average nine points to .296.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big arms: Seattle's Randy Johnson pushed his record to 8-8
Saturday with a complete game victory and has struck out 12 or more
in his last five starts.
</P>
<P>
   _ The unexpected: The Mariners have moved third baseman Russ
Davis to left field and he becomes the 58th player to land their
since 1989 besides Ken Griffey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   _ The injuries: Angels righthander Mike James underwent
reconstructive surgery on his right elbow and will miss the rest of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   _ The scoop: Seattle Johnson and teammate David Segui got in a
wrestling match before Saturday's game. Not punches were thrown,
according to witnesses, but Segui missed the game with a sprained
right wrist.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
