<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NL-WEEK13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    National League Week in Review
 &HT;    (EDS: Sunday's games still out: Braves-Marlins, Giants-Rockies,
Padres-Dodgers, Reds-Diamondbacks)
 &HT;    By I. J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST
</P>
<P>
   _ Records: Phillies 3-0 (46-42), Marlins 2-1 (34-56), Mets 2-2
(46-41), Expos 2-2 (36-54), Braves 1-2 (60-31).
</P>
<P>
   _ Interleague records: Mets 9-7, Braves 9-7, Marlins 8-8,
Phillies 7-9, Expos 6-10.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wild-card hunt: Mets 4 games back, Phillies 4 1/2 games back.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big story: The Mets' Todd Hundley came back to the club
Saturday and played a position other than catcher for the first
time in his career, going 1-for-4 against the Expos in left field.
</P>
<P>
   _ The hot bats: The Phillies are hitting a league-leading .278.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big arms: The Braves are walking a league-low 2.7 hitters
a game.
</P>
<P>
   _ The unexpected: Braves Greg Maddux was beaten by the Marlins,
his first loss on the road since April 2 of last season. He had won
16 straight on the road.
</P>
<P>
   _ The injuries: The Mets' Armando Reynoso, who has been out with
discomfort in his right elbow, may rejoin the team this week.
</P>
<P>
   _ The scoop: Marlins manager Jim Leyland 's club opened the
second half against the Braves and said, ``I've got Smoltz, Neagle,
Maddux and Glavine, and my bottom gum surgery. It's not the best
way to start.'' The Marlins took three of four from the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   CENTRAL
</P>
<P>
   _ Records: Reds 2-0 (41-50), Cardinals 3-1 (43-47), Cubs 2-2
(50-41), Brewers 2-2 (45-44), Astros 1-3 (54-37), Pirates 0-3
(40-51).
</P>
<P>
   _ Interleague records: Astros 10-4, Brewers 8-6, Reds 7-6,
Pirates 6-7, Cubs 5-8, Cardinals 4-9.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wild-card hunt: Cubs 2 games back.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big story: Just a couple of weeks ago the Reds had lost 11
straight, but now they have won 11 of their last 12.
</P>
<P>
   _ The hot bats: The Cubs' Sammy Sosa hit his 35th homer and
joins Ernie Banks as the only players in team history to hit as
least that many homers in four consecutive seasons.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big arms: Chicago's Kerry Wood is quickly moving closer to
Curt Schilling in the strikeout lead, with 148. Schilling is at
185. Wood spent the first five starts of the season in the minors.
</P>
<P>
   _ The unexpected: Cardinals starter Todd Stottlemyre became the
first major league pitcher in 19 years to hit anywhere but ninth in
the starting lineup, hitting eighth against the Astros. The last
pitcher to do so was Philadelphia's Steve Carlton.
</P>
<P>
   _ The injuries: The Cardinals activated Ron Gant from the
disabled list and he hit a home run on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   _ The scoop: Mark McGwire's three homers over the weekend puts
him on pace to hit 70.
</P>
<P>
   WEST
</P>
<P>
   _ Records: Dodgers 2-1 (45-45), Padres 1-2 (58-33), Giants 0-2
(52-39), Diamondbacks 0-2 (30-60) Rockies 0-2 (39-52).
</P>
<P>
   _ Interleague records: Dodgers 8-5, Giants 8-5, Padres 6-7,
Diamondbacks 5-8, Rockies 4-8.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wild-card hunt: Giants lead league, Dodgers 6 1/2 games back.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big story: Rockies starter Daryl Kile, a 19-game winner
last year for the Astros, won for the first time at Coors Field
this year when he beat the Giants on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   _ The hot bats: Despite being 13 games under .500, the Rockies,
hitting .277, are just one point away from the league lead.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big arms: In his last two games, San Diego's Andy Ashby
has thrown complete games of 75 and 88 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   _ The unexpected: San Diego's Tony Gwynn has gone hitless in 14
straight at-bats, tying the longest drought of his career.
</P>
<P>
   _ The injuries: The Diamondbacks will get Omar Daal back in the
rotation on Tuesday. Daal has been out with a strained hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   _ The scoop: The Dodgers have reopened talks with the Mariners
for Randy Johnson. Tommy Lasorda is offering infielder Wilton
Guerrero and Antonio Osuna, but Seattle wants Ismael Valdes.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
