<HEADER>
A1254 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEUTSCHEBANK-U.S.-500     07-12 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEUTSCHEBANK-U.S.-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEUTSCHE BANK WANTS A U.S. INVESTMENT TIE-IN
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Calif, N.Y.) (js) 
By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ Reeling from the defections of several top
investment bankers, Deutsche Bank is looking to buy or team up with
a U.S. investment firm to shore up its position in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are absolutely committed to investing more in the U.S.A.,''
said Rolf-Ernst Breuer, chairman of the bank, which is Germany's
largest. ``It isn't enough to be Wall Street watchers; we must be
Wall Street participants.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Breuer said he had no specific target now, he
acknowledged that the bank must either make an outright acquisition
or enter into a significant alliance with a U.S. company. ``It
could be an acquisition, but I could easily imagine a joint
venture,'' he said at a meeting with reporters on Friday night.
``But we have to do our homework. We should not lose sight of what
fits well with Deutsche Bank.''
</P>
<P>
   Other financial industry executives have been speculating for
months about potential acquisition targets for Deutsche Bank. Among
the most frequently mentioned names are those of J.P. Morgan, Paine
Webber, Lehman Brothers and, until recently, Credit Suisse First
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Another name circulating is the venture capital firm Hambrecht &AMP;
Quist of San Francisco, which specializes in corporate finance for
high-technology companies. Hambrecht &AMP; Quist might fill a gap at
Deutsche Bank that was created by the departures of three top
investment bankers who specialized in technology.
</P>
<P>
   Their departures gave Deutsche Bank a rude lesson in the limits
to which money buys loyalty on Wall Street. Three years ago, the
bank recruited star deal makers from Wall Street firms like Morgan
Stanley and Merrill Lynch with huge signing bonuses and pay
packages. At the time, rival firms bitterly complained that
Deutsche Bank was inflating the already sky-high salaries of
investment executives.
</P>
<P>
   But two weeks ago, Credit Suisse First Boston recruited the
three investment bankers for what were said to be hundreds of
millions of dollars. The most visible loss was that of Frank
Quattrone, whom Deutsche Bank had recruited from Morgan Stanley and
who headed Deutsche's technology business in Menlo Park, Calif.
Quattrone, who had written a letter in March to assure clients that
he had no plans to leave Deutsche Bank, is reported to have been
offered a package worth about $250 million. He is also taking as
many as 100 co-workers with him.
</P>
<P>
   From a strategic point, Deutsche Bank executives say they want
to increase their U.S. presence both as investment bankers and
money managers. But in investment banking, Breuer has hinted at
somewhat cautious goals of expanding in certain areas. ``We don't
want to be everything to everybody,'' he said, adding that the
focus has been on ``future-oriented'' businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, he left no doubt that Deutsche Bank had lowered its
expectations of becoming a full competitor in the United States
with the likes of Merrill Lynch, Goldman, Sachs and Morgan Stanley.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Even before Quattrone's abrupt departure, Deutsche Bank had been
having problems in its investment banking. Having bought the
venerable Morgan Grenfell of Britain in 1989, and then investing
billions of dollars in its expansion, costs had rapidly risen and
the bank failed to find its footing in the crucial area of mergers,
acquisitions and corporate finance.
</P>
<P>
   Tensions increased as Breuer started to clamp down on costs and
exert tighter control. Last year, he pushed through a broad
restructuring that brought the London-based investment bank under
the direct control of Frankfurt and did away with the name Morgan
Grenfell. That led to the resignations of the two top executives at
Morgan Grenfell, Carter McLelland and Maurice Thompson, in March.
</P>
<P>
   Breuer insisted on Friday that he had no intention of backing
away from Deutsche Bank's broad push into investment banking.
``There is no pullback with regard to investment banking
opportunities,'' he said. The acquisition of Morgan Grenfell ``was
a brainchild of my own,'' he said, ``and I am still convinced we
could not survive without a third pillar of earnings, which is in
investment banking.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the surprise at Quattrone's recent departure, Breuer
also insisted that Deutsche Bank did not want to retreat from the
United States. Though the bank has no ambition of trying to compete
with big Wall Street firms on a full range of services, Breuer
said, it does want to have a ``meaningful presence.'' In other
words, it still wants to be the biggest foreign bank operating in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Deutsche Bank executives are still angry about
what they consider the shabby behavior of Quattrone and his
colleagues. Even though Deutsche Bank raided rival banks, its
executives complain bitterly about the callous ``job hopping'' and
willingness to jump over to a rival for more money. That, one
executive said, marked a startling difference between U.S. and
German corporate culture.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
