<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-12 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1259 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RADIO-DJS-MEDIA-ART-5     07-12 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RADIO-DJS-MEDIA-ART-520&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRED FOR ON-AIR PRANK, TWO HAVE SHOT AT RADIO BIG TIME
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)   (ART ADV: Photo of Gregg Hughes and Anthony Cumia is being sent to
NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(nk) 
 By ANDREA ADELSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ What's the difference between New York and Boston?
</P>
<P>
   In the Boston area, an April Fool's Day broadcast hoax on
WAAF-FM about the mayor's death cost two afternoon disc jockeys
their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, it earns the pair, known as Opie and Anthony, a
shot at the big time on rock station WNEW-FM. No joke.
</P>
<P>
   Gregg Hughes, or Opie, and Anthony Cumia, whose broadcasting
career began to take off at Long Island's WBAB-FM, developed into a
ratings-winning success over three years in Worcester, Mass. That
ended in an apology by station executives and the team's dismissal
in April for a sketch _ complete with phony sound bites from a news
reporter and a police officer _ about Boston Mayor Thomas Menino's
supposed death in a traffic collision.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor said the prank showed ``a wanton and reckless
disregard for human decency and professional ethics,'' in a letter
to the Federal Communications Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Still, their termination also brought Hughes and Cumia thousands
of e-mails of support from fans and two job offers. Last month, the
pair began their patter of parody and humor weekday afternoons at
the CBS-owned WNEW, where they were hired by Garry Wall, a new
programming director at the No. 23-rated station.
</P>
<P>
   Wall said he hired Hughes and Cumia because of their talent, not
their prank. ``You don't get ratings in the newspaper,'' he said,
adding that the team's on-air personas had been altered to take
into account WNEW's more adult audience. ``There's not as much
toilet humor.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday's Opie and Anthony show, topics included listener
reaction to the pair's discussion of an album cover that showed
singer Patti Smith's unshaven armpits, and a parody of a news
report about children locked in a car trunk.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Eatman, the Los Angeles agent Hughes and Cumia hired
after their dismissal, said, ``They made a fortunate situation out
of an unfortunate circumstance.'' He said his clients' contract
does not contain a no-prank clause, and he declined to say how much
they would be paid at WNEW.
</P>
<P>
   CBS rejected a request for an interview with Hughes and Cumia.
</P>
<P>
   Pranks are to radio personalities what hit movies are to actors.
</P>
<P>
   Like other print and broadcast outlets, radio stations are
pushing against the boundaries of what is considered appropriate
content in a drive for ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Stern's antics draw obscenity fines and buff his
celebrity. A haircut that halted traffic on San Francisco's Bay
Bridge in 1993 catapulted the career of Mancow Miller, who will
reportedly be one of the best-paid radio personalities in the
country when he starts next month at WKQX-FM in Chicago. KROQ-FM in
Los Angeles lived up to its claim to be ``world famous'' by
broadcasting a 1990 faked murder confession, leading the FCC to
adopt a hoax rule that permits sanctions for broadcasts that cause
``immediate and substantial harm.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee Abrams, a radio programming consultant, said he often
received press clippings about stunts and complaints that followed
wrapped around audition tapes by personalities looking for work.
``They are a badge of honor.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Despite the Boston mayor's complaint, no action was taken
against WAAF, said Robert Ratcliffe, deputy chief of the FCC's mass
media bureau. In any case, he said, the gag would not have derailed
the then-pending $2.6 billion acquisition of WAAF's parent,
American Radio Systems Inc., by CBS Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Because CBS continues to operate other Boston area stations,
which were all losing to Opie and Anthony in the ratings, some
radio executives questioned whether CBS had shaped the
controversy's outcome to benefit its local stations.
</P>
<P>
   CBS is required to operate the to-be-sold stations separately,
but keep their business intact. ``That doesn't apply to talent,''
said Steven Lerman, a lawyer who has worked for Infinity
Broadcasting, which CBS acquired in 1996 and which is handling the
planned sale of the stations. In a precautionary effort to avoid
jeopardizing the pending deal, CBS consulted with Justice
Department officials before hiring Hughes and Cumia.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were fired for good cause,'' Lerman said. ``CBS had
nothing whatsoever to do with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Dodge, the former chairman of American Radio, agreed. ``It
was the right thing to do,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
