NYT-07-12-98 1942EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980712.0124 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-12 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1279 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POSTMODERN-THEATER-NY     07-12 1212
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POSTMODERN-THEATER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO VORACIOUSLY CREATIVE DEFINITIONS OF `POSTMODERN'
</HEADLINE>
 (js) 
By MARGO JEFFERSON  
c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Some of the best work billed as theater right now
can't be fitted into just one form or genre, let alone style.
History is too complicated, and our imaginations are too restless.
</P>
<P>
   But what people like to call a postmodernist aesthetic, with its
love of pastiche _ a clever assemblage of previous styles and a
juxtaposition of genres and allusions, all signaling their capacity
for playful irony at every moment _ really isn't enough. This kind
of irony has become as safe, as cliched for us as melodrama was for
an earlier age. It draws energy from parodying earlier forms, yet
rarely generates any passion or daring of its own.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Savion Glover Downtown,'' at the Variety Arts Theater, and
Basil Twist's ``Symphonie Fantastique,'' at Here, do generate
passion, daring, wonder and pure pleasure. Glover's medium is tap,
Twist's is puppetry, both forms that have always been at the mercy
of what is popular and on the margins of what is thought
artistically respectable. They are having their revenge now, with a
wave of voracious creativity.
</P>
<P>
   Glover choreographed ``Bring In 'da Noise, Bring In 'da Funk''
and helps train its ever-changing fleet of wonderful dancers;
Twist's puppeteer colleagues include not only Julie Taymor of ``The
Lion King'' but the less well-known, extremely gifted Theodora
Skipitares and Janie Geiser.
</P>
<P>
   Glover's new show, which he directed and choreographed, has been
called a jam session for five dancers and four musicians and a tap
revue. It has a street-corner insouciance and after-hours chic.
</P>
<P>
   Cannily paced, it moves between solos, duets, quartets and
ensemble numbers; and, with a repertory that includes the songs of
Duke Ellington, Thelonious Monk, Juan Tizol, Irving Berlin and
Chaka Khan, as well as original numbers, it is probably best called
a jazz, Latin and funk musical. (There is a bit of text, too, a few
poems written and recited by Reg Gaines, but they are nowhere near
the quality of the rest.
</P>
<P>
   I preferred the asides of the musicians _ the excellent Eli
Fountain and the Incog-Negroes _ and the voices of the dancers as
they woofed, shouted and egged one another on.)
</P>
<P>
   There is room for the unexpected: guest dancers and musicians
like Dule Hill, Bakaari Wilder and Jared Crawford, ``Noise/Funk''
veterans. And, at the show's end, any members of the audience who
are ready to come onstage and buck, wing or strut their stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Let's call the look hip-hop street and hip-hop suave. It
includes T-shirts and baggy pants, of course (one leg hitched up);
flowing shirts in mauve, brown and white with a light sateen
finish; khaki suit jackets (Nehru collars for the men, classic
lapels for the women), and various hats and caps over braids,
dreadlocks and plain old flowing locks.
</P>
<P>
   Every dancer is first rate. There is Chance Edwards, with his
pristine lines of sound; Abron Glover (Savion's brother),
long-limbed and self-contained; breezy staccato-driven Jason
Samuels, and Ayodele Casel _ what fun to see a woman up there
giving no quarter _ all rhythmic attack and unforced charm. When
they dance together we get the thrill of unison virtuosity (like a
swing band when all the instruments take the first chorus
together), and suspense (those jumps and turns when they land all
together and pick up the beat as if they had never left it).
</P>
<P>
   And when they take their solos, your energies shift. You get to
test your more intimate responses, feel what particular
inflections, ways of moving, ways of building a rhythm and a melody
stir you most.
</P>
<P>
   Glover is a brilliant choreographer and a dream dancer. He says
that when he dances he is ``spitting out those verbs,'' and that's
a great metaphor. His solos are marvels of mood-shifting talk, with
Fountain's tintinnabulating triangles, with the faux Arabian Nights
melody of Juan Tizol's ``Caravan'' and with the languorous
harmonies of Ellington's ``In a Sentimental Mood.''
</P>
<P>
   He talks with each musician; when there is no music but that of
his own feet, he talks to himself. (I like the air of slightly
extraterrestrial distance that comes over him at times. Improvising
can certainly be spurred on by a performer's intense connection to
the audience, but it is also deeply introspective, and sometimes
our pleasure comes from knowing that we are spying on an artist as
he creates.)
</P>
<P>
   Whomever he is talking with, the verbs proliferate. He teases
and challenges and rumbles and rumbas. He speaks in swing and
be-bop phrases, and he free-associates. He produces ballet-timed
leaps, African-influenced stomps with wide and shimmying shoulders
and rag-doll twists cartoon style. He moves across the stage
holding his upper body quite still, led by a toe that taps at the
level of a whisper. And his feet don't just play melodies, they
play chords.
</P>
<P>
   In a state of hyperactive bliss, I went home and looked up
Charles Dickens' equally hyperactive and astonished description of
the great 19th-century black tap dancer William Henry Lane, known
as Master Juba. There he was, wrote Dickens, spinning, shuffling,
cross-cutting, creating rhythms: ``dancing with two left legs, two
right legs, two wooden legs, two wire legs, two spring legs _ all
sorts of legs and no legs _ what is that to him?''
</P>
<P>
   For Dickens, the wonder came from seeing something that was
utterly new to him and pretty new to his culture and his century.
But we are nearing the end of a century, and we are exposed via the
media, however superficially, to the art of many cultures. Certain
forms, genres and styles have been so crushed by use and abuse that
we thought there was nothing more we needed or cared to know about
them; we need to see them rise up and make our hair stand on end.
That is what ``Savion Glover Downtown'' does.
</P>
<P>
   And that is why Basil Twist's ``Symphonie Fantastique'' is also
a small-scale, late-20th-century wonder. The theater seats 75
people. The stage, about the size of an old-fashioned
puppet-theater stage, is a tank filled with water, which, when
lighted, looks like a small movie screen. Unseen by us, Twist and
three other puppeteers turn Hector Berlioz's vehemently romantic
music into a delicious abstract art spectacle. Images drift, float,
zigzag and pounce; we see rhythmic arrangements of bubbles,
feathers, moons and suns, cylinders of light, blocks of color,
curved and geometric shapes.
</P>
<P>
   This is abstract art that looks like abstract film. But it is
something else, too. ``Symphonie Fantastique'' is quintessential
Romantic ballet music, and it becomes clear, watching the patterns
and phrasing of Twist's work, that, just as this is puppetry
without human figures, it is choreography without human beings.
Certainly not choreography that is enslaved to a canonized musical
work. There is grandeur and lavish beauty in Berlioz's music, but
there is bombast, too. The bombast is countered by Twist's visual
wit, while the grandeur is modulated but not effaced by the
delicacy of his method, and by the smallness of the theater.
</P>
<P>
   What an uncanny experience. You are free of human sights and
sounds, but you feel flooded with human emotions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
