<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-12 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1280 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NIGERIA-ASSESS-600&AMP;AD     07-12 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIGERIA-ASSESS-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: BURYING ABIOLA AND LONG-HELD HOPE OF ENDING MILITARY
RULE
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: budgeted earlier as NIGERIA-RDP) 
(js) 
 By ROGER COHEN  
c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAGOS, Nigeria _ As the Nigerian opposition leader, Moshood K.O.
Abiola, was laid to rest, the frenzy of the moment conveyed all
that was being buried with him. Feverish men shoveled red earth
onto the corpse and African chants, and Muslim prayers mingled with
the wailing of the women in the heaving crowd.
</P>
<P>
   For it was not merely the man who most vividly embodied
Nigeria's striving for an elusive democracy who was laid to rest
here on Saturday. It was the specific conviction represented by the
date June 12 _ the day in 1993 when Abiola appeared to have won a
presidential election later annulled by the military government.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since, June 12 has been the touchstone of Nigeria's quest
to end military rule. For Nigeria's opposition, it was a mandate in
abeyance, unfulfilled but compelling, even as Abiola languished in
prison. No matter that five years had elapsed: June 12 was vividly
alive, the banner beneath which the opposition marched.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, however, with Abiola's body in the ground and with
the sober verdict delivered by Western doctors that he died of
heart disease, that opposition seemed for the first time to face
the fact that the mandate of 1993 is beyond resuscitation.
</P>
<P>
   The National Democratic Coalition, the main opposition group,
issued a statement on Sunday saying that the military should
surrender power on October 1 to a 24-member government of national
unity that would pick a chairman and then organize the creation of
new political parties and elections.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking for the coalition, its leader, Abraham Adesanya, made
no attempt to speculate about who that chairman might be. The fact
is the void behind Abiola is too vast for such speculation to make
any sense. Names are sometimes heard here _ the former Vice
President Alex Ekwueme is among them _ but for the moment they
carry no weight.
</P>
<P>
   This void does not appear to alarm Western governments. On the
contrary, there seems to be a certain relief that the so-called
``June 12 issue'' has disappeared with an unexpected finality.
``Frankly, the fact that the question of the mandate has gone away
might make it easier to move forward,'' said one Western official.
</P>
<P>
   This, of course, had also been the view of the military
government of Gen. Abdusalam Abubakar. It had been preparing to
release Abiola when he died, but it was also looking for guarantees
that he would not claim the mandate he was denied. In other words,
a new election was perhaps possible, but on the condition that the
one five years ago would be forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Abiola accepted this condition remains in dispute. What
is clear is that the question is now moot and a new one has arisen:
who or what can possibly be put in his place to take Nigeria toward
the stable democratic system that has largely eluded it since
independence in 1960?
</P>
<P>
   Abiola's funeral suggested just how difficult it will be to
replace so eclectic a man. He was at once an African chief, a
devout Muslim, a supporter of Christian causes, a business mogul
and a larger-than-life example of a rare thing in Nigeria: a
rags-to-riches success story.
</P>
<P>
   In Abiola, an unusually wide swathe of this divided nation could
find some identification, or place some dream, and therein, it
seems, lay the key to his unique popularity.
</P>
<P>
   His funeral, attended by several of his wives and many of his
children, was as volatile as Nigeria is today. It veered between
tumult charged with potential violence and sudden, radiant good
will charged with hope.
</P>
<P>
   The Abiola mansion contains several apartments for his wives,
and in the dwelling once occupied by his second wife, Kudirat,
women who had been close to her were crying. After asserting her
husband's right to lead Nigeria, in 1996, Kudirat Abiola was shot
to death in Lagos by six armed men. Nobody has been arrested or
tried for the crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are so bitter _ it is beyond words,'' said Bimbo Soremekun,
a close friend of Kudirat Abiola.
</P>
<P>
   In a large central room on the first floor, other members of the
family mourned. Representatives of Nigeria's unusually vibrant
press asked to be allowed to say prayers, and one Muslim prayer was
read followed by a Christian prayer.
</P>
<P>
   Abiola, born poor, went to a Christian school _ the Baptist Boys
High School in Abeokuta _ but he also attended Koranic schools from
an early age and chose to become a Muslim when still a young man,
friends said. He was a strong supporter of Islamic causes, but he
also knew many Christian hymns by heart.
</P>
<P>
   The most explosive division in this country is also a religious
one between the mainly Muslim north, dominated by the Hausa and
closely related Falani tribes, and the predominantly Christian
south, from which Abiola came. So his ability to find support in
both areas will almost certainly be hard to reproduce, especially
as his death has exacerbated the cleavage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am in pain; my sisters are in pain; you are all in pain,''
his daughter Wula Abiola shouted to the crowd at the funeral. ``But
we have a memory. And that memory is for democracy and it is for
peace.''
</P>
<P>
   At times peace seemed likely to give way to violence. The
presence of soldiers, even several hundred yards away, incensed
young followers. At others, when disco music was abruptly played,
the whole front yard of the mansion was one seething party. Light
and dark moods moved very close to each other.
</P>
<P>
   As his body, following the Muslim custom, emerged from the house
invisible beneath the white cloth, dozens of Abiola's followers
surged forward, their features marked by the harsh imprint of
poverty and a kind of desperate thirsting for consolation. People
were thrown this way and that, chairs were smashed, and sobbing
women were led away.
</P>
<P>
   After the body was lowered into the ground, a man perched in a
tree began to tear off branches, which were set over the corpse.
Then, to the beat of African chants and the hypnotic lilt of Muslim
prayer, feverish men begen shoveling earth onto the body as tearful
women gazed down from an overlooking balcony.
</P>
<P>
   Not one Western diplomat was present at these extraordinary
proceedings. America and its allies, it seems, had already opted to
place their bets elsewhere. But with the issue of the June 12
mandate at last settled, the real difficulties may be just
beginning in Nigeria.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
