<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Deutsche Bank Is Shopping for Acquisition or Alliance
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Bank, reeling from the recent defection of several top
investment bankers to Credit Suisse First Boston, is looking to buy
a U.S. investment firm or to establish a significant alliance with
one.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of Germany's biggest bank said he did not yet have
a specific target. Industry executives have mentioned J.P. Morgan,
Paine Webber and Hambrecht &AMP; Quist as possible partners.
</P>
<P>
   BET Plans to Start a Film Venture
</P>
<P>
   Robert L. Johnson, the chairman and founder of Black
Entertainment Television, plans to start a venture to make
low-budget films with black stars _ the first black-owned company
to completely own films. The plan would start gradually and would
be based on films with production costs of $3 million and
advertising budgets of $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Two Exchanges Discussing a Merger
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago Board Options Exchange, the world's largest options
exchange, and the Pacific Stock Exchange, a fast-growing regional
stock exchange in San Francisco that controls the third-largest
market in stock options, are discussing a merger.
</P>
<P>
   Real Networks Releasing Software
</P>
<P>
   Real Networks, the leader in the technology that allows music
and video to be sent over the Internet to personal computers, is
releasing its test version of its desktop and network server
software Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Courts Key in Telecommunications
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most important development in the telecommunications
industry continues to be the legal battle between the Bell regional
phone companies and the Justice Department over the
Telecommunications Act of 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Applied Materials Issues Warning
</P>
<P>
   Applied Materials, a make of semiconductor manufacturing
equipment, warned that its fiscal third-quarter results would fall
below analysts' forecasts, hurt by delayed orders and cutbacks in
capital spending by chip makers.
</P>
<P>
   Ammirati Forms Interactive Unit
</P>
<P>
   Ammirati Puris Lintas has formed a division named APL Digital to
specialize in interactive marketing. It has 140 employees in
offices in Hong Kong, London, New York and Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Radio Pair Gets Chance on WNEW
</P>
<P>
   Gregg Hughes and Anthony Cumia, who are known as Opie and
Anthony, joined CBS-owned WNEW-FM, as disc jockeys on weekday
afternoons. They come to the New York station after being dismissed
for a prank they pulled at their last job.
</P>
<P>
   Patent Aims to Calm Crying Babies
</P>
<P>
   A patent has been approved for a voice-activated sound-and-light
box that attaches to a crib. It is intended to play a soothing
message from the baby's mother or father when activated, show a
picture of the parent talking and calm the wailing baby.
</P>
<P>
   Gemstar Approves Rights Program
</P>
<P>
   Gemstar International Group has approved a shareholder-rights
program that is aimed at making a $2.8 billion hostile takeover bid
by United Video Satellite Group more difficult to complete.
</P>
<P>
   Orders for Machine Tools Rose
</P>
<P>
   Orders from U.S. companies for domestic and foreign-produced
machine tools rose 16 percent to an estimated $795 million in May,
with orders increasing in all regions except the Northeast.
</P>
</TEXT>
