<DOCNO> NYT19980712.0129 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-12 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1284 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      07-12 0980
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSOURI: DEMOCRATIC SENATE CANDIDATE ANGERS BLACK  
 NEW HAMPSHIRE: IT'S SUNUNU VS. SOMEBODY  
 ARIZONA: SKY-HIGH TRIBUTE GROUNDED BY FALLOUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   From the start, this year's Senate race in Missouri had the look
of a close contest, with Democrats figuring they might just capture
the seat and nibble away a bit at the GOP's hold on Capitol Hill.
Republican incumbent Christopher Bond, a moderate who has struggled
in more than one election, seemed to Democratic campaign
strategists to be hardly any stronger in 1998 than he was in 1992
when he squeaked through to a second term with just 52 percent of
the vote.
</P>
<P>
   But now the Democrats are not so confident.
</P>
<P>
   Their candidate, Attorney General Jay Nixon, also a moderate,
has alienated many black voters _ 20 percent or so of the
Democratic base in Missouri _ by proposing to end busing as a
school desegregation tool. Many black leaders in the state see the
proposal as a prime example of how Democratic leaders around the
country often take the black vote for granted and some are
threatening to support Bond this fall, stay home or even cast about
for another Democratic candidate.
</P>
<P>
   It is a political tactic being tried by blacks in a number of
close contests this year, most notably in the governors' races in
Florida and Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   Some prominent members of the Missouri chapter of the NAACP have
picketed Nixon at campaign appearances, ignoring his promises to be
a strong advocate for working people and families. One chapter
official called him the ``reincarnation'' of former Alabama Gov.
George C. Wallace; another announced, ``I'm backing Bond.''
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City Mayor Emanuel Cleaver, who is black, sent the Bond
campaign a $200 check the other day, asserting it was not an
endorsement of the senator but part of his ``obligation'' to help
the Democratic Party. The state's senior black elected official,
Rep. William Clay Sr. of St. Louis, has urged senior national
Democrats, including President Clinton, not to help Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Bond campaigns on, but a bit differently than in 1986
and 1992. This year he is working the black precincts hard, showing
up at churches and social clubs and community centers, normally the
places Nixon would be working hard, except this year Nixon is often
avoiding them lest he run into more picketing.
</P>
<P>
   IN NEW HAMPSHIRE, IT'S SUNUNU VS. SOMEBODY
</P>
<P>
   The award for the 1998 election with the most fits and starts _
thus far _ goes to the contest in New Hampshire's 1st Congressional
District, where Democrats have finally settled, for the fourth time
in six weeks, on a candidate to challenge the Republican incumbent,
Rep. John E. Sununu.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   The party's first choice was no choice. Nobody wanted to take on
Sununu, New Hampshire not being fertile ground for Democrats these
days.
</P>
<P>
   But then as the June 12 deadline for filing neared, the party
began having second thoughts about giving a free ride to Sununu,
the son of former Gov. John H. Sununu. A Durham educator, Wayne
Burton, was persuaded to run.
</P>
<P>
   He lasted not quite five days before retreating from the fray,
saying the challenge was too daunting. Once again party leaders
resigned themselves to the prospect that Sununu would slip back in
unopposed.
</P>
<P>
   But then, just 30 minutes before the filing deadline, Cynthia
McGovern, a legislative lobbyist, signed up _ only to pull out a
couple of days later when New Hampshire papers reported that she
had once been arrested on a charge of assaulting a state trooper.
</P>
<P>
   Make that almost pulled out.
</P>
<P>
   Election officials ruled there could be no pulling out once the
filing deadline had passed. When you're in, you're in, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Again Democrats despaired, anticipating the pounding Ms.
McGovern would probably take over the trooper incident.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. McGovern was still determined not to run, so determined
that she moved out of state, to neighboring Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Election officials relented last Monday, conceding, well, that
when you're out, you're out. Not only that, they said the Democrats
could send in a substitute, if they could find one.
</P>
<P>
   They did.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Choice No. 4 - assuming no Republican challenges the
McGovern decision - is real estate agent Peter Flood.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll take it up hill from here to the top,'' he said as he
hit the campaign trail on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   SKY-HIGH TRIBUTE GROUNDED BY FALLOUT
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Barry Goldwater died in late May, Phoenix Mayor
Skip Rimsza suggested that a wonderful way to honor the former
senator was to change the name of Phoenix's Sky Harbor
International Airport to Barry Goldwater International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   He got 2,000 phone calls in a single day from irate people who
said they dearly loved the senator, but naming the airport for him
was a bad idea because Sky Harbor was a better fit.
</P>
<P>
   A better idea, many suggested, would be to name a mountain
range, park or some big building for the senator, who in his
unsuccessful run for president in 1964 did more than any other
Republican to set the GOP on its current ideological course.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor stood firm. But the negative calls continued to flow
in, along with the negative letters and negative editorials, not to
mention the negative poll that showed two of every three Arizonans
wanted to keep the Sky Harbor name.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor toyed with the idea of holding public hearings on the
matter. But then, second thoughts began to nag at him, especially
after both political friend and foe started warning that the name
change brouhaha was turning into the biggest gaffe of his political
career. They urged him to cut his losses.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday he withdrew his proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to move on,'' he said. ``If I made a mistake, it was
a mistake of the heart.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
