<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA REACHES AGREEMENT WITH IMF ON AID PACKAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The Yeltsin government said on Sunday that it had
reached agreement with the International Monetary Fund on a
multi-billion-dollar package to stabilize Russia's financial
markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sides have achieved agreement on all major questions of
principal importance,'' the government of President Boris Yeltsin
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The statement was aimed at reassuring investors before the stock
and bond markets opened on Monday. Negotiators for the monetary
fund had no comment.
</P>
<P>
   As fears have grown about Russia's deteriorating economy, the
Clinton administration urged the IMF bring its negotiations to a
speedy close.
</P>
<P>
   John Odling-Smee, the chief negotiator for the fund, arrived in
Moscow on Friday night and immediately plunged into talks with
Anatoly Chubais, the chief Russian negotiator with the fund.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians have been informed they will receive $11 billion in
new loans this year from the monetary fund if they meet its
requirements.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF financing is part of a package of more more than $20
billion that the Russians hope to assemble from a variety of
sources, including the World Bank, Japan and Western commercial
banks.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, Yeltsin aides have issued a series of upbeat
statements to impress anxious investors. And on Sunday a senior
Russian official said the final details of the IMF accord were
being worked out so that it could be announced on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Representatives of Russia and the IMF will report in detail on
Monday on concrete agreements that have been reached and practical
steps that will be taken soon,'' the semi-official Itar-Tass news
agency said.
</P>
<P>
   In negotiating the agreement the two sides have had to overcome
important differences.
</P>
<P>
   A major issue in the talks, for example, has been the pace at
which Russia should cut its budget deficit. The two sides now agree
that the deficit should be reduced to 2.8 percent of Russia's Gross
Domestic Product in 1999, from about 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even when the negotiations are completed, Russia will
have to overcome hurdles to qualify for the new funds.
</P>
<P>
   Before Russia can qualify for new financing, the IMF is
insisting that the government complete some of the reforms to which
it had agreed as part of an earlier $10 billion loan.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the previous IMF loan, for example, the
Russian government was supposed to have taken steps to limit barter
transactions by monopolies, such as Gazprom, the huge natural gas
company, and United Energy Systems, the electrical monopoly,
Russian officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Another earlier measure the Russians must now carry out involves
new legislation to preclude unauthorized spending commitments. The
monetary fund wants the Yeltsin government to submit legislation to
Parliament that would require governmental organizations to
register all contracts with the federal treasury.
</P>
<P>
   The Yeltsin government plans to rush ahead with these measures.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF will also be watching closely when the government tries
to win parliamentary approval for its plan to reduce its deficit,
overhaul the tax system and undertake other reforms. The
extraordinary parliamentary session is scheduled for Wednesday and
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The new financing Russia is seeking is vital for its efforts to
restore confidence in the nation's financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   Central Bank reserves have declined to about $15 billion, and
some $5 billion of that is in gold, which cannot readily be spent.
Foreign investors, however, own about $20 billion in treasury
bills.
</P>
<P>
   The concern is that foreign investors might panic and withdraw
from the treasury bill market. If they took their ruble proceeds
and converted them into dollars, the Central Bank would not have
sufficient reserves to prop up the ruble. That would lead to a
devaluation of the ruble and a political upheaval.
</P>
<P>
   The new loans would also be used to help Russia restructure its
short-term debt. Russia has been forced to offer treasury bills at
enormous interest rates to try to attract buyers, and even then
many investors have stayed away.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
