<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-12 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1287 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIAN-MUSIC-REVIEW-     07-12 0586
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIAN-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`RUSSIAN RHYTHMS ON BROADWAY': A FLAIR FOR STRAVINSKY'S
TALE-TELLING
</HEADLINE>
 (js) 
By ALLAN KOZINN  
c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Trinity Church, at Wall Street and Broadway, offers
free lunchtime concerts by superb young soloists and ensembles all
through the season, but last year the church staked its claim in
the world of summer festivals by offering a thematically coherent
series. With a grant described in its program book as ``an
anonymous donation to the glory of God and in honor of Johannes
Brahms,'' it commemorated the centenary of Brahms' death with an
overview of his chamber, orchestral and choral works, ``Brahms on
Broadway.''
</P>
<P>
   This year the terms of the supporting donation are unchanged _
still anonymous, still dedicated to God and Brahms _ but apparently
the donor has agreed to allow Brahms' music a rest. Now Trinity is
presenting ``Russian Rhythms on Broadway,'' a wide-ranging 10-week
survey that touches on everything from Russian folk song and
liturgical works to Romantic and early modern chamber and
orchestral scores.
</P>
<P>
   All the concerts are on Thursdays at 1 p.m., and in the most
recent installment, Richard Auldon Clark conducted the Manhattan
Chamber Orchestra in two early works by Stravinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The program began with a semi-staged version of ``Renard,''
Stravinsky's 1915 burlesque in which Renard does his best to catch
a rooster for dinner but is outfoxed by the other barnyard animals.
Its companion was ``L'Histoire du Soldat,'' the story of a simple
soldier's series of encounters with the devil, composed in 1918.
</P>
<P>
   What they share, apart from allegorical lessons about the
pitfalls of temptation and pride, is a musical omnivorousness. In
``Renard,'' Stravinsky weaves folk styles and old church modes into
a modern orchestration that drips with the acid humor that was
already a Stravinskian thumbprint.
</P>
<P>
   That sardonic quality suffuses ``Histoire'' as well, and the
centrality of duplicitous figures in both works _ the fox and the
devil _ makes it seem fitting. But where Stravinsky brought
``Renard'' to life with transformations of antique musical models,
in ``Histoire'' he drew from jazz, ragtime and tangos, similarly
bent to suit his own style.
</P>
<P>
   The performances at Trinity treated both works well. In
``Renard,'' the Songfellows vocal ensemble _ Mukund Marath and Greg
Davidson, tenors; Jared Stamm, baritone, and Ross Crolius, bass _
sang with clarity and vigor, wearing masks that represented the
fox, cat, goat and rooster, and acting in a stylized way that
reflected the score's olden currents and suggested a medieval
church play. Costuming touches like a red Mostly Mozart apron
undercut that impression to a degree, much as the humorous touches
in Stravinsky's score did.
</P>
<P>
   The orchestra supported Songfellows solidly, although only its
broadest strokes could be heard clearly; much of the detail was
lost in the church's swimmy acoustics. ``Histoire'' fared better in
that sense. Stravinsky's scoring, for septet, is notably more
transparent, and Clark's ensemble was equal to its often soloistic
challenges. Particularly striking were Karen Rostron's earthy
readings of the recurrent fiddle figure and Chris Gekker's clean,
virtuosic trumpet playing.
</P>
<P>
   Claire Bloom narrated the tale, and if the amplification was
heavier than necessary, it did not destroy the considerable nuance
with which she distinguished each character's voice, and the
soldier's various changes of heart.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
