<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: IN THE PREMIER LEAGUE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ANTHONY LEWIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Governments in Italy since World War II have lasted, on
average, 11 months. Romano Prodi has now been prime minister for
more than two years. Interviewing him just before a critical
political test, I began by asking, ``Will you survive?''
</P>
<P>
   ``In principle I didn't survive all this time,'' Prodi said,
smiling. ``In reality I did. If I look at rationality, there are
some problems. But politics is never rational.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the leaders of democracies around the world, Prodi is
unique. He has no party and no political past. He was a professor
of economics at the University of Bologna when, a few years ago, he
began campaigning for a shake-up in Italian politics. He proposed a
new center-left coalition with himself, a man who had never held
elective office, as leader. Amazingly, it worked.
</P>
<P>
   After two years in office, he continues to take delight in his
odd position.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I told [Prime Minister Ryutaro) Hashimoto [of Japan) that
I delivered my first speech in Parliament as prime minister,''
Prodi said, ``he was furious! He waited years. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I am in the luxurious position of not having any burden of a
party _ and being indispensable to the government.''
</P>
<P>
   What makes Prodi interesting is not just his survival skills, or
his sense of humor. It is what he has done in office.
</P>
<P>
   When The Financial Times of London surveyed Italy last month,
its headline was, ``Italy: Promoted to Europe's Premier League.''
(The top English football teams play in the Premier League.)
</P>
<P>
   Prodi's prime goal when he took office was to have Italy
included in the planned European Monetary Union and its common
currency, the euro. That looked impossible. The rules for joining
required a country to have a budget deficit of not more than 3
percent of gross domestic product, and Italy's deficit was 7
percent.
</P>
<P>
   But when the EU made its decision, two months ago, Italy was
included. In two years the Prodi government had cut the deficit
below 3 percent of GDP. The annual inflation rate was also down, to
1.7 percent. And the interest rate on government bonds was down to
5.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   How was it done? In a word, discipline. Prodi resisted pressures
for what in Washington is called pork-barrel spending. The lure of
the euro was a big help. All parties wanted to see Italy in the
monetary union, and Prodi could tell them that without fiscal
discipline it would not happen.
</P>
<P>
   Maintaining discipline is harder now, without the leverage of
the euro. But Prodi plans a further round of reforms, including
reform of Italy's notoriously inefficient state bureaucracy.
Whether he will survive to carry them out depends on the working of
his half-finished project to reshape the political system.
</P>
<P>
   He wants what he calls a ``normal'' democracy, with a left party
and a right party. What he has is a bloc of genuinely reformed
ex-Communists and some centrists in his coalition, and a right-wing
group including ex-Fascists as the opposition _ neither with a
majority in Parliament. Standing apart are the Refounded Communists
_ unreconstructed Leninists. Prodi needs their support in votes of
confidence to survive. And they have undertaken to give him that
support at least until the autumn.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that the coalition has worked for two years is
important,'' he said. ``Ideology is declining. It's a fantastic
change in the country _ former Fascists and Communists as part of
the system.''
</P>
<P>
   Italy has troops in Bosnia and Macedonia, and concerns in
Kosovo. ``Sometimes I ask myself if it is possible to keep people
living together,'' Prodi said. He saw the European Union as the
model for the solution: ``A higher authority that respects regional
and ethnic identities.''
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago Prodi visited Iran, the first Western leader to do
so since the election of its moderate president, Mohammad Khatami.
I asked how he appraised Khatami.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows democracy,'' Prodi said. ``He knows how important it
is for Iran to be in the international community again. He has read
the political philosophers. I discussed Machiavelli with him, and
Bertolt Brecht's `Galileo.'''
</P>
<P>
   I wonder whether any Western political leader but Romano Prodi
would discuss the works of Bertolt Brecht with Khatami.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
