<HEADER>
A1304 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NIRELAND-UNREST-ART-7     07-12 1241
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-UNREST-ART-725&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARSON DEATHS OF 3 BROTHERS HAS ALL SIDES REELING IN ULSTER
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(nk) 
 By JAMES F. CLARITY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALLYMONEY, Northern Ireland _ Three young Roman Catholic boys
were burned to death in their home early Sunday morning in an arson
attack that police said was the work of Protestants.
</P>
<P>
   Political and religious leaders, both Protestant and Roman
Catholic, throughout the British province denounced the killings,
which followed more than a week of Protestant violence linked to
the banning of a Protestant march through a Catholic area and
heightened fears of a breakdown in the Northern Ireland peace
agreement reached this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Ballymoney, a largely Protestant village 40 miles north
of Belfast, stunned residents, some weeping, walked quietly around
the mostly Protestant public housing complex of Carnany Estate,
made up of two-story white stucco row houses. They stared up at the
scorched walls and windows of the upstairs room where the three
Quinn boys _ Richard, 10, Mark, 9, and Jason, 7 _ had been sleeping
when attackers threw a flaming gasoline bomb though a downstairs
window at about 4:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   The boys' mother, Christine Quinn, 29; her Protestant boyfriend,
Raymond Craig, 31, and a woman friend who was in the house were
unable to reach the children before escaping.
</P>
<P>
   When firefighters and police arrived, they found the boys dead.
The boys' father, John Quinn, who was separated from their mother,
was believed to be in England, where he lives and works.
</P>
<P>
   There were no arrests by Sunday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday afternoon, as young girls brought bouquets of flowers to
the site, handing them over to the police who stood guard around
the house, grief-stricken neighbors and relatives discussed the
tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were just typical boys _ just ran about and played
football, sat about watching videos,'' said Shirley Patton, Mrs.
Quinn's cousin and a Protestant. She said that although Mrs. Quinn
is a Catholic, she sent her sons to a local public school.
</P>
<P>
   All but a few families in the area are Protestant, Mrs. Patton
said, standing in her doorway, a British Union Jack fluttering from
the side of her house. Her son, Russell, 11, who had been a friend
of the dead Quinn boys, played with a small dog to distract
himself. Asked what he thought of the incident, Russell lowered his
head and said softly, ``Deadly.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Patton's father, Robert, had one word for the people who
killed the boys: ``Trash.'' He was helping to arrange the funeral
at a nearby Catholic church.
</P>
<P>
   Another neighbor, Richard Rogers, an unemployed salesman, said
someone in the housing complex must have given the arsonists
information to indicate where the Catholic family lived. Rogers, a
member of the Progressive Unionist Party, which represents a
Protestant paramilitary group that is observing a cease-fire, said
he doubted Protestant paramilitaries had any part in the fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sad, sick individuals full of sectarian hatred,'' he said
about the arsonists.
</P>
<P>
   He, like many others, linked the boys' death to the outbreaks of
violence by Protestants that have accompanied a standoff between
British security forces and members of the Protestant Orange Order
who are protesting a ban on parading through a Catholic
neighborhood in Portadown, south of here.
</P>
<P>
   The Orange Order, Rogers said, insists it holds ``the high moral
ground'' in the dispute over the Portadown march. ``But where's the
logic when children are burned in their beds?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   His words were echoed by Archbishop Robin Eames, the Church of
Ireland's Protestant Primate, in an appeal to the Orangemen who
have been demonstrating in Drumcree on the edge of Portadown.
``Quietly walk away,'' Eames said. ``In the name of God, please
leave the hill at Drumcree. You've made your points.''
</P>
<P>
   Public anxiety rose Sunday night when the Orange Order declared
it would not call off its protests and was asking all 70,000
members to join the demonstrations in Portadown.
</P>
<P>
   Some Orangemen said the British government was ultimately to
blame for the killings by blocking their parade. Others said
Protestant paramilitaries must have had a hand in the firebombing,
which came 10 days after Protestant arsonists burned 10 Catholic
churches, destroying three.
</P>
<P>
   In Belfast, the leader of the Progressive Unionist Party, David
Ervine, said all sides were to blame for the ``savage, savage''
act. ``We are morally bankrupt in a situation that will bring us to
hell.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The first public official to arrive at the housing complex
Sunday morning was the Rev. Ian Paisley, the hard-line Protestant
leader who called the killings ``diabolical, hellish.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our sympathy goes out to the family,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As political leaders and clerics deplored the killings and
called for calm, the question most people here were asking was:
Would the horror of the boys' deaths help end the violence that has
been spreading in the province, or only worsen it?
</P>
<P>
   The violence has threatened to undermine the Northern Ireland
peace agreement approved last spring and the new Assembly, which is
to enact political reforms to give the province's Catholic minority
greater power.
</P>
<P>
   At Drumcree, where the Orangemen have been attacking policemen
blocking the roads to the Catholic area, a few Orange Protestants
said today that the boys' deaths might decrease the number of
protesters, particularly on Monday, when about 500 Orange parades
are to take place around the province to celebrate the 17th-century
Protestant victory over Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   But the prevalent view seemed to be that of a 41-year-old civil
servant, who declined to give his name for fear of reprisals. He
said the protests must continue at Drumcree. ``It's a matter of our
freedom, our right to walk on the Queen's highway,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He blamed British officials, including Prime Minister Tony
Blair, who refused to let the march go down the Garvaghy Road in
the Catholic area. Catholics view the parades as triumphalist and
demeaning to them.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Pollock, an Orange supporter, said she was ``totally
devastated'' by the boys' deaths, but added that the Orangemen are
right to stand up to the Catholic community because ``they're
taking Northern Ireland away from us. They want a united Ireland,
which we don't want.''
</P>
<P>
   Protesters who have attacked the troops and the police at
Drumcree are ``just extremists, just a bunch of kids hanging about
with nothing to do,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, she conceded, ``There's too much hate and not enough
love.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, several hours after the firebombing, a British
Government commission denied an appeal by the Orange Order against
the ban on the march at Drumcree. The two leaders of the new
Northern Ireland Assembly, David Trimble, a Protestant, and Seamus
Mallon, a Catholic, urged the Orangemen to give up their protests
and go home.
</P>
<P>
   Ronnie Flanagan, the chief constable of police for Northern
Ireland, said: ``What went on last night was not protest. We
believe we are investigating the sectarian murder of three children
_ Richard, Mark and Jason Quinn _ asleep in their beds. That's not
protest. That's murder.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-98 2022EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980712.0139 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-12 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1305 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-PURPLE-HOUSE-75     07-12 1048
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-PURPLE-HOUSE-750&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PURPLE HOUSE MAKES SOME TEXANS SEE RED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mexico)  (lb) 
 By SARA RIMER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Sandra Cisneros, the poet and novelist whose work
explores the relationship between home and identity, did not want
her own long-yearned-for house to be bland or timid or understated.
The old coat of beige paint it had would not do. Ms. Cisneros found
what she was looking for in Sherwin-Williams Corsican purple.
Overnight, her bungalow became the Purple House.
</P>
<P>
   It has become a kind of blank canvas, as well, layered with
symbolism and inspiring intense passions and debate in this proudly
Mexican-American city.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on who is looking at it, it is a work of art, a
flagrant violation of the rules in Ms. Cisneros' historic
neighborhood, a flag signifying Mexican-American pride, an
embodiment of border culture, a symbol of freedom of expression, a
sign of Ms. Cisneros' identification with her Mexican-American
roots, a reflection of Ms. Cisneros' uppityness, a brilliant
publicity stunt, a tourist attraction.
</P>
<P>
   ``My granddaughter calls it the Barney house,'' said the Rev.
Tom Chavana, a nondenominational minister who lives across the
street.
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio has plenty of colorful buildings _ the new library
is enchilada red _ and a purple house might not have created such a
stir were it not for its being in the historic Victorian King
William neighborhood. The city's Historic Design and Review
Commission ruled that Corsican purple was historically incorrect _
even if it was ``exquisite,'' as Milton Babbitt, the architect in
the group, called it _ and had to be changed.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, with the novelist and the city negotiating over
the color, the house is still purple, though its original intensity
has faded somewhat in the Texas sun.
</P>
<P>
   Elsa Calderone, 73, who lives a block away and is confined to
her home because of poor health, insists on being driven by
whenever she goes to the doctor. ``It's like a fairy tale,'' said
Mrs. Calderone, whose own house is white. ``I belong to the King
William Association and I agree with their standards, but once in a
while you need something like that to brighten up your life.''
</P>
<P>
   People have come from all over to see the house, writing down
their opinions _ everyone has an opinion on the Purple House _ on
the legal tablet that Ms. Cisneros, ever the probing novelist, has
attached to a clipboard on her front gate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beautiful house,'' wrote Jeff from San Francisco. ``I love the
color. What's the problem?''
</P>
<P>
   A man named Gene Elder wrote: ``I love the discussion that
purple has brought to the community.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it _ they can shove it,'' wrote Maria from Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   One of seven children of a Mexican upholsterer and his
Mexican-American wife, Ms. Cisneros, 43, grew up up in Chicago but
traveled often to Mexico City to visit her grandmother. ``What the
house is saying is, `I'm very Mexican, and I'm proud of it,' and
that it's another way of being American,'' the author said in a
recent interview.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Gossen, the vice chairman of the historic commission, said
he thought the Purple House was saying something else. ``It's not
about ethnicity,'' he said. ``It's about eccentricity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ms. Cisneros has written about the working class and
downtrodden all her life,'' added Gossen, a banker whose house is
brown brick. ``Yet she's acting like the privileged class that
doesn't have to follow the rules.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the purple, Gossen finds it ``appalling.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Cisneros drives a small red pickup truck with a bumper
sticker that says ``Wild Women Don't Get the Blues.'' She is
``nobody's mother, and nobody's wife,'' according to the author's
note in her acclaimed novel ``The House on Mango Street'' (Vintage,
1991). She shares her two-bedroom house on Guenther Street with
five cats, three dogs and two parrots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course her house is purple,'' Jan Jarboe, who is also a
writer living in San Antonio, said admiringly. ``I'm surprised it
isn't dripping with rhinestones.''
</P>
<P>
   Rhinestones do, in fact, decorate the horseshoe beside Ms.
Cisneros' front door. Her dog Violetta, a small mutt who often
accompanies her to readings, has a rhinestone collar.
</P>
<P>
   Ramon Vasquez y Sanchez, who oversees public art for the city
and also sits on the commission, says he considers the Purple House
to be public art, and historic besides.
</P>
<P>
   ``The color purple is pre-Columbian,'' Sanchez said. ``If you
want to see purple, go to Mexico. I told them, `You're using a
northeastern palette for colors. What you should do is realize
where you're at.'''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The mansions built by the wealthy German merchants who settled
Ms. Cisneros' neighborhood in the late 19th century are mostly
white and beige. But the historic commission has not aggressively
enforced color rules, and King William, home to struggling artists
and laborers as well as bankers and lawyers, also has bungalows
painted pink, orange and even red, white and blue.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The House on Mango Street,'' the narrator, a young girl
named Esperanza who lives in the Chicago barrio, is ashamed of her
``sad red house, the house I belong but do not belong to.'' What
she longs for: ``A house all my own. With my porch and my pillow,
my pretty purple petunias.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Cisneros' porch has a pink floor, a bed for lounging and a
stuffed bull on the wall. Outside there are pink geraniums, yellow
sunflowers, a flock of pink plastic flamingoes and a purple swing
set.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always wanted my own swing set,'' the author said, giving a
tour the other day.
</P>
<P>
   Her house is filled with books, altars to the Virgin of
Guadalupe, and the exuberant paintings of her artist friends. The
walls are green, pink, purple and even white.
</P>
<P>
   As for the exterior, both Ms. Cisneros and the city say they
hope to reach a compromise. Ms. Cisneros, who has rejected such
suggested colors as Plymouth green and Colonial-revival tan, has
proposed repainting the roof terra cotta. The city has yet to
respond.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a novel,'' said the author, who is finishing her
second novel, ``Caramelo,'' about a Mexican-American family. ``You
have to guess how it will end.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
