   Lead story:
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-ELECTION (Tokyo) _ Voters in parliamentary elections give
Japan's governing party a brutal drubbing, setting the stage for
the resignation of Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto and creating
new uncertainties about the country's political and economic
course. By Nicholas D. Kristof. (We plan to move the story by 8
p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.) 1,570 words. The story runs under a
2-column, 3-line hed.
</P>
<P>
   reefer: RUSSIA-IMF (Moscow) _ The Yeltsin government says it has
reached agreement with the IMF on a multi-billion-dollar package to
stabilize Russia's financial markets. By Michael R. Gordon.
(Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Top center story:
</P>
<P>
   SOC-WORLDCUP (Paris) _ The World Cup final; France beats Brazil,
3-0. By Jere Longman. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``s'' news
file.) Story runs under 3-col. photo; photos, sidebars inside
Sports.
</P>
<P>
   Off-lead story:
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS-INCUMBENCY (Austin, Texas) _ There is no better
demonstration of how the political climate has dramatically changed
this election year than in the commercials candidates are
broadcasting. After years of shunning Washington and
politics-as-usual, even incumbents who once went out of their way
to portray themselves as government outsiders are proudly
trumpeting their insider credentials. An examination of hundreds of
commercials shows that a striking proportion of contenders are
cramming their ads with bland but, they hope, convincing pitches
about their ``experience'' and ``record.'' By Richard L. Berke.
(Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.) 1,600 words.
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-UNREST (Ballymoney, Northern Ireland) _ Three young
Roman Catholic boys were burned to death in their homes in an arson
attack in this largely Protestant village. By James F. Clarity.
(Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.) With map.
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   GIFT-TO-BROOKLYN (New York) _ A college professor and his wife
have left millions of dollars to Brooklyn institutions, including
Brooklyn Polytechnic. A tale of heartwarming generosity made
possible by savvy investing. By Karen Arenson. (Scheduled to move
by 8:30 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.) 1,800 words.
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-COMMANDO (Miami) _ As Luis Posada Carriles nears the end of
his career as the most notorious commando in the anti-Castro
underground, he details for the first time his 37-year relationship
with exile leaders in the United States and with U.S. authorities.
By Larry Rohter and Louise Bardach. (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m.
ET in ``i'' news file.) Special Report: 5,300 words; with graphic
timeline.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE STORIES PROMOTED ON PAGE 1:
</P>
<P>
   LUNA-MOTH (New York) _ The endangered, lovely Luna moth is being
reintroduced to Central Park, part of a plan to reintroduce one
species to each borough. Riding delicate pale green wings, with
scalloped, gossamer edges trailing in the darkness, the luna moth,
one of the most spectacular insects on Earth, flew through the
nights of New York City before it succumbed to the stresses of
pesticides and development. Now the luna will be taking flight here
once again. On July 20, the 29th anniversary of the lunar landing,
the Parks Department plans to release the first of several hundred
of these elegant moths. By Carol Kaesuk Yoon. (Scheduled to move by
9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-TALKS (Flint, Mich.) _ Developments in the GM-UAW
negotiations. By Keith Bradsher. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in
``a'' news file.)
</P>
