<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980712.0153 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-12 20:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1323 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      07-12 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: IS THERE A RIGHT TO SEX? 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Does a poor man have as much right to sex as a rich
man? Ask anybody that question, and the answer will be yes.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, the recent decision by Kaiser Permanente, the
health plan of 9 million people nationwide, not to cover the cost
of the potency pill Viagra will meet with disapproval.
</P>
<P>
   This despite Kaiser's upfront explanation: The $7 pill costs too
much. If Kaiser were to pay for unrestricted use of the
sought-after drug, pharmaceutical bills would jump 10 percent _ a
cost that would sharply increase premiums paid by all.
</P>
<P>
   Some other health plans, worried about their images at a time
that every HMO wears a ``kick me'' sign on its back, will pick up
the cost of one potency pill a week. Even so, Kaiser's frankness
draws the larger issue that politicians hate to confront: Should
medicine be rationed, and if so, by whom?
</P>
<P>
   The answer used to be: Leave it up to doctors. Supposedly,
patients would then get the treatment they needed, unhampered by
the niggling naysaying of insurance company accountants.
</P>
<P>
   But that did not account for an epidemic of incurable greed.
Insured patients were greedy (``Never mind that $100 X-ray, doc,
give me a $1,000 MRI''); doctors were intimidated (``If I don't
give this hypochondriac all the expensive tests he wants, he'll sue
me for malpractice'') as well as greedy (``Why shouldn't I make as
much as a trial lawyer?'').
</P>
<P>
   This incentive to waste and overcharge drove up demand for
medical services without increasing the supply. The result was the
incredible inflation of costs. Insurance cost more and covered less
because the one law you can't repeal is supply and demand.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton came up with an answer: Let government manage
care, ration medicine on the basis of need and subsidize health
care for everyone with increased taxes. This liberal approach
wasn't crazy, but Americans overwhelmingly rejected her approach as
overly intrusive.
</P>
<P>
   That did not stop the idea of ``managed care'' as a rationer;
some institution has to say no, to play the villain, to limit
demand. And so we had the rise of HMOs as a hate object, with some
of the mismanaged ones deserving the fury that patients would have
aimed at bumbling government.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, liberal politicians are offering to ride to
the rescue by having government carefully manage the privately
managed care. Because publicly financed campaigns and tobacco
taxing fizzled as voter-turnouters, ``patient protection'' has
become the Democrats' chosen issue this fall.
</P>
<P>
   That's why we see the president pitching a ``patient's bill of
rights'' that would force the insured to pay for more benefits.
(It's not the employer or the HMO that pays; in the end, the
insured pays.) Such pressure pushes Republicans to counter with
tax-free medical savings accounts and closer regulation of the most
stupidly bureaucratic of the HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   But few will whisper a truism of American life: People who can
afford it are able to buy better health care. The poor, elderly,
disabled and otherwise dependent are entitled to an adequate level
of treatment, but above that level is the best care that money
should be able to buy.
</P>
<P>
   If you work hard, save and invest, you and your family will eat
better, shelter better, travel farther and enjoy yourselves more
than others. Although nobody in America need starve, live without a
roof, or be denied basic medical care or equal opportunity, the
reason most of us earn and save money is to do much better than
subsist.
</P>
<P>
   But isn't that unfair? John F. Kennedy had the answer: ``Life is
unfair.'' The world now knows that nonmonopoly capitalism makes
life better for more people than leveling-down socialism.
</P>
<P>
   To the point: Should the government direct that the price of
something as life-enhancing as a potency pill be within easy reach
of poor and rich alike? The nonpopulist answer few politicians dare
utter: No. The free market does it better.
</P>
<P>
   High initial price and heavy demand will soon draw other pill
makers to produce a better pill at a lower price, which competing
health plans will eagerly cover. The patient's insurance bill will
cost less than a spinmeister's ``bill of rights,'' and all of us
geezers, rich and poor, will be happily rutting around like
rabbits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-98 2041EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
