<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-12 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1326 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK13-COX     07-12 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Maddux ignores accomplishments
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Miami _ No one in baseball studies the game closer than Greg
Maddux, who relies on a near-photographic memory of players and
performances every time he takes the mound. About the only thing he
specifically ignores is how he has performed over his 11 years in
the majors. He finds his life is easier that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``That may be why I do it, to keep the weight of expectations
off my shoulders,'' Maddux said. ``It's my way of trying to control
it. I understand the expectations on me are as high as anyone,
expect maybe (St. Louis' Mark) McGwire and a couple guys like that.
The expectations are tough to deal with sometimes but you try to do
what you can to lighten them.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Maddux was aware his loss Saturday night ended his
10-game win streak but he had no idea he had also won 16 straight
on the road until the Marlins beat him 4-3. He knows he is having a
strong year but doesn't know he leads the league in four
categories. He won't look back, primarily because he doesn't want
to know.
</P>
<P>
   ``I refuse to do it,'' he said. ``I'm aware I've had some pretty
special years but I'm also aware it doesn't matter. It's not going
to help me win my next game. How many young pitchers throw shutouts
and win just one of their next five games? They may have gotten a
little too excited about it and it's easy to forget what you did to
get ready for your next game.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1993 All-Star break, Maddux is 93-28 (.769). His ERA
over the last six years (2.04) is the lowest posted since World War
II and the second-best, Sandy Koufax's 2.19, isn't even close. When
Maddux pitches another 248 innings to reach the 3,000-inning
all-time qualifying status, his career ERA (now 2.74) figures to be
among lowest in history with Grover Cleveland Alexander (2.56) and
Whitey Ford (2.74). Maddux doesn't want to hear the history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not history yet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pride's one-day tour
</P>
<P>
   Curtis Pride accompanied the team to New York Sunday night but
flew to Richmond this morning, where he will join the Richmond
Braves for one game against Pawtucket. The club then plans to
activate him in time for Tuesday's game with the Mets and return
rookie Randall Simon to Richmond.
</P>
<P>
   Pride has still not lived down injuring himself June 27, when he
split his left index finger pounding a wall with his bat. Ryan
Klesko's appendectomy would have provided him the opportunity for
several starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been tough,'' said Pride. ``I would have had a lot of
chances to play. The last couple weeks with Ryan out, I would have
had a chance. Being on the DL has driven me crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Klesko, meanwhile, saw his first action since June 28 on Sunday
and while he was able to drive a ball deep to center with his first
swing and was robbed of extra bases by Mark Kotsay in the eighth,
the Atlanta left fielder went 0-3 with an RBI. Some swings left him
in obvious pain but while it has been 13 days since he had his
appendix removed, Klesko says his weight is not down from his usual
220.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not after the way I've eaten around this place the last five
days,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Life of Brian
</P>
<P>
   Former Brave Brian Edmondson, whom the Marlins claimed off
waivers June 4, made his second appearance against his former club
and allowed an unearned run and a Andres Galarraga single in two
innings of work. That lowered his ERA to 1.31 in 14 appearances
since joining the Marlins. He had a 4.32 ERA with the Braves and
credits his improvement to his slider, which he said the Braves did
not encourage him to throw.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
