<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-FRANCE-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARIS EXPLODES IN JOYOUS CELEBRATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ A million Parisians stormed the Champs Elysees Sunday
night in an early celebration of their July 14 Bastille Day
national holiday unleashed by France's first victory ever in the
World Cup soccer championship, a 3-0 win over Brazil in the Stadium
of France in St. Denis.
</P>
<P>
   Black and white, Muslim and Christian, Arab and Asian, the
people of Paris trooped down the avenue together Sunday night. It
was, the French coach, Aime Jacquet said, a moment of ``national
communion.''
</P>
<P>
   And as the French came together to wave blue-white-and-red
flags, honk horns, and toss cherry bombs and firecrackers onto the
granite cobblestones under a shimmering clair de lune, in the sheer
exuberance of suddenly being on top of the world after a long
period of doubt about whether they had what it took to compete in a
global economy, the Champs Elysees became a Latin quarter, a
celebration of the Gallic spirit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole world is here,'' boasted one of the celebrants,
Rachid Kasimi, a French soccer booster from the racially troubled
suburb of Asnieres who said his family emigrated here from Morocco.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most beautiful avenue in the world, and we're
going to stay here all night,'' he shouted over the din created by
drivers of cars trapped in the celebratory madness honking staccato
victory rhythms, and people shouting ``We've won, we've won.''
</P>
<P>
   Youths with the tricolor painted on their cheeks jumped into
water fountains on the Avenue Victor Hugo. Similar scenes of
delirium played themselves out in Lille, Lyons, Marseilles and
Bordeaux Sunday night, temporarily uniting in joy a people whose
most commonly shared value until recently seemed to be pessimism
about the future. The spontaneous march down the Champs Elysees
will be mirrored by a parade up the avenue Monday afternoon by the
winning French national team, a day before the usual Bastille Day
military ceremonies along the same axis from the Arc de Triomphe to
the Place de la Concorde.
</P>
<P>
   President Jacques Chirac, a conservative who buried the
political hatchet and attended the match Sunday night with
Socialist Prime Minister Lionel Jospin, both wearing scarves with
the national colors, also invited the team, affectionately dubbed
``les bleus'' for the blue color of their team uniforms, as guests
of honor at the Bastille Day celebrations at the Elysee Palace on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The team is as racially diverse as France's spontaneous
demonstrators. Two of the goals were scored by the French team's
top playmaker Zinedine Zidane, whose North African origins made two
Algerian women who gave their names as Nadia and Farida proud to be
among the victory celebrants on the Champs Elysees Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Gabriel Muller, a young black man who had watched the match in a
bar in Montparnasse, said he came to the avenue because the bar had
become too crowded. Soon, so was the Champs Elysees, a mile-long
avenue of eight lanes that is still the place to see and be seen.
It was filled entirely with flag-waving pedestrians half an hour
after the game ended at 11 p.m. And the 164-foot-high Arc de
Triomphe was emblazoned with blue laser signs proclaiming, ``Thank
you, Blues.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``The game was great, Brazil played really well, and it was a
thrill to see our team win,'' said Carla Dupont, a French
journalism student who, with her friend Sophia, was handing out
free plastic boaters Sunday night for one of the soccer
tournament's corporate sponsors, Snickers.
</P>
<P>
   There were only a few querulous French eyebrows raised at the
fact that the corporate soccer sponsors included such multinational
companies as Coca-Cola, McDonald's and Fuji Film. With unemployment
stuck above 12 percent for most of the past three years, and still
at 11.9 percent, France needs jobs wherever it can get them, and
some French officials expressed hope that a soccer victory that had
brought the host team from behind in a truly multinational
tournament would also leave France with enhanced self-confidence.
</P>
</TEXT>
