<DOCNO> NYT19980712.0169 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-12 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1361 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROSPERITY-JOBS     07-12 0568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROSPERITY-JOBS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lack of training leaves jobs open
 &HT;    By Dale Dempsey
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ New development and new businesses are not the
only way a region can grow and prosper.
</P>
<P>
   An area can also look for ways to shore up holes or weaknesses
in its economy.
</P>
<P>
   In the Miami Valley, one of the largest roadblocks to increased
prosperity is a critical lack of trained workers. A study by Wright
State University and the University of Dayton found that even in
this time of low unemployment, more than 48,000 jobs are unfilled
in the eight counties surrounding Dayton. About 12,500 of those
jobs pay at least $30,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   The situation is a problem for the tool and die industry,
transportation, health, retail and the skilled trades. Creation of
jobs in the Miami Valley is a weak 1.4 percent compared with more
robust 9 percent and 10 percent rates in Ohio's other metropolitan
areas and the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could double the size of this business if we could just get
people,'' said Bob Long of Long Electric. ``I've run employment ads
for months and maybe I'll get one call.''
</P>
<P>
   The shortage of workers affects the inventory of products that
can be manufactured and sold, drives up the cost of housing
construction and remodeling and cuts off billions of dollars from
the local economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be you could build a house in 120 days, now it can
take three months longer,'' said David Bohardt of the Homebuilders
Association of Dayton and the Miami Valley.
</P>
<P>
   The shortage is even more critical in the tool and die industry,
which is one of the region's core industries. One tool and die job
can create two or three other jobs in the area, according to Jim
Whalen of Gem City Engineering.
</P>
<P>
   Dayton is the fourth largest center for tool and die work in
North America, behind Los Angeles, San Francisco and Chicago, but
it could be doing even better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Could we produce more and sell more around the country and the
world if we had more qualified candidates? The answer is yes,''
Whalen said.
</P>
<P>
   The tool and die trade has 1,800 unfilled jobs, representing
more than a 10th of the work force of 17,000. Of those, 5,700 will
retire in the next 10 years, creating an even greater demand,
Whalen said.
</P>
<P>
   Tool work can pay $40,000 to $60,000 with four years training
out of high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that is just the beginning,'' Whalen said. ``It can lead
to becoming a tool inspector, a designer or even a shop owner.''
</P>
<P>
   But even high-paying jobs do not appear to be attracting people
to relocate in the Miami Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's because it is an industrywide shortage,'' he said.
``Everyone in the country has the same kind of problems.''
</P>
<P>
   The tool industry is trying to address the shortage with the
creation of the Tool Town foundation, which is part of the 2020
Vision plan. The foundation's goal is to build a training and
research facility called Tool Town in northeast Dayton, recruit
5,000 workers in the next five years and 1,500 each year after that
and market the area's tool expertise more effectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to expand business by $500 million in the region,
a 25 percent increase,'' Whalen said. ``We want to brag to the
world that we are the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Dale Dempsey writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
