<DOCNO> NYT19980712.0170 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-12 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1362 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROSPERITY-POLL-COX     07-12 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROSPERITY-POLL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Never have so many had so much _ and so little time to enjoy it
 &HT;    (EDS: One part in a series of articles on prosperity by the
Dayton Daily News.)
 &HT;    By Dale Dempsey
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Most of us are better off, but few of us are
frivolously spending our money, vacationing in the Riviera or even
flying off to Vegas for the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to money, we're a conservative bunch.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the findings from a Dayton Daily News poll: Despite an
economy that Alan Greenspan says has ``moved beyond history,''
nearly 70 percent of residents polled at random in five area
counties said they did not take any more vacation time last year
than they did the year before, and only 12 percent took vacations
out of the country.
</P>
<P>
   What the poll shows is that our '90s lifestyle is choking our
free time and, in many cases, adding more stress to our lives.
Forty-two percent said they have less free time than their parents
did at their age, and 31 percent said that the primary wage earner
in their family works more than 50 hours a week outside the home.
Thirteen percent said they work 60 hours or more.
</P>
<P>
   Libby Sanders, a heavy equipment operator at AK Steel, said she
works 12 hours a day, seven days a week to make ends meet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't live on Cherry Knob Hill,'' she said. ``It's tough. I
recently had to buy a new car, so now I have payments to make.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Sanders was one of the poll respondents who is optimistic
about the economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think things will change for the best,'' she said. ``I've
always had hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Most people in this area give the economy high marks while an
even higher percentage are confident about the future.
</P>
<P>
   Suzy Peterka of Dayton isn't one of them. Peterka, who operates
a day-care center for children, said she still sees a lot of people
living ``paycheck to paycheck.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It just seems worse to me now,'' she said. ``Most of the
people I see have to work two jobs just to get by.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherry Egbert and her husband, Craig, of Washington Twp.,
operate an auto-repair business and own a nightclub. They find free
time hard to come by.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sixty hours a week is nothing, and it seems like you're not
making any more money,'' Sherry said. ``I thought things were
easier in the '80s for some reason. It seems we have to do more
just to keep our heads above water.''
</P>
<P>
   Others, however, said the economy has given them extra cash and
a more comfortable lifestyle. They're living better even if they
are driving the same car.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Gifford, a news anchor at WHIO-AM (1290), said he is
looking to buy a house, has been able to invest a little bit and
has also been able to ``buy a few new toys.'' Like 59 percent of
the respondents in the Daily News poll, he thinks his generation
has it better than his parents' generation. ``We certainly have a
lot more luxuries now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Daily News poll found people here have a strong personal
attachment to the area. About 31 percent said they have ``strong''
personal ties to the area, while another 55 percent said they have
``very strong'' ties to the Miami Valley.
</P>
<P>
   The economy of the '90s has created a highly mobile workforce,
however. Twenty-two percent of those surveyed said they were ``very
likely'' to change jobs in the next five years, and 16 percent said
they were ``somewhat likely.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the '50s and '60s, few workers now stay put in one job or
even one career. In 1983, men age 55-64 typically spent more than
15 years with their current employer, U.S. Department of Labor
Statistics show. By 1996, the median had dropped to just over 10
years. Only about a third of America's workers have been with their
current employer 10 years or more.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband's job as a sales manager has kept the family on the
move around the country, but Reva Cosby of Centerville has used her
time in the Miami Valley to take advantage of the higher education
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   A teacher at Kiser Middle School, Cosby has earned her master's
degree at Wright State University and is working on her doctorate
in education leadership at the University of Dayton.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me this has been a good place,'' said Cosby, who has two
children. ``I think our family has a bright future. We have good
neighbors and friends I wouldn't trade and our kids have been able
to play more.''
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, Americans still consume at a slightly higher rate
than they save and those figures are reflected locally. Twenty-five
percent said they are not able to save anything, and another 12
percent said they save less than 5 percent. Overall, 63 percent
said they are saving 10 percent or less of their income.
</P>
<P>
   But while they may not be socking money away in saving accounts,
a significant number of residents are playing the stock market in
one way or another. About 30 percent said they had invested in
mutual funds over the past year, 25 percent in stocks and 12
percent in bonds. Overall, about 41 percent said they had market
investments of some type.
</P>
<P>
   The story that emerges is that people are working hard, having
less free time than they would like but generally enjoying the
financial rewards of a strong economy. Prosperity for individuals
and families may have come at a cost to the community, however.
Fifty-three percent of the residents polled said they found no time
for volunteer work of any kind, not church work, not community
work, not political activity. Twenty-eight percent said they manage
up to five hours a week of community service.
</P>
<P>
   Public service is considered by many planners to be a key
element in building strong communities.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Dandaneau, a professor of sociology at the University of
Dayton, observed that much volunteer work in the past was done by
women who stayed at home, and that the increased demand for two-job
couples diminishes the time people can spend in community service.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that people don't have the desire,'' he said. ``A lot
of people would love to trade time for money.''
</P>
<P>
   Dandaneau characterized the late 1990s as an odd time in
history, when people are not as involved in social causes like the
Civil Rights or women's movements. ``There is a sense of just
floating,'' he said. ``This is a more open society than it's ever
been. That's a real achievement built on years of struggle.
Sometimes we get complacent.''
</P>
<P>
   Dale Dempsey works for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
Contact Dale at (937) 225-2270.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
