<HEADER>
A1373 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTO-TALKS-1     07-12 1310
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-TALKS-1,000&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOP-LEVEL TALKS STALLED IN GENERAL MOTORS STRIKE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLINT, Mich. _ Frustrated by deadlocked talks to end a crippling
strike at two auto parts factories here, the chief negotiator for
General Motors announced late on Sunday afternoon that he would
return to his office in Detroit, while the top union negotiator
warned that it would be difficult to settle the strike before
mid-August.
</P>
<P>
   The company's top negotiator, Gerald Knechtel, vice president
for North American personnel, said that GM, the world's largest
automaker, would pursue a three-week-old legal grievance against
the United Automobile Workers union. The company has accused the
union of using the parts factories to stage an illegal national
strike although GM's national agreement with the UAW has more than
a year to run. The union denies the accusation, and the issue will
go to arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   Knechtel also said that the company would step up a review of
its investment plans in the United States. The statement was the
latest of several veiled threats by GM to close assembly plants and
end production of some car models if the union does not accept the
company's ideas for improving productivity.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Knechtel said GM was considering unspecified actions,
of which employees would be notified before any public
announcement. The company has said repeatedly in the last three
weeks that it might cut off health insurance coverage for 100,000
laid-off UAW workers and their families, on the ground that their
union membership made them indirect participants in a national
strike. Knechtel declined to say whether GM now planned to take
such action.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Shoemaker, the union's vice president for GM issues,
said that he planned to stay here and expected to be able to
continue bargaining with Knechtel by telephone. Knechtel and
Shoemaker said that talks would continue among junior negotiators
at the two factories here where workers are striking and at parts
factories in Indianapolis and Dayton, Ohio, where workers have been
threatening to strike.
</P>
<P>
   Shoemaker said ``It'll be hard to resolve this sooner than
mid-August.''
</P>
<P>
   Shoemaker has consistently been more gloomy than Knechtel about
the likelihood of a settlement. He has two strong incentives to be
more gloomy: Predictions of a long strike tend to hurt GM's stock
price, which puts pressure on the company to compromise, while
union members are more likely to scrimp on household expenses and
guard their savings if no settlement is in sight. But even Knechtel
said on Sunday afternoon that he was disappointed by the lack of a
settlement, although he made no forecasts about when a deal might
be possible.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides had tried to reach a deal by Sunday night, when GM's
two-week annual summer shutdown ends. The breakdown in top-level
talks means that one of the costliest strikes in American history
will keep almost all of GM's North American assembly plants closed
for days or weeks to come, at a cost to the automaker of $400
million a week in lost after-tax profits. The automaker has laid
off 161,000 workers across North America, including 44,000 Mexican
workers, 11,700 Canadian workers and several thousand workers in
the United States represented by unions other than the UAW.
</P>
<P>
   About 3,200 workers went on strike on June 5 at a metal parts
factory here that makes hoods and fenders for pickup trucks and
sport utility vehicles and makes engine supports for most G.M. cars
and trucks. Nearly 6,000 workers walked out on June 11 at a nearby
parts factory that makes speedometers, spark plugs, engine air
filters and many other automotive components.
</P>
<P>
   Knechtel had said on Friday that GM was insisting that
settlements be reached in Dayton and Indianapolis as part of any
deal here. But on Sunday, Knechtel said that the main impasse
blocking a settlement involved an insistence by the UAW that GM
invest more money in the metal parts factory.
</P>
<P>
   Knechtel accused the union of waging the strike for ``bad
reasons,'' later explaining that ``it's for reasons involving
demands to put investment into a non-competitive business, and we
won't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The union has insisted that the factory would be competitive if
the car maker spent more money to update its equipment. But GM
contends that the factory's productivity has been hurt by outdated
work rules, including a rule that allows 600 welders of engine
mountings to stop work after four-and-a-half to six-and-a-half
hours of labor, provided that they have completed enough auto
parts.
</P>
<P>
   Before high-level talks broke down on Sunday, a lower-level
negotiator provided the first details to emerge from the dispute at
the metal parts factory. The negotiator, who insisted on anonymity,
said that many union safety grievances and other minor issues have
been resolved. GM has also reached an informal understanding with
the union that the 600 welders would be required to produce more
parts before they can stop work, making it harder for workers to
finish in less than eight hours, the negotiator said.
</P>
<P>
   But four sticking points remain in the talks at the metal parts
factory here, the negotiator said. First, GM wants to retain some
discretion over whether it proceeds with a $180 million investment
here that was announced last year but later placed on hold. Second,
GM has not yet fixed a timetable for the return of parts-making
equipment removed by the company from the factory over Memorial Day
weekend in preparation for a strike.
</P>
<P>
   Third, GM has also resisted union demands to move several
enormous presses here that stamp hoods and fenders out of rolls of
galvanized steel. Moving the presses would improve their speed and
productivity but require a costly redesign of a production line
here, the negotiator said.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, GM has been reluctant to proceed with previous plans to
install two gigantic new presses here, each more than 100 feet long
and packed with the latest technology. The presses are among six
being made for the company in Japan because there are no steel
smelters left in the United States with the equipment to make the
enormous gears needed for the presses. GM has become leery of
installing the expensive machinery in a strike-prone factory with
relatively low efficiency.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   All these issues are similar to those at other factories where
GM has been quick to compromise in previous strikes. But GM
executives have become increasingly concerned that the automaker is
not keeping up with productivity gains at Ford Motor Co. or at
Chrysler Corp. which has agreed to a merger later this year with
Daimler AG.
</P>
<P>
   While any settlement here will not set a legal precedent for
changes in contracts at other local units of the UAW, the company
has been trying to show the union that it will no longer give in
easily in labor disputes. The rules that allow welders to stop work
early here were common in the industry right after World War II,
for example, but have disappeared at rival automakers.
</P>
<P>
   David Healy, an auto analyst with Burnham Securities, said that
the collapse of talks this weekend was likely to hurt GM's share
price when stock trading resumes on Monday. A lengthy and costly
strike makes GM less likely to increase its dividend or buy back
its shares, he said.
</P>
<P>
   GM dealers have virtually run out of popular sport utility
vehicles and pickup trucks, although they still have plenty of
slower-selling cars. Ronald Zarrella, the company's group vice
president for North American sales, service and marketing, warned
on July 1 that if the strike lasted through the end of the month,
GM's market share could decline permanently as many customers would
start buying cars and trucks from rival automakers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
