u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-BRAZIL-5     07-12 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-BRAZIL-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR BRAZILIANS, STUNNED SORROW FOLLOWED BY GRUDGING ACCEPTANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By DIANA JEAN SCHEMO  
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil _ On Copacabana beach, the giant stage
had already been erected, with the festivities for Brazil's fifth
world cup victory celebration lined up for Sunday night. Thousands
of fans, many wearing green and yellow for the national flag,
gathered on the sand to watch the game, undeterred by the winter
rain.
</P>
<P>
   But as day gave way to night, Waldir Alonso, one of those who
had come to watch, fought off pessimism as France scored goal after
goal. With the last, scored in the final seconds of the game,
Alonso stared at the screen and felt a vise tighten over his heart.
He fought back tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our party's over,'' said Alonso, 49.
</P>
<P>
   Well, not quite. A half hour or so later, after France raised
the World Cup trophy in triumph, drummers from a local samba school
took the stage and started pounding, and the beach broke out in
samba, almost automatically. In a nation known for its passion for
soccer and Carnaval, the reminder of the annual pleasurefest
countered the sense of loss with a drumbeat so overpowering the
only possible answer was dance.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the sorrow here was genuine, if brief. Some fans
left the beach with their faces closed to the world, disconsolate
and weeping, as it became clear Brazil would lose. Sportscasters
whose excited calls of ``gooool'' usually resemble a foghorn held
together by a g and an l, Sunday night announced points as if they
were balloons with the air being let out.
</P>
<P>
   The expectation of triumph had been steep and so widespread that
headlines warned of excessive optimism in recent days, and public
opinion polls showed Brazilians feeling better about everything
from unemployment to government. T-shirts around town read,
``Victory Is Ours,'' and the Rio government had put some 2,500
extra police on overtime for the expected party.
</P>
<P>
   With such a buildup, defeat had its crushing side, especially
for those in Paris. The Brazilian coach, Zagallo, walked out of a
televised press conference in anger. Soccer is so tied up into the
national consciousness that one broadcast ended with the announcer
telling viewers that, despite the loss, ``We don't have to be
ashamed to be Brazilian.''
</P>
<P>
   That slip was quickly smoothed over by another announcer, but
echoes of it could be heard on the sand.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were inferior,'' said Alonso, a set designer for a
television soap opera. ``The French deserved to win. They had a
good defense.'' Emir Sader, a sociology professor at the University
of Sao Paulo and at Rio de Janeiro State University, said Sunday
night's defeat would likely lead to a phase of introspection in
Brazil, and ``to questioning a certain omnipotence that Brazil was
feeling.'' It would probably dim the current president, Fernando
Henrique Cardoso's, bid for re-election, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ronaldo Helal, author of ``Problem, Passes and Deadlock: Soccer
and Mass Culture in Brazil,'' (1997, Vozes Publishers, Petropolis,
Brazil) agreed. ``When Brazil loses, it's a pessimism that's
total,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love my country, but I know what defeat means,'' said Marcos
de Salles, a 26-year-old painter. ``This was a fair defeat.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Though some here blamed overconfidence for Brazil's defeat, the
optimism also brought the fans comfort and hope for the next World
Cup in 2002. There were no widespread reports of violence by
Brazilian fans, here or in France.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played well,'' said Fatima Santos, 52, who stared at the
screen and held her 12-year-old daughter, Roselia's, head on her
shoulder before the music started up. ``We're a country that came
from poverty to reach victory. We're a country of soccer,
illuminated by God, with a destiny. We can't win all the time. We
have to give a chance to other countries, who are also God's
children.''
</P>
<P>
   Venceslau de Souza, a 42-year-old cardiologist, wore the hat and
team colors. Forgetting the defeat, he broke into an irrepressible
samba as the band from Governor's Island, outside Rio, started up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't even expect Brazil to reach the quarter finals,''
said Souza. He recalled that when the team initially left for
Paris, they appeared ill-prepared, and had stunned the nation with
their string of victories. ``I'm very proud,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
