<HEADER>
A1375 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAVES-MAIN13-COX     07-12 0421
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-MAIN13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves let series go to Marlins
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Miami _ The Florida Marlins, in the midst of one of the biggest
dives a defending world champion has ever taken, ran the table this
weekend, defeating Denny Neagle, Greg Maddux and then finally Tom
Glavine, a 5-3 loser on Sunday, which should tell you everything
you want to know about high the team charter flew on the way to New
York.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's unbelievable,'' said Andres Galarraga, who should know.
He went the entire weekend without an RBI, just as Walt Weiss and
Michael Tucker went a combined 1-for-25 in their first series after
the All-Star break. Welcome to your second half.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's frustrating, but that's baseball,'' said Chipper Jones,
who hit his 23rd homer in the fourth inning, matching his total
from 1997. ''It's not played on paper. It's not played inside TV
sets.''
</P>
<P>
   Glavine (12-4), who had been 6-0 this season after Braves'
losses, was knocked around for 11 hits, eight of them coming in the
second and fourth innings, when Florida did all its scoring. Mike
Redmond, before this year a five-season minor-league staple in the
Marlins' system, went 3-for-3 with two RBIs and winning pitcher
Brian Meadows (8-6) even drove in the fifth run with a fake bunt
infield single.
</P>
<P>
   It was that kind of weekend. Twenty-eight of Florida 35 hits
were singles. Still, the Marlins won three of four. The Braves
become the first team this year the Marlins have beaten three times
in succession.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gone through one of those things from the eighth inning
(Saturday) through today, where everything they hit found a hole,''
said manager Bobby Cox. ``And they bunched them every time, which
is good. That gives you a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, since Neagle joined the Braves on Aug. 28, 1996, no team
has ever beaten Neagle, Maddux and Glavine in any order in
succession. The idea of dropping Maddux and Glavine on consecutive
days was just as remote. Combined, they had one loss in their
previous 21 starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it happens,'' said Glavine. ``We're all going to have bad
games every once in a while. That's why we don't have a lot of
losing streaks around here because chances are that all three of us
aren't going to have off-games in succession. When we do, it's a
big deal to everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Particularly the Marlins, who have now closed all the way to
within 24 1/2 games of first place.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
