<SLUG> BC-NASCAR-NOTEBOOK13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NASCAR Notebook: Craven comeback stumbles
 &HT;    By Tom McColliste
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUDON, N.H. _ Reality struck Ricky Craven where it hurts
Sunday. Right in the heart.
</P>
<P>
   Four days after his dramatic comeback effort in winning the pole
for Sunday's Jiffy Lube 300, he fell on his face, finishing 29th.
</P>
<P>
   And he wasn't suprised.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was an education. We learned a lot,'' Craven said. ``This
is only the fifth time that Tony (Furr) and I have worked together.
We'll be better because of it. There's a whole lot of highs and
lows in this business. It's never predictable.''
</P>
<P>
   But his return and performance had to be. He hadn't been in a
Winston Cup car since Atlanta in March; hadn't tested; and
admittedly wasn't in tune with the highs or the lows.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still a period of transition where we get used to each
other,'' Craven said. ``I really regret some of the decisions I
made on the chassis. Tony asked me my opinion on some things, and I
feel like that was the culprit.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were other things, too. The tire wear was ugly. We had
an oil leak that killed us there. We dumped oil on the tires. It
was just a day where we had our struggles. In the scheme of things,
it wasn't bad. It was a challenge and that's what we're looking
for. It's not over. It's another beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   Skinner's best
</P>
<P>
   Mike Skinner finally is getting better. He showed it with a
fifth-place finish, his first significant performance since
finishing eighth in the Daytona 500. ``This makes a statement that
when I get that other 25 percent (healthy), and if we can still
communicate like we did today, then we'll be good. (Crew chief)
Larry McReynolds coming over here has really been an inspiration to
me. He's the man. We think a lot a like, and today it showed.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayfield slips
</P>
<P>
   Jeremy Mayfield finally had a bad day, and it was a costly one.
After rolling through 16 Winston Cup events with just one finish
out of the top 20 _ 23rd at Texas _ he finished 30th. Making
matters worse, he dropped from second to fourth in the Winston Cup
points standings and now trails Jeff Gordon by 137 points. ``I
started losing the brakes about halfway and finally hit the wall.''
He was running ninth at the time. ``We'll be back.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
