<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-ATHLETICS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS FALL TO SECOND WITH 7-5 LOSS TO ATHLETICS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Ivan Rodriguez doubled into a double play
yesterday, and the Rangers ran themselves out of a brief stay in
first place in the American League West.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' most heinous base running came in the fifth inning
and kept them from providing a comfortable lead for starter Darren
Oliver. Instead Oliver fell apart after a great start and the
Rangers fell, 7-5, to Jimmy Haynes and the Oakland Athletics at
Oakland Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   The loss snapped the Rangers' five-game winning streak and
dropped them back to second place after the Anaheim Angels defeated
the Seattle Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver, hoping to reverse his poor first-half performance,
retired the first 13 batters he faced, then allowed eight of the
next 10 to reach base. Five scored, and Oliver is 4-7 with a 6.96
earned-run average.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' Oliver said. ``I'm so frustrated right now ...
I really don't know what to say. Things happen so quickly in this
game it's unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Rangers manager Johnny Oates: ``Sometimes you get out of
sync and can't get back into the groove. That shows you what he's
capable of when he's on. But there aren't a lot of Greg Madduxes
floating around out there. It's hard to do. If it was easy, there
would be more guys like him floating around.''
</P>
<P>
   Haynes wasn't Maddux, either. The Rangers had nine hits against
him for two unearned runs, both coming in the eighth inning after
the Athletics had built a 7-0 lead. What hurt was having four
runners thrown out in the first five innings when the game was
scoreless.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not good,'' Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   The fifth was the most painful, starting with Rusty Greer's
single to center. Rodriguez followed with a line drive over third
baseman Mike Blowers' head.
</P>
<P>
   The ball bounced toward the corner, but left fielder Brian
Lesher made a nice sliding stop to cut it off. Third baseman Jerry
Narron put the stop sign on Greer, but he ran through it and was
thrown out at home plate on the relay throw from shortstop Miguel
Tejada.
</P>
<P>
   Narron took the blame, saying he put up the stop sign too late.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should have held him earlier; that's the bottom line,''
Narron said. ``I saw the left fielder slide and I didn't think he'd
come up with it cleanly.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Greer: ``I saw Lesher slide for the ball and when he slid,
I said Jerry is going to send me. So I was busting around the bag.
When I got to the bag he was still sending me. But when I got by
the bag, I saw him stopping me. If I had stopped right away, I
could have gotten back to the bag. It was bang-bang, I had to do it
right there, instead I decided to keep going.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez also got too ambitious after seeing the play at the
plate. With Greer attempting to slide around the tag and catcher
Mike Macfarlane having to dive to get the out, Rodriguez broke for
third and was thrown out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just tried to make third, but I was running late,''
Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hit some balls hard off Haynes,'' first baseman Will Clark
said, lamenting the Rangers' missed chances. ``A lot of them.''
</P>
<P>
   That included the first inning, when Clark lined a two-out
single off Haynes. Juan Gonzalez hit a double into the left-field
corner but again the Lesher-to-Tejada-to-Macfarlane relay proved
effective. Clark tried to run over Macfarlane at the plate, but the
Athletics' catcher held on for the out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tejada made a great throw, Macfarlane blocked the plate and I
had nowhere to go but over him,'' Clark said. ``I couldn't go
around him and if I slide under him I don't make it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
