<DOCNO> NYT19980712.0203 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-12 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1407 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LUNA-MOTH-845&AMP;ADD-NYT     07-12 1215
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUNA-MOTH-845&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRINGING BACK LOST SPECIES, SOME ON ETHEREAL WINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By CAROL KAESUK YOON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Riding delicate pale green wings, with scalloped,
gossamer edges trailing in the darkness, the luna moth, one of the
most spectacular insects on earth, flew through the nights of New
York City before it succumbed to the stresses of pesticides and
development.
</P>
<P>
   Now the luna, which park rangers say has been missing from the
city for decades, will be taking flight here once again. On the
evening of July 20, the 29th anniversary of the lunar landing, the
Parks Department plans to release the first of several hundred of
these most elegant of moths in the Sheep Meadow in Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   But whether the lunas, giants among moths, with wings spanning 4
inches or more, will be able to establish themselves in Manhattan
remains a question in this admittedly experimental effort that some
are hailing as brilliant and others are predicting will almost
certainly fail.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the moth release is one of a number of reintroductions
of native species to the New York City area, part of an undertaking
known as Project X. An idea of Parks Commissioner Henry Stern,
Project X has a dual mission of increasing biodiversity and drawing
more people into the parks.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Urban Park Rangers, who head the project, brought
back 10 species of plants and animals to parks from which they had
disappeared (hence the name X, as in the Roman numeral). Last
year's releases got butterfly weed blooming again in Brooklyn, wood
frogs croaking in Queens and woodchucks chucking in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   This year rangers will reintroduce screech owls, bobwhite quails
and short-tailed weasels, among others. On the tentative plant list
are dazzlers like columbine, pink lady-slipper and even
prickly-pear cactus.
</P>
<P>
   But while this feel-good project may pique public interest, many
scientists expressed concern over the amount of research being done
to ensure the project's long-term success.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very romantic idea to reintroduce species,'' said Dr.
Steven Handel, restoration ecologist at Rutgers University, ``but
just taking a species and putting a bunch of them in, hoping that
they will survive, is a shot in the dark.''
</P>
<P>
   Restoration projects can be extremely difficult. Many efforts to
bring back just a single species, done with considerably more
research, pilot projects and participating experts than the rangers
can muster, have failed over the long term.
</P>
<P>
   Among the biggest obstacles are the nuances of an animal's or
plant's requirements for survival, which can be very difficult, or
impossible, for biologists to identify and which may no longer even
exist in the habitat. At Inwood Hill Park in Manhattan, for
example, nearly all the salt-marsh bulrush planted last year died.
Rangers will try again in another spot this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought it was going to be easy,'' said Bram Gunther,
director of the Urban Park Rangers. ``But we lost it all.''
</P>
<P>
   The people for whom the species are being reintroduced can be a
problem as well. Most of the white turtlehead planted last year in
Kissena Park in Queens was also lost, much of it because of
trampling by walkers who strayed off the path. And while the
Eastern box turtles put into High Rock Park on Staten Island have
survived, there is still no sign of baby turtles.
</P>
<P>
   And there have been missteps. The Parks Department's plan to
bring the Eastern chipmunk to Central Park last year was rejected
by Health Department officials, who pointed out that these rodents
can be hosts for ticks carrying the agent that causes Lyme disease.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Project X releases, however, appear to be taking
quite well to their new homes, at least so far.
</P>
<P>
   As for the coming luna moth release, reactions among biologists
varied.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a marvelous idea,'' said Dr. Charles Remington, an
entomologist at the Peabody Museum of Natural History at Yale
University. ``I'd say go ahead and give it a try, because it's one
of the most beautiful lepidopterans in the whole world. I think
there's terrific potential for success.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Dale Schweitzer, a conservation biologist specializing in
butterflies and moths who works with the Nature Conservancy, said:
``I really think that if an area does not have luna moths now, it's
probably because it's not capable of sustaining a population. At
best it's a waste, or it could be something a lot worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Most experts suggest that the luna moths were done in by some
combination of large-scale DDT spraying in the 1960s along with
urbanization and possibly the bright city lights.
</P>
<P>
   This time, too, the lights of the city may prove too dazzling
for these moths, biologists say, as moths are often confused by
lights, flying around them, failing to find mates and becoming easy
prey for bats and birds.
</P>
<P>
   But Remington notes that the females laden with eggs typically
do not fly to lights. Also working in the moth's favor, Remington
said, is that luna moths in the region go through two generations a
year, allowing them to establish themselves quickly. In addition,
he said, luna moths seem to manage in grimy city air.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   More worrisome, Schweitzer said, is that the luna moths being
released, rather than being gathered from, say, nearby New Jersey
populations, are being bought from a breeder who mates females from
Pennsylvania with males from upstate New York.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to making the introduction less likely to work,
since the moths may be adapted to different conditions from what
they will find in Central Park, the threat such moths pose is the
``pollution'' of native luna moth populations like those in New
Jersey or Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a struggling population of native lunas anywhere in
the region, and biologists say one might still exist even in
Central Park, then interbreeding with these out-of-town moths that
may be better adapted to life elsewhere could be their death knell.
</P>
<P>
   Robert DeCandido, the ranger who is overseeing the luna moth
project, said rearing local moths for release in Central Park would
have required a prohibitive amount of labor. ``They brought
peregrine falcons into the Eastern United States from all over the
world _ Africa, Argentina,'' he said. ``It's been successful. It's
a great reintroduction.''
</P>
<P>
   Still others questioned the aesthetic value of a night-flying
moth in the park, where many people are reluctant to stroll after
dark.
</P>
<P>
   Urban Park Rangers, well aware of their critics, say they think
it is still worth trying to restore this grand, green beauty to its
former home. (DeCandido noted that he can only hope to have lunas
to release on the 20th, at the Moon Day 29 festival, as the moths
emerge from their cocoons according to their own schedule, not the
Parks Department's. The festival will take place from 8 to 11 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   The rangers say they will continue to introduce more native
plants and animals and are on the lookout for good candidates for
next year. They note, however, that not every species once found in
the city will have a shot at coming back: black bears, rattlesnakes
and native roaches have not made the list.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
