<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-12 21:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1408 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GINGRICH-NUCLEAR-450&AMP;     07-12 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GINGRICH-NUCLEAR-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GINGRICH HELPED END PANEL ON THE SPREAD OF NUCLEAR ARMS
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: N.Y., Pa., Okla., Calif. Miss., Neb.)  (js) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT  
c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Speaker Newt Gingrich, who has criticized President
Clinton for not curbing the spread of missiles and nuclear arms,
helped to kill a special commission last month that had been
created to address that very problem.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to reports that China had shipped missile parts and
know-how to Iran and Pakistan, Gingrich said in a letter to House
members on May 14, ``Those dangerous, illegal and destabilizing
transfers have gone almost completely unacknowledged'' by the
administration.
</P>
<P>
   But just before the House recessed last month for two weeks,
Gingrich and a top foreign-policy lieutenant, Rep. Benjamin Gilman
of New York, quietly killed a panel set up to streamline the
efforts of 96 federal offices that address the threat of
proliferation.
</P>
<P>
   Headed by John Deutch, a former director of central
intelligence, the eight-member panel had just begun to untangle the
overlapping government jurisdictions that try to combat the spread
of nuclear, chemical and biological weapons and the means to
deliver them. With the end of the Cold War, proliferation has
become one of the main threats to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're dealing with the No. 1 subject in the world right now,''
said Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., who was vice chairman of the panel.
</P>
<P>
   Despite that challenge the commission is now dead. Aides to
Gingrich and Gilman, who heads the House International Relations
Committee, said the panel got a late start, was ineffective and was
dominated by experts picked by Democrats, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
   With the commission's mandate due to expire in late June, the
Senate easily approved an extension in March, to July 29, 1999. But
Gingrich and Gilman delayed a House vote for 13 weeks, forcing the
panel to fold.
</P>
<P>
   ``They brought up the problem less than a week before the
recess, and it was a very busy week,'' said Gingrich's spokeswoman,
Christina Martin, explaining why the House refused to throw the
panel a lifeline.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans on the panel, as well as many in the Senate and from
past administrations, were stunned by the House snub. They say
Gingrich and Gilman are playing politics with a deadly serious
issue that cuts across party lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were doing important work and now we've been cut short,''
said Henry Cooper, a senior Pentagon official in the Bush
administration whom Gingrich appointed to the panel. ``There wasn't
any partisan substance to our deliberations.''
</P>
<P>
   Brent Scowcroft, President Bush's national security adviser,
said in an interview: ``It's a shame that because of some
bureaucratic rigidities they let this thing die. They were on the
right track.''
</P>
<P>
   Specter said he found no ``substantive objection'' in the House
complaint and vowed to revive the panel this year.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The commission seems to have hit every pothole in the road since
it was set up in October 1996 by the Intelligence Authorization Act
to improve how the government addresses proliferation problems.
</P>
<P>
   It took Clinton 14 months to appoint his four choices to the
panel, formally known as the Commission to Assess the Organization
of the Federal Government to Combat the Proliferation of Weapons of
Mass Destruction. That delayed the first meeting until last Jan.
29.
</P>
<P>
   Gilman objected to the makeup and, in particular, to one member,
Robert Gallucci, the president's special envoy on proliferation
issues. Gilman said he feared that Gallucci would have a conflict
of interest as both a policy maker and an independent adviser.
</P>
<P>
   The four other panelists were two former Democratic
representatives, Dave McCurdy of Oklahoma and Anthony Beilenson of
California; a former Democratic senator, J. James Exon of Nebraska,
and Daniel Poneman, a former national security aide to Bush and
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Deutch said he was willing to add four members to be appointed
by Gingrich and Sen. Trent Lott of Mississippi, the majority
leader. But Deutch said he balked at removing a current member or
limiting the panel's scope.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say they care about nonproliferation policy but they
wanted to control how the commission approached the problem,''
Deutch said of Gingrich and his allies.
</P>
<P>
   The final blow was on June 18, when the general counsel of the
CIA ruled that unless the House acted by June 26, the panel's
authority would end.
</P>
<P>
   Gilman's aides fault Gingrich for not scheduling a floor vote on
a bill to address House Republican concerns. ``The leadership in
the House controls the legislative schedule,'' a spokesman for
Gilman, Jerry Lipson, said. ``If they decide a bill will have time
on floor, it'll have time on floor. If not, it won't.''
</P>
<P>
   The speaker's colleagues fault the White House. ``There is
little the commission could do to address the lack of attention
paid by the Clinton administration to the frightening issue of
nuclear-weapons proliferation,'' said Ms. Martin, Gingrich's
spokeswoman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
