<HEADER>
A1409 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLITICS-INCUMBENCY-1     07-12 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICS-INCUMBENCY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-850(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN CAMPAIGN '98, BEING AN INSIDER IS BACK IN 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Eds: SUBS 5th graf, Sen. Christopher ..., to CORRECT, Bond is from
Missouri, sted Mississippi.) 
 (ATTN: Mo., Texas, Ga., Neb., N.C., Mass., Md., Calif., N.M., Ark.,
Ky., Ohio, Ill.)  (nk) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Majestic and historic, the dome of the U.S.
Capitol was once the favored backdrop in television commercials of
contenders for public office. But in recent years, the only
candidates who dared feature the dome in their advertisements were
challengers who made it a symbol of government gone awry.
</P>
<P>
   Now the dome is back, in all its patriotic glory.
</P>
<P>
   There is no better demonstration of how dramatically the
political climate has changed this election year than in the
commercials candidates are broadcasting around the country. After
years of shunning Washington and politics-as-usual, even incumbents
who once went out of their way to portray themselves as government
outsiders are proudly trumpeting their insider credentials, the
legislation they passed and their connections in Washington or
their state capital.
</P>
<P>
   An examination of hundreds of commercials broadcast by Democrats
and Republicans alike shows that a striking proportion of
contenders are cramming their advertisements with bland but, they
hope, convincing pitches that include insider attributes like
``experience'' and ``record'' and ``proven.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Christopher Bond, R-Mo., this week unveiled a commercial
with this tag line: ``So much experience. So much he's done.''
</P>
<P>
   Here in Texas, the advertisements for Republican Gov. George W.
Bush emphasize that despite his accomplishments, like enacting
``the toughest juvenile justice laws,'' there is much more for him
to do.
</P>
<P>
   The slogan for the campaign of Roy Barnes, a Democratic
candidate for governor in Georgia, is typical: ``Experience and
ideas that work for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray Strother, a Democratic media consultant who advises Barnes,
said the commercials he made for the Barnes campaign in 1990
pointedly did not emphasize the Democrat's record.
</P>
<P>
   ``Six years ago or four years ago, when we filmed our
commercials we wouldn't film them in the marble halls of
Washington,'' Strother said. ``We actually hid incumbency from
people. But experience is no longer a liability. People don't want
to burn down government. They want somebody who can manage it _ and
they're afraid to turn it over to novices.''
</P>
<P>
   Greg Stevens, a Republican media consultant, explained the shift
this way: ``Because there's less anger, voters want people who are
going to get things done. And they perceive that you get more
things done if you have real experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Several strategists explained that their emphasis on
accomplishments is not based merely on gut instinct but on focus
groups and polls showing that voters have had enough of outsiders
who claim that their naivete about the legislative process is an
asset. These days, voters often rank experience and integrity as
the two most important characteristics that they seek in a
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason that both parties are reluctant to bash the
status-quo is that both Democrats and Republicans are now the
status quo themselves. In 1994, Republicans could deride the
Democratic-controlled Congress and White House. Now, they run the
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Six years ago, every Republican was outside the temple saying,
`Tear the temple down!''' recalled Alex Castellanos, a Republican
media consultant. ``We're in the temple now.'' As a result, he
said, he and his colleagues were ``risk averse'' in their
advertising approaches. ``Why take a chance?'' he said.
```Experience that hears you' is the perfect slogan.''
</P>
<P>
   Many advertisements this year could best be described as
30-second, televised resumes. One after another, they feature
newspaper headlines telling of candidates' accomplishments or bills
they proposed. Even nonincumbents are trying to sound like
incumbents. One of the most popular gimmicks is that candidates are
offering toll-free numbers that voters can call to get booklets
listing their accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Terry, an Omaha, Neb., City Council member who won the
Republican primary for a House seat, produced an advertisement in
which he looked into the camera and made this pitch: ``All of us
running for Congress talk about what we'll do. But how do you know
we can? Well, I'm the only Republican running with a record. I've
gotten results.''
</P>
<P>
   Another trend this year is the greater hesitancy to run slashing
attack ads. Those who are lashing out are relying less on anonymous
narrators; instead, several politicians are calmly critiquing their
rivals themselves _ directly to the camera.
</P>
<P>
   When Lauch Faircloth first ran for the Senate in North Carolina
six years ago, his advertisements had a decidedly anti-Washington
cast. But now that he is a Republican incumbent, the National
Republican Senatorial Committee is running a commercial that tries
to play up Faircloth's stature as an insider who could not be
corrupted by Washington. ``Washington's a crazy city,'' the
narrator says as grainy images of the city fill the screen. ``They
pay people not to work and they even elected a convicted drug-user
mayor. But our Lauch Faircloth is shakin' up the place _ doing what
he promised.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The anti-incumbency fervor was always more intense at the
federal level than in state campaigns. But several consultants for
gubernatorial candidates said they, too, were dwelling on
experience and incumbency this year more than in recent elections.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts Gov. Paul Cellucci, a Republican, was lieutenant
governor before taking over from William Weld less than a year ago.
But in Cellucci's quest this year for a full term, he is already
portraying himself as an entrenched incumbent. ``Governor Cellucci
balanced eight budgets in a row,'' the announcer intones in one
commercial, ``and has taken Massachusetts from deficits to a record
surplus.''
</P>
<P>
   In his advertisements, Maryland Gov. Parris Glendening, a
Democrat who faces a spirited primary challenge, ticks off what the
announcer describes as a ``real record of accomplishment,'' from
225 new state troopers to cutting the state income tax. ``It's a
good start,'' the announcer says, ``but there's more to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   Though candidates are proclaiming their experience, many still
prefer to deliver their pitches outside the confines of the
wood-paneled committee hearing rooms in the capital.
</P>
<P>
   New York Rep. Charles Schumer, who is running in the Democratic
Senate primary, tries his insider pitch from a classroom. The
advertisement closes with these words scrawled on a blackboard:
``Chuck Schumer for Senate. He's done more ... He'll do more ...
For you.''
</P>
<P>
   The tone was set in California when Lt. Gov. Gray Davis won an
upset victory in the Democratic gubernatorial primary in June by
portraying himself as far more experienced than his two
better-financed rivals. His advisers said the slogan, ``Experience
money can't buy,'' was central to Davis' swift rise in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   Weeks later, Heather Wilson, a Republican candidate in a special
election for the House in New Mexico, appropriated the Davis pitch
in her own successful campaign against a wealthy Democratic state
senator, Phil Maloof. ``Experience money can't buy,'' the announcer
says. ``Heather Wilson for Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Candidates who lack Washington experience are trying to play up
whatever experience they do have. In one of his commercials, Scott
Ferguson, who ran in the Democratic primary for Senate in Arkansas,
looked into the camera with this appeal: ``Arkansas doesn't need a
senator with a lot of Washington experience. We need a senator with
Arkansas experience.''
</P>
<P>
   He was defeated by former Rep. Blanche Lambert Lincoln, who
declared in her commercials that she had even more experience.
Washington experience.
</P>
<P>
   David Dixon, a Democratic media consultant, created offbeat,
original commercials that emphasized that his candidate for a House
seat in Kentucky, Jonathan Miller, was a family man. But Miller
lost the Democratic primary to Ernesto Scorsone, whose
advertisements reminded viewers that when The Lexington
Herald-Leader endorsed him ``they cited his experience.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to tug more on the emotional heartstrings,'' Dixon
said, ``but people want to hear more about your resume.''
</P>
<P>
   In a primary for a House seat in Ohio, two Republicans dueled
over just who had the most experience. A commercial for former Rep.
Frank Cremeans featured a shot of the Capitol dome and the slogan,
``We need a congressman with real experience.''
</P>
<P>
   But in her advertisements, Nancy Hollister countered that
Cremeans did not get much done when he was in Washington. ``You've
probably heard that former Congressman Frank Cremeans has never
passed a bill,'' the announcer intones. The advertisement went on
to list Ms. Hollister's record as lieutenant governor, with this
close: ``The bottom line: Nancy Hollister gets results.'' Ms.
Hollister won.
</P>
<P>
   Russ Schriefer, a Republican media consultant, said Washington
insiders are so in vogue that he featured former Sen. Bob Dole in a
commercial for Loleta Didrickson, who lost the Illinois Senate
primary this spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used Bob Dole at the end of the ad standing in front of the
Capitol, with just a tag, `Hey Loleta, we need you out here.'''
Schriefer recalled. ``A couple of years ago, four years ago, you
wouldn't have done that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-98 2134EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
