<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCDOUGAL-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCDOUGAL SEEKS TO POSTPONE EMBEZZLEMENT TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DON VAN NATTA JR .    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The lawyer for Susan McDougal has asked a
California state court judge to postpone her embezzlement trial,
which was scheduled to begin on Monday, after he received 1,500
pages of new evidence from prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. McDougal is charged with bilking the conductor Zubin Mehta
and his wife, Nancy, out of $150,000 between 1989 and 1992, when
Mrs. McDougal worked as their assistant and bookkeeper. Although
these charges have no connection to the Whitewater case, Mrs.
McDougal's lawyer, Mark Geragos, said he believes the California
state prosecutors are cooperating with Kenneth Starr, the
independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a classic example of the office of the independent
counsel using this California prosecution to put further pressure
on my client,'' Geragos said.
</P>
<P>
   For refusing to answer questions about the Whitewater case, Mrs.
McDougal served 18 months in jail on a civil contempt of court
citation, and she has steadfastly refused to cooperate with Starr's
inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Geragos said that the new California evidence, which he
described as ``a desk full of sophisticated accounting records and
ledgers,'' was delivered to his office on June 26, one day after
Mrs. McDougal was unexpectedly released from a California prison
for health reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hardly think it was a coincidence,'' Geragos said.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Bakaly, the spokesman for Starr, did not return
telephone calls on Saturday. The California prosecutor, Jeffrey
Semow, also did not return calls last weekend, but he has
repeatedly denied that he had colluded with Starr, saying he had no
idea who Susan McDougal was when she was arraigned in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, Mrs. McDougal pleaded not guilty to grand theft,
check forgery and fraudulent use of credit cards, among other
charges.
</P>
<P>
   The basis of the state case is the Mehtas' financial records,
which show several transactions in which Mrs. McDougal is accused
of making unauthorized personal purchases and charging them to her
employers. The records show that she charged hotel stays, clothes
and thousands of dollars of personal air travel, according to a
financial audit conducted by the Mehtas' accountant, Alan Byron,
who testified at Mrs. McDougal's preliminary hearing in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Since a federal judge ordered her released from a California
prison on June 25, Mrs. McDougal has stayed at her parents' home in
Camden, Ark., as part of a 90-day home-detention sentence. When she
was released, she had served three and a half months of a two-year
prison sentence after she was found guilty of taking part in a
fraudulent scheme to obtain a $300,000 loan that was paid to a
company she created called Master Marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the proceeds went to pay the debts of Whitewater
Development Co. in which she and her late husband, James McDougal,
were partners with President Clinton and Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Geragos said he needed two weeks to study the new evidence
before he would be ready to go to trial. Mrs. McDougal is also
scheduled to undergo medical tests on Monday for a severe spinal
condition, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's in pretty bad shape, but she's also in good spirits,''
Geragos said. ``The irony of this delay is, she can't wait to go to
trial.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-98 2148EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980712.0224 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-12 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1435 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-METS-EXPOS-575&AMP;AD     07-12 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-EXPOS-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS 5, EXPOS 2 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Mets' only constants for most of this season have
been starting pitching and defense. It would be foolish to argue
that Todd Hundley's long-awaited arrival could have had any effect
on the struggling bullpen Sunday, but his presence in the lineup
seems to have produced positive results already.
</P>
<P>
   So, in Hundley's second game back, the Mets put together one of
their most complete performances in quite some time en route to a
5-2 victory over the Montreal Expos at sold-out Shea Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   There was an ``effectively wild'' outing, as catcher Mike Piazza
put it, from Hideo Nomo, who struggled with his command more than
his back in tying his career high with seven walks, but allowed
just two hits and two runs in five and a third innings. Nomo said
he was not bothered by the lower back strain that forced him out of
his last start, July 1 in Toronto, after just three innings.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza, who admitted he had been pressing with men on base,
delivered a run-scoring single in the first inning and gave much of
the credit to Hundley, who was hitting behind him.
</P>
<P>
   Brian McRae's sixth home run in the last 17 games, a two-run
blast in the sixth, erased a 2-1 deficit and put the Mets (46-41)
ahead for good. Butch Huskey tied his career high with four hits
and scored two runs. And the Mets got their first strong outing
from the bullpen in weeks. Jeff Tam (who picked up his first major
league victory), Greg McMichael (whose return from the Dodgers
seems to have solidified the bullpen) and Dennis Cook (who struck
out the side in the ninth) provided three and two-thirds innings of
hitless relief.
</P>
<P>
   All of which added up to the Mets' second straight victory after
losing nine of 11.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley went 0 for 2 with a walk and a strikeout before
departing for a pinch-hitter in the seventh with the Mets still
holding a 3-2 lead. Afterward, the converted catcher expressed
relief at finally being able to catch a couple of balls in left
field. Other than that, Hundley's contributions have been mostly
psychological thus far. But after more than a month of struggles,
maybe that is what the Mets needed most.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's meant everything,'' manager Bobby Valentine said of
Hundley's return from elbow surgery. ``The guys are feeling
confident. I feel confident. All the waiting is over. All the talk
about what happens when he gets here is over. Everyone has seen
what happens. We relax and play a good game of baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   The most calming effect may eventually be on Piazza. Despite a
.345 batting average in his first 39 games with the Mets, coming
into Sunday, Piazza was hitting just .206 (7 for 34) with runners
in scoring position, with one home run and seven runs batted in.
Part of the problem, he said, was that he usually had men in
scoring position once a game at best.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I would get a guy in scoring position, it almost felt
like Little League,'' Piazza said. ``If you don't get him in, you
don't know when your next chance is going to be.''
</P>
<P>
   But with Hundley batting behind him, it takes some of the
pressure off. There was a reason why Piazza saw a 1-2 fastball from
the rookie right-hander Javier Vazquez (3-7) with Lenny Harris on
third and one out in the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``No question about it,'' said Piazza, who lined that pitch to
left for a run-scoring single. ``He's a potent hitter. If you get
by me, you've got to get by him.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   What Hundley provides, Piazza argued, is more balance to a
lineup that has gone through what Piazza called its offensive
``peaks and valleys.'' Just as Piazza's initial insertion into the
lineup seemed to relax the rest of the Mets after his May 22 trade
here, so has Hundley's the last two days. And maybe even a little
before, because of the new competition for playing time in the
outfield.
</P>
<P>
   Both Huskey and McRae _ and even Bernard Gilkey, to a lesser
extent _ have been hitting better as of late. Huskey is 8 for 13
(.615) since the All-Star Game break. McRae, who now has 12 home
runs, quietly leads the team in extra-base hits with 32 _ one more
than Piazza has with three teams this season _ despite a .239
batting average.
</P>
<P>
   Should the Mets continue to get that kind of production behind
Piazza and Hundley, and should McMichael help right the bullpen now
that he is back in the right-handed set-up man role, the Mets
actually may be able to put their month-plus troubles behind them.
</P>
<P>
   If the last two days mean anything, that is.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-98 2149EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
