<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-12 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1440 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOBACCO-TALKS-880(2TA     07-12 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-TALKS-880(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EAGERNESS ON BOTH SIDES IN LATEST TOBACCO TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash., Colo., N.Y., Calif., N.C., Miss., S.C.)  (lb) 
 By BARRY MEIER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the recent talks aimed at reaching a new tobacco settlement,
the best clues to strategy were probably found in the five state
attorneys general with whom the tobacco industry chose to
negotiate.
</P>
<P>
   To cinch a new deal with the 37 states that have remaining
lawsuits, cigarette makers need, at a minimum, to get participation
from the biggest states and from those most eager to settle, and
also bring in some political figures who had participated in last
year's talks.
</P>
<P>
   So, not surprisingly, among the five attorneys general at the
recent talks was Christine Gregoire of Washington, the state with
the next case scheduled to go to trial and one that is considered
weak.
</P>
<P>
   Also present were attorneys general of Colorado and of the
nation's two largest states, New York and California. And although
his state has not sued the industry, Mike Easley of North Carolina
participated as well. He was heavily involved in negotiations that
led to last year's $368.5 billion proposed settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Most state attorneys general had celebrated the completion of
that agreement, believing that they could play a central role in
altering how cigarettes are marketed and sold. But with the
collapse of that plan in Congress, the goals of those same
officials these days are far more limited, practical and political.
</P>
<P>
   Under last year's plan, tobacco companies agreed not only to
reimburse the states for billions of dollars spent treating
tobacco-related ills, but also to allow the government to regulate
nicotine and pay penalties if youth smoking did not decline. A new
proposal under negotiation would still reimburse the states and
lead to some marketing restrictions but would not involve many of
the sweeping aspects of the previous accord, like nicotine
regulation.
</P>
<P>
   The new talks, aimed at resolving the 37 state claims, which
lawyers said involved an industry proposal worth about $200 billion
over 25 years, broke down last week over money. But as state
attorneys general gather Monday outside Durango, Colo., for their
annual meeting, they will hear more details about where the talks
are headed.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those involved in the tobacco debate said they believe
that many state officials, after having their previous plan
rebuffed by Congress, are eager to accept a scaled-back settlement
rather than risk lengthy court fights with tobacco producers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't blame these states for wanting to strike a deal,''
said Matthew Myers, a lawyer with the Campaign for Tobacco-Free
Kids, an advocacy group in Washington. ``They have their lawsuits
and they have every right to try to resolve them.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a desire that has not escaped the cigarette industry,
which views the state lawsuits as the most politically troublesome
and potentially costly claims it faces.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers familiar with the industry's position say that producers
are eager to settle as many state claims as they can, a strategy
apparently reflected in their approach to the recent talks. With
settlements in hand already with two big states, Florida and Texas,
including New York and California in the new negotiations would
ensure that a large portion of the nation's population would be
covered by settlements.
</P>
<P>
   And company lawyers were careful to talk only with those lawyers
or states that were eager to settle, said consultants familiar with
the industry's strategy. For example, one of those who participated
in the latest talks was Attorney General Gail Norton of Colorado,
who filed her lawsuit just two weeks before last year's settlement
deal was achieved and lobbied Congress to accept the deal. Her
office declined to comment on the talks.
</P>
<P>
   The tobacco companies, said one lawyer who spoke on the
condition of anonymity, ``wanted to do an end run around those
states where they would not get a receptive ear.''
</P>
<P>
   There is also little question that cigarette industry
negotiators are dealing with a different cast of state officials
this time, a group that may be less organized and more dispirited.
Key state leaders like Michael Moore, the Mississippi attorney
general who helped develop last year's accord, and Hubert Humphrey
III, the Minnesota attorney general, who pushed producers into
greater concessions, have settled their cases and are no longer
directly involved.
</P>
<P>
   Other notable groups were not represented at the talks. White
House officials, who were consulted last year, were kept in the
dark. In response to the new initiative, administration officials
circulated a memorandum on Friday indicating that they would press
for narrower tobacco legislation that would give the Food and Drug
Administration regulatory authority over the product.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Myers, the anti-smoking advocate who participated in last
year's talks, said he knew nothing about the discussions. And
Richard Scruggs, a plaintiffs' lawyer from Pascagoula, Miss., and
another architect of last year's deal, said he had not been told
about the new talks, even though he represents 26 states with cases
pending against the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Scruggs can thank another plaintiffs' lawyer, Joe Rice of
Charleston, S.C. Rice, who also helped negotiate last year's
accord, represents the same states as Scruggs and was a central
player in the latest round of talks.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Rice, who initially denied that such talks were under way, has
declined all comment. But lawyers familiar with tobacco
negotiations said cigarette producers reached out to him recently
because he is eager to settle his cases.
</P>
<P>
   The opportunity to restart tobacco talks presented itself last
month after a court ordered that cigarette lawyers and the
Washington state attorney general, Ms. Gregoire, hold mediation
talks aimed at resolving that state's tobacco lawsuit, which is
scheduled to go to trial in September.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gregoire's case is believed by many legal experts to be
relatively weak, because a state judge has knocked out some of its
central claims. And tobacco lawyers apparently seized on the
possible legal calamity facing Ms. Gregoire by intimating to her
that they would settle her case only if other states were brought
into broader talks, said lawyers familiar with the discussions.
``They wanted to use her as leverage,'' one of those lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Ms. Gregoire said she believed her case was
strong. Scott Williams, a spokesman for the tobacco companies,
denied that they had brought any pressure on Ms. Gregoire.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, the talks soon broadened, bringing in state
attorneys general like Dan Lungren of California and Dennis Vacco
of New York. While these states are critical because of their size,
the political fate of both men may also be affected by the role
tobacco plays in campaigns this fall.
</P>
<P>
   It has already become an issue in Lungren's bid to become
governor. He has come under sharp attack by both Gray Davis, his
Democratic opponent, and anti-tobacco groups for, among other
things, being slow in suing tobacco producers.
</P>
<P>
   Lungren was the 37th of the nation's 41 state attorneys general
to sue the industry, filing just eight days before the $368.5
billion plan was finalized last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``His record on tobacco is terrible,'' said Stanton Glantz, a
professor at the University of California at San Francisco and an
anti-tobacco advocate.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Stutzman, a spokesman for Lungren, said the California
official believed that his record on tobacco was strong and that
the state's lawsuit had been delayed because the
Democrat-controlled Legislature had passed a bill several years ago
making it difficult for the state to bring a successful case
against cigarette makers. As a result, Lungren had to wait for the
Legislature to repeal the bill before filing his action, Stutzman
said.
</P>
<P>
   While Vacco of New York, who is running for re-election, did
file his lawsuit several months before settlement talks started
last year, he also had come under criticism for, among other
things, hiring lawyers who were also political contributors to
represent the state. Vacco's press office did not return telephone
calls on Friday but he has previously denied any connection between
the contributions and the hiring of the lawyers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
