<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLD </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUP GOES TO FLYING FRENCMEN 
</HEADLINE>
 CUP-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; SAINT-DENIS, France _ The French national team now has a World
Cup trophy to go with its Legion of Honor medals. The Brazilians,
meanwhile, might find joining the French Foreign Legion a safer
alternative than returning home.
</P>
<P>
   France dominated Sunday's championship game, taking a 3-0
victory against an uninspired Brazil team, which offered its least
competitive performance in a final ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came here to win, we have been working for two years for
that and we fully deserved it,'' France coach Aime Jacquet said.
``We all had the same feeling, we were on the same wavelength. We
started off with poor press, and I can never forgive that, but now
everyone can see France has great players.''
</P>
<P>
   The greatest of them was Zinedine Zidane, who headed in two
corner kicks in the first half, and accepted the winner's medals
from President Jacques Chirac as most of the 80,000 fans chanted
``Zizou'' amid waving France tricolor flags.
</P>
<P>
   The French became the seventh nation to capture the title, which
has been an exclusive club of Argentina, Brazil, Germany, and Italy
in the last 30 years. They maintained the tradition of European
teams winning on their continent, broken only by Brazil in 1958 in
Sweden. They also became the first home team to win the title since
Argentina in 1978 and tied for the biggest rout in the final game
with Brazil's wins over Sweden (5-2) in 1958 and Italy (4-1) in
1970.
</P>
<P>
   France offered little in the way of creative, scintillating
offense throughout the tournament, and Jacquet was criticized
heavily for his midfield-clogging, spoiling tactics. But the
players became comfortable with their identity, submerging their
urges toward an aesthetically-pleasing style to settle for
capitalizing on opponents' errors.
</P>
<P>
   And the French certainly became adept at making the opposition
pay for lack of concentration.
</P>
<P>
   There were many Brazilian failures, mostly sins of omission.
They were not proactive enough to cause problems or to put the
French defensive midfielders on their heels. Brazil's
uncharacteristic predictability allowed France to dominate the
midfield.
</P>
<P>
   Part of Brazil's problem was that Ronaldo was playing at half
speed because of leg problems. In fact, the original starting
lineup had Ronaldo on the bench and Edmundo starting, but when
coach Mario Zagallo was in the midst of explaining the situation,
he had an argument with Brazilian journalists and left the
interview room.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first half was entirely dominated by France,'' Zagallo
said. ``I was cheering for the first half to end so that we could
change the style of play. France had two attacks and we had two in
the first half, and they scored on both of theirs.
</P>
<P>
   France barely had to form an offensive strategy, except to blast
some speculative long balls toward Stephane Guivarc'h.
</P>
<P>
   But Brazil also was guilty of sins of commission.
</P>
<P>
   Roberto Carlos, whose mistakes helped lead to goals for Denmark
and the Netherlands, again botched a clearance, giving France a
corner in the 28th minute. Instead of simply sending the ball out,
Roberto Carlos took it to the end line and attempted a bicycle
kick. He protested the linesman's ruling by grabbing the corner
flag. But that did not alter the decision, and France capitalized
as Zidane outmaneuvered Leonardo to head in Emmanuel Petit's
corner.
</P>
<P>
   Zidane headed in another in the 46th minute, this time on a low
corner from Youri Djorkaeff. Again, the opportunity was set up by a
defensive error, this time as Junior Baiano misjudged what seemed
to be an unthreatening lofted pass from Lilian Thuram. Guivarc'h
took advantage to go in alone on Claudio Taffarel, who deflected
his low, left-footed shot for a corner.
</P>
<P>
   Ronaldo had little impact on the game after a 31st-minute
collision with goalkeeper Fabien Barthez. He sent his best shot, in
the opening minutes of the second half, directly into Barthez's
hands from a difficult angle in the goal area.
</P>
<P>
   Even before that, though, Brazil seldom attacked, seldom
pressured the French defense. The result was that France was able
to settle in to a comfortable pace, and Brazil was unable change
gears until after halftime, when Denilson entered the match.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that France was able to dictate tempo and pressure the
Brazilians with a one-forward alignment indicates the Brazilians'
lack of preparation. This was a game that favored the aggressor,
and France was much more assertive.
</P>
<P>
   This was shown by Marcel Desailly, who was ejected midway
through the second half after earning a second caution. The French,
also missing suspended central defender Laurent Blanc, were
sometimes reckless in tackling, but received the benefit of the
doubt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
