<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-SCENE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANCE CLAIMS CUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAINT-DENIS, France _ The French have a word for it _
incroyable. Les Bleus, who've always been failure's poster boys,
soccer's new world champions? Incroyable. Unbelievable.
</P>
<P>
   Zizou and Lolo and Thuthu and the rest of their blue-shirted
playmates had to grab the golden trophy Sunday night, shake it over
their heads, kiss it, and tell each other, incroyable or not, that
it was true. France had beaten Brazil, 3-0, in the World Cup final
in the Stade de France, touching off the most exuberant celebration
in this country since, well, last Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   President Jacques Chirac, wearing a bleu-blanc-rouge muffler
around his suit collar, jumped up and down like a giddy schoolboy.
Zinedine Zidane, who knocked in the first two goals with his
balding pate, embraced captain Didier Deschamps forehead to
forehead. Fabien Barthez, the black-garbed goalkeeper with the
shaved head and goatee, went to his knees, buried his face in his
hands, and wept. While the Brazilians stood in disbelief, hands on
hips, the French danced and hugged and agreed that this was indeed
incroyable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came here to win,'' French coach Aime Jacquet declared.
``We were not going to be satisfied just being in the final.'' Yet
nobody expected this. Not beating the world champions by three
goals. Not shutting them out despite playing a man short for the
final 22 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Les Bleus, who hadn't even qualified for the last two Cups, had
made history just by reaching the final. ``We aren't expected to
win,'' Deschamps had conceded. ``A victory would be a bonus.''
</P>
<P>
   What even the players hadn't counted on, though, was the
groundswell of passion and patriotism that had been building from
Normandy to Languedoc for weeks and which pushed them beyond
themselves. France never has been a soccer country, possibly
because Les Bleus always have been fortune's fools, always defeated
in the big match, always decu, disappointed, and disillusioned.
</P>
<P>
   But once France beat the Italians in a nerve-wracking
penalty-kick shootout and the Germans (their nemesis since 1870 or
so) were upset by the Croatians, everyone began talking about le
reve _ the dream. ``Even I am beginning to dream,'' admitted
Chirac, the cheerleader in chief.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, everybody was sporting a blue jersey and a tricolor
face and shouting ``Allez les Bleus'' and forgetting history.
France was ready for a wild summer fling with its soccer team,
broken heart be damned.
</P>
<P>
   Three hours before the match, thousands of fans without tickets
took the Metro out to this northern working-class suburb, just to
mill around the stadium and come away with a taste. Then they went
back to Paris, to watch the match on the five giant screens that
had been set up across the city.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the Stade, there was _ sacre bleu! _ a pep band playing
in the upper deck. And as soon as they stepped onto the floor of
this 80,000-seat flying saucer, Les Bleus were swept up and carried
off on a rolling wave of drums and noise and singing that never
stopped.
</P>
<P>
   ``On va gagner'' (We're going to win), their fans chirped, and
when Zidane scored on a header off a corner kick _ his first goal
of the tournament _ they began believing it. Then Zidane scored on
another just before the half and le jour de gloire was at hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tous ensemble, tous ensemble, oui, oui'' was the chant. All
together, all together, yes, yes. What Les Bleus had done was bring
a fractious France together. They are black and white, born in
Paris and Lyon and Bordeaux and in Guadeloupe, in Senegal and
Ghana. Zidane, the beloved Zizou, is the son of Algerian immigrants
who grew up in a poor neighborhood in Marseille.
</P>
<P>
   All together, they had brought La France to the brink of
something magnifique and La France had fallen in love with them.
``We have this wonderful rapport with the country,'' Jacquet said.
``We have the whole country behind us.''
</P>
<P>
   When Marcel Desailly was sent off in the 68th minute and Les
Bleus had to play 10-on-11, tens of thousands of throats boomed out
``La Marseillaise'' again and again, urging Zizou and his copains
to keep running on tired legs. Finally here came Emmanuel Petit,
the squad's ponytailed bad boy, on a mad dash upfield, screaming
for the ball as the referee was looking at his watch, craving _ and
scoring _ a delightfully unnecessary third goal.
</P>
<P>
   That was the beau geste that capped the wild summer fling, that
got Chirac flinging up his arms in a victory salute and Michel
Platini, the organizing committee chief, pumping his fists in glee.
Platini was the star of the 1982 and 1986 teams that were stopped
just short of the final. Sunday night, for luck and solidarity, he
wore his old blue jersey beneath his blazer.
</P>
<P>
   When the weeping and the dancing and the hugging was done, Les
Bleus came up one by one, Zizou and Lolo and Thuthu and the rest,
to shake hands with Monsieur le President, to get their gold medals
and to grasp the trophy with both hands to make sure that le reve
was real.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere in the Pantheon, just before midnight, Voltaire nudged
Zola. ``Champion du Monde? Incroyable, n'est-ce pas?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
