</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980712.0230 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-12 22:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1450 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TINABROWN-MEDIA-1STLD     07-12 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TINABROWN-MEDIA-1STLD-WRITETHRU-875(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TINA BROWN EDITS HER CAREER TO MATCH THE ZEITGEIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Subs to clarify positions of Newhouse and Florio in 4th
graf.)  
(lh) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER with GERALDINE FABRICANT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Of all the documents that passed over Tina Brown's
desk in June, two received particular attention. One was the
proposed five-year contract that would ensure she remained The New
Yorker's editor through mid-2003. The other was Brill's Content,
the ballyhooed new magazine about the press.
</P>
<P>
   The contract was an invitation to continue to edit the magazine
whose words had set it apart as an intellectual arbiter and whose
balance sheet _ over which she had little control _ had set it
apart as a financial sinkhole. Brill's Content was proof that
alternatives existed, that a high-profile editor with well-endowed
backers could create a magazine with instant impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sort of intrigued by the Brill label and the things he
had been able to do,'' Ms. Brown said in an interview. ``They did
give me additional impetus'' to think about alternatives. And
Harvey Weinstein, the co-chairman of the film production company
Miramax, was aggressively seeking to enlist her to create a
magazine and a company, which she would partly own.
</P>
<P>
   At Conde Nast, she remained close to S.I. Newhouse Jr., chairman
and chief executive of Advance Publications, of which Conde Nast is
a unit, but her influence no longer matched her ambitions. To the
outside world, The New Yorker's editor was winning the
public-relations battle with Conde Nast's chief executive, Steven
T. Florio, over who deserved the blame for The New Yorker's
financial woes. But within the company, Florio increasingly got his
way. She did not, and she felt vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   And Weinstein wanted her to do something she had never done, to
shape a magazine _ ``put down the editorial DNA,'' in Ms. Brown's
phrase. She would be both an owner and a participant in the profits
of the individual films or books spun off from the magazine
articles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why be the owned star, if you can be the star owner?'' asked
Stephen Schiff, a screenwriter who is a friend of the editor.
</P>
<P>
   That may be an easier question to answer than the questions of
the entertainment executives who admire Ms. Brown, but do not
admire magazines. Sumner M. Redstone, the chairman of Viacom Inc.,
said: ``Entertainment companies are moving away from print. They
are simply not that interested.'' But he added that if anyone could
pull off such a venture, it would be Tina Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Others who attended this weekend's annual Sun Valley meeting of
media company executives asked what good ownership is, when quality
magazines can cost $10 million, $20 million, $30 million or more to
start and often lose money for five years.
</P>
<P>
   And among journalists, eyebrows were raised about the up-front
effort to tie the fact-based craft of nonfiction to the
fantasy-based world of film. ``If the stated purpose of this is to
develop entertainment packages, that's not what journalism is,''
said Bill Kovach, the curator of the Nieman Foundation.
``Journalists survey the world to inform the citizen, not with the
idea of creating a property to entertain the citizen.''
</P>
<P>
   That sort of skepticism did not deter Ms. Brown, who said: ``I
certainly don't intend to ever compromise the journalistic
integrity of the magazine for an end game with Hollywood. If I did,
it would have a short life.''
</P>
<P>
   What she intends is to recreate the successes of her 20-year
editing career. At Tatler, Vanity Fair and The New Yorker, she
constantly put new geist in the Zeitgeist. Last week, she edited
her career with the same instinct for emerging trends. Like Brill,
she is setting out to defy the odds that a new magazine will get
lost in the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Like Geraldine B. Laybourne, the leading force in children's
television programming who left Walt Disney Co. and ABC last month,
Ms. Brown is leaving a large corporation to work for herself.
(Although it is also true that Ms. Brown's new company, as a unit
of Miramax, will ultimately fall under the large corporate umbrella
of Walt Disney Co.)
</P>
<P>
   Like Martha Stewart, the multimedia arbiter of all things
tasteful, Ms. Brown and her partners hope to make a magazine the
core of a lucrative empire encompassing books, movies and
television productions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been an editor in chief for 20 years,'' Ms. Brown said.
``If a job was what I was going to be doing, this was the best job
in the world. But I had reached the point in my life when I wanted
to do more than a job.'' She added: ``Just thinking about this
week's magazine, fun and exciting as it was, wasn't enough to keep
me intellectually challenged. I wanted to grow in a more lateral
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brown, whose resume contains little in the way of financial
background, sought out Ron Galotti, the publisher of Vogue, to talk
to Weinstein. ``I said I really need to have a business partner
with me to ascertain that this isn't just high-concept without
having its feet in nitty-gritty land,'' she said. In the end,
Galotti decided to join her as a part owner of the new venture.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that was so unique about this was that it made sense
right away,'' he said. ``It's not some far-fetched idea that
required exaggerated thinking. You create a high-quality magazine
and give young writers a place to start. Tina has the sensibility
to do that more than anyone else. She has an instinct for it.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   And, he said, ``the editorial aspect of the magazine will have
no commercial overtone at all,'' and advertisers will not influence
the content of articles. But, he said, working for Miramax, a film
company with its own publishing arm, could give advertisers wider
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to one of the larger cosmetic companies,'' Galotti
said. ``They are looking to move our tentacles into the Hollywood
area.''
</P>
<P>
   A shot in a Miramax film, he said, could include such an
advertiser's products: ``I would immediately see a bathtub
surrounded by the Elizabeth Arden product or Clinique.''
</P>
<P>
   And he added, ``I think clients are looking for new
out-of-the-box ideas and ways to position products and brand their
concepts.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, the magazine might do an article on Italian
automobile executive Gianni Agnelli, while Miramax produced a
companion biography to run on the Arts &AMP; Entertainment cable
channel.
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein was unfazed by business executives' predictions of
five years of losses before a magazine could be profitable. ``I
have never followed a traditional formula in my life, and I don't
believe in them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Galotti and Ms. Brown gave no details about the extent of their
ownership stake or the amount of backing Weinstein has committed to
the publication. Weinstein said only that Galotti and Ms. Brown
would have salaries and would participate in the profits from
individual films or books as well as have an ownership stake in the
company.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brown said in an interview that she and Weinstein ``have
been friends for some time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel that the kinds of movies he makes are the kind of
journalism we try to do,'' she said. ``He has this incredible gift
for making good things commercial. I found myself asking, surely
The New Yorker can't be harder to market than `The English
Patient?'''
</P>
<P>
   The remark underscored her continuing frustration at the
financial strategies employed by Conde Nast at The New Yorker.
Although she remains discreet about any direct criticism, dwelling
mostly on the closeness of her relationship with S.I. Newhouse Jr.,
her partisans on the staff of The New Yorker are scathing about
Steven Florio and dismissive of his brother, Thomas Florio, who
served as The New Yorker's president until last month.
</P>
<P>
   Then, according to both Florios, Tom Florio asked his brother
for a new job, saying the presidency was far less attractive when
many of the management and production functions would be melded
into the larger Conde Nast structures. Steve Florio agreed and
suggested Tom Florio take over as publisher of Conde Nast Traveler.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brown was not consulted about that move, nor about Tom
Florio's successor, David Carey. Though she repeatedly praises
Carey as ``a terrific hire,'' she also confided to friends that the
magazine would be in better financial shape if some of her
suggestions for increasing circulation revenue had been heeded a
year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The New Yorker lost $11 million last year. But that loss masked
the steady improvement of the magazine's performance since 1993 _
when Steven Florio was the president and Tina Brown the incoming
editor. That year, it lost $30 million.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brown's failure to gain any authority over the business side
rankled, particularly when her name was juxtaposed with reports of
the magazine's financial losses. Her suggestions about tying The
New Yorker to new publishing or film ventures were also ignored,
although 20 of the magazine's pieces had been optioned for films
during her tenure, and at least as many were becoming books.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had made such a success editorially, and to have all the
business problems dragged across the papers and everything with it,
it was extremely dispiriting,'' said one of the magazine's editors,
speaking on condition of anonymity. At a dinner for her staff on
Thursday, Ms. Brown said, ``Sometimes in the last six months I have
felt so vulnerable and exposed.''
</P>
<P>
   But despite this, and despite the increasing irritations
associated with the move into the new Conde Nast tower being built
in Times Square (staffers were constantly complaining about their
new accommodations, she confirmed), Ms. Brown had planned to sign
the contract as recently as mid-June, although she would have
preferred to have a shorter-term agreement.
</P>
<P>
   She never got around to asking for that, she said. Weinstein got
there first. As Ms. Brown tells it _ an account confirmed in
general by Weinstein _ he read about her coming contract renewal,
and he reminded her of conversations they had had months before
about the prospects for a new magazine. Then, feeling she had not
taken him seriously, he called her agent, attorney Morton Janklow,
during the last week of June.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brown heard him out, but had other worries. Her mother, who
had been suffering from cancer for about a year, was fading
rapidly. Telling Janklow to work out some details with Weinstein,
she spent her time with her mother.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother died on June 30. Five days later Ms. Brown called
Weinstein and asked him to meet with her and Galotti in New York.
``The Monday after the Fourth of July, I surfaced after this
terrible five days,'' Ms. Brown said. ``I felt strangely strong at
the end of that experience. My head began to clear for the first
time in a long time, and I began to feel a tremendous desire to
have my motors raced.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday they met at her Manhattan brownstone and later at her
lawyer's office. The deal was completed after more than 40 hours of
discussions and contract drafting.
</P>
<P>
   At 8:30 that morning, Ms. Brown called Newhouse and asked to
meet with him. She walked from The New Yorker's offices to Conde
Nast and told him of her resignation.
</P>
<P>
   A Conde Nast executive, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
that there is a long list of possible candidates to succeed Ms.
Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Newhouse has promised a selection by midweek. Among those on the
list, the executive said, were James Truman, the company's
editorial director; Peter Kaplan, the editor of The New York
Observer; David Remnick, a New Yorker writer, and Dominique
Browning, the editor of the Conde Nast magazine House &AMP; Garden.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
