<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-12 22:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1462 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-COL-CRONYISM-NYT &LR;      07-12 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-CRONYISM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: AT CITY HALL, SHADES OF ALL IN THE FAMILY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ELIZABETH KOLBERT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ What parent wouldn't be proud?
</P>
<P>
   After spending practically a lifetime laboring in the vineyards
of New York politics, Raymond Harding, leader of the Liberal Party,
now has not one but two sons serving the city in high places.
</P>
<P>
   His younger son, Russell, 34, agreed last month to head the
city's Housing Development Corp., which finances housing for low-
and middle-income families. Then last week, his older son, Robert,
40, assumed the even more impressive post of city budget director,
a position that puts him in charge of a budget larger than that of
most states.
</P>
<P>
   Could a father hope for better proof of his good example than
that his sons would, for the public good, shoulder such heavy and,
one can only presume, unfamiliar responsibilities?
</P>
<P>
   After all, until his appointment to head the housing finance
agency, Russell Harding had no background in financing housing. And
until his appointment to head the budget-writing office, Robert
Harding had no background writing budgets.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, some people have had mean, cynical things to say
about both appointments. As soon as Russell, a college dropout, was
named to his $111,000-a-year position, there were cries of
``Patronage! Patronage!'' When, on top of that, Robert was then
named to his $137,000-a-year position, critics waxed practically
apoplectic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tammany had higher standards than this,'' declared Richard
Wade, the urban historian, who was once himself active in the
Liberal Party. ``How could you have a nationwide search and come up
with the kids of Ray Harding?''
</P>
<P>
   Edward Rogowsky, another longtime student of New York politics
and director of City University's government internship program,
marveled at what an obvious act of cronyism the appointments seemed
to represent. ``Are there any members of the Harding family left
who need a job?'' he asked with mock concern.
</P>
<P>
   At the news conference announcing Robert Harding's appointment,
Harding, pere, was challenged by reporters about his son's rather
thin-looking credentials. He scoffed at their naivete.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anybody thinks Rudy Giuliani would turn over the management
of a $34 billion budget for political considerations,'' he said,
``they don't know Rudy Giuliani.''
</P>
<P>
   Harding has a point. To be sure, the choice of not one but two
Harding boys for high positions represents, in sheer mathematical
terms, a staggering coincidence. And yes, Harding played a critical
role in the mayor's 1993 election when he secured for the
distinctly unliberal Giuliani the Liberal Party line.
</P>
<P>
   But that does not mean that the sons' appointments are a payback
to their father, whose loyalty, it could be argued, has already
been amply recompensed.
</P>
<P>
   More significant is what these all-in-the-family choices suggest
about Giuliani's narrowing circle. Rather than bringing in new
talent and outside perspectives, he appears, in his second term, to
be looking increasingly inward, drawing on a smaller and smaller
group of intimates for counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why Robert Harding, until recently the city's lobbyist in
Albany, had been chosen to head the budget office, Abraham Lackman,
a former city budget director, defended him as smart and hard
working. But, he said, ``probably Bob's strongest point is that the
mayor trusts him.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all administrations tend in their waning years to become
more insular. In their third, and perhaps not coincidentally final,
terms, both former Mayor Edward Koch and former Gov. Mario Cuomo
were also faulted for their circle-the-wagons style of governance.
The only difference, some say, is that in Giuliani's case, the
wagons seem to be closing in a little sooner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Either because the circle was smaller to begin with or because
he is so terrifying to work with,'' Rogowsky speculated, ``with
Rudy it is just happening earlier.''
</P>
<P>
   When this columnist contacted Harding directly to ask about his
sons' recent appointments, he repeated his assertion that he had
nothing to do with securing them and added that it was not his
place to defend the mayor's decisions. ``I don't comment,'' he
said, ``on City Hall.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor did he stoop to defending himself. Instead, with the stoic
dignity that has served him so well for so many decades, he said:
``I've lived my life the best way I know how. If people find that
objectionable, there's very little I can do about it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
