</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-DEVILRAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORTUNE MEETS TALENT: YANKEES' 10TH STRAIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)  (lb) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ If the New York Yankees are not the best
regular-season team in history, they might be the most fortunate,
or maybe they are so lucky because they are so good. Serendipity
and talent every day, in varying increments. Every day, it's
victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees broke a ninth-inning tie with Tampa Bay on Sunday
when Chuck Knoblauch was hit by a pitch with the bases loaded, and
they went on to add six more runs, the 9-2 final score blurring the
vacillating nature of this game. The Yankees have won 10
consecutive games; they have a 65-20 record and lead their division
by 15 games.
</P>
<P>
   They are to baseball what Microsoft is to the computer industry,
and no lawyers can protect the rest of the American League. ``The
Yankees are by far the best team we've played all year,'' said
Roberto Hernandez, the Tampa Bay reliever who hit Knoblauch. ``They
do what it takes to win. They find a way.''
</P>
<P>
   David Wells, a starting pitcher in the All-Star Game last
Tuesday, left Sunday's game after five innings because of what he
and the Yankees said was a bruised right big toe. Wells said he
injured the toe slipping down the stairs and banging his foot
against a wall on Wednesday in his Tampa Bay-area home. An X-ray
revealed no fracture.
</P>
<P>
   Wells has suffered gout in his right big toe in the past, but
Brian Cashman, the Yankees' general manager, said there was no
indication that Wells' current trouble was related to gout. Wells
said he did not expect to miss his next scheduled start, on Friday
in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees led by 2-1 when Wells departed, but Tampa Bay tied
the game in the bottom of the sixth. Relievers from both teams
pitched effectively through the eighth inning. Hernandez, the Devil
Rays' closer and one of the game's hardest throwers, took over in
the ninth, with the strategy of Tampa Bay Manager Larry Rothschild
clear: hold off the Yankees for an inning or two with his best
reliever and try to squeeze across a run.
</P>
<P>
   But Hernandez complicated the situation immediately, walking
Darryl Strawberry on four pitches to open the inning. After jogging
to first, Strawberry turned and looked toward the Yankees' dugout
in anticipation, and sure enough, Homer Bush sprinted out to run
for him.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, 25, plays only rarely, and yet his job is extremely
difficult. About twice a month, he is inserted into a crucial
situation as a pinch-runner, and any hesitation or misread could be
a pivotal blunder.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, he told his wife, Monica, whose name is tattooed over
Bush's heart, that he has a difficult time staying focused in the
early innings, keeping his concentration, for he knows there's
virtually no chance he will play. Before the seventh inning,
however, Bush begins preparing for the vague possibility he will
pinch-run in the eighth or ninth; his role, he has told friends, is
something like that of a closer.
</P>
<P>
   He will start stretching, and during Saturday's game he saw Tim
Raines jog around the sofas and lounge chairs in the clubhouse
here, and Bush liked the idea; in the seventh and eighth innings
Sunday he started jogging in the clubhouse, and then running up and
down the steps that lead to the Yankees' dugout, before sprinting
onto the field to replace Strawberry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Homer's never nervous,'' said Jose Cardenal, the Yankees'
first-base coach. ``He's always cool when he gets out there. He's
just very aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush edged off first, his lead four and a half steps. Chad
Curtis, the next batter, squared to bunt, and once Bush saw Curtis
get the ball down on the ground, toward the mound, he burst for
second. Hernandez fielded the ball and threw to second, but Bush,
diving in head first, reached the bag and banged into shortstop
Kevin Stocker, knocking him backward. Safe.
</P>
<P>
   Bush led off second, Curtis off first. Scott Brosius bunted, to
the left side, and Hernandez charged the ball. Rushing this time,
he whirled and fired to third and appeared to have a great chance
at getting Bush; diving head first again, Bush heard the throw
bounce off the artificial surface, glanced up and saw it slip away
from third baseman Bobby Smith. The Yankees had the bases loaded
and nobody out.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez, his fastball reaching 99 miles an hour, then struck
out Ricky Ledee, the first out in the inning. Knoblauch fell behind
no balls and two strikes and made up his mind just to make contact.
Hernandez threw a ball, then decided to tempt Knoblauch with a
slider. It was 85 mph and spun right onto the top of Knoblauch's
left shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch bent over briefly at home plate, his shoulder
throbbing, realizing he had just forced Bush home with the lead
run. ``The pain only lasts momentarily,'' he said, a pack of ice
wrapped against his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' offense is sluggish, and yet, on consecutive
Sundays, they scored the decisive run when a batter was hit by a
pitch with the bases loaded _ they beat Baltimore 1-0 on July 5.
Bush was good enough, fast enough to create opportunity, and the
Yankees were lucky Knoblauch was hit.
</P>
<P>
   After that, Derek Jeter hit a two-run single, Tino Martinez
laced a three-run double, and soon they were showered and on their
way to Cleveland, a juggernaut in flight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
