<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-DWYER-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON HIS BEST BEHAVIOR, CORONADO'S QUEST WINS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMONT, N.Y. _ Coronado's Quest behaved like a gentleman but ran
like a demon Sunday at Belmont Park, and the combination proved
devastating.
</P>
<P>
   A 3-year-old son of Forty Niner who was held out of the Kentucky
Derby in May because of his history of fractious behavior before
races, Coronado's Quest dominated four rivals and won the Dwyer
Stakes by five lengths over Ian's Thunder.
</P>
<P>
   With the second half of the racing season still to be run, he
served notice that he is a horse of championship caliber.
</P>
<P>
   ``This horse is the bomb,'' said the jockey Mike Smith, a
frequent victim of Coronado's Quest's violent behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``He ran great and gave a real professional performance. He
loaded well, broke well and behaved perfectly. It's nice to see
that from him, considering where we came from.''
</P>
<P>
   Shug McGaughey, who trains the colt for Stuart Janney III of
Maryland, said: ``He didn't give us any problems, and he was very
professional. I have to consider this one of his best races,
considering that we were carrying 124 pounds and also for the fact
that they really tested him.''
</P>
<P>
   McGaughey accepted the chance for future tests against the stars
of the Triple Crown campaign, with the first one probably on Aug.
9, in the Haskell Invitational at Monmouth Park.
</P>
<P>
   The testers will include Real Quiet, winner of the Kentucky
Derby and the Preakness; Victory Gallop, winner of the Belmont
Stakes, who thwarted Real Quiet by a nose on the threshold of the
Triple Crown, and Favorite Trick, last year's juvenile champion and
Horse of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   For whichever horses can run a mile and a quarter, there is also
the Travers at Saratoga on Aug. 29.
</P>
<P>
   For people drawn by his record of bad behavior, Coronado's Quest
may have been a disappointment Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   For people drawn by his record as a racehorse, he was a smashing
success.
</P>
<P>
   He was allowed to be saddled in a stall at the far end of the
saddling shed and to skip the customary circling of the paddock and
even the post parade. But he exhibited no roughneck tendencies. He
set the tone and the pace of the race, he withstood several
challenges as he turned for home, and he widened his lead down the
homestretch.
</P>
<P>
   At the finish, Coronado's Quest had five lengths on Ian's
Thunder, a 32-1 shot who roared from last place to second.
</P>
<P>
   Ian's Thunder had three-quarters of a length on Scatmandu,
another supposedly reformed rogue who kicked and bucked before the
race while two grooms led him around the walking ring, and who then
rapped his head against the starting gate.
</P>
<P>
   Scatmandu paid for his rambunctiousness. After rallying wide on
the turn for home and mildly threatening Coronado's Quest, he was
forced to settle for the distinction of outrunning Rock and Roll
and the 9-1 outsider Undaunted Mettle, who had fought Coronado's
Quest for the lead for about half a mile before subsiding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had dead aim,'' said Richie Migliore, the rider on
Scatmandu, ``but the winner was too much horse today. My horse got
agitated in the paddock and banged his head on the gate and got cut
up a bit. I'm not giving it as an excuse, and my hat is off to
Coronado's Quest.''
</P>
<P>
   John Kimmel, who trains Scatmandu, said his colt ``banged his
head so hard that he probably ruptured a blood vessel.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was bleeding profusely from his left nostril,'' Kimmel
said. ``He was probably sucking blood into his airway, and that
compromised his finish.''
</P>
<P>
   Coronado's Quest ran the mile and one-sixteenth in 1:42 2/5. He
paid $2.90 for a $2 bet to win and earned $90,000. He has now won
eight of his 12 races and banked $860,000.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The low point in his career came last winter in Florida when he
became the talk of the town with his boorish behavior before races
at Gulfstream Park. He threw Smith once, refused to let him get
into the saddle another time and generally carried on, even though
he was allowed to be saddled privately.
</P>
<P>
   But McGaughey persisted. He skipped the Kentucky Derby and its
clamorous scene, and held the colt out of the Preakness and the
Belmont because of a foot injury. But Coronado's Quest won both the
Wood and the Riva Ridge in New York, and on Sunday showed exemplary
social graces and winning speed as he captured the Dwyer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
