<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GONZALEZ-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANCE TOWERS OVER WORLD; IT'S NO WONDER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 1998 World Cup final will go down as a tremendous upset,
perhaps one of the greatest in the decades-long history of the
planet's most gripping sports tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Underdog France 3, mighty Brazil 0.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quel'' surprise.
</P>
<P>
   France, a nation with precious few victories in major team
sports since Napoleon's squad had some big wins in the early 1800s,
a team sans outstanding individual players, over the one-name
magicians from the greatest soccer-playing country in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Incroyable.''
</P>
<P>
   A tremendous upset.
</P>
<P>
   Or was it?
</P>
<P>
   France had an unbelievably easy road to the finals, emerging on
top of the weakest group in the field, knocking off
defense-oriented squads from Paraguay and Italy (in penalty kicks),
and drawing Germany-killers Croatia in the semis.
</P>
<P>
   Surely the comeuppance would come against the gifted Brazilians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will win,'' Brazil coach Mario Zagallo said. ``Have no
doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no doubt in this corner, or in many other places
around the globe.
</P>
<P>
   Surely the real final was played Tuesday, when Brazil beat
Holland in one of the most entertaining matches of the six-week
tournament. All the experts said so.
</P>
<P>
   The French, though, begged to differ. They believed they could
win.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, in retrospect, we should have believed along with them.
</P>
<P>
   The first clue came in the 2-1 victory against Croatia in the
semifinal. With its forwards missing in action, France needed
offense from somewhere, anywhere. It came from the unlikeliest
source.
</P>
<P>
   Defender Lilian Thuram, who hadn't put the ball in the back of
the net in 37 international matches, scored both goals. That's the
equivalent of a .200-hitting shortstop going deep twice to put his
team in the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   A team of destiny? Hogwash. But clearly something unusual was
going on.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had come too far to lose'' was Thuram's simple explanation.
</P>
<P>
   The second clue came when Croatia knocked off the Netherlands to
take third place. Perhaps the teams on that side of the bracket
weren't so weak after all.
</P>
<P>
   The real tipoff, though, came before kickoff.
</P>
<P>
   The French players were supposed to be nervous, weren't they?
But there they were, arms draped on each other, belting out their
national anthem with gusto, smiling.
</P>
<P>
   It was a great snapshot, and a major hint that we were about to
witness something special.
</P>
<P>
   The relaxed, confident French team, buoyed by the cheers of a
once-blase nation, proceeded to do the impossible. They didn't just
beat the Brazilians, they dominated them.
</P>
<P>
   When it was ended, we had one of those rare moments that
transcend sport.
</P>
<P>
   You didn't have to be a tennis fan to get the warm fuzzies over
Jana Novotna's redemption at Wimbledon. You didn't have to be a
baseball fan to get a tear at the sight of Walt Weiss' son in the
stands at the All-Star Game after surviving a bout with the deadly
E. coli bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   And you didn't have to be a soccer fan to appreciate what the
home country did yesterday at Stade de France.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, perhaps it takes an appreciation of the sport to understand
the brilliance of Zinedine Zidane's two goals, or the toughness of
the French defense _ two goals in seven matches, one on a penalty
kick? Now, that's incredible _ or how much of a rout a 3-0 result
is.
</P>
<P>
   But even a nonsoccer fan can understand the depth of feeling
when the most coveted prize in the sports world is won by the host
country.
</P>
<P>
   The lasting images from the World Cup final won't be Zidane's
two headers, or goalie Fabien Barthez's save of Ronaldo's
point-blank blast.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they will be of the French celebrating in the streets,
and of the explosion of noise when French captain Didier Deschamps
held the trophy aloft.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 World Cup gave us some great moments. It gave us
Croatia's run to the semifinals, the emergence of England teen-ager
Michael Owen, the attacking play of the Dutch, the usual quota of
superlative goals and fantastic saves. It gave us high-scoring
games, and the high drama of penalty shootouts. It gave us that
marvelous commercial with the Brazilians in the airport.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, though, the 1998 World Cup gave us a great moment in
national pride. It gave us a group of competitors rising to new
heights for the greater glory of the homeland.
</P>
<P>
   An upset? Of course.
</P>
<P>
   But really, it shouldn't be that big a surprise.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
