<DOCNO> NYT19980712.0251 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-12 22:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1481 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOCCER-CUP-ROBERTSON-     07-12 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCCER-CUP-ROBERTSON-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
A sight to behold for one and all
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Dale Robertson
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle &QL; 
PARIS _ One day became an entire year. And, like that, decades of
failure would be put summarily to rest.
</P>
<P>
   Dawn broke cold and gray Sunday. Almost wintery, at least by
Houston standards. But, by 2 p.m., summer was upon us.
Prophetically, there would be blue skies for Les Bleus.
</P>
<P>
   And, by midnight, it was Christmas, New Year's Eve and Bastille
Day happening at once.
</P>
<P>
   While les bon temps had rolled rather remarkably even in the
hours leading to the kickoff, you cannot imagine the scene once
France's stunning home-field 3-0 demolition of mighty Brazil was
complete. A wait of three generations was over, and three
generations of French fans threw themselves into a frenzy of
celebration the magnitude of which never has been seen in our neck
of the woods.
</P>
<P>
   Meaning from New York to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Charlemagne. Louis XIV. Napoleon. De Gaulle. Now Zidane. The
World Cup trophy, which remains the planet's most prized sporting
possession whether we Americans choose to accept it, finally
belonged to the country of its roots.
</P>
<P>
   Remember Richmond Avenue the night the Rockets beat the Knicks
and put our demons to rest? Now picture Richmond with at least a
million people descending upon its sidewalks _ six hours before
kickoff. Things, of course, got crazier afterward as the TVs
clicked off and jubilant fans flooded onto the Champs-Elyses as
well as into the Latin Quarter, turning the City of Light into the
City of Noise.
</P>
<P>
   No car horn went unhonked. No firecracker went unpopped. No
silly song went unsung. And, believe me, no l'eau de vie _ whiskey,
etc. _ went undrunk.
</P>
<P>
   Although scattered tiny pockets of sanity could be found on the
side streets of the Left Bank, the main boulevards looked as if you
had simultaneously dropped the Super Bowl, the Final Four, the
Indianapolis 500 and the Game 7s of the World Series and the NBA
Finals into New Orleans' French Quarter on the Fourth of July.
</P>
<P>
   At 2:30 a.m., three hours after the trophy presentation, the din
outside my hotel was actually building.
</P>
<P>
   The only comparable experience we've known in the United States
was the American hockey team's upset of the Russians in the 1980
Olympics. But Lake Placid lacked Paris' population base by just a
bit. As for France, it hadn't felt, or exhibited, such a national
euphoria since the Nazis shuffled out with their hands in the air.
</P>
<P>
   After some hand-wringing, I decided to spurn the offer of a
scalper's ticket costing gobs of francs, concluding it would be
better to take in the spectacle side by side with the real people,
not the nearly 80,000 high-rollers at the Stade de France out in
Saint-Denis. But finding an interesting spot from which to watch
proved infinitely more difficult than you would believe.
</P>
<P>
   The free ``football parcs'' with their giant TV screens filled
up early. The one at the Hotel de Ville (city hall) had closed its
gates five hours before the match began. And, if a bar or
restaurant owned a TV, it also had at least 10 times as many
customers as it had standing room, much less tables and chairs, or
meals.
</P>
<P>
   The throng crowded outside the Pizza Vesuvio on the
Champs-Elyses a block down from the Place Charles de Gaulle Etoile
probably numbered 2,000 by halftime. Meanwhile, one of the more
famous, usually packed bistros across the boulevard had maybe 10
customers and a larger number of waiters thinking only about
beating Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   One kind soul residing at No. 37 on the Rue des Longchamps in
the fashionable 16th arrondissement did his part for Liberty,
Egalite and Fraternity by putting his set out on the second-floor
balcony, facing the street. Within minutes, several hundred people
had gathered below, cheering his largess as well as Les Bleus, and
blocking traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Well, I say traffic. There was none to speak of during the game
in a city where gridlock is almost de rigeur. Most graphic would be
the contrast on the Etoile, into which 12 major avenues feed and
where normally several hundred motorists at any given moment stage
a free-for-all in the closest of quarters. But shortly after
kickoff, I counted only six cars from my perch atop the Arc de
Triomphe, where I wound up watching Paris watch France win the
World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Superb game. Better view.
</P>
<P>
   The security staff had cleverly tuned one of its closed-circuit
TVs into the match. So, for 35 francs, and a willingness to hike
the 200-odd steps up to the terrace, I had myself a front-row seat
for the soccer and a grand old city about to stage the party of its
modern existence.
</P>
<P>
   Later, when victory was secure, the Arc turned into a billboard
of tribute to France's most glorious triumph since Napoleon's
heyday. The players' faces were being projected onto the landmark
as blue laser lights beamed CHAMPIONS CUP DU MONDE! and MERCI LES
BLEUS! onto the glowing facade.
</P>
<P>
   Mercy indeed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
