<SLUG> BC-NY-MISSING-MILLIONAIRE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INQUIRY WIDENS IN VANISHING OF SOCIALITE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Utah, Calif., Nev., Fla., Bahamas)  (lb) 
 By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The mother-and-son team of traveling con artists who
are the prime suspects in the mysterious disappearance of an
82-year-old woman from her Upper East Side town house a week ago
were apparently preparing to swindle at least one other wealthy
Manhattanite, the police said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Sante and Kenneth Kimes _ whom the police suspect of trying to
bilk the woman, Irene Silverman, out of her luxurious home and who
were found carrying her expired passport after she disappeared on
July 5 _ had apparently set their sights on at least one other
target in New York City, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   The police said a speck of blood was found on the seat belt of
the Kimeses' teal-green 1997 Lincoln Town Car, and detectives are
anxiously awaiting the results of lab tests to see if the blood
matches Mrs. Silverman's DNA. The Kimeses have not been charged in
connection with Mrs. Silverman's disappearance; they are now being
held on a warrant in the passing of a bad check in Utah to buy the
Lincoln.
</P>
<P>
   But the Kimeses are considered suspects in a number of other
crimes in Los Angeles and Las Vegas, and in Florida and the
Bahamas. And the New York City Police Department has indicated that
it believes that Mrs. Silverman was not their only intended mark in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is some evidence that they were in fact looking at least
at one other person,'' Assistant Chief Kevin Farrell, the commander
of Manhattan detectives, said Sunday outside Mrs. Silverman's home
at 20 East 65th St.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives said they believed that the Kimeses were trying to
cheat Mrs. Silverman, a former ballerina and wealthy socialite, out
of her town house, which she had divided into units and rented out.
Kenneth Kimes was one of her tenants, and investigators said that
he brought two notaries to the house and that Mrs. Silverman had
grown suspicious of him in the days before she vanished.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Kimes, 63, has a criminal record going back to 1961 for
crimes as varied as keeping Mexican domestic workers in virtual
slavery, stealing a mink coat from a Washington hotel, and several
counts of credit-card fraud. She and Kenneth Kimes, 23, who was
arrested on a shoplifting charge in Florida, are viewed as suspects
in a number of swindles and crimes across the country.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities want to question the Kimeses about a missing
banker in the Bahamas who was last seen in their company, the
slaying of a Los Angeles businessman who the police believe may
have been swindled by them and a case of arson in Las Vegas that
the police believe may have been planned to enable the Kimeses to
collect the insurance. So far, the Kimeses have adamantly refused
to answer any questions, the New York police said.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives from the Los Angeles Police Department came to New
York to see if they could establish a link between the Kimeses and
the murder of David Kazdin, 63, a businessman who was found dead on
March 14 in Los Angeles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-98 2305EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
