<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980712.0254 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-12 23:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1559 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-LPGA-375&AMP;ADD-NYT &LR;      07-12 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-LPGA-375&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECORD WEEKEND IN A REMARKABLE ROOKIE SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By IRA BERKOW   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYLVANIA, Ohio _ For Se Ri Pak, the astonishing 20-year-old
rookie from South Korea, winning the Jamie Farr Kroger Classic by
tying a Ladies Professional Golf Association tour record with a
phenomenal 23 under par seemed as easy for her as a walk in the
cemetery. She did everything but whistle.
</P>
<P>
   She stunned golf followers when she shot a 10-under-par 61 on
Friday to break the LPGA record for lowest single round, added a 63
on Saturday, establishing a record for lowest score on consecutive
tournament days, and finished Sunday with a 66 for a total of 261,
nine strokes ahead of Lisa Hackney and 10 ahead of her playing
partner Sunday, Karrie Webb. Her four-round total was the lowest
score ever for an LPGA event, four shots better than the former
mark, held by three golfers.
</P>
<P>
   Pak, in white baseball cap, dark glasses, black-and-white
striped blouse and white shorts, hardly looked right, hardly looked
left. She just kept her focus _ and her shots _ straight ahead,
just as her father taught her to do when he decided that camping
out in a cemetery was just the thing to develop mental toughness in
his daughter, then about 13.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to make her brave,'' said her father, Joon Chul Pak,
``to give her big heart.''
</P>
<P>
   He had put up a tent for them in the cemetery and then left her
to be alone.
</P>
<P>
   His wife was not thrilled with that discipline, and others
imposed on young Se Ri. ``She's going to die,'' she warned.
</P>
<P>
   But the father, seeing great potential in his daughter,
persisted. As she got better, as she won a string of amateur
tournaments in Korea, the game of golf grew more pleasurable. With
a gentle smile and a game built to a considerable degree on the
power emanating from her solid frame, she has won two straight LPGA
tournaments; her Farr Classic victory follows her win last week in
a 20-hole playoff against the amateur Jenny Chuasiriporn in the
U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it got scary, especially when it got really dark,
and I had to walk home alone around midnight,'' she said this
evening, recalling those days in the cemetery in her hometown of
Daejeon, about 100 miles south of Seoul. And she smiled.
</P>
<P>
   She can smile about it now. But what effect did that experience
have on her golf game today? ``No shaking,'' she said. ``Not
scared.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Her parents seemed relatively calm as well, as they, along with
a large and enthusiastic gallery, followed her while she piled up
birdies on this hot afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Her father carried and sat on a portable chair, and her mother
was nearby under a small parasol. A family friend had
responsibility for Pak's 10-week-old beagle, for which she paid,
she said, ``Three hundred bucks!''
</P>
<P>
   But she can afford it, winning $120,000 for this tournament and
jumping from fourth place to first on the LPGA tour earnings list
at $645,170, some $44,000 ahead of Liselotte Neumann.
</P>
<P>
   Pak has had the most sensational start of any woman on the tour
since Nancy Lopez won nine tournaments, including five in a row, in
1978. Pak also won the season's second major tournament, the LPGA
Championship. Not since Julie Inkster in 1984 had any rookie won
two majors in the same year.
</P>
<P>
   She said she believes she has many more worlds to try to conquer
in golf. ``I have many, many years left,'' she said, noting that
she has much work to do on her game and ``I just start.''
</P>
<P>
   What little suspense there was Sunday afternoon centered on
whether she would break the record for shooting the lowest under
par in an LPGA tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is aware of the record,'' said her manager, Steve Kil, as
he walked the course. ``She hopes to break the record.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt I could make the record if I hit my putts, and shot my
shots,'' she said. ``But it would be difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   She began the day 18 under par and needing to shoot 6 under par
for a final round of 65 (she shot a 71 in the opening round) to
break the record of 23 under par, set by Wendy Ward last year in
the Fieldcrest Classic and matched by Lisa Walters in this year's
Oldsmobile Classic, both on par-72 courses.
</P>
<P>
   She birdied the third hole, bogeyed the fourth, then birdied
Nos. 7, 8, 10 and 11. At No. 16, she sank a 25-foot birdie putt to
bring her to 23 under. She walked to the 17th tee and she slapped
outstretched palms with fans straining from the gallery ropes.
</P>
<P>
   Then, on 17, she whacked a strong drive _ too strong. It was in
the low rough to the left. She barely got out of that jam when her
approach shot landed on the apron to the green. She needed a
40-foot putt for a birdie, and missed by inches. On 18, her pitch
shot landed about 18 feet from the pin. If she canned it, the
record was hers.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd hushed. She lined up the shot and stroked it. It
headed for the hole, and ran out of steam about a foot short.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ooh,'' the crowd groaned. Not Pak. She smiled, hugged Webb,
hugged her caddie, Jeff Cable, and then tossed her ball into the
stands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Se Ri has a good attitude,'' Webb said. ``She's very patient.
I played with her several years ago when we were amateurs. She was
kind of erratic. Not anymore. She's got the whole game.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a game that has come a long way from the time her father,
a top amateur golfer in Korea, took his daughter on the course with
him and, to his surprise, saw her swing a club as if she were born
with it. He had been in the construction business, but had fallen
on difficult financial times, so he had a lot of time to work on
his daughter's burgeoning golf game.
</P>
<P>
   His attention was not necessarily met with enthusiasm from his
young charge. ``She was a teen-ager,'' he recalled, through an
interpreter. ``It was hard keeping her from going out and being
with her friends. So I became her father, her brother, her friend.
We went shopping together, we went to movies together _ and we
played golf, working on it sometimes from 5 in the morning to 11 at
night.''
</P>
<P>
   And sometimes, of course, even later. Like midnight, in the
cemetery.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
