<HEADER>
A1590 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-CAMPAIGN-REFORM-     07-12 0546
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CAMPAIGN-REFORM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: PROMISES, PROMISES 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, July 13:
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the House of Representatives will again take up
consideration of campaign finance reform. By now it is clear that
election-bound legislators are ready to back serious change. The
only question is whether Dick Armey, the majority leader, will keep
his promise to end the dilatory tactics that have kept a fair vote
from taking place.
</P>
<P>
   Armey's vow deserves to be regarded gingerly, given the
Republican leadership's previous record of treachery on this issue.
Rep. Christopher Shays of Connecticut, the Republican leader of the
reform movement, says he believes Armey will keep his word. But
Armey could prove his sincerity right away by setting a schedule
for legislative action that would lead to a straight up-or-down
vote on the core reform bill _ before the House has its next recess
in four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The House bill, known as Shays-Meehan for Shays and his
Democratic co-sponsor, Martin Meehan of Massachusetts, would close
the soft-money trail that has made a mockery of campaign-finance
laws. Right now, political parties can collect unlimited amounts of
soft money for ``party building'' efforts, which have been
interpreted to cover virtually everything, including campaign
commercials masquerading as ``issue ads.'' Shays-Meehan has already
survived many leadership attempts to weaken or shelve it. But about
70 more amendments and 9 counterproposals are still in the wings.
Since most of them were offered by opponents as delaying tactics,
Armey can make them melt away if he really has the will to do it.
</P>
<P>
   The amendment being debated on Tuesday, offered by John
Doolittle, R-Calif., is typical of opposition tactics. Its backers
are peddling the amendment as a protection for advocacy groups like
the NAACP that want to produce voter guides. But the Shays-Meehan
bill already has specific language exempting voter guides from its
provisions. The real point of the amendment is to gut the bill's
restrictions on the ability of special-interest groups to flood the
airwaves with ``issue ads'' promoting particular candidates during
the 60 days before an election.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional addiction to soft money is reaching epic
proportions. The gaming industry alone recently poured $250,000
into the Republican Senate Campaign Committee, and the Senate
killed a proposal ending the ability of high rollers to write off
losses for tax purposes. The connection between six- and
seven-figure donations and the passage of special-interest
legislation is always fuzzy, but until the soft-money stops, voters
will have a right to be cynical about congressional motives.
</P>
<P>
   Enemies of reform have a friend in the clock, since the
Republican leadership in the Senate is equally determined to delay
the legislation to death. Given their dependence on the megabuck
campaign donations that Shays-Meehan would outlaw, the leaders can
be forced into action only by constant public pressure. When
members of Congress are on the campaign trail looking for support,
voters must demand to know not only how they voted on reform, but
also what steps they took to force a fair vote.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
