<HEADLINE>
COMEDY SHOW AUDIENCE BARES ALL TO HELP FIGHT DOMESTIC VIOLENCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Will also move in the ``n'' California news file.) 
BY LEE CONDON 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Los Angeles -- As a group of female comics prepared to take the
stage at Elysium Fields, a clothing-optional club in the canyon
suburbs, one of the audience members offered a piece of advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you get nervous, just try to imagine the audience in their
underwear,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the crowd, of course, was wearing nothing at all Sunday.
The comics, who opted to keep their clothes on, visited Elysium to
present Stand Up Against Domestic Violence, a performance
benefiting Los Angeles area women's shelters and domestic abuse
counseling programs. The event coincided with Elysium's 23rd annual
celebration of National Nude Recreation Week.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother really wants me to marry a Jewish man, and they're
much easier to pick out here,'' joked comedian Carol Ann Leif in
front of the 25 naked or mostly naked people gathered at Elysium's
outdoor amphitheater.
</P>
<P>
   Leif admitted to being nervous about playing to an audience in
the buff, announcing, ``OK, I'm over it,'' after taking her first
look at the group.
</P>
<P>
   Leif is one of several female comics who regularly participate
in benefits for the Theatre of Hope for Abused Women. The
performers were organized by fellow comic Heidi Joyce.
</P>
<P>
   The Theatre of Hope puts on plays every Sunday at the Bitter
Truth Theater in North Hollywood, Calif., and also offers
educational plays and art therapy programs at shelters and
transitional homes for victims of domestic abuse.
</P>
<P>
   The comic activists came together to entertain the nudists
Sunday mostly because Elysium's program manager, Betty Lesley
Meltzer, has become involved with Theatre of Hope.
</P>
<P>
   For many people, Elysium is a way to get away from the stresses
of daily life, Meltzer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being into nudity is certainly a nonviolent activity. If
people are left to naturalness they are not prone to violence,''
Meltzer said. ``There's no way you can get hot around the collar
because you don't have a collar.''
</P>
<P>
   Cliff Gartside, a 44-year-old Arco employee from Santa Monica,
Calif., agreed, saying the atmosphere at Elysium is the perfect
antidote for domestic stress. When he and his wife, who is also a
member, get into an argument, she frequently suggests that he ``go
to the club and relax.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For me it's a little piece of heaven in the metropolis of Los
Angeles where there's no crime and no hate,'' Gartside said. ``Then
I go home and I give my wife a big hug. It's really simple.''
</P>
<P>
   Elysium Fields, a nonprofit educational organization, has called
its eight-acre Topanga Canyon campus home for 30 years, surviving
numerous battles with Los Angeles County over its right to exist.
</P>
<P>
   Dana Lange, whose late father founded the club in 1968, said the
comedy show was just one of many special events it puts on. Some of
the performers wear clothes, others take it all off.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a magician perform nude once, and I didn't think he'd
be able to do the tricks without any clothes, but he did,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Lange said Elysium offers all sorts of educational programs, all
of them focused on teaching people about ``the wholeness of the
human body.'' The programs include yoga, water dancing, nude figure
drawing, dancing, self-hypnosis and tummy toning. Lange said she
looks forward to working with the Theatre of Hope again.
</P>
<P>
   ``For women escaping from violence, one of the biggest issues is
self-esteem. Our whole thing is about self-acceptance,'' Lange
said. ``We often get people in transition in their lives.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
