<SLUG> BC-BOX-OFFICE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LETHAL WEAPON 4' PROVES DEADLY TO WEEKEND COMPETITION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Will also move in the ``n'' California news file.) 
BY DAVE MCNARY 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Los Angeles -- ``Lethal Weapon 4'' blasted the competition with
an estimated $33.1 million at 3,117 theaters nationwide during its
Friday-Sunday opening, studio sources said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The explosion-laden sequel, with Mel Gibson and Danny Glover
reprising their roles as wisecracking LAPD detectives Martin Riggs
and Roger Murtaugh, came in at the high end of expectations.
Trackers had been wary of the franchise's potential because of
recent poor performances by other sequels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lethal Weapon 4,'' carrying an impressive $120 million price
tag, opened amid a massive promo campaign highlighting such staples
as car crashes, gunplay and the well-established camaraderie
between Gibson and Glover. Reviews were mixed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the kind of action movie people want to see,'' said
analyst Arthur Rockwell of Drake Capital Securities. ``Even though
the franchise may seem a bit dated, Mel Gibson is still a huge
draw.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Bucksbaum, head of the Reel Source tracking service, said
the addition of Chris Rock to a cast that included Joe Pesci and
Rene Russo helped bring in African-American viewers. He predicted
that ``Lethal Weapon 4'' will gross $115 million to $120 million
domestically and double that number overseas, where action films
traditionally play well.
</P>
<P>
   Best performance in the series came with ``Lethal Weapon 2'' in
1989 with $147.3 million domestically. For Warner Bros., it was the
biggest opening since ``Twister'' took in $41 million in May 1996
and an indication that the studio's unprecedented slump _ eased
recently by ``City of Angels'' and ``A Perfect Murder'' _ may have
ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``The studio had a pretty solid opening but the real test for
`Lethal Weapon 4' will be next weekend,'' said Bucksbaum, citing
strong expected openings by Sony's costume drama ``The Mask of
Zorro'' and 20th Century Fox's goofy comedy ``There's Something
About Mary.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox has taken the unusual step of showing sneak previews of
``Mary'' twice, once on Wednesday and again on Sunday. ``The buzz
on `Something About Mary' is incredible,'' Bucksbaum said. ``It's
somewhat crude, but I don't think that bothers anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Disney's second weekend of ``Armageddon'' delivered solid
returns, with $22.4 million at 3,136 theaters after its opening
fell short of expectations. The asteroid disaster flick has topped
$98 million in a dozen days and could match the $138 million
overall from Paramount's similar offering, the 2-month-old ``Deep
Impact.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Disney has to be relieved that `Armageddon' clearly has decent
legs,'' Rockwell said. The studio spent $140 million to finance the
project and an additional $60 million on marketing worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   DreamWorks SKG's opening of ``Small Soldiers'' followed in
third, with $14 million at 2,539 sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very pleased, especially in a crowded market like
this,'' said distribution chief James Tharp. Exit surveys after
showings of the movie of toys running amok showed strongest support
from young boys with significant backing from young girls and
parents, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's third weekend of ``Dr. Dolittle'' finished a respectable
fourth, with $12.7 million at 2,874 theaters, to give the Eddie
Murphy comedy $89 million after 17 days.
</P>
<P>
   Disney's third weekend of ``Mulan,'' with Murphy as the voice of
a wisecracking dragon, came in fifth with $6.8 million at 2,756
theaters to push its 24-day take to nearly $92 million. The
studio's 36th animated movie will finish far above the $100 million
grossed by its ``Hercules'' last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Sony's opening of ``Madeline,'' a family comedy based on the
stories of Ludwig Bemelmans, followed in sixth with a moderate $6.6
million at 1,863 sites.
</P>
<P>
   A quartet of holdovers were battling for the seventh slot, led
by a pair of critical favorites _ Universal's third weekend of
``Out of Sight'' with $3.9 million at 1,975 theaters and
Paramount's sixth weekend of ``The Truman Show'' with $3.7 million
at 2,186 locations.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's fourth weekend of ``The X-Files'' followed in ninth, with
$3.6 million at 1,900 theaters, followed by Disney's fifth weekend
of ``Six Days, Seven Nights'' with $3.3 million at 1,961 sites.
</P>
<P>
   The overall weekend performance topped the same period last
year, led by the $30.5 million second weekend of ``Men In Black''
and the $20.5 million opening of ``Contact.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there was some make-up this weekend for the slow
Fourth of July and there's a lot more diversified major product,''
Rockwell said. ``The marketplace is truly crowded.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Truman Show'' has taken in $116.4 million in 38 days,
making the Jim Carrey project the 111th highest domestic grosser in
Hollywood history, trailing ``Rocky's'' $117.2 million. ``Deep
Impact'' garnered in $400,000 at 602 screens to match ``Platoon''
for 70th place at $137.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   Paramount's 30th weekend of ``Titanic'' grossed $425,000 at 463
theaters and has now taken in $589 million after 206 days.
``Titanic'' leads ``Star Wars'' as best domestic grosser by $128
million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-98 2324EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
