<SLUG> BC-NY-STICKBALL-REUNION-725&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD-TIMERS RETURN FOR A DAY OF NEW YORK STICKBALL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By MOLLY O'NEILL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The cars started arriving on East 111th Street before
8 a.m. Sunday. Most were late-model vehicles. Some had license
plates from as far away as Florida. Each glided into a parking
space like a horse into a barn, instinctively and without question.
</P>
<P>
   It was, after all, a perfect day to play ball.
</P>
<P>
   Cool, blue and without a shred of the humidity that can cause
arthritic joints to ache, the day was also a custom-made for the
30th annual 111th Street Old-Timers' Games. And car by car, members
of the Bronx Old-Timers stickball team arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Between them, the 15 men boast more than 700 years of stickball
play, a collective batting average of .376 and six members in the
Stickball Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Playing is a point of honor to this team. It is also a habit, a
reason to gather the old neighborhood, and an exercise in hope.
</P>
<P>
   Their baseball-like game was, after all, once the soul of barrio
life. The sound of their broomsticks slamming pink rubber spaldeen
balls was a signal that all was well on the streets of upper
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after several lean decades, stickball is making a comeback.
At least, that's what the old-timers say. They also say that their
annual exhibition game on East 111th Street inspires young players,
or at least shows them that the streets can be used for something
other than trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think about it,'' said Charlie Ballard, 79, a retired salesman
who is, as far as anyone knows, the oldest stickball player still
in the game. ``A level playing field, one swing. That's the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Watching the opposing team's pitcher deliver a mean lob, he
said, ``Based on my experience, you grow up playing by those rules,
you grow up a decent man.''
</P>
<P>
   Now playing his 72nd season, Ballard has a lifetime average of
.405 and is a member of the Stickball Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   He and his teammates, he said, survived beat cops confiscating
their customized broomsticks _ even before they had broken a window
_ collisions with traffic, alternate-side-of-the-street parking
and, more recently, Rollerbladers.
</P>
<P>
   In moving-on-up from the old barrio, the old-timers have also
survived a veritable stickball diaspora. Still, rare is the Sunday
that local team players do not drive back to East Harlem to pick up
a game. And for the last three decades, even players who have moved
to distant states have returned for the annual game.
</P>
<P>
   Now, not everyone crowding the two blocks between Madison and
Lenox Avenues Sunday credits stickball alone for pulling nearly
5,000 people to the blocks.
</P>
<P>
   There were as well mountains of fried chicken, pulled pork, rice
and beans, empanadas, plenty of beer and a nonstop whir of blenders
whipping up fresh pineapple, coconut milk and rum. And there was
music. And families.
</P>
<P>
   Stickball, Irma Aroni said, may have brought her and her husband
together. But she was dubious about the life lessons the game
imparted. Her husband, John Nocco, has been a stickball pitcher
since ``God have mercy, forever, but at least 60 years now,'' she
said. And while stickball has been good to him, she said, facts are
facts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The barrio raised the old-timers decent _ it was very tight,
everybody looked after each others' kids,'' she said, motioning to
the group of five old-timers' wives with whom she stood. ``We spent
every Sunday watching them play before we were married and then
when we had young kids.'' she continued. ``But sooner or later, we
all moved up to the Bronx.''
</P>
<P>
   The stickball wives gathered every Sunday to watch the husbands
swing broomsticks, run into fire hydrants and dispute calls. But
the ball dropped with their husbands' generation.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of our kids played stickball,'' said Julia Martinez,
whose husband, Candido, is a utility player and switch-hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a barrio thing, and when they moved out of the barrio,
the kids played basketball and football,'' Mrs. Martinez said.
Besides, how could the sons compete with such all-star fathers?
Even in their seventh decade, the old-timers play like maniacs.
</P>
<P>
   Now the grandchildren, that's a different story. ``The
old-timers have mellowed, and a lot of them are trying to get the
grandchildren into it,'' Mrs. Martinez said. ``Charlie and Vito
even give stickball clinics over on 105th,'' she said, referring to
Ballard and Vito Giannone.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Having finally agreed to a playing field that including a birch
sapling as first base, a mutable second based marked only by the
opposing team's infielder and a gutter for third base, four
old-timers gathered with the wives to reminisce over the scrapbook
that Giannone had brought.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was 1941, St. Nicholas Avenue, the day I went through a
window for that fly ball,'' said Giannone, who is also a Stickball
Hall of Fame player. He pulled up his pant leg to display the faded
scars of the resulting 16 stitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I'm not saying it wasn't a hustle,'' Ballard said. ``We
stole the brooms from fire escapes, and we played for money.
Everybody bet; the winning team took the pot.'' He said that with
one season's proceeds, he bought a kitchen suite, a bedroom suite
and a living room suite. Beneath the myth of stickball, in other
words, lurked a swindle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We poached everybody to field an unbeatable team, and then we
bragged around and got other blocks to challenge us on their turf,
which was good for us 'cause they raised a lot more money than our
block,'' Ballard said.
</P>
<P>
   Ballard added that stickball has not been about money since 1967
or thereabouts. Besides, it wasn't just the money they won that
kept him and his teammates from ever getting into trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all had something good to live for,'' he said. ``We all
looked forward to Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of people cheered for Charlie Ballard several minutes
later when he took a regulation one-bounce pitch with a long Ted
Williams stroke.
</P>
<P>
   They cheered even before the ball rocketed toward Madison Avenue
and disappeared. They kept cheering as the septuagenarians battered
their 20- and 30-year-old opponents. Again. The Old-Timers never
lose.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not yet,'' said Ballard, softly. He gazed up to the adjacent
apartment building, where people hung cheering from the windows,
and let his blue-rimmed brown eyes rest on the crowded sidewalk,
near the spot where the teams roster had been written in chalk.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't lost anything yet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
