<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-MARKETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL UNCERTAINITY SHAKES JAPANESE FINANCIAL MARKETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (With JAPAN-ELECTION and JAPAN-POLITCS)  
(lh) 
 By SHERYL WuDUNN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Japan's stock markets and currency tumbled Monday
morning, as investors worried about economic disarray following the
severe beating that the governing party took in parliamentary
elections on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's leaders have been under pressure from abroad for months
to clean up the banking system's morass of bad debts and to lift
the economy out of recession. Though they finally have the
beginnings of a blueprint to tackle the problems, the defeat of the
governing Liberal Democrats suggests that pushing through economic
legislation will be even more difficult than in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``The uncertainties are enormous,'' said Russell Jones, chief
economist at Lehman Brothers Japan. ``Who leads Japan? Are we faced
with lower house elections? What does it mean for the process of
putting through the legislation for the bank bailout and tax
cuts?''
</P>
<P>
   In the first 20 minutes of stock trading, the benchmark Nikkei
225 average fell to 15,810.09, down 279.97 points, or 1.74 percent
from its close on Friday. And the yen fell sharply against the
dollar to a one-month low, falling to 144 yen, down from 141.39 in
late trading in New York on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Investors had been relatively sanguine about the prospects for
economic policy in the last couple of weeks, particularly with talk
about permanent tax reform and a cleanup of the nation's bad debt.
</P>
<P>
   But the resounding message of protest against the Liberal
Democrats throws into question the ability of the nation's leaders
to push through economic policy.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberal Democrats will now have to work more closely with
the opposition parties to pass legislation, and this is likely to
stall the process.
</P>
<P>
   As Japan's economy was sinking in a recession this spring,
governments abroad were already criticizing the slow pace at which
Japan's parliament was pushing through a $116 billion spending plan
to spur growth _ and that was when the Liberal Democrats had a firm
hand in the governing coalition and when the opposition parties
were extremely weak.
</P>
<P>
   The election results now raise the possibility of calls for an
election in parliament's lower house, where the governing Liberal
Democratic Party currently has a majority.
</P>
<P>
   The stock market rebounded after its initial fall, and in late
morning trading, the Nikkei benchmark stood at 16,023.58, down
66.48, or 0.4 percent, from Friday's close. The yen recovered to
trade at 142.55 near midday. Nonetheless, the market's jitters
themselves are likely to aggravate the problems for the banks and
for the government.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese have been suffering a credit squeeze as the nation's
banks have cut back on their lending around the country. The banks
have also pulled back from lending elsewhere in the region, leading
to credit squeezes in Hong Kong, South Korea and Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that part of their capital cushion is made up of
stocks, so as the prices of those stocks fall, there is more
pressure on banks to trim lending to ensure they have enough
capital in proportion to those loans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
