A1601 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-METS-HUNDLEY-450&AMP;     07-12 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-HUNDLEY-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON BASEBALL: HUNDLEY'S RETURN SHAKES UP THE METS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Never before has a routine fly ball to left field at
Shea Stadium been greeted with such enthusiasm and such anxiety.
But this was Todd Hundley backtracking on Vladimir Guerrero's
climbing shot into the wind Sunday, and he is not an ordinary
outfielder nor an ordinary Met. Right now, Hundley is Mr. Met, a
sort of savior slogging around in left.
</P>
<P>
   So the fans hollered before Hundley even moved into position to
catch the ball in the third inning. He retreated to the lip where
the grass meets the warning track before reaching up to corral the
ball with both hands for the third out.
</P>
<P>
   The fans kept hollering as Hundley's decent catch apparently
obscured the fact that a catchable looper by Javier Vazquez,
Montreal's pitcher, inexplicably plopped in front of him earlier in
the third after he took two steps back when he should have charged
forward. But Hundley redeemed himself and is 2-for-2 in not being
terribly embarrassing at the new position.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get that one under my belt was a lot of relief,'' Hundley
admitted.
</P>
<P>
   Relief for Hundley, for Manager Bobby Valentine and for the
peppier Mets, who stifled the dismal Expos, 5-2.
</P>
<P>
   For the second straight day, the Mets proved they could win,
they proved they could win while hiding Hundley's bat in left and
they proved that they could win while playing their version of
musical outfielders. Actually, Hundley's bat was totally hidden to
the 51,568 fans of baseball and Beanie Babies as he was 0-for-2
with a walk.
</P>
<P>
   But Hundley's presence was huge. Mike Piazza singled in Lenny
Harris from third with the first run when Vazquez, a rookie,
uncorked a fat, 1-2 fastball to Piazza, probably because Hundley
was swinging on deck. Butch Huskey, who lost his spot in the lineup
to Hundley on Saturday, responded with four singles in four
at-bats, and Brian McRae, whose playing status is not as tenuous
because he is the team's only true center fielder, clubbed a
game-turning, two-run homer in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   McRae, usually a silent sort, pumped his fist after he passed
first. Obviously, the outfield shuffling that Hundley's return has
caused has jostled some egos. Good. The often-moribund Mets needed
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a coincidence? No,'' Hundley said bluntly, when asked
whether his return inspired the other outfielders. ``We've got to
have guys who can contribute. Whatever mix is working, that's what
we're going to have to do. With me coming back and possibly taking
some of their playing time, they're going to have to kick it into
gear. It's a good, healthy situation. I'm not against them. They're
not against me. It brings out the best in all of us.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Hundley is right. If the Mets are going to even have a chance to
secure a wild-card berth in a season that has included too many
exasperating moments from the bullpen and too many underachieving
moments from the lineup, they need Hundley to bash and they need
the other Mets to feed off Hundley.
</P>
<P>
   So let Huskey traipse past the lineup card that included his
name in right field and suddenly announce that he was in a better
mood Sunday. Hint, hint. Let Bernard Gilkey, who pinch-hit for
Hundley in the seventh because Hundley has a pulled muscle on the
left side of his back and is still hesitant to bat right-handed,
insist that this is not a controversy. Then why did Gilkey even
raise the idea? Let McRae talk about pressure and competition being
an inherent part a major leaguer's life. Fine, then let the
competition continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure every man in here is up to the challenge,'' Gilkey
said.
</P>
<P>
   After Huskey first said that he had nothing to prove, he added:
``Of course, you want to take full advantage of your opportunities.
You can't put too much pressure on yourself. This game is tough
enough. For some reason, I relaxed today.''
</P>
<P>
   McRae minimized the internal competition before saying, ``If you
don't do the job, they're going to find someone else to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Precisely. Valentine will do that each day, no matter how he
sugarcoats it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a problem,'' Valentine claimed. ``Everyone wants to
make it a problem. The problem was when we didn't have enough
outfielders for the first 80 games.''
</P>
<P>
   Remember, this is only two victories. Not enough reason to get
giddy or expend too much oxygen discussing the wild card. Still,
the Mets rejoiced a bit because Hundley's presence has rejuvenated
their lineup and their clubhouse. He is their leader even when he
is wearing sunglasses in the outfield instead of a catcher's mask
behind the plate. Hundley is back. The Mets should hope he helps
keep it this intense in Flushing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd like to think that,'' Hundley said. ``I just want to
win. The bottom line is whatever Todd Hundley has to do to help
this team win, I'll do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
