<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CONSTRUCTION-DEATH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. SOJOURN ENDS IN DEATH BY BURIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By SOMINI SENGUPTA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Only five months ago, Lucas Gomez helped the eldest
of his six brothers, Luis, make the journey from their home in
Ecuador, squeezed him into the apartment he shared with more than a
dozen compatriots in Corona, Queens, even found him a job at the
construction company where he worked.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Luis, 32, lay in an open casket, his hands folded around
a black rosary. At his feet was a bouquet of red roses and a ribbon
carrying a message from Lucas, 23. ``Siempre Te Recordare,'' it
read _ ``I will always remember you.''
</P>
<P>
   Luis Gomez's life in America ended Friday afternoon when he was
buried alive in a 6-foot hole. A coworker on a backhoe filled in
the pit at the TriBeCa construction site, apparently unaware that
Gomez was still underground.
</P>
<P>
   About eight hours later, when he learned his brother was
missing, Lucas Gomez _ who had been working for the same company,
Safeway Construction, at another site that day _ summoned several
friends and began digging. In 20 minutes, he recalled, they spotted
his brother's head and called the police.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the Medical Examiner's office, Ellen Borakove,
Sunday described the cause of death as ``asphyxia due to burial in
earth.'' It was ruled an accident, and no one has been charged by
the police. Officials with the federal Occupational Safety and
Health Administration are investigating.
</P>
<P>
   Lacking immigration papers, Luis Gomez earned about $80 a day
and hoped someday to be able to send money to his wife and their
six children, age 2 to 13, in Ecuador, Lucas said. But first, Luis
had to pay off the the $7,000 that it took to get to America, his
brother said.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, no one answered the phone at the Brooklyn
headquarters of Safeway Construction, which had been contracted by
Con Edison to check whether gas and electricity lines were
accurately marked on the utility's maps.
</P>
<P>
   According to OSHA records, Safeway Construction has been cited
at least once, in October 1994, for violating federal rules on
protecting employees during an excavation and on the operation of
hand tools.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Con Edison, Joseph Petta, said he could not
comment on Safeway's safety record, or on whether Con Edison would
continue working with the company.
</P>
<P>
   Luis Gomez worked for Safeway Construction for less than two
months, his brother said. The two were last together Friday morning
before Lucas went to work at a construction site in Astoria,
Queens, and Luis headed to lower Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   When Lucas returned home that evening, the answering machine was
crammed with messages from their boss, inquiring about Luis, who
had apparently disappeared shortly after noon. Lucas Gomez said he
knew then that something had gone awry.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, he struggled to understand how workers could have been
unaware that his brother remained in the hole. During an
excavation, he said, someone usually checks the pit for tools. ``I
don't know how they couldn't have seen him,'' he said at the wake
Sunday at the Buen Pastor Funeral Home in Corona.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did Lucas know quite what the future held for him, only that
he would need to continue working. It will cost about $6,000 to
send Luis back to his hometown, Cuenca _ almost as much as it cost
to bring him to New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-98 2341EDT &QL; 
