<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BOY-DROWNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNATTENDED BOY DROWNS AT A BRONX BEACH 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By AMY WALDMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The body of a 12-year-old Bronx boy who had been
swimming at Orchard Beach after it closed was found Sunday about
150 yards from shore, the authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   The police ruled that the drowning of the boy, Hiro Lora of
Morris Heights, was accidental. It was the first drowning at a city
beach this year.
</P>
<P>
   Hiro apparently arrived at the beach with a 15-year-old girl and
her 12-year-old brother about 5:45 p.m. Saturday, said Edward
Skyler, a spokesman for the Department of Parks and Recreation.
Guillermo Neiva, the father of the siblings and the only adult
accompanying the children, stayed in his car in the parking lot and
read, according to Skyler and friends and family of Hiro.
</P>
<P>
   The beach's lifeguards go off duty at 6 p.m., and swimming is
supposed to stop then, Skyler said. The police conduct regular
sweeps of the sliver of sand to make sure no one is swimming, but
beachgoers are permitted to remain on the sand until 8 or 8:30
p.m., when the police clear the beach. Hiro and his friends, who
were at the border of Sections 8 and 9, about halfway down the
beach's 1.1 mile-long crescent, apparently continued going in and
out of the water after 6 p.m., Skyler said.
</P>
<P>
   The boy's friends last saw him in knee-deep water about 8:30
p.m., the police said. At 8:45 p.m., Neiva reported Hiro missing,
and the police began a search using scuba, harbor and aviation
units. Bloodhounds tracked Hiro's scent to the water, but the
search was called off because of darkness. The search resumed
Sunday, and the police found the boy's body at 11:50 a.m., said a
Police Department spokeswoman, Officer Lee Ann Tracy.
</P>
<P>
   Parks officials said that the last drowning at the beach, which
is just west of Long Island Sound, was in 1996, when a 51-year-old
man who was intoxicated went swimming at night and drowned.
</P>
<P>
   An investigator who spoke on condition of anonymity said there
did not seem to be a strong undertow or changing currents Saturday
night. But Skyler noted that the water's depth increases sharply,
from 5 to 15 feet, about 150 yards from shore, where Hiro's body
was found.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he just headed into the water and got in over his
head,'' the investigator said of the boy. ``From what I understand,
he could swim a little, but nothing spectacular.''
</P>
<P>
   The boy's friends and family, who gathered Sunday night at his
apartment to console his mother, Teresa Lora, said Neiva had
originally planned to take the children to a swimming pool, but
took them to the beach, without Ms. Lora's permission, because the
pool was closed. Neiva was among those at the Loras' apartment
Sunday night, but he refused to comment on the accident.
</P>
<P>
   Teresa Lora, a home care attendant originally from the Dominican
Republic, lay on her only child's bed Sunday night, saying that she
felt a ``big sadness.'' Her son, who she brought from the Dominican
Republic six years ago, wanted to become a doctor, she said, ``to
help poor people and build me a big house in the Dominican
Republic.'' Friends said he was a good student who often cooked for
his mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``My whole family talked about his future,'' said Daulin Guzman,
18, a friend. ``He was so certain what he wanted to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-98 2343EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980712.0263 </DOCNO>
