<HEADER>
A1607 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRADLEY-WORLDCUP-COX     07-12 0568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-WORLDCUP-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A spectacle of worldly proportions
 &HT;    By Mark Bradley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three billion people watched it. The Buddhist son of Algerian
immigrants scored the first two goals. Two men who work for Arsenal
in North London engineered the final goal. The winning captain
spends winters playing in Turin. The losing captain has lately been
based in Japan, which will serve as co-host with South Korea when
next this event convenes. It really is a World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   The most famous team on the planet was supposed to win again but
did not. The holders were unhorsed by a team representing a country
that deems soccer secondary to rugby. Of the 11 men who started for
France on Sunday, nine play elsewhere professionally. The Coupe de
Monde usually belongs to those nations that consider football among
life's essentials, alongside food and shelter. Which only goes to
show that passion can be overrated.
</P>
<P>
   Or can it? Belying that sophisticated reputation, France backed
its stylistically challenged team with a fervor found normally ...
well, pretty much everywhere else in the world. The rap on this
French side was that it had no strikers, no goal scorers. This was
half-right. The French played four games in the tournament's
knockout stages, and no striker scored a goal. But midfielders and
even defenders did, which only goes to show that hard work cannot
be overrated.
</P>
<P>
   The midfielder Zinedine Zidane was Sunday's star, scoring twice
on headers. Zidane's reputation as a big-game player had taken a
beating lately; he'd been nigh-invisible in consecutive Champions
League finals with his club Juventus. But those were only for
European supremacy. This was for the whole wide world. Twice Zidane
rose on precise set pieces, the Brazilians' notorious inattention
to detail finally their undoing.
</P>
<P>
   Ronaldo was the invisible man this day. (Speculation holds that
he was hurt _ a knee, an ankle, something.) The Brazilian midfield
was overrun by Youri Djorkaeff. Roberto Carlos, who'd scored the
Goal of the Decade on a bending free kick against France last
summer, got nothing done. With better finishing by the hapless
Stephane Guivarc'h, the French might well have won 6-nil.
</P>
<P>
   There was no single MVP in this World Cup. There were four. The
French defenders _ Marcel Desailly and Laurent Blanc in the middle,
Lilian Thuram and Bixente Lizarazu on the wings _ draped an iron
curtain over the penalty area, yielding but two goals (one on a
penalty kick) in five weeks. The French keeper Fabien Barthez
authored all manner of tactical blunders but was never made to pay.
Even with Blanc suspended for Sunday's game, even with the mighty
Desailly ejected in the 68th minute, the French defense was so
well-grounded that fearsome Brazil could find no space.
</P>
<P>
   And then it was over, Patrick Viera feeding Emmanuel Petit to
clinch it. In all of sports, nothing matches the winning of a World
Cup for sheer spectacle. That the hosts won this one made it
exponentially stirring. As the gallant French players embraced
victory and one another, TV kept cutting to the Arc de Triomphe and
the masses gathered underneath, and it looked like the prettiest
sight in ... well, the world.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Bradley's column appears in the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-98 2343EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
