<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-12 23:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1610 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-TRAFFIC-DEATHS-NYT     07-12 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TRAFFIC-DEATHS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAFFIC DEATHS FALL SHARPLY IN NEW YORK CITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By DAVID W. CHEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK - The number of pedestrians and bicyclists killed by
drivers in New York City declined sharply in the first five months
of year, putting the city on a pace to reach record low,
preliminary police records show.
</P>
<P>
   The figures, which were obtained by a pedestrian advocacy group,
Transportation Alternatives, show that from Jan. 1 to June 3 of
this year, 71 pedestrians and bicyclists were killed by motor
vehicles _ a 36 percent drop from the same period in 1997, in which
111 were killed.
</P>
<P>
   All year long, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has vigorously pushed
traffic enforcement as a means to make New York City safer:
instructing the police to erect pedestrian barricades, hand out
more speeding tickets, discourage jaywalking and install new signs
informing drivers that the speed limit is 30 miles per hour in most
places.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it appears that those efforts are beginning to pay off.
</P>
<P>
   Extrapolated to year's end, the number of pedestrians and
bicyclists killed in the city would be about 168 _ which would be
significantly lower than the previous low of 245 in 1996, said John
Kaehny, executive director of Transportation Alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised by the magnitude of the reduction,'' Kaehny
said. ``Something good is happening right now.''
</P>
<P>
   But as is so often the case in the world of statistics and data
collection, several caveats must be mentioned. For one thing, the
corresponding five-month figure for years before 1997 was not
immediately available on Sunday night, according to the police. For
another, projections are always just that, subject to unusual or
unexpected circumstances _ warmer weather in the final months of
the year, for example, meaning more people outside and more chances
of accidents.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, several bits of important information that would
offer a more complete picture were not immediately available, said
Charles Komanoff, a pedestrian safety advocate and board member of
the Tri-State Transportation Campaign, a nonprofit group. These
include a borough-by-borough breakdown, the total number of crashes
and injuries, and the number of summonses for moving violations.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, statistical adjustments aside, there appears little
doubt about the general trend related to pedestrian deaths: down.
</P>
<P>
   It was in 1898 that New York City had its first pedestrian
killed by a motor vehicle, Kaehny noted. And during the 1940s and
50s, sometimes more than 1,000 pedestrians and bicyclists were
killed a year.
</P>
<P>
   But in subsequent decades, that figure began to dwindle, thanks
to better emergency medical care and improved school busing. The
fading of the unbridled, but occasionally dangerous, game of
stickball to a warm memory also did not hurt those statistics,
Kaehny said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, traffic deaths for pedestrians and bicyclists stood at
365. Then came a drop that has since leveled off at around 250
deaths. Until this year, that is, if the numbers hold.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking at record lows at this point, based on those
preliminary figures,'' said David Billig, a spokesman for the
city's Department of Transportation.
</P>
<P>
   At the current pace, New York would be approaching the numbers,
per capita, posted by London, long considered a model of
pedestrian-safety policy and planning, Kaehny said. About 15 years
ago, London introduced a campaign to reduce speeding through
widespread advertising, camera-activated enforcement and speed
bumps. The results were remarkable, as the number of pedestrian
fatalities declined dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   This time, New York transportation advocates and city officials
attributed the sharp decline to the Giuliani administration's
multipronged campaign to make the city's famously incorrigible
drivers a little more law-abiding.
</P>
<P>
   In March, for instance, the city unveiled a much-publicized
``zero tolerance'' day, in which police officers used hand-held
radar guns and unmarked cruisers to catch speeding motorists, and
installed more than 1,100 new signs informing motorists of the
speed limit.
</P>
<P>
   A total of 224 speeding tickets was issued that day, more than
75 the usual daily total. And the show of force, by all accounts,
intimidated some motorists into easing up a little on the
accelerator.
</P>
<P>
   ``All these initiatives are focused on raising public awareness
about traffic safety,'' said Billig.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-12-98 2351EDT &QL; 
