<SLUG> BC-BOX-NELSON-425&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BRUTAL NIGHT CLAIMS NELSON 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ If a boxing card can be measured by the number of
participants who landed in the hospital, then the show at the
Alamodome on Saturday night was brutal. And perhaps no one felt the
sting worse than Azumah Nelson, the three-time world champion who
may have fought the last fight of an illustrious career.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson, 39, broke his left hand in the fifth round, on his way
to losing a 12-round decision to James Leija. He was taken to
Baptist Memorial Hospital shortly after the fight for X-rays. He
followed Troy Dorsey, who went to the hospital for stitches to
close deep cuts over both eyes that brought an end to his bout
against Gabriel Ruelas at 1 minute 25 seconds of the sixth round.
</P>
<P>
   And Tracy Harris Patterson (61-6-1) went to the hospital for
stitches in his lower lip, which was severely cut by a punch from
Goyo Vargas (37-6-1) in the second round. The fight was stopped at
1:02 of the sixth round after swelling shut Patterson's right eye.
</P>
<P>
   The prospects for the losers were not bright. Dorsey's loss to
Ruelas (45-4) was his eighth in his last 12 bouts and dropped his
record to 15-11-4. And in the ring after the fight, Nelson (39-5-2)
hinted that he might retire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe yes, maybe no,'' Nelson said when asked whether he would
retire. ``I have to go home and think about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson has many things to keep him busy at his home outside
Accra, Ghana. He owns a teakwood plantation and ceramic tile and
cooking-utensil factories, and has a large family _ a wife and six
children.
</P>
<P>
   One thing was certain: there will not be a fifth fight against
Leija, because Leija does not want one. Nelson's record against
Leija is now 1-2-1. Outside of the broken hand, Nelson was not
battered in this fight. But he could not beat Leija (36-3-2) as he
had done in 1996 when he stopped him in the sixth round.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson fought cautiously during the early rounds, which he lost.
Even though he was more aggressive after the fifth round, he could
not make up the lost ground. Nelson won no more than four rounds on
any of the three judges' scorecards, and one gave Nelson only two
rounds, the fourth and the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a real tough fight, but it was nothing different from
the first three,'' Leija said. ``I had a great barrier in front of
me. In the fifth, sixth and seventh rounds, I didn't know what was
going to happen. After what happened in the sixth round in the last
fight, I was just wanting to get past the sixth round.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Leija said he was not aware that Nelson had broken his hand in
the fifth round. The hard-hitting Nelson could never bait Leija
into the kind of slugfest that would have been beneficial to him.
Nonetheless, after the fight, Leija's face looked like he had stuck
his head into a hornet's nest. Big red lumps covered his forehead,
and his right eye was completely closed. There was an accidental
head butt in the 10th round that opened a cut inside Leija's right
eye.
</P>
<P>
   Leija, his manager, Lester Bedford, and his promoter, Dan
Goosen, believe his showing against the wily Nelson has catapulted
him into the lightweight championship mix, which now includes
Arturo Gatti, Kevin Kelley, Shane Mosley and Prince Naseem Hamed.
</P>
<P>
   ``James is the type of fighter who fits perfectly into HBO's
130- to 135-pound picture,'' Goosen said.
</P>
<P>
   For Goosen, this fight card dovetailed nicely with his Aug. 15
pay-per-view show in El Paso, Texas. Miguel Angel Gonzalez, who
defeated Alexis Perez on a fifth-round technical knockout, will be
on the Aug. 15 show, fighting John Molina. The main event will be
Rafael Ruleas versus Kostya Tszyu in an elimination bout to
determine the No. 1 contender for the World Boxing Council's
lightweight title.
</P>
<P>
   All of the winners on Saturday night's card were Hispanic
fighters, and Goosen said he will cater to the Hispanic audience
for the El Paso show by adding the featherweights Luisito Espinosa
of the Philippines and Juan Carlos Ramirez of Juarez, Mexico, to
the card.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
