<HEADLINE>
BURTON WARMS TO YANKEE HOSPITALITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUDON, N.H. _ For the second straight year, a dominating
performance by Jeff Burton turned the Jiffy Lube 300 into a game of
follow the leader.
</P>
<P>
   Burton blew by Jeff Gordon on the 78th lap and after that was
never in danger of losing his lead. Leading for 191 of the 300
laps, Burton won this NASCAR race at the New Hampshire
International Speedway for the second straight year, finishing
7.439 seconds ahead of Mark Martin. Gordon was a distant third.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, there was little excitement and even fewer meaningful
passes as Burton's No. 99 Ford Taurus roared around the 1.058-mile
oval, leading by almost a full straightaway for the final 60 laps.
Burton, the ninth different winner in 17 races on the circuit this
season, turned Sunday's fastest lap at 29.927 seconds and averaged
102.996 miles per hour in a race slowed by six cautions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just had a dominant car,'' said Burton, whose victory was
the fourth of his Winston Cup career. ``It was just one of those
days when you mash the gas and the car goes, and you turn the wheel
and the thing steers. It's the kind of day a race driver dreams
about.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he ever worried that he might be caught, Burton
said: ``No. Not today. I can't say that often, but we were right
today.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the postponement of last week's Pepsi 400 in Daytona
Beach, Fla., because of widespread fires, Sunday's race was the
midpoint of the 33-event Winston Cup series. And with 16 races
remaining, Gordon held onto his slim lead in the championship.
Martin improved his rank in the points race from third to second,
trailing Gordon by only 52 points. Dale Jarrett, who finished
seventh, moved up to third and is 98 points behind. Jeremy
Mayfield, whose right front tire blew with only five laps left in
the race, finished 30th and fell from second to fourth in the
points competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to look at the championship now,'' said Gordon, who
led for 73 laps Sunday and has nine top-10 finishes in his last 10
races. ``Every point, every position really counts out here as
tight as the championship is. Mark Martin has been consistently
strong everywhere we've gone. We've been fortunate to finish ahead
of him a few times, but I don't expect that to happen every
weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's victory did not improve Burton's Winston Cup
championship hopes since he remained in eighth place, 393 points
behind Gordon.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ricky Craven's 29th-place finish was probably not what he was
hoping for, but for him, this weekend still had its moments.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, at the place Craven considers his home track, he
climbed into the cockpit of a Winston Cup car for the first time
since his crash last March in Atlanta, where he sustained a severe
concussion, and drove his Chevrolet to the front of the field.
</P>
<P>
   As Craven entered Turn 3 on Friday afternoon, he surely did not
look like a driver who had been away from the circuit for more than
four months recuperating from post-concussion syndrome. His
pole-winning qualifying time was more than a half-second faster
than that of his teammate, Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody could touch the 99,'' Gordon said of Burton's
overpowering performance. ``He was so strong. He was definitely in
a different league than us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
